<title>Marywood College</title>
</head>

<body background="/images/backgrnd.gif">
<img src="/images/mwlogos.jpg" align=left hspace=10>
<h1>Marywood College</h1>
<h2>Curriculum - Courses and Descriptions</h2><br clear=left><hr>

<center><b>Foundation Curriculum</b></center>
<p>

<b>SW 501 	Theory and Practice of Social Work I (3)</b><br>
The first in a series of practice courses which introduces the students to an array of knowledge, values and skills that comprise the core of social work practice.  The focus includes the philosophical foundation, the self-awareness and values of the helping person, the professional relationship and theoretical and practical approaches to problem-solving.  Taken concurrently with the practicum education course, 
SW 591.  In this course are other substantive areas of the curriculum including ethics, human growth and behavior, research and social policy.<p>

<b>SW 502	Theory and Practice of Social Work II (3)</b><br>
A continuation of SW 501, SW 502 reemphasizes contact and contracting while moving to the stages of intervention, evaluation and termination.  The Life Model is the framework for the social work practice emphasized in SW 502.  An equal emphasis is placed on the core helping skills and the various roles social workers may assume.  Taken concurrently with 
SW 592, Practicum II.  Prerequisite:  SW 502.<p>

<b>SW 591	Practicum Instruction I (3)</b><br>
<b>SW 592 	Practicum Instruction II (4)</b><br>

Students spend sixteen hours a week in social work settings, developing knowledge and skill in social work practice by working under qualified supervision.  Focus is on professional use of self as a helping person and on integration of the total learning experience as it relates to and sheds light on social policy and social work practice.  Taken concurrently with SW 501 and SW 502, theory and practice courses.  <p>

<b>SW 601	Psychosocial Analysis of Human Behavior (3)</b><br>
It is essential that the social worker understand how human persons develop and grow as bio-psycho-social beings over their life span; also what life events are anticipated and the ways in which social work practice can enhance this process.  In addition, when life chances are limited due to personal or environmental barriers, social workers also need to understand the consequences and connect theoretical material, practice skills and policy understanding to create maximum positive resolutions.<p>

<b>SW 602	Social Science Perspectives on Human Behavior (3)</b><br>
The goal of this course is to provide knowledge of social institutional factors that shape human behavior.  Aspects of human behavior are examined in their social context, emphasizing structure, culture, class, 
ethnicity, race, sexuality and age.  Social and social psychological theories are examined for understandings of the interactions between individuals and the social environment.  Contemporary 
human-social problems will be discussed from the perspective of social theory and in terms of personal and collective ethical stances.  <p>

<b>SW 635	Human Biology and Social Work (0)</b><br>
A short course for students without undergraduate preparation in human anatomy and physiology, this course is to help social workers identify the biological stresses facing their clients and provide a framework for incorporating this understanding into a bio-psycho-socio-cultural framework.  <p>

<b>SW 801	Introduction to Social Welfare (3)</b><br>
This first required course in the Social Policy Sequence examines the social work and analyzes its historical development in the relevant political and economic contexts.  Emphasis is placed on the dynamic relationship between social welfare as an institution and modern 
industrial/post industrial society. Included is an introduction to some basic analytical concepts, such as universality and selectivity, institutional and residual, and public and voluntary. <p>

<b>SW 971	Ethical Issues in Social Work Practice (3) </b><br>
This course has been designed to foster sensitivity to ethical concerns and to provide knowledge and experience in ethical decision-making. Students become familiar with the philosophical base of ethics, while considering social work values and ethical dilemmas in practice at all levels and developing expertise in using a decision-making model.  The implications of such ethical practice are reviewed.  Case materials reflect a variety of issues, levels of practice and diversity of populations.<p>


<center><b>Advanced Curriculum</b></center>
<p>

The foundation courses described previously are taken (with the first elective) in the first year of study by full-time students and in the first two years by part-time students.  As students move to more advanced levels of their studies, more specialized courses are offered to assist in the acquisition of knowledge and skills in greater depth. <p>


Every full- and part-time student is required to undertake two semesters of social work research courses concurrently with the chosen concentration.  These courses assist the student to focus critical analysis on the relationship of social work practice methods to the realities of client needs, agency services and policies affecting the delivery of services.  In these courses the student is to carry out a 
research project that grows out of the practice situations.  It is out of the convergence of the methods concentration, practicum experience and research, supported by elective choices, that the student is expected to develop skill and competence for advanced social work practice.<p>



<center><b>Concentration Courses</b></center>
<p>

<b>SW 511	Social Work Intervention with Individuals, Families 
  and Small Groups I (3) </b><br>
Critical assessment of theoretical concepts and practice techniques. This course builds on the Life Model of SW 502 and provides further theory and practice skills in working with small, interpersonal systems. Taken concurrently with SW 593, Practicum III. <p>

<b>SW 512	Social Work Intervention with Individuals, Families 
  and Small Groups II (3) </b><br>
This course further develops advanced skills in differential interventions with a variety of systems.  Emphasized are the differential selections of practice theories and intervention strategies, utilization of community- and organization-level interventions and critical assessment of one's own practice. Prerequisite: SW 511. Taken concurrently with SW 594, Practicum IV. <p>

<b>SW 531	Administration in Social Welfare I (3) </b><br>
Designed for students preparing for supervisory or mid-management roles. Introduces principles of managerial settings.  Examines organizational problems and issues in administration within the value system of social work.  Influences of funding patterns, organizational environments, structure and staff roles on program planning and implementation are considered.  Prerequisites: SW 501 and 502.  Taken concurrently with 
SW 593 or by permission. <p>

<b>SW 532	Administration in Social Welfare II (3) </b><br>
Continues the focus of SW 531 on building management competencies and approaches to tasks required of managers with social work values.  The course will emphasize several aspects of fiscal management, budgeting, funding through proposal writing and grant relationships and effective human resource utilization.  Prerequisite:  SW 531.  Taken concurrently with SW 594 or by permission. <p>

<b>SW 593	Practicum Instruction III (4) <br>
SW 594	Practicum Instruction IV (4) </b><br>
Students are to take SW 593 and 594, Practicum Instruction III and IV, along with their methods concentration courses, in order to carry out practice activities that exemplify and develop skill in the method chosen.<p>

<center><b>Research Courses </b></center>
<p>
<b>
SW 703	Social Work Research: Design and Methodology (3) </b><br>
This course builds upon the research knowledge infused throughout the foundation curriculum and 
focuses on research methodology.  At the end of this course, students submit a proposal for a practice-based research project, including a rationale for the study, a review of relevant research and the 
methodology of the study.  Accordingly, the course content will include the basic forms of research and the logical progression of research from the problem formulation and design stage to various data 
collection techniques and interpretation. <p>

<b>SW 704	Social Work Research: Implementation and Analysis (3) </b><br>
Implementation of the research proposal developed in SW 703 is the central concern of this course.  Students explore analysis issues and expose their individual data sets to a variety of statistical analyses. Students are introduced to the need for and function of qualitative and quantitative analysis as essential components of social work research and practice.  The end products of SW 703 and 704 include a research paper and formal oral presentation or poster presentation.<p>


<center><b>Policy Course </b></center>
<p>

<b>SW 802	Social Policy and Social Issues (3)</b><br>
Historically, the social work profession has sought to change the environmental circumstances which limit people's lives.  This course, building on foundation policy, teaches the student to use a conceptual framework in analyzing social policy issues and advocating for change. Significant contemporary issues in social welfare, including poverty, racism and sexism are selected and examined, and students complete policy analyses of the issues of their choice.  Prerequisite:  SW 801.<p>


<center><b>Electives</b></center>
<p>

Electives allow study of a particular intervention methodology or area of significance for social work.  The School offers a range of elective choices to respond flexibly to priority concerns and emerging issues in social welfare, in accord with faculty resources and student interests. A minimum enrollment of ten students is required for an elective to be offered.  <p>

In consultation with their educational coordinators, students may select some of their elective course work in Marywood's Graduate School of Arts and Sciences.  Course offerings in the departments of Art Therapy, Counseling and Psychology, and Public Administration can enrich a student's social work education. <p>

<b>SW 535	Child Abuse and Neglect: Treatment and Strategies (3) </b><br>
Provides the historical and theoretical framework for understanding child abuse. Surveys neglect and 
physical, sexual and emotional abuse, focusing on situations where social workers are likely to be intervention agents.  Provides a foundation of knowledge and skills needed to work effectively with 
families affected by abuse and/or neglect and to apply social work expertise to public policy decisions. Students will assess their personal values and the societal factors that influence work with these client 
systems. <p>

<b>SW 561	Family Intervention (3)</b><br>
Social work theory stresses the importance of interpersonal and societal transactions as equally vital areas of both assessment and intervention. The family is the basic unit of social analysis in this approach.  This course builds on the history and traditions of family therapy in the basic social services and examines practice issues, family therapy concepts and approaches used in contemporary social work intervention. <p>

<b>SW 564	Techniques of Group Leadership (3) </b><br>
This course is designed for students who seek to improve their leadership skills as professional social 
workers with groups of various types.  The structure of the course is developed on the assumption that enrolled students will have been exposed to introductory knowledge regarding group phenomena, together 
with relevant experiences in the practice of group leadership.  Students, then, are expected to have begun to raise specific questions regarding issues of their respective problems in role performance and to be 
oriented toward the refinements in use of self toward the established purposes and goals of the target unit.  The class-group will be structured to provide opportunities for exploring such questions. <p>

<b>SW 565	Social Work Practice with Groups</b><br>
The practice of social work in group settings as presented in this course relies on a conceptual model focused on mutual aid within an ecological framework.  The course also examines the underlying philosophy of group work and a theoretical understanding of small group dynamics.  Specific issues of group practice, techniques and skills are explored.  <p>

<b>SW 571	Supervision in Social Work Practice (3) </b><br>
This course is designed to provide the students with the requisite knowledge for assuming the basic 
responsibilities of supervision.  The course examines the purpose, principles and methods of supervision applicable to many settings in social work.  It deals with the role demands upon the supervisor and 
supervisee.  Emphasis is placed upon the educational and administrative elements of supervision.  The course is taught in the context of the School's emphasis on an eco-system approach.  The commitment of 
the School to women and minorities will be explicitly addressed. <p>

<b>SW 575 Social Work in Employee Assistance Programs (3)</b><br>
This course provides an overview of the role of EAPs in industry, as well as the role of the social worker.  
A clinical focus related to individuals, families, groups and environmental issues develops an understanding for effective social work treatment and intervention. Additionally, a focus on profit 
management philosophies explores strategies for social worker success in the corporate environment. <p>

<b>SW 621	Psychopathology (3) </b><br>
The purpose of this course is to identify and develop an understanding of the issues inherent in the study 
and assessment of abnormal behavior. The course explores current paradigms for viewing psychopathological behavior and analyzes the commonalities and differences among these perspectives, 
emphasizing possible explanations of causality.  Major cognitive, affective, personality and character disturbances will be addressed within the framework of the DSM III-R classification system. <p>

<b>SW 625	Alcoholism:  Addiction and Co-Dependency (3) </b><br>
This course provides an overview of the problem of alcoholism for the individual, the family and society.  Social workers need to be prepared for effective practice with individuals and families so affected. They 
also need to understand current policy initiatives.  The course will provide a model for effective social work treatment and intervention at different levels of practice. <p>

<b>SW 810	Issues in Child Welfare</b><br>
This course considers child welfare practice with diverse and vulnerable families and develops implications for future service design.  The policy context of practice, including public and private programs and services in child protection and child welfare, and current evaluative research provide a base for discussion of contemporary issues.  <p>

<b>SW 906	Experiencing Group Membership (3) </b><br>
This experiential course uses the self and the medium of the group process to develop an understanding of group dynamics, roles, structure and process.  The Pass/Fail evaluation of students facilitates a serious and honest attempt to explore the use of self while developing a conceptualization of group work. <p>

<b>SW 908	Women's Issues and the Practice of Social Work (3) </b><br>
This course focuses on the unique pressures and problems that confront women today, with emphasis on the barriers and stresses facing poor women, minority women and aged women.  Attention is directed toward evolving a practice perspective that is most suited to meeting the particular needs of women clients.  Within the field of social work itself there is evidence that women social workers are victims of discriminatory practices; this issue is also addressed. <p>

<b>SW 925	The Minority Experience and Social Work Practice (3) </b><br>
Social workers have an historic commitment and ethical imperative for practice that empowers disadvantaged individuals and groups.  This course examines devaluing attitudes toward others, the ethnocentrism, prejudice, bias, discrimination and racism that permeate our society, then explores ways these attitudes have shaped the experiences of selected ethnic and minority groups.  Students are prepared for more sensitive and effective practice.  The theme of the course is "achievement against the odds." <p>

<b>SW 941	Concepts and Issues in Gerontology (3) </b><br>
This course is designed to provide a theoretical perspective on the aging process to aid students in understanding and analyzing social policies and treatment programs for aging persons.  Issues related to adult development are examined, with emphasis on biological, psychological and sociological aspects of the process of aging. Implications for social work practice are stressed. <p>

<b>SW 951	Managing Stress: Theory and Practice (3) </b><br>
Based on the supposition that stress increases susceptibility to illness and has negative impact on family and work, this course integrates theories of stress, professional knowledge and interventive skills to help students understand their own and their clients' stress responses. Students will learn new ways to cope with stress and ways to help clients manage stress and enhance mastery over environmental demands. <p>

<b>SW 965	Human Sexuality: Issues for Social Work (3) </b><br>
Given the social work profession's commitment to the right of self-determination for all, this course aids in understanding and analyzing social policies and treatment.  The main focus is upon specific contemporary issues related to human sexuality and their implications for social work practice.  Biological, psychological and sociological aspects of sexual development and personal/professional values concerning these issues are explored.  <p>


<center><b>Independent Study </b></center>


Independent study may be undertaken by a student in order to explore a specific area of interest.  The plan 
of study and bibliography are developed by the student, in cooperation with a faculty mentor, according to guidelines established by the School.  Normally, independent study is available to students who have 
completed the courses in the foundation curriculum with a 3.50 average.  Independent study plans must be approved by the student's educational coordinator and the dean.  No course regularly offered by the School 
may be taken as a subject for independent study, though such study may take an existing course as a point of departure for pursuing a topic in greater depth.<p>


