<H1>Marywood College</H1>
<H2><FONT SIZE=6>D</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>OCTORAL</FONT><FONT SIZE=3> </FONT><FONT SIZE=6>P</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>ROGRAM</FONT><FONT SIZE=3> </FONT><FONT
 SIZE=4>IN</FONT><FONT SIZE=3> </FONT><FONT SIZE=6>H</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>UMAN</FONT><FONT SIZE=3> </FONT><FONT
 SIZE=6>D</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>EVELOPMENT</FONT>
<BR></H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<CENTER><HR ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=100% SIZE=2></CENTER></P>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<CENTER><B>The Faculty and Their Research</B></CENTER></P>
<P><B>Stephen C. Burke</B>, Associate Professor of Social Work, 1994; Ph.D., University
 of Minnesota, 1992. Public sector systems, programs, change and strategies. Development/
Family Readiness. Military Family Institute.</P>
<P><B>Gail Cabral, I.H.M.</B>, Chair of the Doctoral Program, 1995; Professor of 
Psychology, 1991; Ph.D., Catholic University of America, l978. Myers-Briggs Type 
Indicator; gender differences; social-cognitive development, particularly in the 
area of friendship relations; relationship of psychology and religion.</P>
<P><B>Catherine Campenni</B>, Assistant Professor of Counseling and Psychology, 1994;
 Ph.D., Adelphi University, 1987. State dependent learning; gestalt organization 
of auditory events; gender differences in children's play; psychology and marketing.</P>
<P><B>Kathryn Clauss, I.H.M.</B>, Assistant Professor of Counseling and Psychology,
 1995; Ph.D., Seton Hall University, 1995. Influence of family dynamics and adjustment
 to college; relationship of family dynamics to personality development.</P>
<P><B>Lois K. Draina</B>, Chair and Associate Professor of Education, 1989; Ph.D.,
 Virginia Commonwealth University, 1985. Institutional leadership; educational administration;
 Catholic schools; non-profit board development.</P>
<P><B>Mary Anne Fedrick</B>, Assistant Vice President, Academic Affairs; Ph.D. Candidate,
 Penn State, 1995. Management and delivery of information technology in higher education;
 higher education organization and culture, leadership roles for librarians.</P>
<P><B>Michael A. Foley</B>, Chair and Professor of Philosophy, 1994; Ph.D., Southern
 Illinois University, 1973. Philosophy and punishment, death penalty, insanity defense,
 crime and human nature, law and society issues (censorship, pornography, freedom
 of speech and press, drug legalization, fourth, sixth and eighth amendment rights).</P>
<P><B>James L. Gearity</B>, Dean, GSAS and Associate Professor; Ph.D., University
 of Minnesota, 1979. Higher education management; history, cultures of education 
in America; marketing for nonprofit organizations in America; symbols of American
 culture.</P>
<P><B>Joanne Gumpert</B>, Associate Professor of Social Work, 1992; D.S.W., Adelphi
 University, 1992. Rural social work practice, small group practice, qualitative 
research design, peer group dynamics.</P>
<P><B>Lee Harrison</B>, Associate Professor of Nutrition and Dietetics, 1984; Ph.D.,
 New York University, 1984. Personality type (MBTI) and its effects on career choice,
 competence and ability to predict success, nutrition support/critical care, food
 habits. Children's health and nutrition, women's health and fitness, geriatric nutrition
 and health, attitudes and perception of health practitioners.</P>
<P><B>Elizabeth Hartley</B>, Associate Professor; D.S.W., University of Pennsylvania,
 1985. Social work ethics, social policy, substance abuse, women's issues.</P>
<P><B>Dorothy J. Jeffreys</B>, Professor; Ph.D., University of Michigan, 1987. Military
 adolescents, women, families, trauma and abuse.</P>
<P><B>Douglas Lare</B>, Assistant Professor of Education, 1995; Ed.D., Lehigh University,
 1994. Teacher education; educational leadership.</P>
<P><B>John Lemoncelli</B>, Associate Professor of Counseling and Psychology, 1992;
 Ed.D., Temple University, 1983. Adult survivors of abuse; clinical practice training;
 pastoral counseling.</P>
<P><B>Alan M. Levine</B>, Director of Research for the Military Family Institute,
 1996, Professor of Nutrition and Dietetics, 1993; Ph.D., New York University, 1985.
 Sports nutrition, human performance, wellness/health promotion, children's health
 and nutrition.</P>
<P><B>Marie Loftus</B>, Professor, Chair and Professor, 1988; Ed.D; Pennsylvania 
State University, 1975. Health and life style habits of military children; gender
 differences in mathematics.</P>
<P><B>Floyd McWilliams</B>, Director, Academic Computing, 1995. Ph.D., Indiana State
 University, 1996. Technology planning, coordination, and implementation, particularly
 as key to school district leadership, more generally, leadership as a social phenomenon.</P>
<P><B>Nancy M. Nagy</B>, Assistant Professor of Education, 1994; Ph.D., Temple University
 1994. Diagnostic reading literacy and language development; teacher effectiveness.</P>
<P><B>Edward J. O'Brien</B>, Chair and Professor of Counseling and Psychology, 1992;
 Ph.D., University of Massachusetts at Amherst, 1980. Cognitive approaches to self-esteem
 change; stress and coping; computerized assessment and intervention.</P>
<P><B>Jane R. Reohr</B>, Undergraduate Academic Dean. Ed.D., Boston University. Social
 psychology; relationships/friendships; group functioning; organizational functioning
 and structure of organizations; women's studies; non-verbal communication.</P>
<P><B>Anthony C. Russo</B>, Chair and Associate Professor of Special Education, 1982;
 Ed.D., University of Maryland, 1976. Adult literacy, inclusion strategies.</P>
<P><B>Barbara Sadowski</B>, Director of Planning and Institutional Research, 1994;
 Ph.D., University of Maryland, 1978. Effects of technology (especially computers)
 in program enhancement and enrollment; multimedia use by pre-college teachers (factors
 involved in and effects of). Measurements of productivity in higher education. Outcomes
 assessment in private colleges.</P>
<P><B>Mary Salvaterra</B>, C.S.J., Associate Professor of Education, 1991; Ph.D.,
 Syracuse University, 1990. Block scheduling and curriculum development in secondary
 schools; educational leadership.</P>
<P><B>Terry L. Singer</B>, Dean, 1984 and Professor of Social Work, 1996; D.S.W.,
 University of Pittsburgh, 1975. Sexual Harassment, social work education and human
 sexuality. Broadly interested in various substantive areas of social work practice.</P>
<P><B>Pamela C. Twiss</B>, Assistant Professor, 1994; Ph.D., University of Pittsburgh,
 1993. Poverty and associated problems, unemployment and community development.</P>
<P><B>Joanne Whelley</B>, Associate Professor; D.S.W., Fordham University, 1990. 
Child Welfare, family preservation, and professional ethical dilemmas.</P>
