<P><IMG SRC="http://www.marywood.edu/images/mwlogos.jpg" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 VSPACE=0 HSPACE=10></P>
<H1>Marywood College</H1>
<H2><FONT SIZE=6>D</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>OCTORAL</FONT><FONT SIZE=3> </FONT><FONT SIZE=6>P</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>ROGRAM</FONT><FONT SIZE=3> </FONT><FONT
 SIZE=4>IN</FONT><FONT SIZE=3> </FONT><FONT SIZE=6>H</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>UMAN</FONT><FONT SIZE=3> </FONT><FONT
 SIZE=6>D</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>EVELOPMENT</FONT>
<BR></H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<CENTER><HR ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=100% SIZE=2></CENTER></P>
<P><B>The Social Work Specialization</B> is designed for those who seek a career 
within the broad scope of social work practice, such as in human services, administration,
 policy and program development, or as a faculty member of a school of social work
 in an accredited college or university.</P>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>P</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>ROGRAM</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=4><B> </B></FONT><FONT
 SIZE=5><B>D</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>ESCRIPTION</B></FONT></CENTER></P>
<P>This sixty-credit program, leading to the degree of Doctor of Philosophy (Ph.D.),
 combines an interdisciplinary core, team-taught and common to all students, with
 discipline-based areas of concentrated specialization. Particular course titles 
are tentative and may change, but the components of the Doctoral Program in Human
 Development are:</P>
<P><B>I. The Interdisciplinary Core (15 credits)</B></P>
<P><UL>
<P><LI><A HREF="course.htm#hd1021">Human Development 1021 </A>-- Development and 
Change: Foundations for the Practitioner (4 credits)</LI>
<LI><A HREF="course.htm#hd1031">Human Development 1031</A> -- Social and Economic
 Dimensions of Human Development (4 credits)</LI>
<LI><A HREF="course.htm#hd1041">Human Development 1041</A> -- The Physiological and
 Psychological Basis of Human Development (4 credits)</LI>
<LI><A HREF="course.htm#hd1051">Human Development 1051</A> -- Selected Topics Seminar
 (3 credits)</LI>
</UL>
<P><B>II. The Research Core (9 credits)</B></P>
<P><UL>
<P><LI><A HREF="course.htm#hd1011">Advanced Statistical Analysis I 1011</A>
</LI><LI><A HREF="course.htm#hd1013">Advanced Statistical Analysis II 1013</A>
</LI><LI><A HREF="course.htm#hd1014">Qualitative Research 1014</A>
</LI></UL>
<P><B>III. The Specializations (27 credits)</B></P>
<P><UL>
<P><LI><I>The Social Work Specialization</I>
<BR><UL><LI><A HREF="course.htm#ecdpp">Ethnic and Cultural Dimensions of Professional
 Practice</A>
</LI><LI><A HREF="course.htm#mpa">Models of Policy Analysis</A>
</LI><LI><A HREF="course.htm#pswp">Paradigms of Social Work Practice</A>
</LI><LI><A HREF="course.htm#progadm">Program Administration</A>
</LI><LI><A HREF="course.htm#swprofethics">Professional Ethics</A>
</LI><LI><B><U>Electives</U></B>
<BR><UL><LI><A HREF="course.htm#swhist">The History of Social Welfare and The Social
 Work Profession</A>
</LI><LI><A HREF="course.htm#swprogeval">Program Evaluation</A>
</LI><LI><A HREF="course.htm#phspd">Planning in Human Services and Program Development</A>
</LI><LI><A HREF="course.htm#cdsmt">Cross Discipline Seminar on Models of Teaching</A>
</LI><LI><A HREF="course.htm#swecdp">Social Work Education Curriculum Development
 and Policy</A>
</LI><LI><A HREF="course.htm#swmte">Mentored Teaching Experience</A>
</LI></UL></LI>
</UL></LI></UL>
<P><A NAME="DDE_LINK1"></A><B>IV. Comprehensive Examination</B></P>
<P>Upon completion of thirty credits (twelve interdisciplinary core credits, nine
 research credits and nine specialization credits) the student will take a qualifying
 exam. The exam may be in the form of an integrative paper written in response to
 a question or a series of questions provided by the faculty.</P>
<P><B>V. The Dissertation (9 credits)</B>
