<HTML>
 <HEAD>
 <!-- $MVD$:app("MicroVision WebExpress") -->
 <TITLE>Regulations</TITLE><META
  NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
 <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Nelson Wood">
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>
 <P>
 <IMG SRC="/images/mwlogos.jpg" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 VSPACE=0 HSPACE=10></P>
 <H1>
 Marywood College</H1>
 <H2>
 <FONT SIZE=6>D</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>OCTORAL</FONT> <FONT SIZE=6>P</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>ROGRAM</FONT> <FONT SIZE=4>IN</FONT> <FONT SIZE=6>H</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>UMAN</FONT> <FONT SIZE=6>D</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>EVELOPMENT</FONT><BR></H2><P ALIGN=CENTER><CENTER><HR ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=100% SIZE=2></CENTER></P><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><CENTER>Doctoral
   Program Regulations and Policies</CENTER>
 </H2>
 <H3>
 Registration and Residency Requirements</H3>
 <P>
 There is no formal residency requirement.</P>
 <P>
 Students are required to take the core interdisciplinary and research courses with their cohort. This will ordinarily require three continuous Fall and Spring semesters of seven (7) credits each.</P>
 <P>
 Although efforts will be made to schedule courses at times that are amenable to students, registration in this program indicates willingness to abide by the policy described above. Students are expected to show flexibility regarding scheduling and registration.</P>
 <H3>
 Admission Policies</H3>
 <P>
 Admission to the Doctoral Program in Human Development is competitive. The faculty are seeking a diverse student body whose members manifest superior academic achievement, a sensitivity to interdisciplinary inquiry, and evidence of professional leadership in their careers.</P>
 <H4>
 I. Common Admissions Requirements</H4>
 <P>
  <OL>
   <LI>A master's degree from an accredited college or university.<LI>
   Recent graduate-level courses in Research Methodology and in Statistics. (If needed, such courses as PSY 503 and 504 or SW 703 and 704 may be taken during the academic year or summer session prior to enrollment in the doctoral program.)<LI>
   Three letters of recommendation from people who can address in depth the academic achievement and professional accomplishments of the applicant. At least two of these letters should be from teachers or a current supervisor.<LI>
   A reflective essay of approximately one thousand words, addressing the personal and/or professional goals which would be met through participation in this interdisciplinary program.<LI>
   Graduate Records Examinations (GRE) General Test scores. Official scores from exams taken within the past five years may be submitted.<LI>
   TOEFL (Test of English as a Foreign Language) score, if an international student.<LI>
   Personal interview and writing sample. A preliminary review and screening of applications will be done based upon the submission of the materials described above. The Admissions Committee will then invite a small number of applicants to campus for personal interviews. While on campus each applicant will be required to write a brief essay on a topic selected by the committee. Final selection will be made after the on-campus interview.</OL>
 <H4>
 II. Specialization Admissions Requirements</H4>
 <P>
 <U>Social Work</U>: The following would be the usual requirement of expertise for Social Work applicants:</P>
 <P>
  <OL>
   <LI>An MSW degree.</P>
   </OL><P>
 <U>Counseling Psychology:</U>
 </P><P>
  <OL>
   <LI>Coursework and/or experience in psychological assessment and psychotherapy.<LI>
   A preliminary personal interview with the Counseling Psychology faculty.</OL>
 <H3>
 Transfer of Credits</H3>
 <P>
  <OL>
   <LI>The core interdisciplinary courses will not be waived in any case.<LI>
   No more than six credits will be accepted as transfer credits. These will need to be not only post-master's courses, but will need to be clearly doctoral level courses. Such a determination will have to be based on an examination of quality and content of the courses after the student has matriculated in the doctoral program.<LI>
   While it could happen that students already have more than six credits in specialty courses required for certification, the acceptance of these courses for certification would not lessen the number of Marywood doctoral credits required to complete the program.</OL>
 <H3>
 Graduation Requirements</H3>
 <H4>
 Standards for Continuation</H4>
 <P>
  <BLOCKQUOTE>
  A cumulative Q.P.A. of 3.25 is the minimum for continuation in the program. Students who fail to maintain a 3.25 average in their course work will be given one semester to re-establish the required 3.25 average.</BLOCKQUOTE>
 </P>
 </BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4>
Qualifying Exam</H4>
<P>
 <BLOCKQUOTE>
 Students will be expected to take the qualifying exam after 30 credits of doctoral courses have been completed.</BLOCKQUOTE>
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4>
Time Limitation Policy</H4>
<P>
 <BLOCKQUOTE>
 All work must be completed within seven years of the beginning of doctoral study. The beginning of doctoral study is defined as the beginning date of the earliest doctoral course, whenever taken, listed on the approved doctoral plan of study.</BLOCKQUOTE>
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
 <BLOCKQUOTE>
 Extensions of the terminal date are considered only when there is substantial evidence that the student has made regular and consistent progress toward completion of degree requirements. Extensions will be granted only if the student has been granted a leave of absence for medical or other good reasons. <I>Written application for extension, with full documentation of serious cause, must be made to the Chairperson/Dean of the Graduate School of Arts and Sciences. </I>This period of time is rarely extended. Any extension must have the approval of both the department and the graduate dean.</BLOCKQUOTE>
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4>
Progress Toward Candidacy</H4>
<P>
 <OL>
  <LI>Faculty advisors will monitor students throughout their first year and subsequent years regarding grades, and behavioral and ethical standards. Anyone with concern about the progress of a student academically or professionally should make such concerns known to the advisor.<LI>
  A qualifying exam will be administered after 30 credits are completed, including 9 credits in research, 12 credits in the interdisciplinary courses and 9 credits in the specialization courses . In the case of the student who fails the qualifying exam, there will be allowance to retake the exam twice.<LI>
  Candidacy becomes effective when the comprehensive examination has been passed and the student has successfully defended his/her dissertation proposal.</OL>
<H4>
Dissertation</H4>
<P>
 <BLOCKQUOTE>
 Dissertation committees composed of at least three faculty members must be approved by the Dean. Although the dissertation advisor does not need to be the student's program advisor, at least one member of the committee must have faculty status in the student's specialty area. The Chair/Advisor of the Dissertation Committee must be a faculty member in the <U>respective area</U>. The other two members must be doctoral level professionals, one of whom must be from the Marywood College faculty.</BLOCKQUOTE>
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
After passing the Qualifying Examination, the student must submit the dissertation proposal to the Doctoral Degree Committee. In addition, proposals must be submitted to Marywood's Institutional Review Board in keeping with academic and professional standards.</P>
<P>
When the dissertation has been approved by the student's mentor and by the other members of the dissertation committee, students will register their intent to defend. Dissertation defenses will be scheduled at least five weeks after such an Intent to Defend form is submitted.</P>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
