<img src="/acnews/rabbit.jpg" align=left hspace=10>
<right><H1><i><b>Announcing . . .</b></i></h1></right><p>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<b><h2>PAC Building is now  being networked!</h2></b>

At the completion of this semester, the PAC building will be the latest 
addition to the campus network.  This is the last classroom building to 
go on-line, thus completing an important phase in the growth of the 
campus network.  Physical plant has completed the wiring stage of this 
process and soon the components to complete the job will be in place, 
bringing on-line the labs, selected classrooms and faculty offices.  
Students and faculty in the PAC will have access to all the services 
provided by Academic Computing Services, the Campus Wide 
Information System as well as full access to the Internet.  State-of-the-art 
technology in this building continues Marywood's trend of providing the 
most current technologies to its students and faculty.<br>  
Further updating of Marywood's network services continues with  the Learning 
Resources Center being rewired and outdated equipment replaced.  This building was first 
wired in 1989 when MELVIN was brought on-line. Use of this network has increased a 
hundredfold; thus re-wiring will provide greater efficiency.<p>

<h2><b>Computing Conference Coming to Marywood</b></h2>
Marywood College will be the host for the Twelfth Annual Eastern Small 
College Computing Conference to be held in the fall, October 25-26, 1996.  
A call for participation is being made for papers, presentations and 
panels.  Topics are to be focused on the impact of computing in an 
academic setting in disciplines as far ranging as music and fine arts to 
linguistics and political science.  The deadline for abstracts and panel 
proposals is March 8 and should be sent to <a href=mailto:dumdum@ac.marywood.edu>Dr. Rex Dumdum</a> or<a href=mailto:smetana@ac.marywood.edu> Dr. Joan 
Smetana</a> of the Dept. of Business and Managerial Science here at 
Marywood.   Please give this careful consideration - Marywood College 
should be well represented at this conference not only as a host but with 
active participants.  For further information, contact Dr. Dumdum or 
Dr. Smetana at 348-6274.<p>


<h2><b><i>Strategic Role of the World Wide Web</b></i></h2>

<i>by Dr. Floyd McWilliams	</i>
<p>
<img src="/acnews/web_erth.jpg" align=left hspace=10>
Before discussing the strategic role of the World Wide Web ("Web" hereafter), let us agree 
on what it is and is not.  The Web is an extension of the Internet with three primary features 
comprising the extension: significant use of graphics, powerful linkages between the almost 
infinite "isles of information" on the Internet, and search machines for taking advantage of 
the linkages.  Ours is a graphical world: television is currently the primary means by which 
people obtain information about the world around them in large part because it is graphic in 
nature.  The Web, then, moves the Internet from text-based to graphics-based.  The quest for 
information can be terrifying -- there is so much of it "out there."  Human beings tend to 
seek information like this: "Hmmm, I want to know about educational software, well actually 
about remedial educational software, well actually about remedial educational software that 
promotes thinking skills, well ..." you get the idea.  Web linkages work much the same way.  
You find an entry that is "about" the subject in which you're interested and it has <b>built into 
the text and graphics</B> keywords that can be clicked on and which take you to other entries 
that may reside on a different computer, possibly in a different country.  The power of the 
linkages is multiplied by the "search engine."  "Search engine" is just fanciful terminology 
for the software that facilitates the searches you make.  The search engine exists to make 
"about the subject" as precise as possible.<p>
	With that introduction to the Web why is it important?  In particular, why is the Web 
important to those of us at Marywood College?  The answer has two parts: first, the Web is 
important because it has the features we just discussed: it is graphic, it has useful linkages, and 
it has a powerful means of finding things; second, the Web is important because of 
McWilliams's fifth law of technology: "In the world of technology, hype is reality."  The 
Web is important because segments of society that are important to us believe the Web is 
important.  Another way of saying this is "Marywood needs to participate in the Web because 
many people who are important to us believe that Marywood should participate in the Web."  
Who are these "people who are important to us?"  One segment of the population that we 
know for certain believes in the power of the Web are prospective students.  We have already 
had high school students ask us "What is Marywood's URL?"  The term "URL," as well as 
"home page" and other terms were explained in the article World Wide Web Addresses, 
Making Sense of URLS  published in our fall edition.  As is discussed in that article, 
Marywood has a home page, but it is still in the "dotting the i's and crossing the t's" stage.<p>
	Let us speak briefly of reality as well.  The Web is not the answer to all of society's 
problems.  It is not a cure for the common cold, nor is it a solution to all of Marywood's 
needs, not even our recruiting needs, although I do believe it can be a useful tool in recruiting 
and other areas.  The two negatives I have observed about the Web at this time in its brief 
history are the extent of the hyperbole and that nobody, not even Bill Gates, knows where all 
the hype and the reality are taking us.  I will posit that it will be an exciting ride once we jump 
on the "Web express," but more than that I will not venture.<p>

<h2><b>Find Pricing Pentiums and Power Macs Perplexing?</b></h2>
<img src="/acnews/flip.jpg" align=left hspace=10>
So you've decided to take the big step and buy that computer you've 
been thinking about for the past year and a half.  Don't try just tossing a 
coin.  Now that you've made that purchasing decision you will find 
yourself facing a lot more choices that have to be made.  How big a hard 
drive do I need?  How fast a processor is fast enough for the software I 
want?  Do I really need 8 megabyte of RAM?  Should I get a Macintosh or 
PC (an IBM compatible for the neophyte)?<p>
Before even taking a step out your door to begin shopping decide exactly what you want this 
computer to do for you.  Some of the following questions should be answered:
<ul>
<li>	What do I think it will primarily be used for?
<li>	What type of computer am I most comfortable with?
<li>	What type of computer do I (or anyone else who might be using the computer) have at work?
<li>	Is there a specialized software program that I need which will work only on a Macintosh or PC?
<li>	In my chosen profession what type of computer am I likely to find in the field?
<li>	Will I want a computer that my children can use?
</ul>
	There are some basic guidelines that most experienced computer owners will follow in 
today's market.  Just keep in mind that the computer you buy today will probably be out of 
date in 6 months.  Technology is moving too rapidly to keep up.  That doesn't mean that 
you should put off buying the computer.  It simply means that you should buy as high-end 
computer as you can comfortably finance.  It is not practical to buy a 350MB hard drive 
when a 500MB hard drive might cost only $100 more.  So here are some things to look for 
whether it be a PC or Macintosh:
<Ul>
<li>	Look for a 500MB hard drive--a gigabyte (1 billion bytes) is better yet.  The hard drive is used to store 
your programs and files.  Perhaps you feel that you will use your computer only for word processing.  
Believe me, once you get hooked you'll find lots more uses for it than just typing reports.  That's when the 
bigger hard drive will really come in handy.  Some software packages are voracious storage pigs!!
<li>	The display (monitor) should be a super VGA (SVGA) color and at least 15".  (This is virtually 
standard on any machine you'll see.)
<li>	8MB RAM is minimal, particularly if you have a CD-ROM drive and 16MB on up is better.  This 
will determine how quickly screen changes will be made and how many different applications you can have 
open at the same time.  It also will affect overall speed to some degree.
<li>	Pentium processors have come down considerably in price and are almost as affordable as a 486DX.  
Buy a Pentium or a Power PC on the Macintosh side if you can swing the cost; they're faster and more up 
to date.
<li>	Look to see what pre-installed software (besides the system software) comes with the computer.  Some 
you may find you will seldom use; but, on the other hand, a good integrated application such as <i>Claris 
Works</i> can be extremely useful and save you the expense of buying additional programs.
<li>	How about extras like a CD-ROM drive or a modem?  Are they really necessary?  Some software 
packages will be on as many as 12 or more disks (<i>Microsoft Office</i> comes on 23 disks), making 
installation tedious to say the least.  Buy the CD version of the application and you'll complete the 
installation in half the time without popping disks in and out.  There are complete encyclopedias now 
available on CDs as well as wonderful children's programs such as <i>Where in the World is Carmen 
Sandiego</i>.   Will you use a modem?  It depends on how fascinated you are with "surfing the Web," doing 
research in Marywood's library in the comfort of your own home or maybe even shopping on American On 
Line or Prodigy.
<li>	An extended keyboard (one with function keys and number pad), a good mouse and Windows ('95 or 
ver. 3.1) or the Macintosh OS 7.5 are essentials.  A      3 1/2" floppy disk drive is pretty much standard.
<li>	Should I get a tower or a computer that my monitor sits on?  This should be determined by the 
amount of space you have to place your computer.  Towers can be placed either alongside the monitor or on 
the floor; but remember your monitor will sit lower.  
<li>	Speaking of space, the question might also arise as to whether a laptop should be purchased instead of a 
desktop computer.  A laptop can do everything a desktop can do but provides the luxury of popping it in a 
briefcase and taking it anywhere you want or sitting it on your lap while you loll in bed, all your materials 
spread around you.  Laptops are a bit pricier which can be an important factor and not quite as flexible to 
upgrade.
<li>	What kind of warranty is provided?  Some manufacturers will come to your home and service your 
machine for 1 year with a limited warranty over 3 years.
<li>	How about a printer?  As far as I'm concerned a computer isn't worth a heck of a lot unless I can print, 
and it's not much fun having to go somewhere else to do it.  We'll talk about printers in the next 
newsletter.
</ul>
	Where should you go to buy this computer?  After careful research, Academic 
Computing usually buys its software and hardware directly from the dealer or through 
magazine ads.  It eliminates the middle man.  You can do the same. The key is to shop just as 
carefully for a computer as you would for a car.  There are lots to chose from with a wide 
variety of prices and features.  Educate yourself first; know at least as much as the salesclerk 
so that you can make an intelligent choice.  If you need more ideas or are still confused, call 
Academic Computing Services, ext. 2391.  Our Coordinator of User Services, Kay 
McClintock, will do her best to guide you towards a purchase you'll be happy with. <p>


<h2><b>Is It Contagious?  A Look at Computer Viruses</b></h2>

<img src="/acnews/sick_mac.jpg" align=right hspace=10>
	Thousands of new computer viruses are discovered every year.  Worse 
yet, that virus that just ate your disk was created by somebody with 
nothing better to do than make your life miserable.  You might say 
viruses are a kind of computer vandalism; and, in most cases, it is 
impossible to track down the culprit.  Unfortunately viruses are fairly 
easy programs to write, so they will probably always be a fact of life for 
computers.  <p>
	Computer viruses got their name from the way they can copy themselves from program 
to program, just like a biological virus duplicates itself.  (Yes, in a sense they are contagious!) 
Basically, viruses change the code of other programs to include a small copy of itself.  When 
you run the infected program, the virus is activated and copies itself to even more programs.  
This keeps going on until the virus is triggered to do its dirty work, which can be anything 
from making the computer slower, to completely erasing your work, to putting something 
silly on the screen.<p>
	Don't think that because your disk doesn't have any programs on it you're safe.  You're 
not!  All disks have a small program contained in a hidden place called the boot sector; and it, 
too, is vulnerable to attack.<p>
	Luckily, avoiding problems caused by viruses is not complicated.  Basically you need to 
follow five rules:<p>
<ol>
<li>Most important:  keep a backup copy of all your work.  That alone will protect you from 
more then just viruses!
<li>Don't panic if a virus is detected on your disk.  More damage could result from a poorly 
thought-out cure then what the virus, itself, might have done.  Just keep in mind that most 
viruses don't do damage right away, but get help to remove it as soon as possible.
<li>Make sure that the computers you use are protected by anti-virus software.  Academic 
Computing Services keeps all of their computers protected, and makes that same software 
available to anyone who wants it.
<li>Write-protect any installation disks you have at home.  That makes it impossible for a 
virus to infect them.
<li>Be careful where you get your programs from.  It is always better to get commercial 
software, or at least get it directly from the author.
</ol>
	If you have any other questions about viruses, just turn your head and cough!  Or 
better yet, ask us!<p>

<h2><b>New Faces</b></h2>
	Two new lab assistants, <b>Lolita Nogan</b> and <b>Mike Florax</b>, have just been hired to 
replace Heidi Erikson and Lisa Polishan who have left Marywood College.<p>  
	<b>Lolita</b> is a full-time non-traditional student who is working towards her BFA degree.  She 
hopes to teach art in the public school system, and currently has five children within it.   
Lolita has joined our staff because she feels that working as a computer lab assistant gives her 
the experience to help and teach,when necessary, other students when they are in need.  <p>
	<b>Mike</b> is a native of the Netherlands, but has lived abroad since the age of sixteen.  His 
first international experience was when his family moved to Brazil, South America, where his 
father had taken a position for AKZO-NOBEL.  Mike attended high school in Sao Paulo, 
Brazil, and graduated in 1987, the same year he moved to the United States in order to attend 
La Salle University, Philadelphia.  Upon graduation Mike has worked in Brazil as well as the 
U.S. for AKZO-NOBEL.  His goal now is to finish his MBA in finance at Marywood and then 
move to Wilmington, Delaware, to get a position with an international corporation.<p>

<h2><b>Computer Problems?  Who to Call . . .</b></h2>
	It's 9 o'clock at night and you've been slaving at the computer for 
the last two hours trying to finish that paper due tomorrow.  You're 
ready to print and nothing happens!!  This little scenario could happen at home or here 
in one of our labs.  Help is just a phone call away.   <b>Jason Reed</b> and <b>Stacey Gay</b>, our two 
highly trained weekend and evening support specialists will lend a sympathetic ear and do 
their darndest to help solve the problem.  The help desk phone number is <b>348-6215, ext. 
6295</b>.  If they're away from the desk momentarily, a message with your name, phone number 
and description of the problem will give them a chance to provide you with a knowledgeable 
response.  They check messages frequently and will get back to you as soon as they can.<p>


