<head>
<!-- Thanks for looking at our Web page.
     Please let us know how we can improve our site. -->

<title>Marywood College</title>
</head>

<body background="/images/backgrnd.gif">
<img src="/images/mwlogos.jpg" align=left hspace=10>
<h1>Marywood College</h1><h2>Art</h2>
<h2><i>Chairperson: Matt Povse, M.F.A</i></h2>
<br clear=left><hr>


At Marywood,  you'll find artist-teachers 
who'll help you realize your creative potential, state-of-the-art facilities to mold your artistic concepts into reality and a professional foundation for a career in the exciting and competitive art world.<p>

For persons with creativity and skill, opportunities in today's art world abound, in such fields as commercial photography, graphic design for on-line computer services, residential interior design, 
ceramics, metalworking, painting, teaching art, curating collections, and managing museums.  Your professors at Marywood, as practicing artists, understand this world and will work closely with you to help you develop aesthetically and professionally.  They'll offer a foundation as well as help you learn to rely on 
your own vision.  You'll leave Marywood with a grounding in the liberal arts, a set of technical skills, a knowledge of artists past and present, field work and internship experience, a portfolio: in short, the background you need to approach a career in art, teaching, or administration or to pursue graduate study 
in art.<p>

You'll also leave Marywood with a realization of the value of art as a medium of communication.  The 
study and practice of art at Marywood are intended to lead you to heightened social awareness, spiritual insights, and a quest for "truth" in nature and humanity.  The goal of every Marywood student's education 
learning to live responsibly in an interdependent world is emphasized in the art program, where you'll be encouraged to develop responsibility, empathy, and professionalism to be reflected in your contributions to 
the quality of life of the wider community.<p>

<H3>Faculty</H3>

Faculty members in the Visual Arts Department are committed, caring, and creative.  They teach classes; 
advise on course selection, internship opportunities, and portfolio development; and instruct in the use of appropriate technology for various art and design areas.  In addition, they continue to develop their own 
aesthetic visions.  In the past three years, a dozen faculty have exhibited their work in national and international exhibitions; and faculty have been featured in <i>Artists Magazine</i>, <i>Art in America</i>, <i>Fiber Arts</i>, <i>Ceramic Monthly</i>, <i>Metalsmith</i>, <i>American Craft </i>and <i>Step by Step</i>.<p>

<b>Professor Hoffer </b>wrote and illustrated <i>Between Mirror and Past and Picasso at Vallauris</i> ; <b>Professor Olfano</b> did research on night photography in the desert and <b>Sister Ludwick</b> 
researched medieval style and iconography.  And <b>Sister Heffernan </b>was honored as national 
<b>Teacher of the Year in 1994-95 </b>by the Council for Advancement and Support of Education!<p>

<b>Matt Povse, M.F.A.,</b> Chair  (ceramics)<P>
<b>Steven Alexander, M.F.A. </b> (painting)<P>
<b>Lynn Berkowitz, M.F.A. </b> (fibers)<P>
<b>Ann Marie Castelgrande, M.A.</b>  (art education)<P>
<b>Stephen Colley, M.F.A.</b>  (foundation program)<P>
<b>Charles Consagra, B.A.,</b> B. Arch.  (interior design)<P>
<b>Dennis Corrigan, M.F.A.</b>  (illustration)<P>
<b>Jim Downer, M.S.,</b> M.A. candidate  (computer, 
foundation program)<P>
<b>Sister Ave Maria Foley, I.H.M., M.A.</b> (foundation program)<P>
<b>Robert Griffith, M.F.A.</b>  (sculpture)<P>
<b>Aimee Griffith-Colley, M.F.A.</b>  (foundation program)<P>
<b>Sister M. Cor Immaculatum Heffernan, I.H.M.,  M.A., M.S., M.F.A.</b>  (art education, design)<P>
<b>Lisa Hinkle-Marin, M.A.</b>  (photography)<P>
<b>Peter Hoffer, M.F.A. </b> (printmaking)<P>
<b>Anne Kearns, M.A.,</b> M.F.A. candidate (interior design, 
art education)<P>
<b>Sister Rosemary Ludwick, I.H.M., MA.,</b> Ph.D. candidate  (art history)<P>
<b>Eugene Ogozalek, M.B.A., A.I.A.</b>  (interior design)<P>
<b>Sam Olfano, M.F.A.</b>  (photography)<P>
<b>Pamela Parsons, M.F.A.</b>  (painting)<P>
<b>Linda Partridge, Ph.D.</b>  (art history)<p>
<b>Sandra Ward, M.F.A.</b>  (gallery director)<p>
<b>Maxine Watter, M.F.A, C.A.S. </b> (foundation program)<p>
<p>


<h3>Facilities and Technology</h3>

You'll find an amazing array of advanced technological support for art studies at Marywood.  Each area of 
emphasis is backed by state-of-the-art facilities; as you advance through the program, you'll have access to increasingly sophisticated equipment.  Computer resources include AutoCad software, word processing 
and spreadsheet applications, and technology for graphic design, photography, illustration, and interior design majors.  You'll also find weaving looms and blueprint machines; a photography studio with black 
and white and color darkrooms and an advanced lighting studio; a ceramic studio equipped for a wide variety of techniques; a foundry with state-of-the-art metalworking facilities; and sculpture and painting 
studios.<p>

In addition, all Marywood students benefit from two on campus art galleries: the Suraci Gallery for 
permanent collections and the Contemporary Gallery which features a variety of temporary exhibits including visiting artist and faculty/student shows.<p>

<h3>The Regional Advantage: Putting Knowledge to Work</h3>

Marywood's location offers aspiring artists, designers, teachers, and curators a wealth of opportunities.  Students can view exhibits both at museums in New York City and Philadelphia, and in the more local 
region at two museums, national historical sites, numerous arts organizations, and university and private galleries.<p>

As for internships, you'll find a wide variety of options.  Recently, students have done internships at Time-
Warner Inc.; Kemener Museums; Educational Center for Certification in National Kitchen and Baths; with magazines headquartered in New York City; and in local architecture firms and museums.<p>


<h3>The Degrees</h3>

<b>B.F.A. Design:  Bachelor of Fine Arts with an emphasis in</b><br>
<dd>	Graphic Design 
<dd>	Illustration 
<dd>	Interior Design
<dd>	Photography<p>
 
<b>B.F.A. Studio Arts:  Bachelor of Fine Arts with an emphasis in</b><br>
<dd>	Ceramics  
<dd>	Painting  
<dd>	Sculpture
 <p>

<b>Bachelor of Arts in</b><br>
<dd>	Art Education
<dd>	Art Administration
<p>

<h3>Requirements of the Program</h3>

All beginning Art students take the foundation program a core curriculum of studies in drawing, color, painting and two-and-three dimensional design in their freshman year.  After that you'll begin courses in your chosen program.  <p>
<ul>
<li><b>Bachelor of Fine Arts</b><p>
</ul>
<dd>All B.F.A. majors must fulfill at least 91 credit hours in art, including the foundation program, art history and criticism, and specific requirements pertinent to their area of interest.<p>
<ul>
<li><b>Bachelor of Arts in Art Education</b><p>
</ul>
<dd>Offered in conjunction with Marywood's Department of Education, this program requires at least 60 credit hours in art and leads to K-12 certification. <p>
<ul>

<li><b>Bachelor of Arts in Arts Administration</b><p>
</ul>
<dd>A total of 63 credit hours is required, of which 24 are in business, 24 in art, and 15 in a secondary concentration of either music or drama.<p>

In order to fulfill degree requirements (for programs other than arts administration), you'll be required to 
exhibit, as a senior, a portfolio of work indicating the range and highest quality of work you've achieved in studio production.  Most programs also require fieldwork or internship experience.  Some students take five years (ten semesters) to complete the program, others four years (eight semesters plus summer 
options).   You'll be glad to know that Marywood's program is accredited by the National Association for Schools of Art and Design.<p>


<h3>Sample Art Courses:</h3>

Creative Art for Children<br>
Sculpture<br>
Intaglio Printmaking<br>
Ceramics<br>
Fashion Book Illustration<br>
Packaging Design<Br>
History of American Illustration<br>
AutoCad for Interior Design<br>
Advanced Advertising Graphics<br>
Jewelry and Metal Design<br>
Photography as a Means of Self Expression<p>


<h3>Just the Facts</h3>

Student:faculty ratio: 14:1<br>
Average class size: 14<p>

<b>After Marywood:</b>  a significant number go directly into careers in art, business, teaching including recently the Smithsonian, Metropolitan Museum of Art, and Getty Museum, and Mancini and Duffy, Steelcase, Highland Associates, and Sie Matic Kitchens.  Others go on to graduate programs, 
including recently Louisiana State, Miami of Ohio, Notre Dame, Ohio State, Rochester Institute of Technology, and Syracuse University.<p>



<b>For more information,  please contact:</b><br>

Mr. Matt Povse, Chair<br>
Art Department<br>
Marywood College<br>
Scranton, PA  18509<br>
717/348-6278<br>
povse@ac.marywood.edu<br>
http://www.marywood.edu<br>


