<head>
<!-- Thanks for looking at our Web page.
     Please let us know how we can improve our site. -->

<title>Marywood College</title>
</head>

<body background="/images/backgrnd.gif">
<img src="/images/mwlogos.jpg" align=left hspace=10>
<h1>Marywood College</h1>
<h2>Business and 
Managerial Science</h2>
<h2><i>Chairperson: Samir Phillip Dagher, M.B.A., Ph.D</i></h2>

<A HREF="/www2/busweb/index.htm">Departmental Web Page</A>
<br clear=left>
<hr>



At Marywood, you'll find supportive faculty with practical as well as academic knowledge of business, a well-established internship program for on-the-job experience  and the foundation for a challenging career in the business world of tomorrow. <p>

Business leaders are increasingly called upon to develop flexible, creative strategies for success in a competitive global economy.  As a Marywood graduate, you'll be well 
prepared for managerial and administrative leadership through a broadly based business curriculum integrated with the liberal arts.  You'll choose a major in accounting, business 
administration (concentrating in financial planning, management, or marketing), computer information and telecommunication systems, hotel and restaurant management, 
international business, or retail business management.  Whichever you choose, you'll gain knowledge in the fundamentals of business as well as technical and communication skills.<p>

But Marywood doesn't just turn out students prepared for success as business analysts, 
bank officers, financial planners, computer programmers, hospitality managers, system 
analysts, stockbrokers, fashion retailers, accountants, administrators, insurance 
underwriters, and other business leaders.  The business faculty will also help you understand how to use your knowledge to meet human needs and how to work as an ethically and socially responsible professional.  A goal of your education  as it is for 
every Marywood student  will be to learn to live responsibly in an 
interdependent world.<p>

<h3>Faculty </h3>

You'll find a group of dedicated and knowledgeable faculty members, committed to helping you prepare 
for a rewarding career in the business world.  They have practical business experience in addition to their academic training, and know how to present the variety of business philosophies that predominate in the 
US and abroad.  Faculty members teach the business courses, supervise your field work experiences, advise you on course selection and internship opportunities, and still find time for their own research (you'll find their research interests listed below).  <p>

<b>Samir Phillip Dagher, M.B.A., Ph.D.,</b> Chair (corporate acquisition and divestment)<p>
<b>Uldarico Rex Dumdum, Jr., M.E., M.S., Ph.D.</b> (information systems technology)<p>
<b>Joseph J. Galante, M.B.A., M.S.,  J.D. </b>(accounting and taxation)<p>
<b>John Hawley, M.B.A., C.P.C.U., C.L.U., F.L.M.I.</b> (insurance and financial planning)<p>
<b>Gale A. Jaeger, M.B.A., Ph.D. Candidate</b>(retail management)<p>
<b>Raminder Luther, M.B.A., Ph.D. </b> (financial issues in corporate strategic planning)<p>
<b>Brian Lynch, M.B.A., Ph.D.</b>  (information systems technology)<p>
<b>George Marcinek, M.B.A., C.P.A.</b>  (accounting rules: implications on corporate reporting)<p>
<b>Joseph R. O'Brien, J.D.</b>  (legal responsibilities of corporate executives)<p>
<b>Frank Opshinsky, M.S.</b>  (computer networking)<p>
<b>Joan G. Smetana, M.S., Ed.D.</b>  (management accounting)<p>
<p>

<h3>Facilities and Technology</h3>


The business and managerial science program benefits from Marywood's commitment to provide all students with state-of-the-art technology.  You'll find computer facilities with the latest in word processing 
and spreadsheet software, as well as specialized business applications  and programming facilities for 
students majoring in computer information and telecommunications systems.  Like all Marywood students, you'll enjoy the privileges of the library, with holdings of more than 200,000 volumes; 1,100 
periodicals; and 40,000 nonprint items.  The library also participates in a national and international interlibrary loan network with 5,000 other libraries.<p>

<h3>The Regional Advantage: Putting Knowledge to Work</h3>

As a business student, you'll be strongly urged to take advantage of the opportunities offered by corporations participating in the department's internship program.  You'll have the chance for on-the-job 
training at a variety of firms in the Scranton-Wilkes-Barre region or elsewhere (in the New York City-Philadelphia corridor or even beyond), including such firms as Akzo Nobel Salt, NATWEST, Prudential 
Securities, Metropolitan Life Insurance, and Peat Marwick. You can participate in the internship program in your junior or senior year (accounting majors participate in spring of senior year only) if you meet the 
program's requirements.<p>

<h3>Requirements of the Program</h3>


Students studying business and managerial science at Marywood have a choice of six majors.  In addition to foundation business courses and a philosophy course in business ethics, an economics course, and a 
mathematics course there are specific requirements for each of the majors.  (The philosophy, economics, and math course credits count toward the 64 credits in core liberal arts and skills required of every 
Marywood student.)<p>

<b>Accounting </b>prepares graduates for careers in public, corporate, or government accounting, or for 
work in a consulting practice.   Students majoring in accounting are required to complete a minimum of 60 credits in business, of which 27 
are required accounting credits.<p>

<b>Business Administration</b> majors prepare for careers as administrators in a variety of organizations in the 
public and private sectors.  Students are required to take 60 credits in business, of which 12 are specified for all business administration majors.  Each student is required to choose a concentration in which a 
minimum of 18 credits are to be completed.  The concentrations are <b>Financial Planning</b> (which blends accounting, economics, and statistics knowledge with such courses as  investment planning, portfolio  
management, and money and banking); <b>Management</b> (preparing graduates for work in social agencies, business firms, and other organizations in the areas of personnel management and human relations); and 
<b>Marketing </b>(emphasizing preparation in quality and customer-focused marketing for businesses).<p>

<b>Computer Information and Telecommunications Systems</b> prepares students for the evaluation, programming, design and development of systems, within national and multinational organizations.  Students are required to take 60 credits in business, of which 27 are specific to the major.<p>

<b>Hotel and Restaurant Management</b> prepares students for management careers in such service sector areas as lodging, food service, tourism, recreation industries, hospitals, 
and schools.  Students are required to take 68 credits in nutrition and dietetics and business.<p>

<b>International Business</b> prepares students in the areas of global marketing and international finance, and management of international operations.  Students are required to complete 45 credits in business and 21 credits in a foreign language; they are also urged to spend a semester abroad.<p>

<b>Retail Business Management</b> offers students interested in careers in the diversified retailing and fashion fields a four-year program with great career opportunities.   Students are prepared for positions at the  creative and executive levels in the retail and fashion industries.  In addition to 54 required credits in business, students participate in supervised fieldwork experience equivalent to six credits.<p>

<b>For more information, please contact:</b><br>

Dr. Samir Phillip Dagher, Chair<br>
Business and Managerial Science Department<br>
Marywood College<br>
Scranton, PA 18509<br>
717/ 348-6274<br>
dagher@ac.marywood.edu<br>
http://www.marywood.edu<br>



