<title>Marywood College</title>
</head>

<body background="/images/backgrnd.gif">
<img src="/images/mwlogos.jpg" align=left hspace=10>
<h1>Marywood College</h1>
<h2>Communication Arts</h2>

<h2><i> Chairperson: Michael M. Mirabito, Ph.D.</i></h2>
<br clear=left><hr>


At Marywood, you'll find a program that 
ranges from telecommunications to theater 
arts, opportunities to gain experience in up-to-date facilities beginning your freshman year  and faculty committed to preparing you for a creative career in the twenty-first century's "hot" field of communication.<p>

Opportunities for creative people abound in the rapidly exploding field of communications:  in video production, advertising, playwriting, desktop publishing, acting, media reporting, teaching, and 
administration.  You'll find that Marywood's broadly based program, which provides professional study and experience integrated with the liberal arts, is an excellent preparation for a challenging career.  You'll 
be able to choose from the following options:  advertising and public relations; telecommunications (specializing in broadcast or corporate communications); theater arts; performing arts; secondary school 
teacher certification; and arts administration.  Or, if you see a career opportunity in communications that goes beyond these established programs, you may choose to put together an ad hoc major with guidance 
from your adviser.<p>

You'll have the chance to use your skills and 
interests right away.  Unlike other programs, Marywood's emphasizes access for first-year students to the 
labs, television production facilities, radio station, theaters and student newspaper.  You'll start using this knowledge on and off campus beginning in your freshman year in a series of practica (mini-internships) 
in the area, with the option of longer-term, for-credit internships beyond those.<p>

In the communication arts program, you'll be encouraged to develop independent and creative thinking skills, as well as concern for the society and environment; you'll graduate prepared to serve that 
interdependent world through enhanced communication.<p>

<h3>Faculty</h3>

You'll have ready access to the communication arts faculty  and you'll find they're dedicated to helping 
you put together the knowledge and skills you'll need for a successful career in the communications field.  Faculty members teach the courses; instruct you in the use of the program's specialized technical facilities; 
advise you on course selection and on opportunities for practicum and internship placement; and still find time for their own creative work.  For example, Professor Berkery produces videos; Professor Hammeran  writes plays and screenplays; Professor Merchel directs department plays; and Professor Mirabito has 
written <i>Space Exploration </i>and <i>The New Communication Technologies.</i><p>

<b>Michael M. Mirabito, Ph.D.,</b> Chair (new communication technologies; space exploration) <p>
<b>Julia Berkery, M.S.,</b> Director, Program in Telecommunications  (media and mass culture)<p>
<b>Jay Hammeran, M.P.W., </b>Director, Program in Advertising and Public Relations  (communications history and effect on society)<p>
<b>Paulette A. Merchel, Ph.D.,</b>  Director, Program in Theater (period plays and television in education)<p>

<b>Adjunct Faculty</b><br>
Kathy Buzad, M.S. <br>
Joseph F. Caputo, M.A.<br>
Larry Newman, M.A. <br>
Barbara Spellman-Shuta, M.A. <br>
Joan O'Brien Volz, M.B.A. <br>
Sister Patt Walsh, M.A.  <br>
Carol A. Weiss, M.S.  <br>
Tony Nicosia, Jr.<br>
<br>

<h3>Facilities and Technology</h3>

The communication arts program benefits from Marywood's commitment to provide all students with up to date technology.  You'll find that communication-specific resources are available to you from the 
beginning.  These resources include<A HREF="/www2/commarts/vmfm.html"> WVMW-FM</A>, an on-air radio station managed and staffed by students 
and operating year-round; <A HREF="/www2/commarts/tvm.html">TV Marywood (TVM-37)</A>, a modern color television facility with 
complementary electronic field, graphics, and post-production operations; Marywood Theater, a 1,100-seat professionally-equipped auditorium with modern lighting and audio  systems; the Black Box Theater,  
a laboratory theater designed with flexible staging; and <i>The Wood Word</i>, the student newspaper.  You'll 
also find computer laboratories with the latest software for word processing, desktop publishing, computer 
graphics, scriptwriting, set and lighting design for TV and theater, and multimedia production; you'll also have access to the Internet.<p>

<h3>The Regional Advantage: Putting Knowledge to Work</h3>

If you'd like to test the knowledge and technical skills you learn at Marywood in a real world setting, you'll find plenty of opportunities in the Scranton/Wilkes-Barre region.  Students can participate in for-credit internships at local radio and television stations, newspapers, advertising and public relations firms, nonprofit organizations, theaters and fine arts centers.<p>

<h3>Requirements of the Program</h3>

All communication arts students are required to take 12 credits in core courses, which include six practica (mini-internships) taken in the freshman through senior years.  You'll also need to meet the College 
requirement for all students to take Dynamics of Speech Communication (or be exempted by satisfactory achievement in a place-out test); and you'll need to complete 64 credits in the College's liberal arts and skills core curriculum.  Each major in the department has its own course requirements.<p>

<b>Advertising and Public Relations</b> requires 48 credits; <b>Telecommunications: Broadcast and 
Corporate Communication</b> offers two tracks, <b>Broadcast Communication</b> and <b>Corporate Communication</b>; you select and complete 48 credits in one track.  <b>Theater Arts</b> requires 42 credits, and <b>Performing Arts</b> requires 30.  For Secondary School Teacher Certification in 
communication arts, you'll be required to complete a professional educational sequence,          15 credits of basic communications requirements, and an additional 15 core credits in either the theater arts specialization or the nonprint media specialization.  Students seeking a degree in <b>Arts Administration 
</b>take 24 credits in either corporate 
communication or theater arts as their primary concentration, 15 credits in their secondary concentration 
(art or music), and 24 credits in business.  Finally, if none of the existing programs meets your needs, you 
may have the opportunity to design a <b>special ad hoc program</b> in communication arts.<p>

<h3>Sample Communication Arts Courses</h3>

Video Production I and II<br>
Advertising Principles<br>
Computer Graphics<br>
Media Performance<br>
New Communication Technologies<br>
Print Newswriting<br>
Public Relations Principles<br>
Stage Directing<br>
Theater Production<br>
Acting<Br>
Writing for Corporate Communication<br>
<br>
<p>

<h3>Just the Facts</h3>

Student-faculty ratio: 12:1<br>
Average class size: 12 students<br>
Degree offered: B.A. in Advertising and Public Relations; Telecommunications; Theater Arts; Performing Arts; or Arts Administration.<p>

<b>After Marywood:</b> most graduates go into careers (including recently as video production personnel at WYOU and ESPN; actors; stage management; radio disc jockeys; vice presidents of 
marketing and public relations; and college professors).  Some go on to graduate work, including recently to SUNY Stonybrook and Sarah Lawrence (in theater) and Ithaca College (in corporate communications).<p>

<b>For more information, please contact:</b>

Dr. Michael Mirabito, Chair<br>
Department of Communication Arts<br>
Marywood College<br>
Scranton, PA  18509<br>
717/348-6209<br>
mirabito@ac.marywood.edu<br>
http://www.marywood.edu<br>


