<head>
<!-- Thanks for looking at our Web page.
     Please let us know how we can improve our site. -->

<title>Marywood College</title>
</head>

<body background="/images/backgrnd.gif">
<img src="/images/mwlogos.jpg" align=left hspace=10>
<h1>Marywood College</h1><h2>Communication 
Sciences and Disorders</h2>
<h2><i>Chairperson: Janet D. Bissett</i></h2>
<br clear=left><hr>

At Marywood, you'll find supportive 
professors dedicated to helping you understand the importance of communication and use that knowledge to help others, a variety of practical experiences in the field and preparation for a rewarding career in a wide range of human services.<p>


If you're interested in a career in audiology, deaf studies, or speech-language pathology, Marywood can provide you with an excellent foundation.  The communication sciences and disorders department 
maintains an active membership in the National Academy of Preprofessional Programs in Communication Sciences and Disorders, and the program's objectives are compatible with standards of the American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, so you're assured of having the strongest set of educational experiences possible.<p>

Your coursework will include theory and practice in the field as well as a background in the liberal arts.  
Your experiences will help you learn to think creatively, develop a sense of social and personal 
responsibility, understand human cultural diversity (including language and value systems), develop confidence, and develop an understanding of human values.  As you may know, the goal of every Marywood student's education is to learn to live responsibly in an interdependent world.  What better way 
to put that goal into practice than to help others develop fully although they may have communicative differences?<p>


<h3>The Faculty</h3>


You'll find that the faculty in the department of communication sciences and disorders are dedicated professionals who will work closely with you to develop the knowledge and skills you'll need to be a strong candidate for graduate school and a professional on the field.  Faculty members teach the courses, 

instruct you in the use of the program's specialized technical facilities, advise you on course selection and opportunities for observation and clinical practice, and still find time for their own research and service to the profession.  Indeed, Dr. Feudo serves as president of the National Academy of Preprofessional 
Programs in Communication Sciences and Disorders.<p>

<b>Janet D. Bissett, Ph.D.,</b> Chair  (licensed in Speech-Language Pathology)<p>
<b>Peter Feudo, Jr., Sc.D.</b>  (licensed in Audiology and Speech-Language Pathology)<p>
<b>Carl Frels, M.Ed.</b>  (certified teacher; fluent in ASL)<p>
<b>Elizabeth Kilker, M.S.</b>  (licensed in Speech-Language Pathology)<p>
<b>Margaret Q. Mariotti, M.A.</b>  (licensed in Audiology)<p>
<b>Sheri Skrutski, M.S.</b>  (licensed in Audiology)<p>
<p>

<h3>Facilities and Technology</h3>

The communication sciences and disorders program benefits from Marywood's commitment to provide all 
students with state-of-the-art technology.  You'll find computer facilities with the latest in word processing and statistical software in the Learning Resources Center.  Technological support specific to the communication sciences and disorders program includes equipment illustrating anatomy and 
physiology and simulating human performance, as well as for analyzing speech, language, and hearing.  Perhaps of greatest interest to you is that Marywood's Human Services Center, where the program is housed, is home to the Marywood Speech and Hearing Clinic.  Here you'll have the chance to work with 
individuals with speech, language, and hearing needs.  The clinic is equipped with video monitors and a complete audiological evaluation facility.<p>


<h3>The Regional Advantage</h3>

You'll find plenty of opportunities to relate your studies at Marywood to real world situations.  To 
complete your required hours of observation, you may choose such local institutions as Scranton State School for the Deaf, St. Joseph's Center and area public schools.  Since Marywood offers the only 
communication sciences and disorders program in the area, you'll also have the chance to put your skills 
to good use as a volunteer at these and 
other locations.<p>


<h3>Requirements of the Program</h3>

Students must successfully complete approximately 45 credits in communication sciences and disorders. 
With the guidance of their faculty advisor, they may also identify other courses that complement their individual program of study.  In addition to the academic course requirements, you'll need to complete observation and supervised clinical practicum or other field experience.  Like all other Marywood
 students, you'll need to complete 64 credits in the College's liberal arts and skill core curriculum.<p>


<h3>Sample Communication Sciences and Disorders Courses</h3>

Speech and Hearing Science<br>
Deaf Studies<br>
Speech and Language Development<br>
Audiology<br>
Computer Competencies<br>
People with Disabilities<br>
Articulation and Phonologic Disorders<br>
American Sign Language<br>
Counseling People with Communication Differences<br>
Anatomy and Physiology of Speech and Hearing<br>
<p>

<h3>Just the Facts</h3>

Student: faculty ratio: 40:1<br>
Average class size: 20<br>
Degree offered: B.S. in Communication Sciences and Disorders<p>

<b>After Marywood:</b> approximately 33% go on to graduate study, including recently audiology (Northern Illinois, Pittsburgh, Syracuse, Vanderbilt); Deaf studies (Bloomsburg); and speech-language pathology 
(Edinboro, Loyola, Montclair, St. Rose).  Other graduates go to graduate school in other disciplines, or are employed in direct care positions in residential or community settings in support of people with disabilities (some of these students apply to graduate programs after two or more years of such 
employment).   <p>


<b>For more information, please contact:</b><br>

Dr. Janet Bissett, Chair<br>
Department of Communication Sciences and Disorders<br>
Marywood College<br>
Scranton, PA 18509<br>
717/348-6299<br>
bissett@ac.marywood.edu<br>
http://www.marywood.edu<br>

