<title>Marywood College</title>
</head>

<body background="/images/backgrnd.gif">
<img src="/images/mwlogos.jpg" align=left hspace=10>
<h1>Marywood College</h1>
<h2> English </h2>
<h2><i>Chairperson: Philip J. Tama, D.Ed.</i></h2>
<br clear=left><hr>


At Marywood, you'll find a comprehensive 
curriculum in English and world literature, 
a dedicated and engaging faculty and a background in critical thinking and writing that will serve you well whatever your goals.<p>

Some people wonder what you can do with an English major; but we take a different approach:  What can't you do with an English major?  At Marywood, you'll develop your abilities to think, to write, to 
communicate: skills that you can call on everywhere from the classroom to the office to the information superhighway.  You'll be required to think critically and analyze what you read for quality, merit, and reason.<p>

But Marywood's program goes well beyond these marketable skills.  You'll find a faculty committed to helping you learn to appreciate literature for its inherent beauty and power and for its relevance to contemporary life.  The background you'll gain in English and other world literatures and the histories 
and cultures behind them will help prepare you to realize the goal of every Marywood student's education: you'll be learning to live responsibly in an interdependent world.<p>



<h3>Faculty</h3>


You'll find the faculty in Marywood's English department to be dedicated teachers and scholars.  Faculty members teach the courses, advise on course selection, collaborate on student research projects, and still find time to pursue their own creative and academic interests.   You'll find their research interests 
listed above.<p>

<b>Philip J. Tama, D.Ed.</b>, Chair  (American short fiction)<p>
<b>Ken Boecker, M.B.A.</b>  (Computer applications)<p>
<b>Deborah E. Brassard, Ph.D.</b>  (Modern British literature, modern American literature)<p>
<b>Joseph F. Caputo, M.A.</b>  (Theatre)<p>
<b>William P. Conlogue, Ph.D.</b>  (19th and 20th century American literature)<p>
<b>Haydn Gilmore, M.A.</b>  (William Faulkner, Dylan Thomas)<p>
<b>Lloyd Hildebrand, M.S.</b>  (Prayer, Children's literature)<p>
<b>Barbara A. Hoffman, Ph.D. candidate</b>  (Writing poetry, Japanese tea ceremony)<p>
<b>Elaine Lisandrelli, M.A.</b>  (English methods)<p>
<b>Sister Christine Mihelich, I.H.M., Ph.D.</b>  (Eugene O'Neill)<p>
<b>Sister M. Immaculata Norton, I.H.M., M.A., M.S.</b>  (Shakespeare)<p>
<b>Annette Sloan, M.F.A.</b>  (American poetry, 1950-present)<p>
<b>Frank Sottile, M.A., D.Ed. candidate </b> (Computer-assisted writing)<p>
<b>Ronald L. Terranella, Ph.D.</b>  (Films, film directors)<p>
<b>Margaret A. Yarina, Ph.D.</b>  (Gothic literature)<p>
<br>

<h3>Facilities and Technology  </h3>

The English program benefits from Marywood's commitment to provide all students with state-of-the-art 
technology.  You'll find computer facilities with the latest word processing and statistical software in the Learning Resources Center (LRC); these labs are available to all regularly enrolled undergraduates.  The 
library, also located in the LRC, has holdings of more than 200,000 volumes; 1,100 periodicals and 
40,000 nonprint items.  The library also participates in a national and international interlibrary loan network with 5,000 other libraries.<p>


<h3>The Regional Advantage: Putting Knowledge to Work</h3>

You'll find a variety of opportunities in the Scranton-Wilkes Barre region to put theory into practice, and 
to learn from those who do.  Students preparing for teacher certification gain field experience and teaching experience in the local school systems.  All English majors benefit from the opportunity to learn 
from the many gifted poets, authors, playwrights, and other artists who visit the campus to give lectures 
and conduct seminars.  Recent speakers were Maya Angelou, Jay MacLeod and M. Scott Peck.<p>


<h3>Requirements of the Program</h3>

All Marywood students are required to take four English courses:  Writing Skills, The Classics in World Literature, The Modern Age in World Literature and an advanced course for which these three are required prerequisites.<p>

English majors must complete a minimum of 42 credits in English.  In addition to the three specific courses listed above, majors take Shakespeare; one course in each of these areas: Genre, American Period, British Period, and Major Writers; two courses in Theme; and four electives.  English majors pursuing 
secondary teaching certification must complete 36 credit hours in English (as well as required Education courses).  In addition to the three English courses specified for all Marywood students, secondary 
certification students take Shakespeare; Structure of Linguistics; English Methods; one course from each of the following areas: Genre, Theme, American Period, British Period, and Major Writers; and one 
course in Communication Arts chosen in consultation with the English department chair.<p>

Students seeking elementary education certification in English major in elementary Education and complete 18 credit hours in English.  Students choosing to minor in English must complete a minimum of 
18 credit hours in English.<p>


<h3>Just the Facts</h3>

Student:faculty ratio:  8:1<br>
Average class size: 20 in writing skills; 25 in literature<br>
Degree offered: B.A. in English Literature<p>

<b>After Marywood:</b>  Approximately 70% go directly into careers in such fields as secondary teaching, editing, retail administration, and publishing.  Approximately 30% go on to graduate study, including recently at Columbia, Dickinson, New York University, and the University of Pennsylvania. <p>


<b>For more information, please contact:</b><br>

Dr. Philip J. Tama, Chair<br>
English Department<br>
Marywood College<br>
Scranton, PA 18509<br>
717/348-6219<br>
tama@ac.marywood.edu<br>
http://www.marywood.edu<br>


