<title>Marywood College</title>
</head>

<body background="/images/backgrnd.gif">
<img src="/images/mwlogos.jpg" align=left hspace=10>
<h1>Marywood College</h1>
<h2>Foreign Languages</h2>
<h2><i>Chairperson: Mary Elizabeth Kenny, Ph.D.</i></h2>
<br clear=left><hr>



At Marywood, you'll find a diverse and accessible faculty, a comprehensive and practical curriculum reflecting the latest 
in foreign language teaching  and the chance to polish your skills in study abroad.<p>

As you are probably well aware, the world has been "shrinking" as a result of technological advances and the pace of this change is likely to increase as we move into the twenty-first century.  Study in French and Spanish at Marywood will help prepare you for the rewards and challenges of living in this increasingly 
interdependent world, by developing both your ability to communicate in another language and your awareness of historical and contemporary culture in countries where these languages are spoken.<p>

You'll have a choice of options:  majoring in French or Spanish; doing a double major in French and Spanish; majoring in either language as a path to certification to teach; or majoring in International 
Business, a joint program between Marywood's foreign language and business departments.  Whichever you choose, you'll be encouraged to pursue some of your studies abroad: in France or at Canada's Laval University for French; in a Spanish or Latin American university for Spanish.<p>


Language study opens doors.  Your work at Marywood (which may also include elementary and intermediate study in German) can prepare you to enter and advance in a wide variety of fields such as 
education, international business, banking, government service, international relations, public relations, telecommunications, journalism, health services, and social welfare.  You'll be well on your way to 
achieving the goal of every Marywood student's education: learning to live responsibly in an interdependent world.<p>

<h3>Faculty</h3>

The foreign language faculty is highly qualified, culturally diverse, and dedicated to the field and their students.  You'll have the chance to learn from them in small classes and will find them accessible when 
you want to discuss your individual goals.  Faculty teach the classes, advise on course selection, share knowledge of study abroad opportunities, and still find time to pursue their own research.  They have recently presented papers at regional,  national, and international conferences on topics as varied as 
"Women under Franco: from Dictatorship to Democracy," and "Migrations and Immigrations: Who are We?"  A French professor and two students who participated in the research presented a paper on the use of French theater and storytelling in the classroom.  Another professor  collaborated on the Anthology of Hispanic Women, published in 1994.  You'll find each professor's research interest listed below you'll find their enthusiasm contagious!<p>


<b>Mary Elizabeth Kenny, Ph.D.</b>, Chair  (use of video in the language classroom)<p>
<b>Claudine Chartrand-Wright, Ph.D.</b>  (theater and storytelling in the French classroom)<p>
<b>Teresa Morrison, M.A.</b>  (pedagogy)<p>
<b>Alice Reyes, M.A.</b>  (pedagogy)<p>
<b>Jose E. Reyes, Ph.D.</b>  (Middle Ages; Catalan literature)<p>
<b>Victoria Jaen-Andres, Ph.D.</b>  (Hispanic women in film)<p>
<p>

<h3>Facilities and Technology</h3>

The foreign languages program benefits from Marywood's commitment to provide all students with state-
of-the-art technology.  You'll find computer facilities in the Learning Resources Center (LRC) with the latest in word processing and statistical software, as well as access to the Internet.  Laser disc and 
interactive video programs are also available.   The library, also located in the LRC, has holdings of more than 200,000 volumes; 1,100 periodicals; and 40,000 nonprint items.  The library also participates in a 
national and international interlibrary loan with 5,000 other libraries.<p>

<h3>The Regional Advantage: Putting Knowledge to Work</h3>

You'll find plenty of opportunities to increase your knowledge and put theory into practice in the Scranton-Wilkes Barre region.  If you study Spanish, for example, you'll be encouraged to work within 
the local Hispanic community, in ESL classes or as part of the College's program for migrants.  There's also an active French-speaking community in the area; they welcome students to practice conversational 
skills and join them in the celebration of holidays. If you're preparing to teach, you'll have the opportunity 
to begin getting field experience in your freshman year.  Students with an interest in international business can pursue internships at local banks and businesses or in multinational companies 
headquartered in this region.  And, of course, you'll have the chance to go well beyond the local region if you choose to study abroad!<p>

<h3>Rquirements of the Program</h3>

<b>B.A. in French; B.A. in Spanish</b><br>
For those students majoring in French or Spanish (but not seeking teacher certification), 33 credits in French language courses or 33 credits in Spanish language courses are required.  Students concentrating in one foreign language are encouraged to begin the study of a second foreign language.  A double major in French and Spanish may be pursued by taking 24 credits (beyond introductory level) in the second language.<p>

For students seeking K-12 educational certification in either language, 30 foreign language department 
credits (including the three-credit course "Structure of English") are required.  Such students must also take the professional component of courses from the education and special education departments.  Students seeking certification in a second language, or Elementary Education majors who wish to 
concentrate in French or Spanish, must complete credits in the language, exclusive of introductory coursework. Some of the required credits in these programs will count toward the 64 credits in core liberal 
arts and skills required of every Marywood student.<p>

<b>B.A. in International Business</b><br>
Students majoring in international business are required to take 21 credits in French or Spanish and 
45 credits as outlined by Business and Managerial Sciences Department.  Students are ordinarily expected to spend at least a semester studying abroad.  As above, some of these credits will count toward the 64 credits in core liberal arts and skills required of every Marywood student.<p>

<b>Minor in French or Spanish</b><br>
An 18-credit minor (exclusive of introductory level coursework) is available in French or Spanish.  This popular option works especially well with majors in business, health sciences, or social service fields.<p>

<h3>Just the Facts</h3>

Average class size: 15<br>

<b>Degrees offered:</b> B.A. in French; B.A. in Spanish; B.A. in International Business<p>

<b>After Marywood:</b>  the majority of graduates go directly into careers, including recently as a professional observer for the U.N.; a Peace Corps volunteer; a sales vice president for a multinational firm; an account executive for a Fortune 500 company; and many teachers.  Others go on for further study, including recently at: American University, Boston College, George Washington, Northwestern, Notre Dame and the University 
of Madrid.<p>


<b>For more information, please contact:</b><br>
Dr. Mary Elizabeth Kenny, Chair<br>
Department of Foreign Languages<br>
Marywood College<br>
Scranton, PA  18509<br>
717/348-6286<br>
kenny@ac.marywood.edu<br>
http://www.marywood.edu<br>


