<title>Marywood College</title>
</head>

<body background="/images/backgrnd.gif">
<img src="/images/mwlogos.jpg" align=left hspace=10>
<h1>Marywood College</h1>
<h2>Health and Physical Education</h2>
<h2><i> Chairperson: Jane Farr, Ph.D.</i></h2>
<br clear=left><hr>

At Marywood,  you'll find new ways to main-
tain a healthy lifestyle, a faculty committed to helping you develop your athletic skills and knowledge  and options to prepare you for an active and rewarding career.<p>

Whether you're interested in a career built on a background in health and physical education  and there are many, from sports medicine/athletic training, to teaching and recreation management  or simply want 
to put into practice the old adage, "sound mind, sound body," you'll find what you need in Marywood's Health and Physical Education program.   All students are required to take two credits in the department, and many elect to take additional courses or participate in sports for fun and challenge.  <p>

If you decide to major in the department, you'll have 
a choice of three programs: sports medicine/athletic training, teacher certification or physical activity specialization.  Whatever you choose, you'll develop an awareness of the relationship of health to all life 
experiences and activities;  become aware of the cognitive, affective and psychomotor aspects of fitness; acquire skills to be reasonably safe in or on or about the water; and learn to create experiences which will promote health and physical development.<p>


<h3>Faculty</h3>

You'll find the faculty in the Health and Physical Education department are committed to helping students make the most of their Marywood education and prepare for rewarding careers.  Faculty teach the courses, advise oncourse selection, help students develop their career plans, and still find time to keep up with advances in the field. <p>

<b>Jane Farr, Ph.D.</b>, Chair  (pedagogy, administration, wellness) <p>
<b>Michael Pringle, M.S., A.T.C.</b>  (sports medicine) <p>
<b>Regina Tomassoni, B.S.</b>  (dance) <p>
<b>Lisa Walsh, M.S.</b>  (exercise prescription) <p>


<h3>Facilities and Technology</h3>

Students at Marywood, whether they are majoring in health and physical education or simply want to participate in sports for personal challenge, have access to a wide array of athletic facilities.  You'll find a 
gym, aerobics room, racquetball courts, a weight room, pool, six tennis courts and playing fields.   In addition to the facilities for sports participation, you'll find a well-equipped training room which allows 
students in the sports medicine program to gain experience in the use of whirlpool, ultrasound, electric stimulation, knee rehabilitation machine and hydroculator.  <p>


<h3>The Regional Advantage: Putting Knowledge to Work</h3>

You'll find a wealth of opportunities to put theory into practice in the Scranton/Wilkes-Barre region.  Students in the physical activity program enjoy a variety of settings for their practica: the YMCA, Red 
Barons Triple A baseball, local resorts, wellness centers, fitness centers and university athletic departments.  Sports medicine students do internships on campus as well as at local colleges, junior 
colleges, and high schools.  In addition, those students preparing for teacher certification will find plenty of opportunities for formal field experience and student teaching in the local school systems.<p>


<h3>Requirements of the Program</h3>

All Marywood students are required to earn two credits in physical education, one in aquatics and one in the basic physical education area (where courses include such sports as aerobic dance, body toning,  bowling, field hockey, karate, racquetball, tennis and volleyball). <p>

<h3>The Major</h3>

Students enter the major in Health and Physical Education in their freshman year, selecting one of these options:<p>
<ul>
<li>
<b>The Sports Medicine/Athletic Training Internship Program</b> gives students the opportunity to become knowledgeable in athletic training and is designed to prepare students in theoretical and applicable knowledge necessary for the National Athletic Training Association (N.A.T.A.) certification examination.

<li><b>The Education Certification Program</b> prepares students to teach in an educational setting and, upon completion, leads to a state teaching certification for grades K-12 in Health and Physical Education.  

<li><b>The Physical Activity Specialization Program</b> is designed for students interested in positions in settings such as health clubs, YMCAs and YWCAs, recreation centers, fitness clubs and wellness centers.
</ul>

All majors take 35 credits in required physical education courses and a minimum of six elective credits.  In addition, each of the three options has its own additional requirements, from the Health and Physical Education department and/or other departments (such as Education and Psychology).<p>

To encourage professionalism and develop the student's abilities to perform in working situations, the department requires each student to earn four non-academic credits by taking a leadership or participatory role in an extracurricular teaching or athletic situation.<p>


<h3>Minors</h3>

Two minors are available to interested students: a 23-credit minor in Health and Physical Education and a 28-credit Coaching minor.<p>


<h3>Just the Facts</h3>

Student: faculty ratio: 20:1<br>
Average class size:  18<br>
Degree offered: Bachelor of Science in Health and Physical Education.<br>
<br>
<b>After Marywood:</b> Approximately 85% go directly into careers as teachers, fitness instructors, recreation coordinators and athletic trainers. Approximately 5% go on to graduate schools including recently at Miami University of Ohio. <p>


<b>For more information, please contact:</b><br>

Dr. Jane Farr, Chair<br>
Department of Health and Physical Education<br>
Marywood College<br>
Scranton, PA  18509<br>
717/348-6259<br>
farr@ac.marywood.edu<br>
http://www.marywood.edu<br>


