<title>Marywood College</title>
</head>

<body background="/images/backgrnd.gif">
<img src="/images/mwlogos.jpg" align=left hspace=10>
<h1>Marywood College</h1>
<h2>Mathematical Sciences</h2>
<h2><i>Chairperson: Marie K. Loftus, Ed.D.</i></h2>
<br clear=left><hr>



At Marywood, you'll find an inspiring 
environment for the study of mathematics: 
small classes, close relationships with faculty and other students, opportunities  for independent research  and the latest in computer facilities and software.<p>

Decision-making in the twenty-first century will increasingly rely on quantitative methods.  The background you'll gain at Marywood will help you prepare for that future.   You'll learn to apply mathematics in evaluating contemporary issues, to understand and use logic, to use calculations 
appropriately and correctly in problem-solving, and to use the computer as a tool in mathematics.  The analytical skills, computer competence, and habit of independent thinking you'll develop at Marywood will serve you well in any number of possible careers, from business to research to teaching.<p>

The department offers several degree options.  You may major in mathematics; major in mathematics while taking the other preparation needed for secondary teaching certification; major in mathematics and 
minor in computer science; or major in another field  such as elementary education  and minor in mathematics.  Whichever option you choose, you'll be approaching the goal of every Marywood student's 
education: learning to live responsibly in an 
interdependent world.<p>



<h3>Faculty</h3>


You'll have ready access to the faculty in mathematics, and you'll find that they're dedicated to helping you put together a program to meet your needs.  Faculty members teach the courses, give advice on course selection, collaborate on student research projects, and still find time to be active and involved in the field.  
They publish papers in national journals; pursue research in applied mathematics in cardiology, nutrition, and oncology; hold offices in the Pennsylvania Council of Teachers of Mathematics; and give 
presentations at meetings of the National Council of Teachers of Mathematics, the Mathematical Association of America, and the Pennsylvania Council of Teachers of Mathematics.<p>

<b>Marie K. Loftus, Ed.D.</b>, Chair  (applied statistics)<p>
<b>Robert C. Blatz, B.A.E., B.M.E., M.S., P.E.  </b>(math modeling)<p>
<b>Craig Johnson, Ph.D. </b> (topology)<p>
<b>Sister Robert Ann von Ahnen, I.H.M., M.S., M.S.</b>  (history of mathematics)<p>
<p>

<h3>Facilities and Technology</h3>

The mathematical sciences program benefits from Marywood's commitment to provide all students with state-of-the-art technology.  You'll find computer facilities with the latest in word processing, spreadsheet, 
and statistical software  in DOS and Macintosh formats  and access to the Internet.  You'll also find software specifically designed for mathematics and computer science students, such as Mathematica, 
Maple, Analyzer, Statview, 
and SPSSX.<p>



<h3>Student Accomplishments and Opportunities </h3>


Marywood mathematics students have the opportunity to conduct independent research in collaboration with faculty members.  Recent student research projects have focused on fractals and their use, and on 
improving quality control in the inspection process of cosmetic containers.  Students also have the opportunity to apply for a grant, awarded and administered by the department, to work with the food, drug, and cosmetic industries in the area of quality control.<p>



<h3>Requirements of the Program</h3>

Mathematics majors take 27 credits in required math courses, three mathematics electives, and eight credits in physics.  Students seeking a B.S. in mathematics with secondary certification take 38 required credits in mathematics, four in physics, and 15 in a combination of education, special education, and psychology, and the student teaching component.  (Students must also fulfill the 64-credit College 
requirement in the liberal arts and skills core curriculum, which will be partially fulfilled by major required courses.)  Students majoring in math may minor in computer science by taking six courses in computer-related areas offered by the math and business departments.  Students majoring in elementary education often choose to minor in mathematics by taking 18 credits in math.  Other students wishing to 
minor in mathematics must complete six courses chosen in consultation with the department chair.<p>


<h3>Sample Mathematics Courses</h3>

Mathematical Models and Computer Techniques<br>
Abstract Algebra	<br>
Theory of Numbers<br>
Geometry<br>
History of Mathematics<br>
Topology<br>
Calculus with Analytic Geometry<br>
Mathematics in Western Culture<br>

<p>

<h3>Just the Facts</h3>

Student: faculty ratio: 10:1<br>
Average class size: 10<br>
Degree offered: B.S. in Mathematics<p>

<b>After Marywood:</b> approximately 80% go directly into careers in a variety of businesses and organizations, including recently AT&T, Bell Labs, the Department of Agriculture, Eastman Kodak, 
Metropolitan Life insurance, Procter and Gamble, The Scranton Times-Tribune, and the University of Alaska.  Approximately 20% go on to further study; recent graduates have attended Boston University, Fairleigh Dickinson, Lehigh, 
New York Institute of Technology and the University of Delaware.<p>






<b>For more information, please contact:</b><br>

Dr. Marie Loftus, Chair<br>
Department of Mathematical Science<br>
Marywood College<br>
Scranton, PA  18509<br>
717/348-6292<br>
loftus@ac.marywood.edu<br>
http://www.marywood.edu<br>


