<title>Marywood College</title>
</head>

<body background="/images/backgrnd.gif">
<img src="/images/mwlogos.jpg" align=left hspace=10>
<h1>Marywood College</h1>
<h2>Math Department</h2>
<br clear=left><hr>

<h1>Mathematics + Marywood = EXCITEMENT</h1>

<i>The programs in mathematics at Marywood are designed to provide a strong foundation in mathematical 
skills and logical thinking, an appreciation for the role of mathematics in other disciplines, and the 
mathematical maturity necessary for graduate studies.</i><p>

<h2>Degree Opportunities</h2>
<ul>
<li>Bachelor of Science in Mathematics
<li>Bachelor of Science in Mathematics with Secondary Certification
</ul>

<h2>Career Opportunities</h2>
Mathematics provides the foundations upon which most scientific and technological advances are built. 
Developments in the past several decades have extended the use of mathematics in society today over a larger 
variety of disciplines than at any previous time in history. As a result, there exists a strong positive correlation 
in numerous fields between your mathematical knowledge and a successful employment upon graduation. A 
degree in mathematics at Marywood College provides you with a strong preparation for an exciting career (or 
graduate study) in such fields as:<p>
<ul>
<li>actuarial science
<li>aerospace engineering and technology
<li>astronomy
<li>communications network design
<li>computer science
<li>economics
<li>management
<li>mathematical modeling (related to research in such fields as biology, chemistry, medicine, social 
science, etc.)
<li>physics
<li>psychology
<li>secondary school mathematics teaching
<li>graduate mathematics
<li>statistics
<li>systems engineering
</ul>

<h2>Why Study Mathematics at Marywood?</h2>
<ul>
<li>All major courses are taught by full-time faculty and all academic advisement provided by faculty.
<li>The average class size is between five and fifteen students.
<li>Semi-Group, the campus mathematics club, affords opportunities to experience mathematics apart from 
required courses.
<li>Faculty and students are actively involved in professional organizations such as PCTM, NCTM, and the 
regional MAA.
<li>The Marywood chapter of Kappa Mu Epsilon, the national mathematics honor society, provides a means 
to recognize outstanding mathematical achievement.
<li>A wide variety of courses are offered regularly including calculus, differential equations, number theory, 
statistics, linear algebra, abstract algebra, mathematical modeling, topology, and analysis.
</ul>

<h2>Professional Facilities</h2>
<ul>
<li>More than 300 microcomputers (both Macintosh and IBM-compatible) are located in nine instructional 
labs and eleven clusters for drop-in use including residence halls. The new 6.4 million dollar Center for 
Natural and Health Sciences houses the Mathematics Department and state-of-the-art multi-media labs 
containing both Macintosh and IBM interactive video stations.
<li>Each location has printers and network connections. Labs are networked to the central Academic 
Information Services computer that provides an Internet gateway as well as access to MELVIN, Marywood's 
on-line library catalog. Electronic mail, bulletin-board services, and access to world-wide network resources 
are available to all regularly enrolled students.
<li>Numerous mathematics software packages are available including Mathematica,  Maple, Analyzer, Non-
Euclidean, Statview, SPSS-X, Geometry Supersupposer,  and various compilers for languages such as 
FORTRAN, Pascal, C, and COBOL.
</ul>

<h2>Program Requirements</h2>
	Mathematics majors (and minors) must maintain a minimum 2.50 QPA in major (minor) courses. 
Transfer students who wish to complete a major (or minor) program offered by the department must take at 
least fifty percent of their major (minor) courses at Marywood.<p>

