<IMG src="/images/mwlogos.jpg" align=left hspace=10> 
<H1>Marywood College</H1>

<H2>Music</H2>

<H2>Chairperson: Sister Joan Paskert, I.H.M., M.M.<BR>
</H2>
<HR>

<P>
At Marywood, you'll find a variety of music degree programs, integrating
a strong liberal arts program with excellent music preparation,
small classes and personal attention from faculty - and the chance
to perform with other hard-working and fun-loving music students.
<P>
Music has been at the heart of Marywood since the beginning: the
bachelor of music degree was one of the first degrees granted
by the College.Today's program offers you the opportunity to earn
your degree in music education, performance, church music, or
music therapy. You'll join a department of gifted musicians with
a sense of purpose and tremendous camaraderie. From the start,
you'll have opportunities to perform solo or in ensembles. You
can participate in Project Voice, a unique vocal program with
daily warm-ups, a master class and a weekly applied lesson. Cultural
opportunities abound, with local chorale and orchestra concerts
and trips to New York to see performing artists. Renowned artists-
national and international- come to campus to perform in the annual
benefit concert to raise money for music scholarships.
<P>
You'll leave Marywood with excellent preparation for a career
as a teacher, music therapist, church organist or choir director,
performer, music librarian, arranger, music journalist, or any
number of other careers focused on music. You'll also leave with
a sense of how music can serve people, communities, and society
as a whole. Indeed, you'll be on your way toward the goal of every
Marywood student's education: learning to live responsibly in
an interdependent world.
<H3>Faculty</H3>

<P>
You'll find the music faculty members are dedicated professionals
committed to helping you develop your musical talents. They are
gifted musicians,and most are active performers. They teach the
music classes, advise students on course selection and performance
opportunities, and serve as mentors to aspiring musicians. In
addition, they find time to publish original compositions, musical
arrangements and articles in professional journals (including
book and music reviews). <B>Professor Herrema</B> was commissioned
to write a major choral-orchestral work to celebrate 150 years
of IHM Community and 80 years of Marywood. <B>Sister Joan Paskert</B>
serves as president of the <B>Pennsylvania Music Teachers Association</B>.
<P>
<B>Sister Joan Paskert, I.H.M., M.M.,</B> <BR>
Chair (Piano)<BR>

<P>
<B>Sister M. Benedicta Berendes, I.H.M., Ph.D.<BR>
</B> (Musicology) <BR>

<P>
<B>Kenneth E. Brader, III, B.S.</B> <BR>
(Brass)<BR>

<P>
<B>Amelia Christian, M.M.</B> <BR>
(Violin)<BR>

<P>
<B>Sister M. Alphonsa Concilio, I.H.M., M.A.</B> <BR>
(Voice)<BR>

<P>
<B>Robert D. Herrema, M.M.</B> <BR>
(Choir and Orchestra)<BR>

<P>
<B>Cheryl L. Jones, M.S.</B> <BR>
(Music Therapy)<BR>

<P>
<B>Steven Mathiesen, M.M.</B> <BR>
(Percussion)<BR>

<P>
<B>Sister Mariam Pfeiffer, I.H.M., M.A., R.M.T. B.C.</B> <BR>
(Director, Program in Music Therapy)<BR>
<BR>
<B>Maureen Vincent-Morgan, M.M.</B> <BR>
(Voice)<BR>

<P>
<B>Sister Miriam Joseph Reinhardt, I.H.M., Ph.D.</B> <BR>
(Music Theory) <BR>

<P>
<B>Sister M. Immaculate Severino, I.H.M., M.M., M.T.C.</B> <BR>
(Piano) <BR>

<P>
<B>Kathleen A. Sears Smith, M.A.</B> <BR>
(Voice)<BR>

<P>
<B>D. Charles Truitt, M.A.</B> <BR>
(Classical Guitar)<BR>

<P>
<B>Edward Wargo, M.M.</B> <BR>
(Flute)<BR>

<P>
<B>William Weber, M.M.</B> <BR>
(Woodwinds)
<H3>The Regional Advantage: Putting Knowledge to Work</H3>

<P>
You'll find a great wealth of opportunities to put theory into
practice in the local region. Music therapy students will find
every type of clinical experience available within a five -mile
radius of campus. Those majoring in performance will find numerous
opportunities to perform as soloists or in an ensemble, at public
and private functions, including receptions and weddings. Music
education and church music majors have opportunities to observe
and participate in local school districts and parishes virtually
from the day they arrive at Marywood.
<H3>Facilities and Technology</H3>

<P>
Music students benefit from Marywood's commitment to provide all
students with state-of-the-art technology. You'll find computer
labs with music printing, word processing, theory tutorial, and
drill-and-practice programs; Yamaha keyboard programs; and a biofeedback
program interfaced with a PC. You'll find practice rooms that
are well-equipped and attractive; a full complement of band and
orchestra instruments (including percussion); multiple organs;
a Music Therapy Clinic; and a Music Education and Therapy Lab.
The Performing Arts Center also includes a 1,100-seat theatre
and a performing arts studio that seats 125. The library in the
Learning Resources Center supports the music program with exceptionally
fine holdings of CDs, records, musical scores and videos.
<H3>Requirements of the Program</H3>

<P>
You'll be glad to know that Marywood is an accredited institutional
member of the National Association of Schools of Music. The Music
Therapy Program also holds full approval of the National Association
for Music Therapy. All music majors are required to take the 34-credit
music core curriculum (except Music Therapy majors, who take 30
credits); pass a piano proficiency exam; and present a senior
recital on their major performing instrument/voice.
<P>
<B>Bachelor of Music in Church Music</B> 
<P>
Graduates of this program are prepared to be ministers of music,
organists, choir directors, and liturgical music teachers, and
to go on for advanced study. In addition to the music core courses,
students are required to take 36 credits of church music and applied
instrument/voice courses, and nine credits in religious studies.
Church music candidates also must complete field experiences in
the freshman, sophomore, and junior years and a two-semester practicum
in the senior year. (In addition, some proficiency in guitar is
highly recommended.)
<P>
<B>Bachelor of Music in Music Education</B> 
<P>
Graduates of this program are eligible for certification to teach
and supervise vocal and instrumental music (K-12) and to go on
for advanced study. In addition to the music core courses, students
take 38 required credits in music education, special education,
and physical education; they also take the professional educational
component of 28 credits (including student teaching). A music
education major must also do 100 hours of assigned fieldwork in
observation during the freshman, sophomore, and junior years.
This program requires at least eight regular semesters and additional
summer sessions.
<P>
<B>Bachelor of Music in Music Therapy</B> 
<P>
Students completing this program are eligible for Board Certification
in Music Therapy and employment not only in traditional clinical
settings (such as agencies serving individuals with emotional,
developmental or physical disabilities), but in expanding areas
of health care delivery (including hospice care, elderly care,
substance abuse programs and oncology treatment centers). They
may be employed in private and public schools, in private practice
or as consultants; or they may pursue advanced degrees. In addition
to the core music courses and proficiency requirements, music
therapy majors must pass a guitar proficiency, and take 48 required
credits in music therapy courses. Professional requirements include
another 25 credits in biology, history, math, psychology, sociology
and special education. Students also complete 140 hours of assigned
clinical/practicum experiences concurrent with their academic
studies. After successful completion of course work, a six month
internship at a training site approved by the National Association
for Music Therapy (NAMT) is required. Upon completion of all these
requirements, students are eligible to take the national certification
examination leading to board certification as a music therapist.
The credential awarded is Music Therapist-Board Certified (MT-BC).
This program requires eight semesters and additional summer sessions.
<P>
<B>Bachelor of Music in Performance</B> 
<P>
Graduates of this program are prepared for solo/ensemble performance,
studio teaching, and advanced study. In addition to the music
core courses, students take 32 credits in their major instrument/voice,
and 13-17 additional music credits. In addition to the solo recital
in the senior year, performance majors must also present a solo
recital in the junior year.
<H3>Collaborative Programs</H3>

<P>
The music department also collaborates with other departments
to offer the <B>B.A. in Performing Arts</B> (music and theater),<B>B.A.
in Arts Administration</B> (concentration in music), and <B>B.S.
in Elementary Education</B> with a Concentration in Music.
<UL>
<LI>Sample Music Courses
<LI>Church Music Accompaniment
<LI>Music Theory
<LI>Conducting
<LI>History of Music
<LI>Influence of Music on Behavior
<LI>Composition
<LI>Marching Band Techniques
<LI>Opera Workshop
<LI>Orchestration
<LI>Music in Special Education
</UL>

<H3>Just the Facts</H3>

<P>
Student:faculty ratio: 8:1<BR>
Average class size: 15-20; also one-to-one lessons.<BR>
Degrees offered: B.M. in Music Education; in Performance; in Church
Music; and in Music Therapy.
<P>
<B>After Marywood</B>: approximately 98% go directly into careers,
such as teaching, working in clinical settings, and working in
churches. Approximately 2% go on to further study, at such institutions
as Catholic University, Marywood, New York University, Temple,
and the University of West Virginia.
<P>
Most graduates within the last five years are working in their
field or related areas, including those who have earned doctorates
and gone into teaching.
<P>
<B>For more information, please contact:<BR>
</B>Sister Joan Paskert, I.H.M., Chair<BR>
Department of Music<BR>
Marywood College<BR>
Scranton, PA 18509<BR>
717/348-6268<BR>
paskert@ac.marywood.edu<BR>
http://www.marywood.edu <HR>

