<title>Marywood College</title>
</head>

<body background="/images/backgrnd.gif">
<img src="/images/mwlogos.jpg" align=left hspace=10>
<h1>Marywood College</h1>
<h2>Nursing</h2>
<h2><i>Chairperson: Mary Alice Golden,  Ph.D.</i></h2>
<br clear=left><hr>



At Marywood, you'll find supportive faculty, state-of-the-art facilities, a wealth of internship opportunities 
and a traditional success rate of 100% of graduates passing the national nursing licensing exam the 
first time.<p>

In the complex world of modern health care, nurses are called upon to make critical decisions, design and analyze nursing care and treatment, master state-of-the-art technology, and communicate as advocates and teachers with other health care professionals, patients, and the public.  Preparing you to meet these challenges as a committed and caring professional is at the heart of Marywood's program.  <p>

Knowledgeable and involved teachers will work closely with you to be sure you take advantage of leading-
edge scientific facilities at Marywood, opportunities in the local region for hands-on clinical experience, and nursing research from around the globe.  You'll leave Marywood prepared to practice in a variety of health care settings: critical care, community health, public health, primary care, acute care, and mental health care.  Add to Marywood's five-semester sequence of nursing courses the broadening foundation of 
the core curriculum in the liberal arts that is part of every Marywood student's experience, and you will be prepared to continue developing personally and professionally, working to meet human needs.  Indeed, you'll be ready to begin living responsibly in an interdependent world: the goal of every Marywood 
student's education, and especially significant for you as a nurse. <p>

<h3>Faculty</h3>

Professors in the nursing program are committed to the nursing profession and to their students.  They 
understand the balance between research and clinical practice that serves as the foundation of a nursing 
career.  Faculty teach the nursing courses, supervise clinical and other practical experience, advise on course selection and local internship opportunities, and still find time to continue their own research 
(you'll see their research interests listed below).  Recently, <b>Professor Perdew</b> published a book on AIDS; <b>Professor Golden</b> published articles in <i>Geriatric Nursing Journal</i> and <i>Journal 
of Long Term Care</i>; <b>Professor McGurk</b> researched turnover in nurse aide employment; <b>Professor Gallagher</b> contributed to <i>Nurse Practitioner Journal</i> and presented a paper at an 
international conference in England; and <b>Professor Gilpin</b> has presented seminars on home health care needs of the critically ill child.    <p>

<b>Mary Alice Golden,  Ph.D.</b>, Chair<br>
(Alzheimer's disease; communication in nursing)<p>

<b>Robin Gallagher,  D.N.Sc.</b><br>
(women's health; high risk pregnancy)<p>

<b>Ruth Gilpin,  M.S.N., M.S.</b><br>
(pediatric health care) <p>

<b>Rita McGurk,  M.S.N.</b><br>
(nursing roles and behavior in health care systems) <p>

<b>Sue Perdew,  Ph.D.</b><br>
(forensics, specializing in assessment of child abuse)<p>
<p>

<h3>Facilities and Technology</h3>


The nursing program benefits from Marywood's commitment to provide all students with state-of-the-art technology.  The department is located in the new Center for Natural and Health Sciences, which houses a 
separate nursing computer lab in addition to general computer labs.  You'll find specialized programs in the nursing lab, including CAI (computer-assisted instruction) and NCLEX preparation software, and interactive video capability.  General word processing and statistical software is available in the lab as 
well.  In the nearby Learning Resources Center, you'll find library holdings catalogued on-line of over 200,000 volumes, more than 1,100 journal subscriptions (134 directly related to nursing and medical science), and 40,000 non-print items (600 directly related to nursing and medical science).  The LRC also 
participates in an interlibrary loan network with 5,000 libraries.  The research collection includes The Cumulative Index to Nursing and Allied Health Literature, International Nursing Index, and Index Medicus.<p>


<h3>The Regional Advantage: Putting Knowledge to Work</h3>

The Scranton-Wilkes Barre region is a great place to apply the nursing knowledge you gain at Marywood.  In addition to getting clinical experience in a variety of hospital settings at three major health care facilities, you'll also have the opportunity to attend regional health-related workshops and seminars.  Internship opportunities abound: at the Community Medical Center, Mercy Hospital's cardiac unit, and Marian Community Hospital.<p>


<h3>Requirements of the Program</h3>

The  nursing program  consists of 136 credits, 55 of which are nursing credits.  Completion of the nursing program is accomplished by completing, at Marywood, the five senior-level nursing courses and the 
requirements of the College.  Before taking upper division courses, you'll need to successfully complete foundation courses in biology, chemistry, nutrition, psychology, sociology, philosophy, speech, and writing; you'll also take courses in statistics and developmental psychology.  These courses will help you fulfill the liberal arts requirements of the College.<p>

<h3>Sample Nursing Courses</h3>

Pharmacology<br>
Pathophysiology<br>
Communication in Nursing<br>
Leadership in Nursing<br>
Introduction to Nursing Research<br>
Aging: A Holistic Approach<br>
Nursing Care of Childbearing/Childrearing Families<br>
Advanced Nursing Care of the Critically Ill Client<p>


<h3>Just the Facts</h3>
 
Student: faculty ratio 15-25:1 Clinical groups: 8:1<br>
Average class size: 20-25<br>
Degree earned: B.S.N.<p>

<b>After Marywood:</b> 100% of those graduating in four of the past five years passed the National Council Licensure Exam (NCLEX) on their first attempt.<p>

100% of graduates go directly into nursing careers; a high percentage also pursue further study, including recently at Allentown College, Misericordia, Penn State, University of Scranton, Wilkes, University of Pennsylvania, and Yale.<p>


<b>For more information, please contact:</b><br>

Dr. Mary Alice Golden, Chair<br>
Department of Nursing<br>
Marywood College<br>
Scranton, PA 18509<br>
717/348-6211 ext. 2543<br>
or 717/348-6275<br>
golden@ac.marywood.edu <br>
http://www.marywood.edu<br>


