<title>Marywood College</title>
</head>

<body background="/images/backgrnd.gif">
<img src="/images/mwlogos.jpg" align=left hspace=10>
<h1>Marywood College</h1>
<h2>Nutrition and Dietetics</h2>
<h2><i> Chairperson: Marianne Borja, Ed.D., R.D., F.A.D.A.</i></h2>

<br clear=left><hr>



At Marywood, you'll find knowledgeable 
and supportive faculty, a comprehensive program that is the only one in northeastern Pennsylvania and the chance to complete in just 
four years the typical five-year program in nutrition and dietetics.<p>

As you are probably aware from reading newspapers and watching the news, nutrition and dietetics are "hot" topics.  As we approach the twenty-first century, finding answers to questions about the best diet 
for people at various stages of the life cycle, the relationship of diet to health, and feeding world populations, is critical.  A Marywood education will help prepare you for leadership and service in this ever-changing and rapidly-growing field.  Dietitians/nutritionists educated at Marywood are prepared for 
involvement in medical nutrition therapy, community nutrition, food systems management, health promotion and clinical nutrition, private practice, sports nutrition, education, business, and research.<p>

You'll find flexibility in the nutrition and dietetics program.  Students may complete four years of study at Marywood and then pursue a one-year accredited internship.  Qualified, highly motivated students may 
apply during the second semester of their sophomore year for the coordinated program which combines 
the traditional four-year program plus internship into a four- year program.  Either way, you'll learn the high-tech science of applying food and nutrition to health, and be prepared to take the National 
Registration Examination for Dietitians and to abide by the American Dietetics Association Code of Ethics.  Beyond that, you'll leave Marywood ready to put into action the College's goal for every student: 
living responsibly in an interdependent world.<p>


<h3>Faculty</h3>

Your professors at Marywood are dedicated to the field of nutrition and dietetics and to preparing students for rewarding professional careers.  All have strong academic backgrounds and most are Registered Dietitians so you'll be learning from the pros.  The faculty teach the nutrition classes, provide guidance in 
student research projects, advise on course selection, and still find time to conduct their own research. Currently, three professors have a major grant for study of "Health and Nutrition of Children in Military 
Families."  Their talents are recognized beyond Marywood: for example, <b>Professor Borja</b> won the American Dietetics Association's Award for Outstanding Educator of Coordinated Programs in 1996; and <b>Professor Harrison,</b> Director of Education and Professional Development, serves as an officer of the Practice Group for Dietitians in Nutrition Support.<p>

<b>Marianne Borja, Ed.D., R.D., F.A.D.A.</b>, Co-Chair  <br>
(food science, community nutrition, food systems management)<p>

<b>Mary Ann Ashton, M.S., R.D.</b>  (gerontology, long-term care)<p>

<b>Lee Harrison, Ph.D., R.D., F.A.D.A., C.N.S.D.</b>, Co-Chair <br>
(gerontology, critical care nutrition)<p>

<b>Sister Michaeline Macedonio, I.H.M., M.S., R.D.</b> <br>
 (food systems management)<p>

<b>Ann McKenna, M.S., R.D.</b>  (medical nutrition therapy)<p>

<b>R. Carlton Bessinger, Ph.D. candidate, R.D.</b> (sports nutrition)<p>

<b>Gina P. Sylvester, Ph.D. candidate, R.D. </b>(nutrition education)<p>


<h3>Facilities and Technology</h3>

The nutrition and dietetics program benefits from Marywood's commitment to provide all students with state-of-the-art technology.  In addition to the program's own food lab, you'll find computer facilities with 
the latest word processing and statistical software in the Learning Resources center (LRC); the computer labs are open to all regularly enrolled undergraduates.  The library, also located in the LRC, has holdings 
of more than 200,000 volumes; 1,100 periodicals; and 40,000 nonprint items.  The library also participates in a national and international interlibrary loan network with 5,000 other libraries.<p>

<h3>The Regional Advantage: Putting Knowledge to Work </h3>

You'll find a wealth of opportunities to put theory into practice in the greater Scranton-Wilkes Barre region.  Marywood's nutrition and dietetics program is affiliated with sixty facilities for supervised 
practical experience.  These include health care facilities acute, long-term, and rehabilitative community agencies, fitness programs, government agencies, school districts, child care facilities, home health organizations, and facilities for the elderly.<p>

<h3>Requirements of the Program</h3>

<i>Coordinated Program (CP)</i><br>
<dd>This program combines the traditional four years of didactic study and a fifth year of supervised practice into a four-year program.  Students who complete the CP earn a Bachelor of Science in Nutrition 
and Dietetics and are eligible to take the National Registration Examination for Dietitians after graduation.  Students apply for the accelerated program during the second semester of their sophomore year and must 
attend summer school during the sophomore summer.  Students are prepared to enter the job market or apply to graduate school.  The CP requires 71 credits in specified nutrition and dietetics courses.  
Marywood's Coordinated Program in Nutrition and Dietetics is currently granted accreditation status by 
the Commission on Accreditation/Approval for Dietetics Education of the American Dietetic Association, a specialized accrediting body recognized by the Commission on Recognition of Postsecondary Accreditation and the U.S. Department of Education.<p>

<i>Didactic Program (DP)</i><br>
<dd>This four-year program leads to a Bachelor of Science in Nutrition and Dietetics.  After completing this program, students need to pursue an accredited internship or other approved route to registration in 
order to take the National Registration Examination for Dietitians.  For this program, 51 credits in nutrition and dietetics are required.  Marywood's Didactic Program in Nutrition and Dietetics is currently 
granted approval status by the Commission on Accreditation/Approval for Dietetics Education of the American Dietetic Association, a specialized accrediting body recognized by the Commission on 
Recognition of Postsecondary Accreditation and the U.S. Department of Education.<p>

<h3>Sample Nutrition and Dietetics Courses</h3>

Food Science<br>
Nutrition I and II<br>
Computers in Dietetics<br>
Sanitation<br>
Medical Nutrition Therapy I and II<br>
Community Nutrition<br>
Social and Cultural Aspects of Food<br>
Basic Foods<br>
Sports Nutrition<br>
Food Systems Management<br><br>

<h3>Just the Facts</h3>

Student: faculty ratio:  15:1<br>
Average class size: 15-25 <br>
CP clinical areas: 10 students<br>
Degree offered: B.S. in Nutrition and Dietetics<p>

<b>After Marywood:</b> 100% of CP graduates take the qualifying examination to become a Registered Dietitian and go directly into careers or graduate school.  As for DP graduates, virtually 100% go on to internships, graduate school, or work in the field.  Alumni include a past president of the A.D.A.!<p>

<b>For more information, please contact:</b><br>

Dr. Marianne Borja, Co-Chair<br>
Department of Nutrition and Dietetics<br>
Marywood College<br>
Scranton, PA  18509<br>
717/348-2573<br>
borja@ac.marywood.edu<br>
http://www.marywood.edu<br>



