<title>Marywood College</title>
</head>

<body background="/images/backgrnd.gif">
<img src="/images/mwlogos.jpg" align=left hspace=10>
<h1>Marywood College</h1>
<h2>Philosophy</h2>
<h2><i> Chairperson: Michael A. Foley, Ph.D.</i></h2>
<br clear=left><hr>


At Marywood, you'll find an involved 
and engaging faculty, a program that challenges you to examine critically life's ultimate questions and a background that will serve you well whatever your goals.<p>

If you join faculty members in Marywood's philosophy department in agreeing with Socrates that "the 
unexamined life is not worth living," you'll value the chance to examine life from a variety of philosophical perspectives.  You'll have the opportunity to become familiar with philosophical theories 
regarding such areas as art, education, history, religion, law, and society, and to study ethical issues in 
relation to business, the environment, and medicine.  You can survey the work of important American philosophers, inquire into the nature and value of sport and play and even analyze sources for the development of your own possible contributions to a more compassionate, just, and peaceful world.<p>


As you might imagine, such studies in philosophy can prepare you for any number of future endeavors (as well as for your own personal fulfillment).  The very nature of Marywood's program requires you to use 
your philosophy studies in conjunction with other studies: The major is offered on an ad hoc basis as part of a double major with another discipline.  Perhaps you're considering law, business, or medicine as a profession.  Perhaps you're thinking of politics or diplomacy. Perhaps you foresee a career in teaching or 
environmental preservation.  Any of these and more can be enhanced through the study of philosophy.  
Whatever your goal, the philosophy program can help prepare you to reach it and to reach the goal of every Marywood student's education: learning to live responsibly in an interdependent world.<p>


<h3>Faculty</h3>

You'll find the faculty  members in philosophy to be committed both to teaching and to involvement in the field.  All faculty members have earned doctorates in philosophy.  They teach the courses, advise on course selection, counsel students on applications of philosophy to future goals, and still find time to 
pursue their own research and writing projects.  Several have received prestigious post-doctoral study grants through the National Endowment for the Humanities.  All serve as expert reviewers for books in 
the field, and publish in the leading philosophy journals.  In addition, <b>Professors Foley and Mohan </b>have co-authored two introductory philosophy texts.  You'll find the faculty's research interests listed below.<p>

<b>Michael A. Foley, Ph.D.</b>, Chair  <br>
(law and society; courts in American society; death penalty; insanity defense)<p>

<b>Sister Dorothy Haney, I.H.M., Ph.D.</b> <br>
 (social ethics and justice, especially in the pursuit of peace; the philosophy of Gandhi; Utopian theory)<p>

<b>William J, Mohan, Ph.D.</b>  (ethics; politics; biomedical ethics)<p>

<b>Peter H. Spader, Ph.D.</b><br>
(phenomenology; business ethics; the philosophy of Scheler; teaching strategies)<p>


 
<h3>Facilities and Technology</h3>

The philosophy program benefits from Marywood's commitment to provide all students with state-of-the-
art technology.  You'll find computer facilities with the latest word processing and statistical software in the Learning Resources Center (LRC); these labs are available to all regularly enrolled undergraduates.  
The library, also located in the LRC, has holdings of more than 200,000 volumes; 1,100 periodicals and 40,000 nonprint items.  The library also participates in a national and international interlibrary loan 
network with 5,000 other libraries.<p>



<h3>Requirements of the Program</h3>

<i>All Marywood students are required to take three courses 
in Philosophy.</i><p>

<b>Philosophy Major</b><br>
Students can pursue an ad hoc major in philosophy in conjunction with a major in another discipline (i.e., a major in philosophy is available only as part of a double-major program).  Students have found the ad hoc major valuable in combination with any number of other disciplines, including pre-law, social 
sciences,  English, foreign languages, psychology, religious studies, and the physical sciences.  The philosophy major requires 36 philosophy credits chosen in consultation with the department chairperson.<p>


<b>Philosophy Minor</b><br>

Students who choose to minor in philosophy are required to take 18 philosophy credits.  Six credits are to 
be taken in the required courses "Introduction to Philosophy" and "Critical Thinking"; the remaining twelve credits may be elected from any category.<p>



<h3>Sample Philosophy Courses</h3>

Critical Thinking<br>
Biomedical Ethics<br>
Perspectives on Women<br>
Utopian Thought<br>
Philosophy, Society, and Law<br>
Philosophy of Art<br>
Perspectives on Punishment<br>
Political Philosophy<br>
Business Ethics<br>
Philosophy of Religion<br>
Environmental Ethics<br>

<br><p>

<h3>Just the Facts</h3>

Average class size: 22<br>

<b>After Marywood:</b>  While some graduates go on to graduate studies in philosophy, the majority use their Marywood studies as a basis for personal enrichment and professional development.  Philosophy majors and minors are strong candidates for law, medical, public administration, and business school programs.<p>



<b>For more information, please contact:</b><br>

Dr. Michael A. Foley, Chair<br>
Philosophy Department<br>
Marywood College<br>
Scranton, PA 18509<br>
717/348-2592<br>
foley@ac.marywood.edu<br>
http://www.marywood.edu<br>


