<title>Marywood College</title>
</head>

<body background="/images/backgrnd.gif">
<img src="/images/mwlogos.jpg" align=left hspace=10>
<h1>Marywood College</h1>
<h2>Psychology</h2>
<h2><i> Chairperson: Donald G. Myers, Ed.D.</i></h2>

<br clear=left><hr>



At Marywood, you'll find supportive faculty, state-of-the-art laboratories, opportunities for field experience and outstanding preparation for a career in the traditional or emerging psychological professions.<p>

A background in psychology from Marywood will serve you well in almost any area of endeavor,  because the faculty seeks to provide you with an in-depth understanding of human behavior and is committed to a 
broad interdisciplinary study of humanity.  You'll be provided with training in scientific and critical thinking, and in research methods and computer use; you'll learn to see psychology as an approach to solving problems and discovering new ideas.  Knowledge gained at Marywood can serve as a basis for the 
graduate work needed for careers in such areas as clinical psychology, community psychology, environmental psychology, experimental psychology, family psychology, forensic psychology, health psychology and more.  Or you can use your studies as a springboard for a variety of careers from 
criminologist or counselor to personnel manager or statistical researcher.<p>

Whatever you choose to do, you'll find the study of psychology will provide you with the opportunity to make significant contributions to society.  You'll be well on your way to the goal of every Marywood student's education: learning to live responsibly in an interdependent world.<p>


<h3>Faculty</h3>

The psychology faculty is dedicated to the field and to helping students develop the skills and knowledge they will need for successful careers and/or further, graduate-level study.  All full-time faculty hold 
doctoral degrees.  Faculty members teach the classes, advise students on course selection and internship opportunities, and act as mentors for student researchers.  In addition, they find time to keep up with the ever-changing study of psychology through their own research; you'll find their research interests listed above.<p>

<b>Donald G. Myers, Ed.D.</b>, Chair  (traumatic brain injury; sexual offenders treatment; prison violence)<p>
<b>Sister Gail Cabral, I.H.M., Ph.D.</b>  (Myers-Briggs Type Inventory; friendship and peer relations; gender stereotyping; social cognition; psychology and spirituality)<p>

<b>Dale Hazlak, M.A.</b>  (forensic issues; sex offenders and victim impact; aggression management)<p>
<b>Edward Heffron, Ed.D.</b>  (social and emotional development in adolescence and young adulthood)<p>

<b>Thomas Kennedy, Ph.D.</b> (psychoanalytic theory; women's development (power); psychotherapy)<p>

<b>Linda McAllister, M.A.</b>  (holistic medicine in mental health intervention; biofeedback and stress management in mental health)<p>

<b>Frank M. Mrykalo, Ed.D.</b>  (coping strategies with psycho-social stress; 
study skills)<p>

<b>Edward J. O'Brien, Ph.D.</b>  (cognitive and behavioral therapies; self-concept; stress and coping; outcomes assessment; technology innovation in higher education)<p>

<b>Theodore Zawistowski, M.A.</b>  (psychology of religion)<p>



<h3>Facilities and Technology</h3>

Psychology  students benefit from Marywood's commitment to provide all students with state-of-the-art technology.   The psychology department is housed in the Center for Human Services, which includes a 
psychology lab, a group process room, and a complete counseling lab with one-way mirrors, interview rooms, and testing rooms and equipment.  Four videotape systems are available to record training sessions.  Leading-edge computer systems, networked to campus and the Internet and interfaced with 
psychophysiology monitoring equipment, are available to psychology students.  You'll also find the major psychology journals and titles on psychology and related areas in the Learning Resources Center library.<p>

<h3>The Regional Advantage: Putting Knowledge to Work</h3>

You'll find a wealth of opportunities to put the knowledge you gain at Marywood into practice in the 
wider community.  If you're in the clinical practices track, you'll need to incorporate at least three credits (each equivalent to 35 hours of field experience) of internship experience into your program.  The field settings for internships include mental health agencies; schools; residential in-patient facilities; rehabilitation centers; correctional facilities; and prisons.  Even if you're not in the clinical practices 
track, you'll be encouraged to participate in field experiences in these and other settings, and will have the chance to join field trips to various institutions in the region.  Another advantage of Marywood's location is the availability of guest speakers representing a variety of professions in the field.<p>

<h3>Requirements of the Program</h3>

Students majoring in psychology are required to complete 45 credits in psychology, 30 of which are to be taken in a specified core sequence, and 15 chosen as electives.  You'll also be advised to take a course in statistics for the behavioral sciences and, if possible, one semester of anatomy and physiology.  If you're 
interested in a career in the clinical psychology area either immediately after graduation or after graduate study in clinical psychology you'll want to follow the clinical practices track, which requires a nine-credit course sequence including an internship experience.<p>

Students who wish to minor in psychology must complete 21 credits, arranged in consultation with the department chair.  If you're highly motivated and qualified, you may have the chance to begin graduate study in psychology or counseling in your senior year, through cooperation with Marywood's Graduate Department of Counseling and Psychology.<p>

<h3>Sample Psychology Courses</h3>

Developmental Psychology<br>
Theories of Personality<br>
Physiological Psychology<br>
Social Psychology<br>
Experimental Psychology<br>
Psychology of Adolescence<br>
Sensation and Perception<br>
Abnormal Psychology<br>
Clinical Psychology<br>
Drugs and Behavior<br>
Forensic Psychology<br>
Psychology of Religion<br>

<h3>Just the Facts</h3>

Student:faculty ratio: 25:1<br>
Average class size: 25<br>
Degree offered: B.S. in Psychology<p>

<b>After Marywood:</b> approximately 30% go directly into careers including recently group home supervisor, manager trainee, mental hygiene therapy aide, personnel manager, admissions counselor, 
psychiatric aide, counselor for the handicapped, and coordinator of a parents' self-help group; others are employed in areas less closely allied with the field.  Approximately 20% go on to graduate work, 
including recently at Binghamton, Bowling Green, Fordham, Marywood, New School of Social Research, San Francisco State, 
St. Bonaventure's and Temple.<p>

<b>For more information, please contact:</b><br>

Dr. Donald Myers, Chair<br>
Undergraduate Psychology  Department<br>
Marywood College<br>
Scranton, PA  18509<br>
717/348-6270<br>
myers@ac.marywood.edu<br>
http://www.marywood.edu<br>

