<title>Marywood College</title>
</head>

<body background="/images/backgrnd.gif">
<img src="/images/mwlogos.jpg" align=left hspace=10>
<h1>Marywood College</h1>
<h2>Religious Studies</h2>
<h2><i>Chairperson: Michael A. Fuchs, Ed.D.</i></h2>
<br clear=left><hr>


At Marywood, you'll find a caring faculty 
committed to helping you explore the ultimate human questions (and your own), the opportunity to test your beliefs in regional or international settings  and a foundation for your own spiritual development or for ministry to others.<p>


The religious studies program is central to the Marywood experience; indeed, every Marywood student takes three courses in the department.  For students majoring or minoring in religious studies, the 
department offers a wide range of study of the beliefs, practices, and values of the Judeo-Christian tradition as well as other religious traditions.  While special attention is given to the Catholic tradition, the offerings are broad enough to benefit you in your own search for religious meaning and for a basis in 
making ethical decisions.  You'll graduate with general knowledge in scripture, morality, sacramental basics, and spirituality, and with a background in ministry.  You'll be prepared to carry out Marywood's goal for all students: learning to live responsibly in an interdependent world.<p>


<h3>Faculty </h3>

The faculty in the religious studies department represent a variety of backgrounds and experience and, while their grounding is academic, they are sensitive to students' religious needs beyond theory.  The 
members of the faculty know each other well and have worked together for a long time: you'll benefit from their long experience in working with students.  They teach the department's courses; supervise your field experiences; advise you on course selection, research projects, and matters of faith; lead the Bible 
tours; and still find time to conduct their own research.  In addition to publishing numerous articles on timely theological issues in newspapers and magazines, faculty have recently presented papers on Karl Barth, The Peace Movement, and The Role of Play in Theology. <p>

<b>Michael A. Fuchs, Ed.D.</b>, Chair<p>
<b>*Reverend Robert J. Barone, S.T.D.<p>
*Reverend William Campbell, S.T.D.<p>
Charles DeCelles, Ph.D. <p>
Sister Maria Rose Kelly,  I.H.M., MA.<p>
Frances R. McCormick, Ph.D.  <p>
John R. Zaums, Ph.D.  </b><br>

<i>*Part-time</i><p>


<h3>Facilities and Technology</h3>

The religious studies program benefits from Marywood's commitment to provide all students with state-of-the-art technology.  You'll find computer facilities with the latest in word processing and statistical software in the Learning Resources Center (LRC); these labs are available to all regularly enrolled 
undergraduates.  The library, also located in the LRC, has holdings of more than 200,000 volumes, 1,100 periodicals and 40,000 non-print items; the library also participates in a national and international 
interlibrary loan network with 5,000 other libraries.<p>

<h3>The Regional Advantage: Putting Knowledge to Work</h3>

If you're interested in using your studies at Marywood as the basis for hands-on experience, you'll find a wealth of opportunities in the Scranton-Wilkes Barre region.  The variety of internship options is as broad 
as the range of student interests.  Religious studies majors observe, study, and work in schools and in youth education and ministry programs.  <p>


<h3>Beyond the Region: International Opportunities</h3>

If you are committed  or want 
to test your commitment  to sharing your talent and compassion with a different population, you may want to participate in the department's International Service Program, which is offered in alternate summers.  
With the approval of the department chair, you'll observe and participate in the culture of a Third World country, preceded and followed 
by a period of reflection and research.<p>

Another meaningful international experience available to Marywood religious studies students is the Biblical Study Tour offered in alternate summers.  With approval of the department chair, you'll 
participate in a two-week, academically oriented study program in the lands of the Bible, preceded and followed by a period of reflection and research.<p>


<h3>Requirements of the Program</h3>

For the major, 36 credit hours in religious studies are required (nine of these credits also help fulfill the 
College requirement of 64 credits in the core liberal arts and skills curriculum).  With the advice and approval of the faculty, majors can pursue one of the following areas of concentration: one for majors who intend to engage in some form of church ministry (such as director of religious education, teacher of 
religion, or youth minister); another for those who want to concentrate their study in the Christian tradition; and a third concentration for those majors pursuing the study of religion as a phenomenon.  All three concentrations prepare a student for graduate work.<p>

For students who wish to minor in religious studies, 18 credit hours are required.  Such a minor can be combined effectively with a major in many other fields, including psychology, music, social work, or elementary education.  <p>


<h3>Sample Religious Studies Courses</h3>

Jesus in the Twentieth Century Perspective	<br>
Modern Belief<br>
Christian Spirituality<br>
Religion and Education<br>
The Catholic Experience<br>
Christian Marriage<br>
Introduction to Eastern Religions<br>
Death and Afterlife<br>
Foundations of Christian Morality<br>


<h3>Just the Facts</h3>

Average class size: 10-12 for major courses; 27 for general courses<br>
Degree earned: Bachelor of Arts in Religious Studies<p>

<b>After Marywood:</b> Most graduates go directly into such fields as youth ministry and teaching religion while pursuing graduate study.  Recently, graduates have gone on to Notre Dame, Boston College, University of Scranton and Catholic University.<p>


<b>For more information, please contact:</b><br>

Dr. Michael Fuchs, Chair<br>
Department of Religious Studies<br>
Marywood College<br>
Scranton, PA 18509<br>
717/348-6211, ext. 2504<br>
e-mail: fuchs@ac.marywood.edu<br>
http://www.marywood.edu<br>




