<IMG src="/images/mwlogos.jpg" align=left hspace=10> 
<H1>Marywood College</H1>

<H2>Sciences</H2>

<H2>Chairperson: Sister M. Anitra Nemotko, I.H.M., Ph.D.<BR>
</H2>
<HR>

<P>
At Marywood, you'll find sophisticated facilities for scientific
investigation and research, opportunities for internships and
clinical experience, and something most undergraduate science
majors only dream of- small classes and individual attention from
the faculty throughout your college career.
<P>
An understanding of science is critical to those who hope to be
informed citizens in the twenty-first century. Marywood's science
programs will provide you with opportunities to develop your problem
solving, critical thinking and analytical skills. You'll find
Marywood provides an ideal environment for learning science: laboratory
facilities are state-of the-art, and faculty members are dedicated
to the teaching profession, and are genuinely interested in the
academic progress of their students. You'll also find a wealth
of opportunity in the surrounding area, including medical facilities,
clinical laboratories, environmental groups and the availability
of speakers from Marywood and local colleges.
<P>
The quality of the educational experience and the dedication of
the Marywood faculty are designed to help you reach the College's
goal for every student: learning to live responsibly in an interdependent
world. What better way to understand and contribute to contemporary
society than through the study of science?
<H3>Faculty</H3>

<P>
The science faculty at Marywood are highly qualified dedicated
professionals. The full-time faculty all hold doctorates from
prestigious universities. In addition to teaching lecture and
laboratory courses, the science faculty advise students regarding
course selection and graduate schools, direct student research,
and prepare qualified majors to work as laboratory assistants.
The expertise of the science faculty has been recognized in the
larger community. Sister Anitra and Dr. Dempsey received National
Science Foundation funding for inquiry-based laboratories in physiology;
Sister Anitra also serves on the Advisory Board of the Pennsylvania
Junior Academy of Science. Dr. Clymer received a grant from the
Wetlands Institute to study fish of the Hereford Inlet; he also
serves on the board of directors of the Lackawanna Conservation
District. Dr. Driesbach developed a high-performance chromatography
method. Dr. Lobo serves on the College Committee for Student Research
and was invited to visit other countries to evaluate and exchange
information in the medical science area.
<P>
<B>Sister M. Anitra Nemotko, I.H.M., Ph.D., <BR>
</B>Chair (anatomy and physiology; aptitude-treatment-interaction
in science education)
<P>
<B>Jay P. Clymer III, Ph.D. <BR>
</B>(ecology of stream and marsh ecosystems; tropic dynamics)
<P>
<B>Thomas P. Dempsey, Ph.D. <BR>
</B>(distance-education productions for science)
<P>
<B>Andrea Driesbach, Ph.D. <BR>
</B>(enzyme kinetics; enzyme inhibition; analytical methods development
for analysis of products of enzyme reactions)
<P>
<B>Leonard G. Herman, Ph.D. <BR>
</B>(synthesis of organometallic compounds and transition metal
complexes; chemical health and safety)
<P>
<B>Francis X. Lobo, Ph.D., S.M., AAM </B>(American Academy of
Microbiology).<BR>
(general and clinical microbiology)
<H3>Adjunct Faculty: Medical Technology</H3>

<P>
<B>Mary Gene Butler, M.S., M.T. (ASCP)</B> 
<P>
<B>Paul J. Cherney, M.D.</B> 
<P>
<B>Thomas V. DiSilvio, M.D.</B> 
<P>
<B>George A. Grinaway, M.D.</B> 
<P>
<B>Joseph King, M.D.</B> 
<P>
<B>F.V. Kostelnik, M.D.</B> 
<P>
<B>Mary Meihofer, M.D.</B> 
<P>
<B>Barbara Scheelje, M.T. (ASCP)</B> 
<P>
<B>Deborah A. Schwab, M.T. (ASCP)</B> 
<P>
<B>Brian O. Spezialetti, M.S., M.T. (ASCP)</B> 
<H3>Facilities and Technology</H3>

<P>
The science program benefits from Marywood's commitment to provide
all students with state-of-the-art technology. The new $6.4 million
Center for Natural and Health Sciences is equipped with four large
laboratories, an environmental wet laboratory, a greenhouse, three
computer laboratories and a multi-media auditorium. Computer software
available to students includes word processing, spreadsheet, statistical
and science programs; you'll also find audio-visual tutorial services.
<H3>The Regional Advantage: Putting Knowledge to Work</H3>

<P>
You'll find plenty of opportunities in the Scranton-Wilkes Barre
region to add to and share your knowledge, whether your future
plans involve the health professions, environmental work, teaching
or business. There are many modern medical facilities in the area
which serve as resources for internships and beginning experiences
in medicine and related areas. A number of government agencies,
such as the Lackawanna Conservation District, offer the chance
for practical experience. Internships for environmental science
and biology majors are available at Connaught Laboratories, the
Lackawanna Wildlife Sanctuary, the National Institute of Environmental
Renewal, and Sierra Laboratory. Indeed, Marywood students have
access to and utilize the Sierra Laboratory, located near campus,
for environmental and biological research; students gain experience
with modern instrumentation, such as gas chromatographs, UV systems
and ion selective meters; inductively coupled plasma (ICP); and
other major pieces of analytical instrumentation. You might also
choose to participate in local groups such as the Earth Conservancy,
CARE, and the Sierra Club.
<H3>Requirements of the Program</H3>

<P>
<B>B.S. in Biology/Preprofessional Studies</B>
<P>
The preprofessional studies program focuses on preparing students
who plan to enter the various professions of medicine- including
physician, dentist, osteopath, veterinarian or researcher- but
offers sufficient flexibility to prepare students for future studies
in law, business administration, and education, and to enter the
ancillary fields of the healing professions. A minimum of 44 credits
in biology is required for the major, as well as required courses
in chemistry, math and physics, which total 30 credits.
<P>
<B>B.S. in Biology/Pre-Chiropractic Program</B>
<P>
This program allows students to begin study in chiropractic medicine
during the senior year. Students complete 106 credits in science
and liberal arts requirements in their three years at Marywood;
the fourth year is spent at New York Chiropractic College. After
the first year of chiropractic study, the student earns Marywood's
B.S. in Biology; another two years and four months of study lead
to the Doctor of Chiropractic degree.
<P>
<B>B.S. in Environmental Science</B>
<P>
This program is designed for the student interested in a career
as a professional environmental scientist, professor, teacher,
research specialist, ecologist, or science executive. The curriculum
provides background for the graduate work and advanced degrees
required by some of these career choices. A total of 58 credits
in biology, chemistry, environmental science, math and physics
are required plus 15 credits of electives.
<P>
<B>B.S. in Medical Technology/Clinical Laboratory Science</B>
<P>
Students can choose one of two options in this program:
<OL>
<LI>Students spend three years at Marywood fulfilling the College
requirements and those of the National Accrediting Agency for
Clinical Laboratory Science (NAACLS), with the fourth year spent
in an accredited, affiliated hospital program.
<LI>Students complete the B.S. program at Marywood and then apply
to affiliated schools of medical technology approved by the Board
of Registry and/or NAACLS.
</OL>

<P>
The minimum requirements of the medical technology program are:
16 credits in Chemistry, 16 credits in Biology, and one course
in math.
<P>
<B>Teacher Education Programs: BS Biology/Secondary Education
and B.S. General Science Education</B>
<P>
The teacher education programs in science are designed to prepare
biology and/or general science teachers (grades 7-12), and are
accredited by the Pennsylvania Department of Education and by
the National Council for Accreditation of Teacher Education. A
student enrolls as a biology and/or general science major and
education minor. There are 78 required credits in biology, chemistry,
physics, environmental science and math for the B.S. Biology/Secondary
Education; 62 credits are required for general science education.
In addition, students must fulfill the education department's
requirements.
<H3>Sample Science Courses</H3>

<UL>
<LI>Human Anatomy and Physiology
<LI>Microbiology
<LI>Principles of Environmental Science
<LI>Genetics
<LI>Undergraduate Research
<LI>Ecology
<LI>Organic Chemistry
<LI>Biochemistry
<LI>Environmental Monitoring and Measurements
<LI>Immunology
<LI>Forensic Analytical Techniques
<LI>General Physics
</UL>

<H3>Just the Facts</H3>

<P>
Average lecture class size: 20<BR>
Average lab class size: 16<BR>
Degrees offered: B.S. in Biology; B.S. in Biology (Pre-Professional);
<BR>
B.S. in Biology (Pre-Chiropractic); B.S. in Environmental Science;
B.S. in<BR>
Medical Technology/Clinical Laboratory Science; B.S. in Biology/Secondary
<BR>
Education; B.S. in General Science Education.<BR>

<P>
<B>After Marywood:</B> A number of students go directly into careers
such as environmental consultant, high school science teacher,
medical technologist and chemist. Others go on to graduate work,
including recently at George Washington University, Philadelphia
College of Osteopathic Medicine,  University of Arizona, University
of Maryland Medical College and the University of Iowa School
of Podiatry.
<P>
<B>For more information, please contact:</B>
<P>
Sister Anitra Nemotko, I.H.M., Ph.D., Chair<BR>
Department of Science <BR>
Marywood College <BR>
Scranton, PA 18509<BR>
717/348-6265<BR>
nemotko@ac. marywood.edu<BR>
