<title>Marywood College</title>
</head>

<body background="/images/backgrnd.gif">
<img src="/images/mwlogos.jpg" align=left hspace=10>
<h1>Marywood College</h1>
<h2>Science Department</h2>
<br clear=left><hr>

<h2><i>Science at Marywood    </i></h2>
<i>The goal of the Department of Science at Marywood is to produce open-minded persons 
who possess knowledge and technical skills which relate to the natural world, along with 
the ability to apply them to appropriate ends.</i><p>

<h3><i>Why Study Science at Marywood?</i></h3>
<ul>
<li>New 6.4 million dollar Center for Natural and Health Sciences
<li>100% of full-time faculty have doctorates from diverse institutions
<li>Excellent academic advisement and preparation for professional and graduate schools
<li> Active student research
<li>Four large state-of-the-art chemistry, biology and physics laboratories
<li> Small class size - individual attention
<li>Wet environmental laboratory
<li>Greenhouse
<li>Laser disk technology
<li>Three computer laboratories/laser printers
<li>Auditorium equipped with media facilities
<li>All laboratories conducted by faculty
<li>Excellent tutoring services available 
<li>Opportunities to work as laboratory assistants
<li>Biology and medical technology clubs
<li>Environmental and clinical internships.
<li>Graduates employed as physicians, researchers, environmental specialists, medical technologists and science educators.
</ul>

<h3><i>Major Programs</i></h3>
<ul>
<li>Biology
<li>Pre-medical, Pre-dental, Pre-veterinary
<li>Environmental Studies
<li>Medical Technology
<li>Teacher Certification Programs in Biology and/or General Science
</ul>

<h4><i>B.S. in Biology </i></h4>
The Biology Program at Marywood College is designed to prepare the student for 
professional, educational and industrial careers. Students are provided with a broad base 
knowledge of living forms and a sense of the organization and continuity that exists in 
nature. The  student is made aware of the individual's responsibility to the world and to 
the environment.<p>


<h4><i>Pre-medical, Pre-dental<br>
or Pre-veterinary Studies</i></h4>
The program in Preprofessional Studies is structured for the highly qualified, 
science-oriented student who may be planning to enter the various professions of 
medicine, including that of physician, dentist, osteopath, veterinarian or researcher.  The 
student's choice of elective courses for the program is based on the requirements and 
suggestions of the professional schools.<p>

<h4><i>B.S. in Environmental Studies</i></h4>
This major is directed toward the student who is pursuing a professional career 
related to the use and protection of the environment. Career goals include resource  
utilization/management, public administration, business law,  waste disposal/control, 
government, architecture and economics.<p>


<h4><i>B.S. in Medical Technology</i></h4>
The program at Marywood was the first program of its type at a private college. 100% 
of our students have been successful in getting clinical internship placements. The course 
of study in Medical Technology follows a dual track program:<br>
<ol>
<li>Students may spend three years at Marywood College fulfilling the college 
requirements and those of the National Accrediting Agency for Clinical Laboratory 
Science (NAACLS).  In this program the student spends the fourth year in an accredited 
hospital program.
<li>Students who complete a baccalaureate program in biology and who have the 
necessary prerequisites, may also apply to any school of medical technology which is 
approved by the National Certification Agency.
</ol>
<p>
Marywood maintains affiliation with the schools of medical technology at 
Abington Memorial Hospital, Abington, Pennsylvania; Sacred Heart Hospital, 
Allentown, Pennsylvania; Robert Packer Hospital, Sayre, Pennsylvania; 
Wilkes-Barre General Hospital, Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania, and Scranton 
Medical Consortium, Scranton, Pennsylvania. Additional placements are also 
possible.<p>


<h4><i>QPA Requirements</i></h4>
Science majors must maintain a minimum grade of C+ in major courses and at least a C 
in minor courses. Transfer students must have earned a minimum grade of C+ in each 
science course. <br>
Students who minor in Biology, Chemistry, Environmental Science or Science must 
maintain a minimum grade of C+ in minor courses.<p>


<h4><i>Credit Transfer Policy</i></h4>
A maximum of sixteen science transfer credits will be accepted by the Science 
Department as applicable toward any of the major science degree programs. A maximum of 
eight science transfer credits will be accepted by the Science Department as applicable 
toward any of the minor programs.<p>


<h4><i>Procedures for Admission</i></h4>
To be admitted to the college a student must:
<ol>
<li>Complete the admission process through the Office of Admissions.
<li>Upon acceptance to the college, schedule an appointment with the Science 
Department to plan an appropriate program.
<li>Register for courses with the appropriate faculty advisor.
</ol>
