<title>Marywood College</title>
</head>

<body background="/images/backgrnd.gif">
<img src="/images/mwlogos.jpg" align=left hspace=10>
<h1>Marywood College</h1>
<h2>Special Education</h2>
<h2><i>Chairperson: Anthony C. Russo, Ed. D.</i></h2>
<br clear=left><hr>



At Marywood, you'll find an outstanding  
program (one of only 200 in the country 
approved by the Council for Exceptional Children), a faculty committed to helping you excel and the chance to  join graduates who routinely score well above the state average in this specialty area on the National Teachers Examination.<p>

     As the twenty-first century approaches, there is both greater awareness of the variety of special human needs and of the variety of options to enable the physically and mentally disabled live fuller and more rewarding lives.  Opportunities for careers in special education have never been greater or more satisfying than now.<p>

Marywood's program prepares you for the challenges and rewards of teaching persons with physical and/or mental disabilities at all levels of development from birth to age twenty-one.  Your coursework in 
professional studies and liberal arts taught in small classes and enhanced with real-world experience beginning in your freshman year will emphasize creative thinking, the evaluation of contemporary educational issues, and development of leadership skills.  The faculty will consider you a professional 
colleague as well as a student: students are required to maintain professional memberships in the Marywood chapters of Council for Exceptional Children and Pennsylvania Association for Retarded Citizens.  You'll graduate prepared to be a leader in the areas of mental retardation, behavior disorders, 
learning disabilities, and multiple disabilities; you'll be ready to serve as a teacher in grades K through 12 in a school or residential setting, as a professional in adult services, or in another position of responsibility in this growing field.<p>

The goal of every Marywood student's education learning to live responsibly in an interdependent world is especially significant for those pursuing studies in special education.  You'll graduate exceptionally well prepared to make a difference in the lives of others.<p>

<h3>Faculty</h3>

You'll find the faculty members in special education to be professional and supportive.  They have experience in both regular and special education classrooms, as well as in a variety of service agencies; and they will work closely with you to prepare you to be a competent, responsible teacher and advocate for 
persons with disabilities.  Faculty who teach the special education classes, help you choose sites for practical experience, supervise your field and teaching experiences, advise you on course selection, support your research efforts, and still find time to keep up with the field through their own research (you'll find their research interests listed below).  Recently, <b>Professor Russo</b>  presented papers at state and 
regional conferences on <i>"Portfolio Assessment"</i> and <i>"Inclusion and the Regular Educators."</i><p>

<b>Dr. Anthony C. Russo, Ed. D.</b>, Chair<br>
(teacher attitudes towards inclusion; inclusion practices)	<p>

<b>*Michael Ostrowski, M.S., Ph.D.</b> candidate<p>

<i>*Part-time</i><p>


<h3>Facilities and Technology</h3>

The special education program benefits from Marywood's commitment to provide all students with state-of-the-art technology.  Specialized facilities for students pursuing special education studies include the 
Microcomputer Center and the Special Education Curriculum Laboratory.  You'll also find an excellent library with many volumes devoted to special education topics, and a collection of audio-visual materials 
related to the major (including a tape collection on individual assessment and teaching modules for early intervention and the at-risk infant).  <p>

<h3>The Regional Advantage: Putting Knowledge to Work</h3>


You'll find plenty of opportunities in the Scranton-Wilkes Barre region to test the knowledge you gain at Marywood.  From the beginning of your freshman year, you'll participate in field experiences in public 
and private residential facilities and local special education classrooms.  Among the sites to choose from are the Lourdesmont Center (a facility for emotionally and socially disturbed adolescents); the Friendship 
House Children's Center (offering mental heath and mental retardation services); the Northeast 
Intermediate Unit; and the Scranton school district.  As a freshman, you'll observe students with various exceptionalities in diverse educational settings.  Sophomores are assigned as active participants in specific 
academic support areas.  By junior year, you'll begin diagnostic evaluation and prescriptive teaching; 
seniors do formal student teaching culminating in total classroom responsibility.  Along the way, you'll be guided by college faculty members and elementary and secondary school teachers.<p>


<h3>Requirements of the Program</h3>

The major in special education requires completion of 126 credits, 61 of which are requirements of the major (including courses in special education, general education, and psychology).  All undergraduate 
students at Marywood earn 64 credits in the core liberal arts and skills curriculum; you'll need to take specific courses within the liberal arts requirement to support the major (don't worry: you'll find these courses noted in the department handbook given to all enrolled special education students).  When you 
complete the departmental requirement, achieve certain competencies, and complete the appropriate NTE (National Teachers Exam) components, you'll be granted an Instructional I Certificate in special education of children and youth with mental/physical disabilities.<p>

You will also have the option of enrolling in the dual certification program with elementary education, which leads to teacher certification in both special and elementary education.  This option requires additional coursework.  Or you may decide to minor in special education, taking 18 credits in special education and spending 20 hours of observation in addition to your major in education.<p>

Whichever you choose, you'll be glad to know that Marywood's special education programs are accredited by the prestigious National Council for Accreditation of Teacher Education (NCATE) and approved by the Pennsylvania Department of Education.<p>

<h3>Just the Facts</h3>
 
Student:faculty ratio: 15:1<br>
Average class size: 15<p>

<b>After Marywood:</b> approximately 90% go directly into teaching or other special education careers; approximately 10% go on to graduate study.  Approximately 85% of students attend graduate school on a part-time basis while teaching.  Recent graduates have pursued further study at Bloomsburg University, George Washington University, Marywood College, Pennsylvania State University, and the University of Pittsburgh.<p>


<b>For more information, please contact:</b><br>

Dr. Tony Russo, Chair<br>
Department of Special Education	<br>
Marywood College<br>
Scranton, PA 18509<br>
717/348-6289<br>
russo@ac.marywood.edu<br>
http://www.marywood.edu<br>


