<IMG src="/images/mwlogos.jpg" align=left hspace=10> 
<H1>Marywood College</H1>

<H2>Social Sciences</H2>

<H2>Chairperson: Dr. John W. Barrett<BR>
</H2>
<HR>

<P>
At Marywood, you'll find a comprehensive program in the social
sciences, faculty members who care about you and your education-and
a wealth of options to prepare you for a challenging and rewarding
career.  An exciting spectrum of careers for the twenty-first
century will be built on a foundation in the social sciences.
Are you interested in the expanding field of health care, which
creates new opportunities daily? Perhaps you've always planned
to attend law school, or become active in politics, or work to
make public institutions better, or teach history? Maybe you want
to better the world through hands-on service in a social agency.
If any of these options-or the many other social science-based
 careers not mentioned here-inspire you, then Marywood can help
you reach your goal.
<P>
You'll find a comprehensive array of social science studies: criminal
 justice, economics, geography, health services administration,
history, legal studies, political science, public administration,
social work, and sociology. You'll combine social science courses
with others in the liberal arts to complete one of these majors:
Comprehensive Social  Sciences; Legal Studies; Health Services
Administration; or Social Work. Whatever you choose, you'll gain
the values, skills, and knowledge to help put into practice the
goal of every Marywood student's education: you'll be learning
to live responsibly in an interdependent world.
<H3>Faculty</H3>

<P>
You'll have ready access to the faculty in the social sciences;
they're dedicated to helping you put together a program to meet
your needs.  Faculty members teach the courses, give advice on
course selection,  collaborate on student research projects, and
still find time to stay current in the field. Faculty contribute
regularly to such journals as American Journal of Alzheimer's
Disease, Antioch Review, Ethnic History Review, Journal for the
Scientific Study of Religion, and The Political Chronicle. Among
the books published by faculty members are <B>Professor John W.
Barrett's</B> <I>Essentials of European History, 1789-1848: Revolutions
and the New European Order</I>; <B>Sister Margaret Gannon's</B>
<I>Paths of Daring, Deeds of Hope</I>; and <I>Classroom: The Computer
Simulated Teaching Experience</I>, by <B>Professor Frederick Fagal</B>.
In addition, faculty members present papers at such conferences
as the American Educational Research Association; the Social Science
History Association; the International Oral History  Association;
and the American Political Science Association.
<P>
<B>John W. Barrett, Ph.D.</B>, Chair (international diplomacy)

<P>
<B>Walter Broughton, Ph.D.</B> (health care services and family
life)
<P>
<B>Frederick F. Fagal, Jr., Ph.D.</B> (statistics, econometrics,
educational policy)
<P>
<B>Michael H. Freund, M.S.W.</B>, Director, Social Work (children's
issues, ethnic relations, social welfare policy)
<P>
<B>Sister Margaret Gannon, I.H.M., Ph.D.</B> (women's studies,
development studies)
<P>
<B>Thomas M. Jackson, J.D., Ph.D.</B>, Director, Legal Studies
(issues pertaining to constitutional law, especially factors underlying
presidential use of force)
<P>
<B>Kathleen P. Munley, Ph.D.</B> (ethnic studies, American labor
movement, American politics)
<P>
<B>Sister JoAnn Trama, I.H.M., M.S.W., Ph.D.</B> (family studies)
<H3>Facilities and Technology</H3>

<P>
The social sciences department benefits from Marywood's commitment
to provide all students with state-of-the-art technology. You'll
find computer facilities with the latest word processing and statistical
 software in the Learning Resources Center (LRC). The department's
suite of offices offers students computer access to the Internet
and to library systems as well as a conference room. The college
library has holdings of more than 200,000 volumes; 1,100 periodicals;
and 40,000 nonprint items. The library also participates in a
national and international interlibrary loan network with 5,000
other libraries.
<H3>The Regional Advantage: Putting Knowledge to Work</H3>

<P>
You'll find plenty of opportunities to increase your knowledge
and put theory into practice in the Scranton-Wilkes-Barre region.
Legal Studies majors intern in local law offices. Social Work
majors hone their skills in such social service agencies as the
Scranton Counseling Center and Catholic Social Services. Health
Services majors intern at local  hospitals. Social Science majors
gain experience in probation and parole at such settings as the
District Attorney's office and the U.S. Marshals Service. In addition,
you'll have the chance to learn from speakers  brought to campus
by student clubs and department honor societies to run seminars
and give lectures.
<H3>Requirements of the Program</H3>

<H3>Majors</H3>

<H4>B.A. in Comprehensive Social Sciences</H4>

<P>
This program leads to a comprehensive social sciences degree,
with a choice<BR>
of professional components.
<UL>
<LI>Comprehensive Social Sciences /General
<LI>Comprehensive Social Sciences/Criminal Justice
<LI>Comprehensive Social Sciences/History
<LI>Comprehensive Social Sciences/Public Administration
<LI>Comprehensive Social Sciences/Sociology
<LI>Comprehensive Social Sciences/Secondary Education
</UL>

<P>
The Comprehensive Social Sciences major prepares students for
careers and/or graduate study in the social science fields. Certification
for the teaching of social sciences on the elementary and secondary
levels is available through programs coordinated by the Education
and Social Sciences departments. Competency in the range of social
science fields provides students with a background for a variety
of careers. Professional options in Secondary Education, Public
Administration, History, Sociology, and Criminal Justice prepare
students for teaching and public service careers. Upon completion
of the program, the Bachelor of Arts in Comprehensive  Social
Sciences is awarded, along with a professional component, if chosen,
in Criminal Justice, Public Administration, Secondary Education,
History or Sociology.
<P>
All students in the comprehensive social sciences degree program
(except those in the education certification programs) must take
a common core of courses: Social Research, Computer Applications
in Social Research, and Coordinating Seminar in the Social Sciences.
All programs require a minimum of 127 credits for graduation;
the secondary education program requires 136 credits.
<H4>B.A. in Health Services Administration </H4>

<H4>B.A. in Health Services Administration/Gerontology</H4>

<P>
These interdisciplinary majors seek to develop in students the
values, knowledge, and skills necessary to enter the field of
health services  administration, with particular emphasis on new
directions in which the health care system is expanding. The majors
integrate courses from Business Administration and Social Sciences,
as well as the core component of liberal arts courses. Graduates
enter the job market in entry level positions pointing toward
health administration in general or in gerontology in particular.
The curriculum also prepares students for graduate school in the
fields of public health, public administration, and sociology.
Health Services Administration (General) students complete, in
addition to the College's core liberal arts sequence, five courses
in Business Administration, six required courses and two elective
courses in sociology and health services administration; four
courses in the areas of economics, law and politics, and three
courses in Public Administration.  Students concentrating in Gerontology
complete, in addition to the College's liberal arts requirement,
five courses in Business Administration, six required courses
and two elective courses in Sociology and Health Services Administration;
four courses in Gerontology; and four courses in the areas of
economics, law and politics.
<H4>B.A. in Legal Studies</H4>

<P>
<B>Preprofessional Program</B> 
<P>
This curriculum is designed for students preparing for a career
in law as an attorney. The program provides a liberal arts and
social science  foundation to enable a student to develop a broad
cultural background;  habits of thoroughness, intellectual curiosity
and scholarship; the ability to organize materials and communicate
the results; and verbal skills. In addition to the 64 credits
in the liberal arts area required of all Marywood students, 66
credits in history, political science, social  sciences, and legal
studies are required to fulfill the preprofessional  program.
<P>
<B>Legal Assistant Program</B> 
<P>
This program, accredited by the American Bar Association, provides
 preparation for a paralegal career. Graduates are qualified to
assume a position as an assistant to attorneys in various substantive
areas of the law. Students are trained to prepare, summarize and
interpret a variety of legal documents; do legal research; conduct
client interviews and maintain file control and handle other administrative
duties on behalf of an attorney. Students in the four-year B.A.
program and the two-year program graduate with a degree in Legal
Studies and a Legal Assistant diploma. The four-year program requires
127 credits; the two-year program, 63 credits.
<P>
<B>B.S.W. (Bachelor of Social Work)</B> 
<P>
This program, accredited by the Council on Social Work Education,
prepares students for beginning professional social work practice.
Students acquire the knowledge, values, ethics and skills necessary
for entering into social work practice at the beginning level
and are prepared as generalists able to help various size client
systems: individuals, families, groups,  organizations and communities.
Of the 64 credits in liberal arts required of all Marywood students,
15 are specified for Social Work majors. In addition, majors must
complete six credits in economics and politics and 48 credits
in the core Social Work curriculum, for a total of 127 credits.
<H3>Minors</H3>

<P>
Minors are available in Comprehensive Social Sciences, Sociology,
Criminal Justice, Legal Studies, and History. Eighteen credits
are required for a minor.
<H3>Sample Social Sciences Courses</H3>

<UL>
<LI>Criminal Justice Theory
<LI>Principles of Economics
<LI>Health Care and the
<LI>Helping Professional
<LI>American Foreign Policy
<LI>Minorities in the
<LI>Modern World
<LI>Constitutional Law
<LI>General Litigation
<LI>Social Problems
<LI>Legal Writing and Research
<LI>Dimensions of Public Administration
<LI>American Political Thought
<LI>Foundations of Social Work
</UL>

<H3>Just the Facts</H3>

<P>
Student: faculty ratio: 20:1<BR>
Average Class Size: 20<BR>
Degrees offered: B.A. in Comprehensive Social Sciences; B.A. in
Health Services Administration; B.A. in Legal Studies; B.S.W.
(Bachelor of Social Work)
<P>
After Marywood: Approximately 60% go directly into careers in
such fields as social work, teaching, paralegal work, and health
services  administration. Approximately 40% go on to further study
in law, the social sciences, and other fields, including recently
at Boston College, Johns Hopkins, Pennsylvania State University,
Syracuse University, The University of Connecticut, and The University
of Pittsburgh.
<P>
<B>For more information, please contact:</B> 
<P>
Dr. John W. Barrett, Chair<BR>
Social Sciences Department<BR>
Marywood College<BR>
Scranton, PA 18509<BR>
717/348-6288<BR>
barrett@ac.marywood.edu<BR>
http://www.marywood.edu<HR>

