<title>Marywood College</title></head>
<body background="/images/backgrnd.gif">
<img src="/images/mwlogos.jpg" align=left hspace=10>
<h1>Marywood College</h1><h2>Art Programs</h2>
<br clear=left>
<h2><i>Chairperson:  Mathew Povse, M.F.A</i></h2>
<hr>
<h3>Philosophy Statement of the Degree and the Department<br></h3>

In conjunction with the mission of the Graduate School of Arts and Sciences, 
Marywood's Art Department offers the Master of Arts and Master of Fine Arts 
degrees.<p>

The Master of Arts program in Studio Art is intended for graduates of schools 
and departments of art/art education who want to develop their talents as 
studio artists, illustrators and ad designers. Study with outstanding 
practitioners in these fields acts as a springboard for further professional 
growth and education.<p>

There are two tracks within the M.A. Studio Art program: "fine" art and 
"applied" art. The "fine" art track provides concentration within a studio area of emphasis (painting, clay, fibers, metal, printmaking, photography). The "applied" art track in illustration and ad design, "Get Your Master's with the Masters," is for working professionals and is scheduled so that they may 
continue to maintain full-time employment. Further information is available 
upon request from the Art Department.<p>

The Master of Arts program in Art Therapy is designed to help meet the need 
for trained professionals in the mental health field and in education, to assist in the development of persons through self-discovery, self-awareness and personal growth, using art as a catalyst for healing and self-actualization.  <p>

The personal development of the graduate student as therapist is essential to 
this program. Students use art therapy in collaboration with the approaches 
described by psychologists. Through a course of study combining theory and 
practice, the program follows guidelines for art therapy training 
recommended by the American Art Therapy Association.<p>

The Master of Arts Program in Art Education is intended for graduates of 
schools and departments of art/art education who are certified to teach. The 
program is designed to enrich the scope of their professional work and to 
extend their academic status.<p>

The Master of Fine Arts Program in Visual Arts is designed to provide 
professional emphasis for persons with an intense commitment to their art 
who intend to become serious professional artists. Concentrations within this 
program include: Clay, Fibers, Metal, Painting, Printmaking, Photography, Ad 
Design and Illustration. Students interested in the Ad Design or Illustration 
concentrations can begin in summer only.<p>

Each program is supported by accomplished, professional faculty, visiting 
artists of acclaim, impressive exhibit offerings and excellent academic and 
technical resources. In certain programs, there are both requirements and 
opportunities for internships/practica, museum research and study tours-all 
designed to provide experiences of breadth and depth for matriculating 
graduate students.<P>

<h3>Application Requirements</h3>

 Applicants to the M.A. and M.F.A. degree programs must meet the general 
requirements for admission to the Marywood Graduate School of Arts and 
Sciences. In addition, the applicant must satisfy the following: <P>

<h3>M.A. degrees in Studio Art and Art Education prerequisites:</h3>
<OL>
<LI>A baccalaureate degree in art or art education or an equivalent credit 
background in art that would support master's degree work. Any student 
who, in the judgment of the department, lacks adequate undergraduate 
preparation must arrange to make up the deficiency.
<LI>A portfolio of eighteen to twenty slides or original work, submitted no later than one month before the last official registration date. The portfolio 
will be judged on its demonstration of both conceptual ability and technical 
competency. 
</OL><p>
( A maximum of six graduate credits may be accepted for transfer.)<p>


A student must file an application for candidacy when twelve credit hours of 
studio work have been completed. Acceptance as a candidate will be decided 
after the following:<p>
<OL>
<LI>Successful completion of the Graduate Record Examination or the Miller Analogies Test.
<LI>Maintenance of a "B" average or better in twelve studio credits taken at Marywood.
<LI>Submission of a portfolio of work from the studio courses taken at Marywood.
<LI>Approval of the student's potential as a graduate student by a committee from the departmental faculty.
</OL>
<P>
Upon completion of 36 credits, a student must register the intention to bring 
the program to completion by means of a comprehensive examination and 
execution of a Professional Contribution.
<P>


<h3>M.A. degree in Art Therapy prerequisites:</h3>
<OL>
<LI>A baccalaureate degree with a major in art education or studio art, OR a baccalaureate degree in a related field (e.g. psychology, social work, counseling, special education). Students entering the Art Therapy program with either degree must have at least eighteen credits in studio art (color
theory, drawing and painting, figure-drawing/modeling and 3-D media) and twelve credits in psychology (general psychology, developmental psychology, abnormal psychology and personality theories).
<LI>Presentation of a portfolio of art, including significant examples of human figure work in the media noted above.
<LI>An autobiography and statement of academic/professional goal.
<LI>Evaluation of each candidate's individual competencies by an art therapy admissions committee. In addition, a personal interview may be required.
</OL>
<p>
(A maximum of six graduate credits may be accepted for transfer.)
<P>
A student must file an application for candidacy when eighteen credit hours 
have been completed. Acceptance as a candidate will be decided after the 
following:<p>
<OL>
<LI>Successful completion of the Graduate Record Examination or the Miller Analogies Test.
<LI>Maintenance of a "B" average or better in eighteen credits taken at Marywood.
<LI>Approval of the student's potential as a graduate student by a committee from the departmental faculty.
</OL>
<P>
After 300 hours of practicum experience, the student will be re-evaluated.
Upon completion of 48 credits, a student must register the intention to bring 
the program to completion by means of a comprehensive examination and 
execution of a Professional Contribution.<P>


<h3>M.F.A. degree prerequisites:</h3>
<OL>
<LI>A Bachelor of Arts degree in Art or a Bachelor of Fine Arts degree.
<LI>Completion of at least eighteen credits of upper division work in the area of concentration chosen and a "B" or 3.00 quality point average in that area. Students who do not meet the 3.00 grade point average, but who possess outstanding or unusual qualifications that promise a significant contribution to the Master of Fine Arts program, may petition for a special review from the Art Department graduate admissions committee.
<LI>A portfolio of studio work indicative of above-average or exceptional ability. No fewer than twenty 2" X 2" color slides should be presented. The majority of these should be in the area of the applicant's interest, but the portfolio also should include a lesser emphasis in related areas. Slides are to be labeled with the applicant's name, date of execution, size and medium of each work shown.
</OL>
<P>
In addition, a personal interview with the admissions committee may be 
required.<p>

The M.F.A. student is advised to take a minimum of twelve credits per 
semester.<p>

Within the M.F.A. program there are four reviews of work in progress and 
student development. These reviews are held after completion of 12, 24, 36 
and 48 semester hours of course work and are designated as follows: (a) 
Initial Review; (b) Candidacy Review; (c) Progress Review; (d) Qualifying 
Review.<p>

Qualifying Review will take place after the final draft of the thesis project 
(Artist's Statement) and prior to the exhibit.<p>

Failure to satisfy two consecutive reviews will result in 
dismissal from the 
program. A student denied advancement in the M.F.A. program may seek a 
Master of Arts in Studio Art at Marywood.<p>

At the scheduled Candidacy Review, the student must evidence a successful 
completion of the Graduate Record Examination or the Miller Analogies Test. 
At this time, any transfer credits will be evaulated by the department.
Upon completion of 60 credits, a student must register his or her intention to 
bring the program to completion. Thesis statement and one-person exhibit 
are required.<p>

Applications are due December 1st and July 15th.<P>

<hr>

<H2>Course of Study</H2><P>

<H2><U>Master of Arts in Studio Art</U></H2>
36 semester hours<BR>

<h3>I. CORE COURSES</h3>
6 semester hours<BR>
ART 546 Design Research	3<BR>
ART 641 The Arts OR ART 549 Aesthetics 	3<BR>

<BR>
<h3>II. CONCENTRATION IN STUDIO ART</h3>
18 semester hours<BR>
At least eighteen semester hours must be taken in the chosen studio field.<BR>
<BR>
<h3>III. ART ELECTIVES<BR></h3>
12 semester hours<BR>
<BR>
The remaining twelve semester hours may be chosen from courses offered in 
studio/art history areas other than the field of concentration.<BR>
<BR>
<h3>IV. PROFESSIONAL CONTRIBUTION (NO CREDIT)</h3>

<b>ART 555E:</b> required of each student at designated time prior to graduation. 
This must be an exhibit in the art gallery of Marywood College.<p>

