<h1>Marywood College</h1><H2>Business Programs
</H2>

<H2><i>Chairperson: S.P. Dagher, Ph.D.</i></H2>
<br clear=left><hr>



<H3>Statement of Philosophy</H3>
The graduate business program enables students to acquire and further 
develop their managerial skills to successfully meet the continuous challenge 
of a technological society and to nurture values conducive to ethical and 
socially responsible behavior.<P>

<H3>General Information</H3>
The following master's degrees are offered by the Marywood College 
Department of Business and Managerial Science:<P>


<b>Master of Business Administration (M.B.A.)<br>
Master of Science (M.S.)</b><br>

The Master of Business Administration degree provides the student with a 
common body of knowledge in business administration via the required "core 
courses" and undergraduate prerequisites for the degree. Students must take 
36 semester credit hours of graduate level courses. Prerequisites include 
eight modules: Accounting Concepts*, Business Economics*, Computer 
Technologies for Management*, Financial Tools*, Managerial Concepts*, 
Marketing and Sales Concepts*, The Legal Environment of Business* and 
Review of Business Statistics*. Those who do not have the needed 
undergraduate credits may be able to fulfill the requirements through 
equivalency exams (DANTE) or through modules offered by departmental 
faculty. For further information, contact the Department Chairperson. <p>

*One credit modules open to graduate students to satisfy undergraduate 
prerequisites. Others intending to register for these modules must have the 
permission of the Department Chair.<P>

In addition, if a student is pursuing the M.B.A. degree in Management 
Information Systems, prerequisites will also include two programming 
languages ("C", COBOL or RPG).<p>

The Master of Science degree program is designed to prepare candidates for 
career advancement and provides the graduate student with an area of 
specialization in Management Information Systems.  Students seeking  the 
M.S. degree in Management Information Systems will have the following 
prerequisites: Accounting I, Accounting II, Computer Tools for Management, 
Financial Management and two programming languages. However, the 
modules offered in the M.B.A. program will satisfy the requirements for 
Accounting, Computers and Finance.<P>

<H3>General Requirements</H3>
Students are required to file an application for candidacy with the 
Chairperson of the Business and Managerial Science Department after 
completing twelve graduate business credits in addition to the undergraduate 
prerequisites specified on their letters of admission. Scores on the Graduate 
Management Admission Test (GMAT) must be received at the time of 
application for candidacy.<P>
<hr>
<H3>Areas of Concentration</H3>
<H4>Courses and Objectives</H4>

<h3>1. Finance and Investment</h3>
The area of concentration in Finance and Investment is designed to<br>
 (1) provide a working understanding of the financial decision-making process in 
profit and nonprofit organizations and  (2) introduce the candidates to the functions of the financial market. This concentration is for career-oriented students in commercial and investment banking, corporate planning and treasury functions, and short-range and long-range domestic and 
international financial planning. Financial tools and techniques in acquisitions, 
divestments and investment analysis for domestic and overseas operations 
are some of the skills provided by this area of concentration.<P>

<h3>2. Industrial Management</h3>
The area of concentration in Industrial Management is designed to provide 
professional preparation for careers in personnel administration and 
industrial relations. The curriculum includes courses in Labor Relations, 
Industrial Psychology, Production Management, Systems Analysis and 
Design/Industrial Problem-Solving and Advanced Human Relations in 
Management.<P>

<h3>3. International Business</h3>

The area of concentration in International Business is intended both for those 
already in multinational corporations involved in international business and 
for those seeking careers in international business organizations. The field of 
training is concerned with finance, information and the flow of goods and 
services between or among nations.  Students concentrating in this field may 
select courses in Management of International Business Organizations, 
Financial Planning, Managerial Accounting, Tax Implications and International 
Marketing. Students are encouraged to be proficient in at least one foreign 
language; however, proficiency in a foreign language is not required.<P>

<h3>4. Management Information Systems</h3>
The area of Management Information Systems promotes the development of 
basic skills appropriate to professional management in the field of 
information science. It prepares the candidate for the evaluation and 
development of information systems within the organization. The student 
develops skills in evaluating current manual systems, designing broader 
computer systems and developing the broader computer systems into a 
totally automated management information system. Students are asked to 
select four courses in this area of concentration. Course selection includes: 
Computer Programming Languages, Systems Analysis and Design/Industrial 
Problem-Solving, Information Systems-Database Management, Accounting 
Information Systems and Telecommunication for Business Systems.<P>

<h3>5. Health Services Administration</h3>
A concentration in Health Services Administration (H.S.A.) is available to M.B.A. 
candidates who desire to prepare themselves for administration positions in 
the health care sector. This area is offered in cooperation with the Public 
Administration Department. The prescribed program requires the M.B.A. core 
courses which total 24 credits of graduate semester hours. The total number 
of credit hours for the M.B.A. with a concentration in the H.S.A. program is 42-
45, depending on the student's background. Admission criteria are identical to 
the requirements specified under the M.B.A. admission requirements and are 
the total responsibility of the graduate business admissions committee.<P>

<hr>
<H3>Master of Business Administration</H3>
Each candidate for the Master of Business Administration degree must select 
an area of concentration. Twelve credits are required in the concentration. 
However, students taking additional concentrations in the M.B.A. program can 
only cross reference one course or three credits. The available areas and core 
requirements are as follows:<BR>
36 semester hours<p>

