<h1>Marywood College</h1><h2>Education Programs </h2>
 <h2><i>Chairperson: Lois K. Draina, Ph.D.</i></h2> 
<br clear=left><hr>

 The diverse programs of the Graduate Education Department are designed to  
incorporate the latest research-based theories on teaching and learning. 
The general aim of all programs is to produce creative teachers who will use  
innovative methods of instruction to develop independent learners. 
The emphasis, therefore, in all courses, is placed on strategies which teachers  
can employ in the classroom to bring about active involvement on the part of  
the learners. <p>

The Graduate Education Department offers:  <p>
l.  M.S. in Reading Education <br>
2. M.A. in Teaching with Elementary Education Certification <br>
3. M.S. in Early Childhood Education <br>
4. M.S. in Elementary Education <br>
5. M.S. in Instructional Technology <br>
6. M.S. in School Leadership <p>
Each degree student enrolled in any of these education programs must  
complete candidacy requirements and submit an approved Professional  
Contribution. Additionally, the student must fulfill all degree requirements  
specific to the selected program. <p>
 
<h3>Certification Programs</h3>
 
Students may obtain a Pennsylvania Instructional I Certificate in Elementary  
Education and in specialized areas, K-12. Determination of what the individual  
student needs for certification will be made after all previous transcripts  
have been evaluated. A student seeking only certification is required to take  
at least fifty percent of the required specialty area credits at Marywood  
College. Eligibility for certification is determined by fulfillment of state  
requirements. State regulations in Chapter 49 of the Pennsylvania Code, 22 PA  
Code 49.18, require that those seeking their first Instructional I Certificate  
must demonstrate that they have successfully completed a teacher  
certification exam in these areas: <p>

 
<b>Core Battery<br>
<ul>
<li> General Knowledge (literature, fine arts, math, science, social studies) 
<li> Communication Skills (listening, reading, writing)
<li> Professional Knowledge (instructional skills)
<li> Specialty Area</b>
 </ul>

<h2>Areas of Certification </h2>
<ul>
<li>Art K-12 
<li>Biology 7-12 
<li>Communication 7-12 
<li>Early Childhood N-3 (requires ELEM ED) 
<li>Elementary K-6 
<li>Elementary Principal K-6 
<li>English 7-12 
<li>French 7-12 
<li>General Science 7-12 
<li>Health/Physical Ed K-12 
<li>Home Economics N-12 
<li>Instructional Technology Specialist K-12 
<li>Mathematics 7-12 
<li>Music K-12 
<li>Reading Specialist K-12 
<li>Reading Supervisor 
<li>Secondary Principal 7-12 
<li>Social Studies 7-12 
<li>Spanish K-12 
<li>Speech and Language Impaired K-12 
<li>Superintendent/Assistant Superintendent's Letter of Eligibility 
</ul><p>
 <hr>
<h3>Master of Science in School Leadership</h3>

36 semester hours <br>
The program in SCHOOL LEADERSHIP consists of 36 hours of graduate work. The  
courses are divided into three categories: nine semester hours in core  
courses which are intended to give the student an understanding of research,  
human development and foundations of education; twenty-four semester  
hours in concentration courses which provide an understanding of  
administration, current issues in education, curriculum planning, supervision  
and evaluation of instruction, law, finances, personnel leadership, and an  
internship in a school setting; three semester hours in elective courses. <p>

The purpose of this program is to provide opportunities for the development  
of the administrative and interpersonal skills needed by practicing and future  
leaders in education. The program is built on the assumption that the public  
and non-public school environments are unique. For this reason, courses and  
other learning experiences are deeply grounded in those principles of public  
and non-public thought and practice. Internships are individualized, based on  
needs and interests of school districts and student participants.   <p>

In addition to an initial interview with the Chairperson of the Department, a  
second interview at the time of candidacy with the Chairperson of the  
Department and a panel of administrators and the successful completion of  
course work, the degree candidate is required to complete a Professional  
Contribution consisting of an oral presentation to faculty and students on a  
topic chosen with the Program Director. To be eligible for an elementary or  
secondary school principal's certificate, the candidate must have had five  
years of professional school experience. <p>

 
<h3>I. CORE COURSES </h3>

9 semester hours <br>
*EDUC 	501 Research Theory 	3 <br>
*EDUC 	502 Multidisciplinary Foundations of Education	3 <br>
*PSY 	514 Human Development	3 <br>
