<h3>III. ELECTIVES </h3>

3 semester hours <br>
This program has been approved by the Pennsylvania Department of Education  
for awarding certification as an elementary and/or secondary principal. <p>
 
<b>*Certification Program in School Leadership </b><br>
Persons seeking an elementary and/or secondary school certificate in the  
Commonwealth of Pennsylvania, who do not wish to receive the Master of  
Science degree, may do so by taking only courses marked with an asterisk  
listed under the degree program. Initial interview and candidacy interview  
are also required. <p>

<h3>Superintendent Letter of Eligibility </h3>

The Superintendent's Letter of Eligibility will endorse an individual for  
appointment as a district superintendent or an assistant superintendent.  
Candidates for this post-masters certification shall: <p>

1. follow normal application procedures for admission to the Graduate School  
of Arts and Sciences, indicating desire to seek this certification. Candidates  
must possess a 3.0 average in all prior graduate work. <p>
2. successfully complete an interview after six credits if a master's degree in  
administration or master's degree plus administrative certification was not  
awarded at Marywood College. <p>
3. successfully complete a minimum of eighteen (18) semester hours in the  
following areas: <p>
<ul>
<li>EDUC 604 School, Community, Public Relations 	(3) 
<li>EDUC 605 Communication Theory and Organizational Dynamics 	(3) 
<li>EDUC 606 Labor Relations and Negotiations 	(3) 
<li>EDUC 607 Business and Facilities Management 	(3) 
<li>EDUC 608, 609 Field-Based Internship 	(6) 
</ul>

At the point of admission/acceptance, the Graduate Education Department  
and the Office of Certification will determine if the candidate has met all  
competencies as outlined by the State Department of Education. If it is  
determined that a candidate is lacking in an area typically part of the first  
administrative endorsement (principalship) more than eighteen (18) hours  
may be required. <p>

Likewise, if a candidate has fulfilled some of the courses required for the  
Letter of Eligibility certification, the courses will not be repeated. As with  
all certifications, fifty percent of required courses must be taken at  
Marywood. <p>

4. provide evidence of six (6) years of teaching or other professionally  
certificated service in basic education, three (3) years of which shall have  
been in supervisory or administrative positions. <p>

 <hr>
 
<h3>Master of Science in Early Childhood Education</h3>

30 semester hours <br>
The program in EARLY CHILDHOOD EDUCATION consists of 30 hours of graduate  
work. The courses are divided into three categories: nine semester hours in  
core courses, which are intended to give students an understanding of  
research, theories of learning and foundations of education; twelve semester  
hours in concentration courses, which provide content basic to the early  
childhood education field, and nine semester hours in elective courses, which  
are geared toward fulfilling the individual needs and interests of students in  
the field. This program is aimed at three different populations: (a) students  
already holding a bachelor's degree in Early Childhood Education; (b) students  
who already have K-6 certification but who also seek a Pennsylvania  
Instructional I Certificate in Early Childhood Education and (c) students  
intending to change their careers from another field to Early Childhood  
Education. The program is intended to serve the needs of teachers in day care  
centers, preschools, kindergartens and the primary grades. Furthermore, it  
addresses the needs of supervisors, administrators, consultants and directors  
of day care centers. In addition to the successful completion of the above  
course work, the candidate is required to pass a written comprehensive  
examination and to complete a Professional Contribution under the direction  
of a member of the graduate faculty. <p>
 
<h3>I. CORE COURSES </h3>
9 semester hours <br>
EDUC 501 Research Theory	3 <br>
EDUC 502 Multidisciplinary Foundations of Education	3 <br>
EDUC 554 Contemporary Learning Theories 	3 <br>
EDUC 555 Professional Contribution 	0 <p>

