<h3>Master of Science in Instructional Technology</h3>

<h4>Coordinator: Sister Patt Walsh, I.H.M. </h4>
36 semester hours <br>
Orchestrated using a brain-compatible learning model, the INSTRUCTIONAL  
TECHNOLOGY Program leads to: <p>
<ul>
<li>PDE certification: Instructional Technologist (24 Credits) 
<li>M.S. in Instructional Technology (36 Credits) 
</ul><p>

IT courses are available in a variety of delivery modes; contact the  
Coordinator for details. Both the certification and the degree programs are  
aimed at meeting the needs of technology coordinators as well as classroom  
teachers seeking to maintain competence in the ever emerging field of  
instructional technology. Though K-12 will serve as the primary focus area,  
instruction is relevant to those seeking positions both in higher education and  
in non-traditional educational settings where the skills of an instructional  
technologist are essential to respond to staff development needs. An  
instructional technologist is considered a "generalist" - one who understands  
both the instructional design process and the technologies that can be  
utilized to best meet the learners' needs. <p>

 
<h3>I. CORE COURSES </h3>

9 semester hours <br>
(required for M.S. degree) <br>
EDUC 501 Research Theory	3 <br>
EDUC 502 Multidisciplinary Foundations of Education	3 <br>
EDUC 554 Contemporary Learning Theories	3 <i>OR </i><br>
MED 554 Brain Compatible Approach to Technology Integration 	3<br> 
MED 555 Professional Contribution	0 <br>
(required for M.S. degree) <p>
 
<h3>II. CONCENTRATION </h3>

24 semester hours <br>
(required for M.S. degree) <br>
*MED  521 Integrating Technology into the Classroom	3 <br>
*MED  515 Issues in Technology Management	3 <br>
*MED 522 Computing and Cooperative Learning 	3 <br>
*MED 524 Instructional Design: Theory and Applications 	3 <br>
*MED 591 Internship 	3 <br>
*MED 520 Models and Modes of Distance Education 	3 <br>
*MED 523 Networks and Databases 	3 <br>
*MED 527 Utilization and Evaluation of Software 	3 <br>
*MED 526 Problems and Issues in Instructional Technology 	3 <br>
*MED 525 Authoring, Presentation, and Desktop Publishing Applications  
	3 <br>
*MED 511 Contemporary Trends in Telecommunications Seminar 	3 <br>
*MED 566 Independent Study 	3 <br>
Students pursuing the PDE certificate need to complete 24 MED credits  
(*courses required) <p>

