*Courses leading to Certification. <p>

<b>EDUC 500,</b> First Semester Certification Seminar, is also required of new  
students seeking an Instructional I Certificate.  <p>

In addition to the successful completion of the course work, a degree  
candidate is required to complete a Professional Contribution under the  
direction of a member of the graduate faculty. Students seeking initial  
certification as part of this program satisfy this requirement by the  
successful completion of a student teaching experience. <p>

<hr>
 
<h3>Courses</h3>

 
<h3>School Leadership</h3>

 
<b>545 Administrative Theory for School Leaders (3)</b><br>
Examines the role of the administrator as instructional leader, manager and  
leader of the community within the school environment. Theory derived from  
leadership principles and current concepts of administration. Communication  
and decision-making skills are emphasized. <p>

 
<b>546 Seminar: Current Problems and Issues in Education (3)</b><br>
Examines practical issues of current concern in education. <p>
 
<b>547 Curriculum Planning for Schools (3)</b><br>
Designed to aid the school administrator, curriculum/media specialist and  
teacher in the role of instructional leader. Augments, through practical  
application, various curriculum theories and trends.  Instructional design and  
curriculum building competencies are stressed. <p>
  
<b>548 Supervision and Evaluation of Instruction (3)</b><br>
Provides the administrator with the knowledge and skills needed to supervise  
faculty and evaluate quality of program instruction. Various approaches will  
be investigated with an emphasis on models of clinical supervision. <p>
 
<b>549 Law and the School (3) </b><br>
Includes an analysis of the legal issues affecting schools. <p>
 
<b>551 School Finances (3)</b><br>
Focuses on aspects of financing needed by school administrators. Includes  
areas such as budgeting, marketing and planning. <p>
 
<b>552 Personnel Leadership in Schools (3)</b><br>
Designed to aid in the development of those skills needed for effective  
leadership in the area of recruitment and hiring of faculty and staff and for  
developing relationships among faculty, students and the community.  
Communication and decision-making skills are emphasized. <p>
 
<b>593 Administrative Internship (3)</b><br>
A structured internship at a selected educational institution, designed to give  
the student practice in school administration. <p>
 
<b>604 School, Community, Public Relations (3)</b><br>
Examines the role of the school district in the life of the civic community.  
Develops public relations programs that effect positive school-community  
interaction. Stresses effective relationships between central office personnel  
and school board. <p>
 
<b>605 Communication Theory and Organizational Dynamics (3)</b><br>
Further develops communication theory first explored in principalship  
program. Stresses effective communication skills. Explores organizational  
systems and related social structures. Stresses motivation theory and change  
dynamics. <p>
 
<b>606 Labor Relations and Negotiations (3)</b><br>
Explores collective bargaining, negotiation skills, union movements and  
related contemporary issues critical to central office leadership. <p>
 
<b>607 Business and Facilities Management (3)</b><br>
Examines financing and construction of educational facilities. Explores  
current state regulations on new and renovated facilities. Gives special  
emphasis to bonding initiatives and aesthetic and environmental concerns. <p>
 
<b>608, 609 Field-Based Internship (6)</b><br>
This course provides an opportunity for the student participant to integrate  
theory and practice in the field of central school office administration. It is  
an individualized program, designed by the student, a faculty mentor and a  
site supervisor. It addresses competencies explored during course work. The  
internship is accomplished at a central school office site. <p>
 
 
<h3>Education-Early Childhood/Elementary</h3>

 
<b>000* Field Experience (0) - Section 09 </b><br>
Involves weekly experience with children and youth in participating public  
and private local schools and service agencies. Requires registration in the  
Office of Educational Field Experience each semester. The minimum hours  
must be met for "satisfactory" grading. <p>

 
<b>442* Student Teaching (6,6)</b><br>
Involves supervised, full-time classroom teaching with gradual assumption of  
total teaching responsibilities in two different placements. Requires  
registration in the Field Experience Office. <p>
 
<b>451* Student Teaching Seminar (1.5)</b><br>
Considers the expanding scope of elementary education, with emphasis on  
evaluative, humanistic, sociological and legal aspects of the  
teaching/learning process. Incorporates research and experience gained  
through student teaching. (In cases where student teaching is done in an  
international setting, 1.0 credit seminar is required.) <p>
 
<b>470* Elementary Curriculum</b><br>
Examines instructional strategies, activities and materials for achieving a  
beginning competence in teaching in these areas: language arts, music/art,  
mathematics, science, social studies and physical education and health.  
Observation and participation in school situations are incorporated into  
course activities. <p>

D-Music/Art 	3 <br>
F-Math	3 <br>
G-Science 	3 <br>
H-Social Studies	3 <br>
J-Physical Education/Health	2 <br>
<i>*These courses, plus EDUC 511, R ED 524 and R ED 526, are intended primarily  
for persons seeking a Pennsylvania Instructional I Certificate in the field of  
elementary education. </i><p>

 
<b>471, 472 The First Five Years: Part I, Part II (3, 3)</b><br>
Children's learning from birth to age five in the context of modern theory is  
covered. Emphasis is also on cognitive development, with special reference to  
curriculum development, organization of learning environments, integrated  
theory and practical applications. <p>
  
<b>473 A, B Teaching Internship (12)</b><br>
Students officially enrolled in Marywood's teaching intern program fulfill  
their student teaching requirements through participation in this semester- 
long course. Once an intern student secures full-time employment in a school  
district, he/she must register for this course. Marywood's teacher intern  
supervisors participate in the supervision of the intern during the semester. <p>
 
<b>498 Elective Modules (l)</b><br>
The following modules are representative of the topics covered: first  
aid/personal safety, nutrition, infant at risk, child abuse and neglect, music  
and movement, microcomputer applications, multicultural activities. These  
one credit electives are graded satisfactory/unsatisfactory. <p>
 
<b>500 First Semester Certification Seminar (0)</b><br>
Scheduled each fall and spring semester, this two-hour seminar orients  
elementary, secondary, special education and K-12 students to academic  
requirements and procedures. Includes observational skills, data-gathering  
techniques, methods of evaluating data from field experience and related  
general topics. <p>
 
<b>501 Research Theory (3)</b><br>
Introduction to the methodology of research-historical, descriptive-survey,  
experimental design, critical interpretation and case study techniques - with  
attention to specialized data-gathering procedures, such as the  
questionnaire, the interview, observation, etc.; introduction to statistical  
concepts. Directed toward the writing of a minor thesis as a degree  
requirement. <p>
 
<b>502 Multidisciplinary Foundations of Education (3)</b><br>
Basic principles of educational theory derived from a study of major works  
and integrated theories from theology, philosophy and social sciences.  
Research of the social sciences on educational problems, processes and value.  
Contemporary issues and practice explored. <p>
 
<b>503 Research Applications: Design and Analysis (3)</b><br>
Engages students in the application of Research Theory (EDUC 501). Two major  
areas of focus are measurement and data analysis techniques appropriate for  
master's level research projects. Students construct instruments, collect  
data and analyze data using appropriate computer software.  Use of  
computer as a research tool is emphasized. <p>
 
<b>506 Problems and Issues in Early Childhood Education (3)</b><br>
Survey of traditional and new programs with special reference to societal  
changes. In-depth study of selected problems in home and child-care  
settings. <p>
 
<b>509 Administration, Organization and Supervision of Early Childhood Education Programs (3)</b><br>
Physical structure, organization and management of environments for young  
children. Study of professional leadership in establishing and maintaining  
effective programs. <p>
 
<b>511 Children's Literature for Early Childhood and Elementary School Teachers (1.5 or 2)</b><br>
Presents a brief history of children's literature, the characteristics of  
twentieth century publications for children, with the relationship between  
literature read by children and the psychology of the child. Evaluation of  
representative current and retrospective titles for classroom use. <p>
 
<b>514 Creative Arts for Young Children (3)</b><br>
Creativity as it relates to art, music and movement activities. <p>
 
<b>515 The Role of Movement in Early Learning (3)</b><br>
Physiological development, motor development and physical education  
activities, with a particular emphasis in pre-school and primary grades. <p>
 
<b>516 Computer Literacy (3)</b><br>
Exploration of the rapidly expanding world of computing in pre-college  
education. An examination of the place of the microcomputer in the learning  
process. Topics include computer-assisted instruction, computers in the arts  
and humanities and ethical and social issues. <p>
 
<b>517 Mathematics for Elementary Teachers (3)</b><br>
Discussion and investigation of the properties of the natural numbers, the  
integers, the rational numbers and the real numbers as these topics may be  
encountered in the elementary school curriculum. <p>
 
<b>518 Techniques of Discipline in Early Childhood Programs (3)</b><br>
Creating rapport; setting clear and precise limits; specific problems and  
alternate solutions, with a special emphasis in preschool and primary grades. <p>
 
<b>521 Learning Problems of the Gifted (3)</b><br>
Understanding the gifted, the gifted underachiever, culturally deprived and  
disadvantaged gifted, with a particular emphasis in the primary and  
elementary grades. <p>
 
<b>523 Seminar: Psychology of Education (3)</b><br>
This course deals with the dynamics of teacher-student-other relationships  
with consideration of learning and classroom management.  Analyzes  
individual differences of students in relation to the educative process.   
Emphasis on relating educational research to current school practice. Lesson  
plan and unit plan designs are covered. <p>

 
<b>526 Elementary Math and Cooperative Learning (3)</b><br>
This course integrates cooperative learning models, teaching  
recommendations from the National Council of Teachers of Mathematics and  
practical applications, involving the use of computers.  A variety of  
cooperative learning strategies will include hands-on activities, modeling  
activities and the use of concrete examples, specifically related to the  
teaching of mathematics. <p>
 
<b>529 Montessori: Theory into Practice (3)</b><br>
Discusses philosophical concepts and theory underlying Montessori education.  
Provides experience with Montessori materials in a Montessori setting. <p>
 
<b>530 The World of Children's Play (3)</b><br>
Theories of play from Plato to Piaget. Analysis of playthings and play  
environments. Study of play as a vehicle for cognitive, affective and  
psychomotor development. <p>
 
<b>537 Essentials of School Law for Teachers (3)</b><br>
Principal provisions in school law affecting teachers. Constitutional,  
statutory, ruling-case and common-law bases for public education  
interpretation; legal procedures. Particular emphasis on Pennsylvania school  
law.<p> 
 
<b>540 Behavioral Problems and Classroom Interaction (3)</b><br>
Deals with interaction between teacher and pupils with effective means of  
dealing with personality and attitudinal problems that influence instruction  
and learning. <p>
 
<b>543 Children with Learning Disabilities in the Regular Classroom (3)</b><br>
Emphasizes identifying learning disabilities within the regular classroom;  
choosing appropriate testing procedures and interpreting findings;  
appropriate and pragmatic approaches to be implemented by the classroom  
teacher; setting up a diagnostic team; training volunteers and parents to  
work with students who have learning disabilities. <p>
 
<b>550 Directed Readings (3)</b><br>
Individually directed readings providing for the special needs of particular  
students. Conferences with instructor and a written report of work required.  
Taken only with permission of Chairperson. <p>
 
<b>554 Contemporary Learning Theories (3)</b><br>
Emphasizes the aspects of learning theory having direct bearing on the  
teaching-learning process. Included: points of view that need to be  
understood by teachers so they might be discerning in their procedures in the  
classroom, their reading of materials in the field and their participation in  
professional discussions. A number of theorists are emphasized. <p>
 
<b>555 Professional Contribution (no credit)</b><br>
Thesis, project, series of demonstrations or professional performance. <p>
 
<b>500A Seminar: First Semester Research (no credit)</b><br>
Orientation to the Professional Contribution procedure. Required of all  
students registering for Professional Contribution for the first time. <p>
 
<b>560 Development of Thinking Skills in Young Children (3)</b><br>
Focus on thinking and the use of thinking games. <p>
 
<b>566 Independent Study (variable credit)</b><br>
Material geared to the needs of the individual student under the direction of  
a member of the graduate faculty, with permission of the Chairperson. <p>
 
<b>570 Utilization and Evaluation of Software (3)</b><br>
Includes discussion regarding capabilities of the computer and how to  
evaluate potential classroom materials. Investigation of appropriate  
characteristics in instructional software. <p>
 
<b>571 Programming for Microcomputers (3)</b><br>
An introductory computing course in reading and writing simple programs.  
Includes problem-solving and test manipulation as well as record-keeping  
and educational administration systems. <p>
 
<b>592 Supervised Internship (variable)</b><br>
Coordinated, guided study in selected school setting or other agency.  
Intended for students who need practical experience in one or more of the  
following areas: observation, teaching, curriculum development, assessment,  
administration. The internship experience is arranged in cooperation with the  
Office of Field Experience. <p>
 
<h3>Instructional Technology</h3>

 
<b>511 Contemporary Trends in Telecommunication Seminar (3)</b><br>
Seminar will survey the trends in emerging technologies and their impact on  
the field of instructional technology. Discussion will focus on the implications  
of these trends on the role of the instructional technologist, so that one  
might best be prepared to understand, manage and direct the focus of  
technology development in instruction. <p>
 
<b>515 Issues in Technology Management (3)</b><br> 
Organization of instructional technology programs on the building, district  
and college levels - including a technological in-service program. Course will  
also study the laws and regulations which govern the selection and utilization  
of media. <p>
 
<b>520 Models and Modes of Distance Education (3)</b><br>
Distance Education - from print based-correspondence courses to compressed  
video interactive experiences - will be analyzed, and the appropriate  
teaching techniques that best respond to each delivery option will be  
identified. <p>

 
<b>521 Integrating Technology into the Classroom (3)</b><br>
A laboratory course in various classroom technologies (from overhead and  
slide projectors through still and motion photography into emerging  
interactive technologies) and materials, including demonstration and  
operation; criteria of applicability, selection and evaluation. Demonstrations  
and projects applicable to classroom teachers as well as technology  
coordinators, including the preparation and production of inexpensive  
resources will highlight the course. <p>
 
<b>522 Computing and Cooperative Learning (3)</b><br>
The theories of cooperative learning will be defined, and then applied to  
computing classroom and laboratory situations. A variety of group settings  
will be examined to identify the appropriate procedures and responsibilities  
that should be followed to enhance the teaching and learning experience. <p>
 
<b>523 Networks and Databases (3)</b><br>
Application of reference and research principles will be applied to both  
database searching and the principles and skills involved in establishing a  
database. Study will include various network structures - including LAN, WAN  
and the Internet. <p>
 
<b>524 Instructional Design: Theory and Applications (3)</b><br>
Course will study curriculum development and instructional design theory.  
Systematic models such as needs assessment and task analysis, as well as  
instructional design, will be applied to curriculum development issues. <p>
 
<b>525 Authoring, Presentation and Desktop Publishing Applications (3)</b><br>
This course will give students hands-on experience with three different  
software applications: an authoring program, a presentations package and a  
desktop publishing application. Software selected for each course listing will  
be appropriate either to the Macintosh or the MS-DOS/Windows environment. <p>
 
<b>526 Problems and Issues in Instructional Technology (3)</b><br>
Seminar will examine specific issues in Internet technologies, new product  
developments and school technology issues. Opportunity will also be provided  
for hands-on experiences as well as discussion with practitioners and  
vendors. <p>
 
<b>527 Utilization and Evaluation of Software (3)</b><br>
Course includes discussion regarding the capabilities of the computer and  
how to evaluate potential classroom materials - from software to videodisk  
and CD-ROM. Investigation of the appropriate characteristics of instructional  
software will be conducted including the selection and use of materials  
relevant to a multi-cultural society. <p>
 
<b>554 Brain Compatible Approach to Technology Integration (3)</b><br>
-----The latest theories in brain research will be examined, and their implications  
for effective integration of technology into the instructional process will be  
defined. A plan for creating a brain-compatible, technology-rich classroom  
environment will be designed. <p>
 
<b>555 Professional Contribution (no credit)</b><br>
Closure experience required for degree completion - includes report that  
demonstrates research skills in a survey of the literature as well as selection  
and application of an appropriate instructional design model. Final product  
should also demonstrate competency in a technology field of the student's  
choice. <p>
 
<b>566 Independent Study (3)</b><br>
Material geared to the needs of the individual student and under the direction  
of a member of the graduate faculty, the independent study option allows the  
student to pursue further opportunities to enhance skills in a technology area  
of the student's choice. <p>
 
<b>591 Internship (3)</b><br>
The Internship experience requires one hundred and fifty hours of supervised  
experience in an instructional technology setting. Students seeking PDE  
certification need to complete the experience in a K-12 related environment,  
others may complete part or all of the required hours in a higher education,  
health care or other non-traditional educational setting. <p>
 
 
<h3>Reading Education</h3>
 
<b>524 Creative Teaching of Language Arts (4)</b><br>
This course explores several models of the reading process. Cognitive,  
psycholinguistic and sociolinguistic theories about how children learn are  
researched. Teachers are introduced to instructional strategies and activities  
that will enable them to actively involve children in the use of language. <p>
 
<b>526 Teaching Content Area Reading (3)</b><br>
This course acquaints students with the recent theories regarding the reading  
process and extends their knowledge on how children read to learn. Emphasis  
is placed upon the psycholinguistic theory of reading; the place of  
metacognition in the reading act  and the relationship that exists between  
teacher, student and text. Instructional strategies are presented to enable  
the teacher to make a practical application of the theories and models  
presented. <p>
 
<b>530 Reading Disabilities and Diagnosis (3)</b><br>
The course focuses on the correlates of reading disabilities and the types of  
informal and formal assessments that can be employed to determine the  
extent of a reading problem. Students have the opportunity to test and  
diagnose children and/or adults under the supervision of an experienced  
clinician. Case studies analyzing the testing information are a requirement of  
the course. <p>
 
<b>533 Remedial Techniques (3)</b><br>
Emphasis in this course is on the different methods and materials that can be  
used to correct the various types of reading problems. More detailed testing  
procedures are also introduced and administered to clients under supervision.  
Case studies analyzing testing results also include instructional programs  
designed to correct specific reading problems. <i>(Prerequisite: R ED 530.)</i> <p>
 
<b>540 Practicum/Seminar (3)</b><br>
Students have the opportunity to test, diagnose and implement a reading  
program for clients. Actual teaching of clients takes place under supervision.  
Practical experience includes: a. audiotaping, videotaping and critiquing of  
testing and teaching; b. writing of case reports; c. interviewing of parents,  
including interpretation of test results and recommendations for continued  
improvement of clients; d. exchanging of ideas with instructor and peers.  
<i>(Prerequisites: R ED 524, R ED 526, R ED 530, R ED 533.)</i> <p>
 
<b>542 Organization of School Reading Programs (3)</b><br>
This course explores current organizational patterns of reading instruction  
and the organization and administration of school reading programs. It  
includes "working sessions" in the development of a philosophy, goals,  
behavioral objectives, resources, program planning, selection procedures, in- 
service education, budgets and evaluation of school reading programs. <p>
 
<b>593 Internship for Reading Supervisor (3)</b><br>
This course provides an opportunity for the integration of theory and practice  
in the field of reading. It is an individualized program, designed by the  
candidate and a mentor. It may include experiences with curriculum  
development, community relations, policy determination, management, staff  
development, instructional design and personal professional development.  
The internship can be accomplished under supervision at the candidate's  
school. <p>



