<h1>Marywood College</h1>

<H2>Foods and Nutrition Program<br clear=left>

Interim Director: Lee Harrison, Ph.D., R.D.</H2><hr>

<H3>Philosophy and Goals:<br></H3>
The Graduate Foods and Nutrition program is housed within the Department of Human Ecology. The overall goal of the course of study is to develop competent professionals who will show responsible leadership and service in meeting human needs. The program aims to provide quality didactic learning experiences which will strengthen the student's background in foods and 
nutrition.<BR>
The objectives of the program include: <BR>
<OL>
<LI>Preparation of students who can think critically in the theoretical and practical areas of foods and nutrition.
<LI>Development of basic knowledge and skills necessary to undertake research in nutrition science, sports nutrition, nutrition support/critical care, nutrition education or food systems management. 
<LI>Achievement of necessary skills and competence to allow students to enter the job market or to continue professional growth within their chosen specialty area. 
</OL>


<H3>Specializations: <br></H3>
Five specific specializations are available in the Graduate Foods and Nutrition program. Students may either identify one area of concentration or choose a generalist orientation by selecting course work from two or more areas.<BR>
<DL>
<OL>
<LI><DT>SPORTS NUTRITION<dd>The specialization in Sports Nutrition is designed to meet the needs of individuals who are interested in pursuing a course of study that integrates nutrition and physical activity in the lives of individuals who seek optimal physical fitness. Graduates of this specialization will be employable in the community and industry where there is a commitment to health promotion, wellness and preventive health care.
<LI><DT>NUTRITION SUPPORT/CRITICAL CARE<dd>The specialization in Nutrition Support/Critical Care is designed to meet the needs of individuals who are interested in pursuing a course of study that will allow them to develop the skills and competencies necessary to provide quality nutrition care to clients in an acute and long-term care setting. Graduates of this specialization will be employable in hospitals, extended care facilities and other health care facilities as clinical dietitians. 
<LI><DT>NUTRITION EDUCATION<dd>The specialization in Nutrition Education is designed to meet the needs of individuals who are interested in obtaining a comprehensive updating of nutrition knowledge and expanding their communication skills. Graduates of this specialization will be employable in the community as nutritionists, educators or health care specialists. 
<LI><DT>FOOD SYSTEMS MANAGEMENT<dd>The specialization in Food Systems Management is designed to meet the needs of individuals who want to develop administrative competence in the management of personnel and resources in food service. Graduates of this specialization will be employable in industry, schools, hospitals, nursing homes and other health care facilities as administrative dietitians. 
<LI><DT>GERONTOLOGY<dd>The specialization in Gerontology is available for professionals who intend to apply the principles of foods and nutrition in a setting serving the needs of an aging population. This is an interdisciplinary program, the completion of which requires the Foods and Nutrition core sequence in addition to prescribed courses from other contributing departments. The joint approval of the directors of the Foods and Nutrition Program and the Gerontology Institute is required.
</OL>

</DL>


<H3>General Program Requirements:<br></H3>
Applicants to the graduate program in Foods and Nutrition are required to have earned degrees in nutrition, foods or dietetics from an accredited undergraduate institution. Other individuals are encouraged to apply with the understanding that they may be required to take various undergraduate courses as prerequisites to satisfy the departmental admissions committee. <BR>

<H3>Dietetic Internship (DI)<br></H3>
<STRONG>DESCRIPTION:</STRONG> The DI is a ten-month, full-time program which provides the practical experience necessary to qualify a student to sit for the Registration Examination.
Students spend 32 hours per week at a field site, gaining experience with a variety of nutritional care, food systems management and community nutrition activities.
  Additionally, there are weekly meetings for seminars, other academic exercises and networking sessions.
Students are also required to enroll in five graduate courses, H EC 501, 508, 536, 581 and 582, which are part of the Master of Science degree program in Foods and Nutrition. Although completion of the M.S. program is not required for registration eligibility,
 students have the opportunity to earn a degree by taking additional course work in the year following the internship experience.<BR>

writing to the Marywood College Financial Aid Office.<BR>
<STRONG>ACCREDITATION STATUS:</STRONG> The DI at Marywood College has been granted Developmental Accreditation Status by the Commission on Accreditation/Approval for Dietetics Education of the American Dietetic Association.<BR>
<STRONG>ADMISSION REQUIREMENTS:</STRONG>  Admission to the DI is competitive. A DI selection committee reviews the application packets of candidates and ranks them on the basis of grade point average, statement of intent and professional goals, quality of letters of recommendation, past work/volunteer experience and overall appearance of the record of the candidate. Ten students are usually selected each year.<BR>
Further information may be obtained by contacting the Program Director.<P>

<H3>Program of Study<br></H3>

<H3>Master of Science in Foods and Nutrition<BR></H3>
36 semester hours<BR>
CORE COURSES <BR>
18 semester hours<BR>
H EC 560 Nutritional Biochemistry	3<BR>
H EC 581 The Energy Nutrients and Alcohol	3<BR>
H EC 582 Vitamins and Minerals	3<BR>
H EC 590 Research Methodology	3<BR>
H EC 595 Research Thesis	3<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Statistics requirement: </STRONG>All students must complete a statistics course in preparation for their theses. This may be accomplished either by enrolling in a graduate level course or by presenting evidence of successful completion of an undergraduate class. In the latter case, an additional three credits should be selected within the specialization areas.<P>
<H3>SPECIALIZATION </H3>
18 semester hours<BR>
<STRONG>A. Sports Nutrition<BR></STRONG>
