<h1>Marywood College</h1><h2>Music Programs</h2>

<h2><i>Chairperson: 
Sister Joan Paskert, I.H.M., M.M<br>
Assistant Chairperson:
Sister Miriam Joseph Reinhardt, I.H.M., Ph.D.</i><br></h2>

<br clear=left><hr>


In accordance with the goals and objectives of Marywood College, the Master 
of Arts degrees in Music are directed toward the full development of the 
candidate as a person and as a musician.<p>

Three degree programs are offered to provide a continuing education 
designed to promote growth, to enrich and update the professional area in 
which the individual functions and to prepare the graduate for further study.
Applicants for a Master of Arts degree in Music must have a bachelor's degree 
in music or a bachelor's degree in another subject plus the equivalent in 
musical studies. Admission to any of the programs will be based on the 
general requirements of the graduate school and upon the recommendations 
of a departmental admissions committee. The Subject Area Graduate Record 
Exam and an audition/interview are required before completion of nine 
credits.<p>

Candidates are required to complete 36 semester hours. An advisor assists 
each student in choice and sequence of courses based upon the program 
elected, background and chief musical interest. Courses are offered in 
summer only. Other studies are available in fall and spring as well.
In addition to required courses, the candidate must successfully pass a 
comprehensive examination and complete a Professional Contribution under 
the direction of a member of the faculty of the Department of Music. The 
Professional Contribution for the Master of Arts in Musicology must be a 
thesis. For the other two degrees, it may take the form of a thesis, a project, 
a series of demonstrations or, with the consent of a recital committee, a 
recital.<p>

<h2>Master of Arts in Music Education;</h2>
36 semester hours (12 hours from each category)<br>
