<h2>Courses</h2>

<b>501 Microcomputer Literacy for Music Educator and Musician (3)</b><br>
"Hands-on" experience writing basic programs to solve problems in the music 
and music education fields; review of available packaged programs using DAC 
board; discussion of steps for program evaluation.<p>

<b>506 Psychology of Music (3)</b><br>
The psychological, physiological and aesthetic impact of musical stimuli on 
people and their musical education.<p>

<b>507 Music in the Middle Ages (3)</b><br>
A study of Western European monophonic and polyphonic music from the ninth 
through fourteenth centuries; includes transcription and performance.<p>

<b>508 Gregorian Chant (3)</b><br>
A practical course in singing Gregorian Chant using modern Gregorian 
notation. History, terminology, conducting and accompaniment of chant are 
included.<p>

<b>511 Analytical Techniques (3)</b><br>
Analytical approaches to major works from the eighteenth and nineteenth 
centuries; compositional techniques and stylistic differences.<p>

<b>512 Music in the Renaissance (3)</b><br>
A study of liturgical and nonliturgical music from the fifteenth to the 
seventeenth centuries.<p>

<b>513 Music in the Baroque (3)</b><br>
A study of the various genres of vocal and/or instrumental music from the 
seventeenth to the mid-eighteenth centuries.<p>

<b>514 Music in the Twentieth Century (3)</b><br>
A study of major developments in concepts and style of twentieth century 
music, with emphasis varying from year to year on specific composers and/or 
forms.<p>

<b>515 Improvisation and Transposition (3)</b><br>
A study of the principles involved and practical application in realizing 
improvisations and transposition in various styles and idioms.<p>

<b>516 Music in the Classic Era (3)</b><br>
A study of the various genres of vocal and/or instrumental music from the 
mid-eighteenth to the early nineteenth centuries.<p>

<b>518 Music in the Romantic Era (3)</b><br>
A history of musical style from Beethoven to Wagner, with emphasis varying 
from year to year on specific composers and/or forms.<p>

<b>520 Advanced Instrumental Conducting (3)</b><br>
Advanced rehearsal and conducting techniques for orchestra, band and stage 
band.<p>

<b>521 Seminar in Elementary Education (3)</b><br>
A course consisting of a discussion and consideration, through oral and 
written reports by each student, of recent practices, issues and materials in 
elementary music education. <i>(Prerequisite: experience in elementary music 
education.)</i><p>

<b>522 Seminar in Secondary Education (3)</b><br>
A course consisting of a discussion and consideration, through oral and 
written reports by each student, of a balanced music program for junior-
senior high school students, with special attention to curricula techniques and 
materials for general music. <i>(Prerequisite: experience in secondary music 
education.)</i><p>

<b>523 Piano Literature and Pedagogy (3)</b><br>
A survey of the literature for the piano from the seventeenth century to the 
present, with emphasis on style and interpretation, teaching techniques, 
methods and available materials.<p>
 
<b>524 Pedagogy of Theory (3)</b><br>
Techniques of teaching harmonic principles through written and keyboard 
application, sight-singing and aural recognition; survey and evaluation of 
current texts; preparation of a two-year syllabus.<p>

<b>525 Administration and Supervision of Music Education (3)</b><br>
Designed for those who are charged with leadership in the field of music 
education; concentration on studies that will initiate and promote good school 
music programs.<p>

<b>526 Care and Repair of Instruments (3)</b><br>
Practical course in proper care of band and orchestral instruments; 
procedures for minor repairs.<p>

<b>530 Choral Arranging (3) </b><br>
Arranging for vocal ensembles of treble and mixed voices.<p>

<b>53I Choral Literature and Conducting (3)</b><br>
A survey of choral literature from the Renaissance to the present. Advanced 
rehearsal and conducting techniques with the class as a performing choral 
group. Consideration given to stylistic interpretation of the music of various 
periods.<p>

<b>532 Advanced Instrumental Techniques (3)</b><br>
A practical view of the profession of instrumental music teaching - the 
qualities needed, preparation and on-the-job relationships.<p>

<b>535 Advanced Orchestration (3)</b><br>
Advanced exercises in orchestral scoring.<p>

<b>536 Instrumental Arranging (3)</b><br>
Review of orchestration fundamentals and the writing of a practical 
arrangement for a students' ensemble.<p>

<b>537A Ensemble Participation: Wind Ensemble (.5)</b><br>
Practical experience in performing ensemble, open to qualified students at 
discretion of the conductor. Maximum combined ensemble credits: three. 
Minimum ensemble participation: two semesters.<p>

<b>537B Ensemble Participation: Orchestra (.5) </b><br>
See MUSC 537A.<p>

<b>537C Ensemble Participation: Campus Choir (.5) </b><br>
See MUSC 537A.<p>

<b>537D Ensemble Participation: Jazz Ensemble  (.5)</b><br>
See MUSC 537A<p>

<b>538 Sixteenth Century Counterpoint (3)</b><br>
Composition of modal melodies in the style of the sixteenth century. Includes 
use of imitation and double counterpoint in writing motets.<p>

<b>539 Eighteenth Century Counterpoint (3) </b><br>
Composition of tonal melodies in the style of J.S. Bach.<p>

<b>541 Composition (3)</b><br>
Work in traditional and twentieth century forms of music composition; 
creative work in free composition, with instruction according to the needs 
and capabilities of the individual student.<p>

<b>542 Survey of Opera (3)</b><br>
A history of operatic forms and styles from the seventeenth century to the 
present. Offered when needed.<p>

<b>543 Introduction to Music Bibliography and Research (3)</b><br>
A seminar designed as an introduction to music bibliography and basic 
research methodology. Individualized project permits optimum benefit to 
students of each degree program. <b>REQUIRED OF ALL CANDIDATES FOR THE M.A. IN 
MUSIC.</b><p>

<b>544 Vocal Pedogogy: The Speaking Voice (3)</b><br>
The anatomy and physiology of the speaking/singing voice; the international 
phonetic alphabet; balanced articulation; healthy use and care of the voice; 
relaxation and stress reduction; training in how specific vocal sounds are 
produced, which of these are healthy and how to identify and correct 
unhealthy voice qualities.<p>

<b>545 The Singing Voice (Part I) (3)</b><br>
Using the IPA in Italian and German songs. Developing a healthy, creative 
vocal pedagogy based on a working knowledge of the psychological, 
physiological and acoustical attributes of the singing voice. <i>(Prerequisite: 
MUSC 544 or permission of instructor.)</i><p>

<b>546 The Singing Voice (Part II) (3)</b><br>
Using the IPA in French songs. Maintaining a healthy, creative vocal pedagogy 
and rehabilitating an abused voice based on a working knowledge of the 
psychological, physiological and acoustical attributes of the singing voice. 
<i>(Prerequisite: MUSC 544 or permission of instructor.)</i><p>

<b>549 Aesthetics (3)</b><br>
This course examines theories of both art and the aesthetic experience, 
beginning with Plato and Aristotle.  Issues include the nature of art, the 
nature of the aesthetic experience, creativity and inspiration, art and nature, 
art and morality.
<p>

<b>550 Applied Music*-Voice (variable credit)</b><p>

<b>551 Applied Music*-Piano (variable credit)</b><p>

<b>552 Applied Music*-Organ (variable credit)</b><p>

<b>553 Applied Music*-Strings (variable credit)</b><p>

<b>554 Applied Music*-Woodwinds (variable credit)</b><p>

<b>555 Professional Contribution (no credit)</b><br>
Thesis or project directed by a member of the faculty.<p>

<b>555W Professional Contribution: Workshop (no credit)</b><br>
Workshop directed by a member of the faculty.<p>

<b>555R Professional Contribution: Recital (no credit)</b><br>
Recital directed by a member of the faculty.<p>

<b>557 Applied Music*-Conducting (variable credit)</b><br>
Permission of Chairperson required.<p>

<b>558 Applied Music*-Brass (variable credit)</b><p>

<b>559 Applied Music*-Accordion (variable credit)</b><br>
*Maximum number of applied credits: six; minimum for a recital: two.<p>

<b>566 Directed Readings (1 or 2)</b><br>
Individually directed readings providing for special needs of particular 
students. Conference with instructor and a written report of work required. 
Taken only with the permission of Chairperson and prior approval of the Dean.<p>

<b>570 Seminar: Liturgy (3)</b><br>
A historical study of the development of liturgical practices in the Roman 
Catholic Church and of their effect on the liturgy today.<p>

<b>599 Independent Study (variable credit)</b><br>
A project or course designed for the individual student's interest and needs 
through self-directed learning. Prior approval of the Dean is required.<p>




