<title>Marywood College</title></head>
<body background="/images/backgrnd.gif">
<img src="/images/mwlogos.jpg" align=left hspace=10>
<h1>Marywood College</h1>
<H2>Theological Studies Program
<br clear=left>
<EM>Chairperson: Frances Rice McCormick, Ph.D.</EM></H2>
<hr>
<H3>Program Goal</H3>
study toward higher degrees, the program offers a solid foundation in Biblical Study and Systematic Theology. Basic courses in moral theology, social justice, liturgy and Christian spirituality provide theological reflection on contemporary concerns vital to the well-being of society and Christian communities.<P>

<H3>Program Objectives</H3>
<OL>
<LI>To satisfy the personal desire to understand one's theological tradition and to integrate contemporary theological developments into that tradition.
<LI>To prepare students for active participation in the life of Christian communities.
<LI>To provide a solid theological foundation for students seeking specific Church ministerial service: adult education/workshops/retreats, liturgy, social justice, parish/diocesan service, etc.
<LI>To help students deal intelligently with contemporary societal and Church concerns: poverty, sexism, racism, medical ethics, etc.
<LI>To challenge students engaged in non-theological careers to recognize religion as one of the major forces in the shaping of culture, history, politics, economics and the media.
<LI>To prepare students for doctoral studies in theology.
</OL>


<H3>Admission Requirements</H3>
1. In addition to the general admissions procedure of the Graduate School as specified in this catalog, the Theological Studies Department requires a written essay of about 300 words, typed, addressing the following issues:
<OL>
<LI>Your professional and/or educational background
<LI>What attracted you to an M.A. program in theological studies
<LI>What you expect to gain through the theological program offered by this College
<LI>How you hope to apply your theological studies once the M.A. degree is attained
</OL>
2. Enrichment students who wish to pursue deeper theological reflection are required to have earned a bachelor's degree from an accredited undergraduate institution. Following the general policy of the Graduate School, up to nine credits earned in Theological Studies are applicable toward the degree, should an enrichment student subsequently seek to pursue the M.A. in Theological Studies.

<H3>Degree Requirements</H3>
1. 36 semester hours of course work, including:<BR>
21 core course semester hours<BR>
12-15 elective course semester hours<BR>
Up to 6 credits may be earned in a related graduate level discipline, subject to departmental approval.<BR>
2. Completion of graduate closure experience. Two options exist:<BR>
a. 33 semester hours plus THEO 584 Research Thesis (3 credits), <EM>OR</EM>
b. 36 semester hours plus THEO 555 Methodology Research (no credit).<BR>
Students should consult the department regarding guidelines governing the graduate closure experience.<P>

<H3>Master of Arts in Theological Studies<BR></H3>
36 semester hours<BR>
<STRONG>I. CORE COURSES</H4></STRONG>
21 semester hours:<BR>
Required of all students<BR>
9 Semester Hours<BR>
THEO 510 Theology and Revelation 	 3<BR>
THEO 515 The Synoptic Gospels 	 3<BR>
THEO 587 Covenant Faith and Moral Development 	 3<BR>
Biblical Studies<BR>
6 Semester Hours<BR>
THEO 513 Gospel of John 	 3<BR>
THEO 516 The Letters of Paul 	 3<BR>
THEO 539 Genesis and Pentateuch 	 3<BR>
THEO 544 The Classical Prophets 	 3<BR>
Systematic Theology<BR>
6 Semester Hours<BR>
THEO 514 The Sacraments 	 3<BR>
THEO 522 Trinitarian Theology and Spirituality 	 3<BR>
THEO 523 Theology of Jesus Christ 	 3<BR>
THEO 543 The Church 	 3<BR>
Summer Institutes 	 3<BR>
Students are encouraged to participate in three Summer Institutes (1 
semester hour each). The Summer Institute offers an opportunity to hear 
visiting theologians speak on a variety of theological subjects and to discuss 
topics selected to meet current needs and theological interest.<P>

<STRONG>II. ELECTIVES</H4></STRONG>
12-15 semester hours<BR>
Students may opt from among department offerings (including remaining core 
courses) or with department approval, from offerings within a related 
graduate level discipline, to complete required semester hours.<BR><HR>

<H2>Courses<P></H2>

<H3>Biblical Studies<P></H3>

<STRONG>513 Gospel of John (3)<BR></STRONG>
A study of the origins of this highly creative picture of Jesus' public ministry. 
The community of the beloved disciple and the origins of its high Christology. 
A cursive exegesis of the gospel and I John.<P>

<STRONG>515 The Synoptic Gospels (3)<BR></STRONG>
The nature of the Gospel material and the methods employed in reading it. 
Pre-70 A.D. Judaism as the context for Jesus' ministry. Jesus and John the 
Baptizer. The aims of Jesus, his message, his followers, his opponents. What 
did he say about himself? The infancy and resurrection narratives.<P>

<STRONG>516 The Letters of Paul (3)<BR></STRONG>
Paul: apostle, pastor, theologian. The social challenge of biblical religion and 
the true notion of freedom. The controversy over the terms of admission for 
Gentiles and Paul's innovative response. His theology of redemption and of 
the salvific plan for all humankind. His positive attitude toward women. His 
understanding of Jesus and of ministry in his name.<P>

<STRONG>538 The Psalms (3)<BR></STRONG>
The characteristics of Hebrew poetry. The poetry of early Israel and its 
relationship to Canaanite religious themes. The development of these themes 
in the psalms and the distinctive Israelite modifications of them. The 
Christian use of the psalms.<P>
539 Genesis and Pentateuch (3)<BR>
The origins of ancient Israel and of her religion. Early Israel as a social 
revolution against Canaanite feudalism. A comparison of paganism and 
biblical religion and the distinctive features of the latter. Genesis: the 
creation stories and the patriarchal narratives.<P>

<STRONG>544 The Classical Prophets (3)<BR></STRONG>
The development of prophetism in Israel. The media and the message of the 
great prophet-theologians of Israel. Their concern for healthy religion. Their 
unleashing of social imagination. Their affirmation of the freedom of God to 
bring about righteousness in quite disruptive ways. The nature of their 
statements about the future. The rise of apocalyptic thought.<P>

<STRONG>561 The Wisdom Literature (3)<BR></STRONG>
Creation theology as Israel's alternate to the salvation history model. An 
emphasis on God's revelation in creation, on human capability and 
responsibility for building community, on the enjoyment and celebration of 
life. The quarrel of Job and Ecclesiastes with unreal spirituality. Personified 
Wisdom and feminine aspects of God. The sage as model for ministry.<P>

<STRONG>566 The Parables of Jesus (3)<BR></STRONG>
A history of parable exegesis. The non-parabolic teachings of Jesus as the 
controlling context for understanding the parables. A discussion of each of 
the parables: the original structure from Jesus and the varying performance 
of it in each of the gospels.<P>
567 The Passion and Resurrection Narratives (3)<BR>
An historical study of the stories about Jesus' death and resurrection. The 
Last Supper. The reasons he was put to death. Was there a Jewish trial or 
were the proceedings largely Roman? The testimony to the appearances of 
the risen Jesus and to the empty tomb.<P>

<STRONG>589 Luke-Acts (3)<BR></STRONG>
A composition-critical analysis of Luke's two-part work. A study of the Lukan 
Jesus and the Lukan salvation-history theology of the Church's mission to all 
humankind. The early Church and its development as a Jewish sect.<P>

<H3>Systematic Theology<P>
</H3>
<STRONG>510 Theology and Revelation (3)<BR></STRONG>
Study of the fundamentals underlying Christian belief: revelation as God's 
presence among us; theology as an articulation of that disclosure and faith as 
gift and response to the same. Examination of specific concepts: creation, 
covenant, Christ, grace, salvation, belief and unbelief.<P>

<STRONG>511 Doctrine of God (3)<BR></STRONG>
Survey of God's divine revelation in both testaments, with a treatment of 
God's names, notions and cult. Deals with current problems, questions and 
relevance of God vis-a-vis modern people. Submits the typically Christian 
revelation of Trinity in God in traditional fashion, with a communitarian, 
"functional" flavor - one that represents and argues to the call and challenge 
gradually to become a human community because the one God is mysteriously 
a Trinity.<P>

<STRONG>514 The Sacraments (3)<BR></STRONG>
A critical analysis of the historical development of Christian anthropology; 
systematic analysis of some modern and contemporary authors. Historico-
dogmatic study of the institution, nature and function of the sacraments in 
the redemptive mission of the Church.<P>

<STRONG>522 Trinitarian Doctrine and Spirituality (3)<BR></STRONG>
A study of the biblical and liturgical roots of the Trinitarian doctrine, early 
doctrinal developments and distinctions between the East and West, the 
scholastic crystallization of doctrinal thought, reasons for the silence 
surrounding this doctrine and contemporary reflections on its significance for 
Christian faith and spiritual life.<P>

<STRONG>523 Theology of Jesus Christ (3)<BR></STRONG>
Traditional aspects of the Incarnation, with consideration of Christ's 
humanity, human knowledge and freedom; modern image of Christ in one's 
neighbor. Some contemporary challenges to Christianity's traditional picture 
and presentation of Jesus.<P>

<STRONG>543 The Church (3)<BR></STRONG>
A comprehensive investigation of its nature, notion, origin and current 
relevance - from the perspective of the pilgrim people of God, historically 
situated in the present, with a tradition and a constant thrust toward 
completion in Christ, the Eschaton. Deals with the Church as the sign of union 
with God and the unity of humanity.<P>

<STRONG>547 Introduction to Liturgical Studies (3)<BR></STRONG>
An introduction to liturgical prayer and liturgical spirituality, with emphasis 
on the meaning and place of worship and ritual, sign and symbol in the 
Christian life. The Church year is studied as the unfolding of the mystery of 
Christ; the Liturgy of the Hours and the Eucharist studied as the celebration of 
that mystery. The "Constitution on the Sacred Liturgy" is discussed in detail.<P>

<STRONG>548 History and Theology of the Eucharist (3)<BR></STRONG>
The theological and historical development of the Eucharist from the New 
Testament period to the reforms of Vatican II, with emphasis on liturgical 
practices through the centuries and the teaching of the Church on the 
meaning of "Real Presence," the Eucharist as a "sacrificial meal" and the 
concept of "memorial" in Eucharistic theology. The present form of the Roman 
Rite is studied in detail.<P>

<STRONG>570 Woman: In God's Image (3)<BR></STRONG>
An examination of the impact of religious thought on women in tribal 
societies and ancient cultures will serve as a prelude to the study of the 
image of woman as it emerged through biblical, patristic and scholastic 
interpretations. Discussion of contemporary re-imaging of women aims to 
shed light on current debates surrounding the admission of women into full 
ecclesial life and the use of gender-inclusive theological and liturgical 
language/images.<P>

<STRONG>575 Theology of Death (3)<BR></STRONG>
A theological, sociological and psychological consideration of the critical 
phenomena of sickness, dying, death and the "thereafter." Some problems 
and implications of these human dilemmas in a technological age. Conclusion: 
the logic, rightness and need for a reaffirmation of resurrection.<P>

<STRONG>583 Topics in Theological Studies (3)<BR></STRONG>
Seminar offered occasionally, covering various topics to meet discipline-
based demand related to issues/trends affecting theological interpretations, 
practices and/or traditions.<P>

<STRONG>599 Independent Study<BR></STRONG>
A project or course designed to meet an individual student's course work 
interests and needs through primarily self-directed learning. Only available as 
scheduled and approved by the Department Chairperson.<P>


<H3>Moral Theology<P></H3>

<STRONG>568 Christianity and Social Justice (3)<BR></STRONG>
An examination of Christian traditions of justice: the biblical mandate to 
uphold human dignity, care for the poor and uphold justice. Analysis of the 
body of Church teaching on social justice from "Rerum Novarum" to the 
present.<P>

<STRONG>587 Covenant Faith and Moral Development (3)<BR></STRONG>
An examination of the nature and task of moral theology in light of its 
historical and theological developments, along with the promptings of  
Vatican Council II. The focus reflects a movement from normative to 
relational morality rooted in Covenant faith and directed toward responsible 
Christian existence. Specific concepts considered: Covenant faith, sin, law, 
conscience, conversion and Christian response.<P>

<STRONG>588 Christian Decision-Making (3)<BR></STRONG>
An examination of the religious roots of today's moral questions. The roles of 
law, authority, conscience and responsibility, viewed in the context of 
Scripture and subsequent Church documents and theological interpretations. 
Specific moral issues will be examined, especially in the areas of business, 
the professions and medico-moral tensions.<P>

<H3>Pastoral Theology<P></H3>

<STRONG>550 Theology of Mission and Ministry (3)<BR></STRONG>
A study of the Church's mission as rooted in Scripture and ecclesial teaching. 
Specific focus on the current Church call to evangelization, embracing the 
missionary character of Christian discipleship. Includes the impact on society 
of the spiritual richness and insight of a faith-life.<P>


<H3>Closure Options<P></H3>

<STRONG>555 Methodology Project (non-credit - S/U)<BR></STRONG>
Completion of an acceptable paper which synthesizes research in Biblical 
Studies and Systematic Theology, gives evidence of a logical theological 
method and demonstrates the contemporary significance of a selected 
theological topic.<BR>

<STRONG>584 Research Thesis (3)<BR></STRONG>
An interpretive and/or analytical study of a theological area of significance 
under the direction of a department mentor. Graduate School guidelines are 
followed during the thesis writing and defense.<BR>


