 <H1>
 Marywood College</H1>
 <H2>
 <FONT SIZE=6>D</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>OCTORAL</FONT><FONT SIZE=3> </FONT><FONT SIZE=6>P</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>ROGRAM</FONT><FONT SIZE=3> </FONT><FONT SIZE=4>IN</FONT><FONT SIZE=3> </FONT><FONT SIZE=6>H</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>UMAN</FONT><FONT SIZE=3> </FONT><FONT SIZE=6>D</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>EVELOPMENT</FONT><BR></H2><P ALIGN=CENTER><CENTER><HR ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=100% SIZE=2></CENTER></P><P ALIGN=CENTER><CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><U>C</U></FONT><U>OURSE
   </U><FONT SIZE=5><U>D</U></FONT><U>ESCRIPTIONS</U></CENTER>
 </P>
 <H2
  ALIGN=CENTER>
  <CENTER>Core Courses</CENTER>
 </H2>
 <H3
  ALIGN=CENTER>
  <CENTER><U>Interdisciplinary Courses</U></CENTER>
 </H3><P>
 <A NAME="hd1021"></A><B>Human Development 1021 -- Development and Change: Foundations for the Practitioner (4 credits)</B></P>
 <P>
 A seminar style investigation of underlying theories and models of human nature, human development, and epistemology with emphasis on foundational assumptions of practice in students' respective disciplines. This is the first of a four course interdisciplinary series required of all doctoral students.</P>
 <P>
 Prerequisite - Admission to Doctoral Program</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="hd1031"></A><B>Human Development 1031 -- Social and Economic Dimensions of Human Development (4 credits)</B></P>
 <P>
 This is the second of four courses which constitute the core interdisciplinary curriculum of the doctoral program at Marywood College.</P>
 <P>
 The course introduces students to the systems model of human growth and development. In this model, it is posited that an understanding of individuals can only be derived from an understanding of the interactions/transactions occurring between the individual and his/her socioeconomic environment at various stages in the life-cycle.</P>
 <P>
 Students will gain a better understanding of: the social nature of humankind; symbolic interaction and social systems theory; major economic theories; life-cycle theory; social control and organizational theory; and, of the primary social institutions influencing human development.</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="hd1041"></A><B>Human Development 1041 -- The Physiological and Psychological Bases of Human Development (4 credits)</B></P>
 <P>
 This course will present current findings from psychology and other sciences to explore such issues as: evolution; nature/nurture; intelligence and learning; the definition of life and development; physical and psychological health; spiritual needs; and the effect of scientific research on the future of human development. The goal of the course is to expand the students' awareness of the impact of scientific discoveries on their professional fields and personal lives.</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="hd1051"></A><B>Human Development 1051 -- Selected Topics Seminar (3 credits)</B>
 </P><P>
 This will be a capstone course that will provide opportunity for students to integrate the major themes of the core interdisciplinary courses, the specialization courses taken to date, and the research component of the program. Content will be organized around the research interests of the students, explicating the interdisciplinary context in which their topic resides. Students will develop a framework for their dissertation topic and proposal.</P>
 <H2
  ALIGN=CENTER>
  <CENTER><U>Research Courses</U></CENTER>
 </H2><P>
 <A NAME="hd1011"></A><B>Advanced Statistical Analysis I 1011 (3 credits)</B>
 </P><P>
 This course teaches the principles and methods of conducting and evaluating empirical research. The course focuses on research methodology and advanced analysis of variance. Examines issues of complex experimental designs and planned contracts.</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="hd1013"></A><B>Advanced Statistical Analysis II 1013 (3 credits)</B>
 </P><P>
 This course examines measurement scales and methods of measurement in psychometrics. The focus of this course is on advanced correlation procedures, multiple regression, factor analysis and meta-analysis.</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="hd1014"></A><B>Qualitative Research 1014 (3 credits)</B>
 </P><P>
 This course teaches design and methodology for qualitative research. The focus of this course is on participant observation, unstructured and life history interviews and document analysis.</P>
 <H2
  ALIGN=CENTER>
  <CENTER>Specialization Areas</CENTER>
 </H2>
 <H3
  ALIGN=CENTER>
  <CENTER>Counseling Psychology Specialization</CENTER>
 </H3><P>
 Students who are admitted to this program will need to provide evidence of course work or experiential training in the following areas:</P>
 <P>
  <UL>
  research methods and statistics<BR>
  assessment<BR>
  counseling and psychotherapy<BR>
  practicum/internship training</UL>
 <P>
 <B><U>Course Descriptions</U></B></P>
 <P>
 <B>Advanced Clinical Courses (15 credits)</B>
 </P><P>
 <A NAME="asspsy"></A><B><U>Assessment and Psychopathology Seminars</U></B><U> (6 or 9 credits)</U></P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="adjpsy"></A><B><U>Seminar in Adjustment and Psychopathology</U></B> Required introductory course in the Assessment and Psychopathology area. Seminar course that will examine advanced current topics in psychopathology and adjustment. Course will examine current status of research in defining psychopathology and adjustment. Review of current literature and methods of study in areas of stress and coping, anxiety, affective disorders, personality disorders, and schizophrenia. Course will cover selected areas based in part on student areas of interest. Development of student expertise in particular area of adjustment and psychopathology. Prerequisite: graduate- level course in psychopathology<U>.</U></P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="intass"></A><B><U>Integrating Seminar on Assessment </U></B>Intensive seminar on integrating multimodal assessment of client functioning. Examination of clinical analysis processes for integrating behavioral, objective, projective, intellectual and neurological assessment, and interview data. Laboratory in test administration and integration of test data. Development of student expertise in particular area of assessment practice and research. Prerequisite: graduate-level courses or experience in objective measures of personality, intellectual and/or neurological assessment, behavioral assessment, and interview practicum.</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="adt"></A><B><U>Assessment, Diagnosis and Treatment </U></B>Examination of the complexities of accurate assessment and diagnosis in the context of an individual's life history. Multimodal assessment procedures are examined in relation to multi-axial diagnosis in DSM-IV. Treatment implications for various diagnoses will be examined in the context of theory, research, and practice considerations. Development of area of student expertise in assessment, diagnosis, and treatment. Prerequisite: graduate-level courses and/or experience in psychopathology, clinical practicum training.</P>
 <P>
 <B><U>Intervention Seminars</U></B><B> (9 or 12 credits)</B></P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="profeth"></A><B><U>Professional Ethics </U></B>Required first course. Examination of the professional roles of the psychologist in various settings. Ethical and legal codes are considered in the context of professional dilemmas confronted in practice. Consideration of the historical development of ethical and legal issues in relation to current practice. Examination of current professional issues (e.g., prescription privileges, managed care) and roles in the context of ethical concerns<U>.</U></P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="ais"></A><B><U>Advanced Intervention Strategies </U></B>Explores theory, research, and practice in psychotherapy. Models of intervention are related to psychotherapy process and empirical validation of methods of intervention. Relationship of intervention strategies to specific psychopathologies will be considered. Selected topics will be addressed based on student interest and students will develop expertise in these specific topics.</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="brether"></A><B><U>Brief Therapy </U></B>solution-based therapies are examined in the context of historical development and current practice. Client and therapist attitudes, values, and goals are examined in relation to treatment outcomes. Research and practice considerations are examined in the use of brief therapy. Relationship of brief care to overall client emotional health and long-term outcomes is considered. Managed care and ethical concerns are examined in the practice of brief therapy.</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="cogther"></A><B><U>Cognitive Therapy </U></B>Intensive examination of cognitive therapy methods such as Beck's cognitive therapy and Meichenbaum's stress inoculation training. Examination of treatment methods, research outcomes, and practice considerations in the implementation of cognitive therapy. Laboratory experiences in the application of cognitive therapy techniques. Development of student expertise in the application of cognitive therapy to specific disorders.</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="BMHP"></A><B><U>Behavioral Medicine and Health Psychology.</U></B> Application of clinical psychology interventions in the context of medical problems and health maintenance. Focus on stress-related medical problems and the promotion of client behaviors that enhance physical well being. Consideration of specific topic areas depending on student interest including coping with medical procedures, compliance with medical advice, stress management in a medical setting, psychological factors related to response to medical problems and recovery. Development of student expertise in specific areas of research and practice.</P>
 <P>
 <B>Practica (6 credits)</B>
 </P><P>
 <A NAME="psypract1"></A><B><U>Practicum I &amp; II</U></B><B> (Required)</B> Advanced supervised experience in major counseling methods related to assessment and intervention will depend on composition of particular teams. Emphases on particular teams will include brief therapy, humanistic methods, family-systems interventions, and cognitive-behavioral therapy. Videotape and audiotape review of performance. Case presentations and conferencing of assessment and treatment issue. Prerequisites: three semesters of supervised practicum and internship experiences at the master's level.</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="psypract2"></A><B><U>Practicum III &amp; IV</U></B><B> (Elective)</B> Extension of Practicum I &amp; II to include more independent and advanced functioning in counseling interventions. Provision of supervision and feedback to other students as assistant to treatment team. Development of multimedia training materials to demonstrate methods.</P>
 <P>
 <B>Advanced Psychology Seminars<A NAME="aps"></A> (3 or 6 credits)</B></P>
 <P>
 To be submitted for review:</P>
 <P>
  <UL>
  Advanced Topics in Developmental Psychology<BR>
  Cognitive Psychology Seminar<BR>
  Stress and Coping<BR>
  Advanced Topics in Neuropsychology and Psychopharmacology<BR>
  Program Evaluation and Outcomes Assessment.</UL>
 <P>
 <B><U>Predoctoral Internship<A NAME="psypredoc"></A></U></B> (Year-long, full-time internship or two years, half-time internship)</P>
 <H3
  ALIGN=CENTER>
  <CENTER>Education Specialization</CENTER>
 </H3><P>
 <B><U>Program Objectives</U></B></P>
 <P>
 <B><U>Education Specialization - Administration</U></B>
 </P><P>
 Students who successfully complete the administration specialization in the Ph.D. in Human Development program will be qualified for leadership positions at the central office level in public and private school districts.</P>
 <P>
 Additionally, students will be leaders and scholars in the field, able to identify and investigate dominant issues in school administration.</P>
 <P>
 <B><U>Program Objectives - Instructional Leadership</U></B></P>
 <P>
 Students who successfully complete the instructional leadership specialization in the Ph.D. in Human Development program will be qualified for supervisory positions in curriculum and instruction at the central office level in public and private school districts.</P>
 <P>
 Additionally, students will be leaders and scholars in their respective fields, able to identify and investigate dominant issues in curricular programming and instruction.</P>
 <P>
 <B><U>Course Descriptions - Education Specialties</U></B></P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="scpr"></A><B><U>School, Community, Public Relations (3 credits)</U></B></P>
 <P>
 This course examines the role of the school district in the civic community. It further develops public relations programs that effect positive school-community interaction and stresses effective relationships between central office personnel and school board.</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="ctaod"></A><B><U>Communication Theory and Organizational Dynamics (3 credits)</U></B>
 </P><P>
 This course expands communication theory first explored in principalship program. It stresses effective communication skills. It explores organizational systems and related social structures and stresses motivation theory and change dynamics.</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="labrel"></A><B><U>Labor Relations and Negotiations (3 credits)</U></B></P>
 <P>
 This course explores collective bargaining, negotiation skills, union movements, and related contemporary issues critical to central office leadership.</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="bfm"></A><B><U>Business and Facilities Management (3 credits)</U></B></P>
 <P>
 This course examines financing and construction of education facilities. It explores current state regulations on new and renovated facilities and gives special emphasis to bonding initiatives and aesthetic and environmental concerns.</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="admint"></A><B><U>Administrative Internship (6 credits)</U></B></P>
 <P>
 This course provides an opportunity for the student participant to integrate theory and practice in the field of central office administration. It is an individualized program, designed by the student, a faculty mentor and a site supervisor. It addresses competencies explored during course work. The internship is accomplished at a central school office site. Student participants register for two semesters of internship.</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="dlc"></A><B><U>Dynamics of Leadership and Change</U></B></P>
 <P>
 This course provides a thorough examination of contemporary leadership theory and styles. Essential leadership skills for 21st century institutions of learning will be explored through the use of case studies and simulations. Models of change and communication strategies will be addressed.</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="pubpol"></A><B><U>Public Policy</U></B>
 </P><P>
 The analysis, development, implementation and evaluation of policy will be the common theme of this course. The relationship between policy and administration will be a focus. Policy making structures will be identified and examined.</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="ist"></A><B><U>Integrative Seminar on Teaching</U></B></P>
 <P>
 This course will attempt to carefully integrate learning theory and the actual practice of instruction. Models of effective teaching will be explored, including methodologies and authentic assessment strategies. A major component of the course will be opportunities for actual college classroom teaching experience.</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="cfid"></A><B><U>Curricular Framework and Instructional Design</U></B></P>
 <P>
 This course is designed to explore advanced concepts of integrative curricular design. It touches such curricular issues as multiculturalism, change, society, transitions, technology, decision making, planning and evaluation. A variety of curriculum projects are explored.</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="profethics"></A><A NAME="edprofethics"></A><B><U>Professional Ethics</U></B></P>
 <P>
 This course will cover ethical practice in the fields of medicine, counseling, psychology, social work and education. This multidisciplinary approach highlights the knowledge base of moral and ethical practice. Specialty areas further explore concept application.</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="paracthru"></A><B><U>Practicum in Human Resources Utilization</U></B></P>
 <P>
 This one-semester internship provides the student participant an opportunity to focus on the creative and effective utilization of faculty, parents and community-at-large to achieve curricular purposes of the school. It addresses both staffing and staff development needs. This internship addresses competencies explored during course work and is accomplished at a central office site.</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="practfmru"></A><B><U>Practicum in Financial and Material Resource Utilization</U></B></P>
 <P>
 The one-semester internship provides the student participant an opportunity to focus on creative and effective resource allocation and budgeting procedures. It also deals with building management and resource enhancement to support curriculum initiatives. This internship addresses competencies explored during course work and is accomplished at a central office site.</P>
 <H3
  ALIGN=CENTER>
  <CENTER>Social Work Specialization</CENTER>
 </H3><P>
 The following courses reflect the spirit of academic preparedness for a broad scope of social work practice. There are five core courses (3 credits each) that all students are required to take. These core courses with their appropriate descriptions are:</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="pswp"></A><B><U>Paradigms of Social Work Practice</U></B></P>
 <P>
 Presents models of practice with individuals, families, groups, as well as communities, organizations, and large institutional systems. It provides an analytical framework for the differential application and efficacy of these models.</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="progadm"></A><B><U>Program Administration</U></B></P>
 <P>
 Elucidates the essential functions of administration including, but not limited to , planning, organizing, staffing, resources management and budgeting.</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="mpa"></A><B><U>Models of Policy Analysis</U></B></P>
 <P>
 Develops models for assessing federal, state, and local policies incorporating economic and</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="swprofethics"></A><B><U>Professional Ethics</U></B></P>
 <P>
 Provides an opportunity for doctoral students to review ethical theory as it is applicable to the profession, to engage in guided consideration of multiple ethical dimensions of the profession, and to explore specific dilemmas experienced in today's world.</P>
 <P>
 <A NAME="ecdpp"></A><B><U>Ethnic and Cultural Dimensions of Professional Practice</U></B></P>
 <P>
 Explores the relationship of cultural diversity and ethnicity to effective intervention strategies, giving special attention to vulnerable populations.</P>
 <P>
 In addition to these core courses, students are required to take four electives. with permission, some electives can be taken from either of the other specializations. The following are elective courses (3 credits each) in the social work specialty:</P>
 <P>
 <B><U>The History of Social Welfare and The Social Work Profession<A NAME="swhist"></A></U></B></P>
 <P>
 Describes the development of social welfare initiative and the social work profession within the US. Students will be required to engage in historical research using primary resources when possible.</P>
 <P>
 <B><U>Program Evaluation<A NAME="swprogeval"></A></U></B>
 </P><P>
 Presents a continuum of program evaluation methods, from more formative to more summative approaches. Emphasizes the systematic application of social research methods to assess social intervention programs.</P>
 <P>
 <B><U>Planning Human Services and Program Development<A NAME="phspd"></A></U></B></P>
 <P>
 Focuses on planning for agency effectiveness, efficiency, and accountability. Gives emphasis to generic planning processes, goal selection, objective specification, alternatives analysis, and planning models in a real world context.</P>
 <P>
 <B><U>Cross Discipline Seminar on Models of Teaching<A NAME="cdsmt"></A></U></B></P>
 <P>
 Incorporates theories of teaching and learning to assist students in developing effective instructional knowledge and skills.</P>
 <P>
 <B><U>Social Work Education Curriculum Development and Policy<A NAME="swecdp"></A></U></B></P>
 <P>
 Promotes an understanding of the Curriculum Policy Statement of the Council on Social Work Education, as well as the accreditation standards for social work programs to support the skills necessary to teach effectively in Schools of Social Work.</P>
 <P>
 <B><U>Mentored Teaching Experience<A NAME="swmte"></A></U></B></P>
 <P>
 Individualized teaching experience within the student's area of teaching interests.</P>
 <P ALIGN=CENTER>
