<h2><a name="1600" href="#1600">1600</a></h2>
<h2><a name="1690" href="#1690">1690</a></h2>
<h3>September 27, 1696</h3>
St. Alphonsus Liguori is born. Future founder of the Redemptorists 
(Father Gillet's community).<p>
<img src="../Lines/sb10.gif" 
alt= 
" ____________________________________________________________________
          ____________________________________________________________________">
<P>
<h2><a name="1700" href="#1700">1700</a></h2>
<img src="../Lines/sb10-1.gif" 
alt="____________________________________________________________________">
<h2>|<a href="#1720">1720</a>|<a href="#1730">1730</a>|<a 
href="#1740">1740</a>|<a href="#1760">1760</a>|<a 
href="#1780">1780</a>|
<P>
<a href="#IHM Timeline"><img 
src="../Graphics/up.gif" alt="HOME"> Return to Top</a></h2> 
<img src="../Lines/sb10-1.gif"
alt="____________________________________________________________________">
<p>
<h2><a name="1720" href="#1720">1720</a></h2>
<h3>December 21, 1726 </h3>
Alphonsus Liguori is ordained to the priesthood. Founder of Redemptorists 
(Father Gillet's community). <p>
<h2><a name="1730" href="#1730">1730</a></h2>
<h3>November 9, 1732 </h3>
Founding of the Congregation of the Most Holy Redeemer. 
Father Gillet's future community.
<p>
<h2><a name="1740" href="#1740">1740</a></h2>
<h3>February 25, 1749 </h3>
Rule and Congregation of the Most Holy Redeemer is 
given approbation by Pope Benedict XIV. Official approval for the 
community to which Father Gillet would eventually belong.<p>
<h2><a name="1760" href="#1760">1760</a></h2>
<h3>June 20, 1762</h3>
Alphonsus Liguori is consecrated a bishop. Founder of Redemptorists
(Father Gillet's community). <p>
<h2><a name="1780" href="#1780">1780</a></h2>
<h3>September 22, 1780 </h3>
St. Alphonsus is separated from his Congregation. This parallels the 
experiences of IHM founders.<p>
<h3>August 1, 1787 </h3>
St. Alphonsus Liguori dies. Redemptorist founder (Father Gillet's community).
<p>
<img src="../Lines/sb10.gif" 
alt= 
" ____________________________________________________________________
          ____________________________________________________________________">
<P>
<h2><a name="1800" href=#1800>1800</a></h2>
<img src="../Lines/sb10-1.gif" 
alt="____________________________________________________________________">
<h2>|<a href="#1810">1810</a>|<a href="#1820">1820</a>|<a 
href="#1830">1830</a>|<a href="#1840">1840</a>|<a 
href="#1850">1950</a>|<a href="#1860">1860</a>|<a href 
="#1870">1870</a>|<a href="#1880">1880</a>|<a href="#1890">1890</a>|
<P>
<a href="#IHM Timeline"><img src="../Graphics/up.gif" alt="HOME"> 
Return to Top</a></h2> <img src="../Lines/sb10-1.gif" 
alt="____________________________________________________________________">
<p>
<h2><a name="1810" href=timeline.html#1810>1810</a></h2>
<h3>April 8, 1810</h3>
Theresa Maxis Duchemin is born in Baltimore. 
Future founder of the Congregation.<p>
<h3>January 12, 1813</h3>
<a href="../Photos/mother_gillet.gif"><img 
src="../Photos/mother_gillet-th.gif"alt="[Picture of Mme. Gillet]"></a> 
Louis Florent Gillet is born and baptized in Antwerp, Belgium. Future 
founder of IHM. Father Gillet's mother is pictured here. <p>
<h2><a name="1820" href=timeline.html#1820>1820</a></h2>
<h3>July 2, 1829</h3>
Sister Marie Therese Duchemin pronounces vows 
as an Oblate Sister of Providence in Baltimore. She was a founding 
member of this order of "coloured" sisters.<p>
<h2><a name="1830" href=timeline.html#1830>1830</a></h2>
<h3>April 8, 1833</h3>
Louis Florent Gillet enters the Redemptorist 
Congregation. He begins his training to become a Redemptorist priest.
<p>
<h3>October 20, 1833</h3>
Louis Florent Gillet is received into the  
Redemptorist Congregation. He becomes a novice.  This is an initial stage 
in his training.<p>
<h3>October 20, 1835</h3>
Louis Florent Gillet professes vows as a 
Redemptorist. He officially becomes a member of the congregation.<p>
<h3>March 10 - 11, 1838</h3>
<a href="../Photos/mass_card.gif"><img src="../Photos/mass_card-th.gif" 
alt="[Picture of Mass Card]"></a> Louis Florent Gillet is ordained to the 
priesthood and celebrates his first Mass</a>. This is the beginning of 
his priestly ministry. The accompanying photograph is of the memorial 
card he gave his mother on the occasion of his first Mass. <p>
<h3>May 26, 1839</h3>
St. Alphonsus Liguori is canonized a saint. IHM patron, founder of the 
Redemptorists (Father Gillet's community). <p>
<h2><a name="1840" href="#1840">1840</a></h2>
<h3>June 24, 1841</h3>
Mother Theresa Maxis is elected superior of the Oblate Sisters. This is 
the first order to which she had belonged.  She was a founding member.
<p>
<h3>April 18, 1843</h3>
Rev. Louis Florent Gillet sails for America.
<p>
<h3>August 6, 1843</h3>
Rev. Louis Florent Gillet begins to preach his first mission in America 
(Grosse Point  Michigan). Theresa Renauld (future IHM) attended this.  
This is the beginning of Father Gillet's American ministry. <p>
<h3>March 9, 1844</h3>
<a href="../Photos/sm_gillet.gif"><img src="../Photos/gillet-th.gif" 
alt="[Picture of Fr. Gillet]"> Rev. Louis Florent Gillet</a> initiates 
his ministry in Monroe Michigan. Here he saw the need that was soon to 
lead to the establishment of the IHMs. <p>
<h3>June 16, 1844</h3>
<a href="../Photos/michigan_map.gif"><img 
src="../Photos/michigan_map-th.gif" alt="[Map of Michigan]"></a> Rev. Louis 
Florent Gillet selects Monroe Michigan as the center for the new 
Congregation. <p> 
<h3>September 19, 1845</h3>
Theresa Maxis arrives at Monroe. The congregation is about to be founded.
<h3>November 10, 1845</h3>
<a href="../Photos/log_cabin.gif"><img 
src="../Photos/log_cabin-th.gif" alt="[Picture of log 
cabin]"></a> Founding of the Congregation of Sisters Servants of the 
Immaculate Heart of Mary at Monroe Michigan (as Sisters of Providence). 
Pictured here is the log cabin which was the Sisters' first home.<p> 
<h3>November 30, 1845</h3> <a href="../Photos/small_theresa.gif"><img 
src="../Photos/theresa-th.gif" alt="[Picture of Mother Theresa]"> Mother 
Theresa Maxis</a> and Sister Ann receive the habit and profess their 
vows. This was the first profession of vows in the Congregation. <p>
<h3>December 8, 1845</h3>
Church of St. Mary of the Immaculate Conception in Monroe is consecrated.
<p>
<h3>December 14, 1845</h3>
<a href="../Photos/sr_celestine.gif"><img 
src="../Photos/sr_celestine-th.gif" alt="[picture of Sr. M. 
Celestine]"></a> First IHM sisters renew their vows. Therese Renauld 
receives 
the habit and is named <a href="../Photos/sr_celestine.gif">Sister M. 
Celestine</a>. She was the first IHM novice. <p> 
<h3>January 15, 1846</h3>
Opening of St. Mary Academy  Monroe. This was the beginning of the IHM 
educational mission. <p>
<h3>April 14, 1846</h3>
Josette Godfroy-Smyth enters the Congregation to become the fourth 
member. As a recent widow she brought her estate ($700 plus furniture) as 
the first major contribution to the Congregation. <p>
<h3>May 26, 1846</h3>
Josette Godfroy-Smyth receives the habit and is named 
Sister Mary Alphonsine. She was the second IHM novice. 
<p>
<h3>September 13, 1847</h3>
Rev Egidius Smulders replaces Father Gillet as 
superior of the Congregation at Monro. He was a Redemptorist who 
continued Father Gillet's work with the community after Gillet left Monroe.
<p>
<h3>October 6, 1847</h3>
<a href="../Photos/sm_gillet.gif"><img src="../Photos/gillet-th.gif" 
alt="[Picture of Fr. Gillet"> Father Gillet</a> leaves 
Monroe. He severs his ties with the Congregation until many years later.
<p>
<h3>December 8, 1847</h3>
Title of Congregation is changed from Sisters of 
Providence to Sisters  Servants of the Immaculate Heart of Mary; 
scapular is changed from black to blue material. This name change would 
cause Father Gillet to later believe that the Congregation had not survived.
<p>
<h3>January 26, 1848</h3>
Rev. Francis Poilvache C.SS.R. dies. He was a 
classmate of Father Gillet who had assisted him in the parish at Monroe.
<p>
<h3>July 27,1848</h3>
IHM Sisters initiate summer program of sacramental preparation. 
<p>
<h3>November 28, 1848</h3>
The Rule written by Rev. Louis Florent Gillet is approved by Bishop 
Lefevre.<p> 
<h2><a name="1850" href=#1850>1850</a></h2>
<h3>December 8, 1854</h3>
Dogma of the Immaculate Conception is proclaimed. The Congregation has 
been under the patronage of the Immaculate Conception from its beginning.
<p>
<h3>May 1, 1855</h3>
Redemptorists are withdrawn from Monroe. This action angered Bishop 
Lefevre.  Mother Theresa's later attempt to reestablish connections with 
the Redemptorists in Pennsylvania would lead to many difficulties. <p>
<h3>November 3, 1855</h3>
First mission outside Monroe opens in Erie Michigan.
<p>
<h3>February 27, 1856</h3>
Sister Ignatius Walker dies. This was the first death in the IHM 
congregation. <p>
<h3>October 2, 1857</h3>
First recorded donation of IHM Congregation to Holy 
Childhood Association. IHMs have promoted the work of this organization 
ever since. It is a division of Catholic Charities which has one of the 
highest percentages of contribution to dire ct service to the poor.
<p>
<h3>February 2, 1858</h3>
<a href="../Photos/pere_celestin.gif"><img src="../Photos/pere-th.gif" 
alt="[Picture of Pere Celestin]"> Rev. Louis Florent Gillet</a> enters the 
Cistercian Order. He finds peace here.  This is where he lives out his life.
<p>
<h3>August 22, 1858</h3>
Louis Florent Gillet receives habit of the Cistercians and takes the 
name Marie Celestin. <p> 
<h3>August 23, 1858</h3>
<a href="../Photos/st_joseph_pa.gif"><img 
src="../Photos/st_joseph_pa-th.gif" alt="[Picture of St. Joseph, PA]"> First 
mission</a> in Pennsylvania opens at St. Joseph's in Susquehanna County. 
From this beginning would spring two Pennsylvania IHM foundations.<p>
<h3>April 1, 1859</h3>
Mother Theresa is deposed as superior general of the Congregation. This 
is the difficulties that would lead to her exile with the Grey Nuns in 
Ottawa, Canada.
<p>
<h3>April 4, 1859</h3>
Mother Theresa leaves Monroe for St. Joseph's in Susquehanna 
County, Pennsylvania. After having been deposed as superior in Monroe.
<p>
<h3>July 24, 1859</h3>
First Reception and Profession Ceremony is help at St. 
Joseph Novitiate.  Bishop Neumann presides; seven new members are 
received. This is the beginnings of what is to become the Scranton 
foundation. <p>
<h3>August 3, 1859</h3>
<a href="../Photos/reading.gif"><img 
src="../Photos/reading-th.gif" alt="[Picture of St. Peter's, 
Reading]"> Mission at St. Peter's</a> in Reading, Pennsylvania is 
opened. This is the first mission in territory later to become 
Philadelphia diocese -- leading to the establishment of the Immaculata 
foundation.<p>
<h3>September 2, 1859</h3>
<a href="../Photos/neumann.gif"><img src="../Photos/neumann-th.gif" 
alt="[Picture of Bishop Neumann]"> Bishop John Neumann</a> 
blesses the convent at St. Peter's in Reading, Pennsylvania.<p> 
<h3>September 8, 1859</h3>
Pere Marie Celestin pronounces his solemn vows as a 
member of the Cistercian Order. He was formerly Father Louis Florent Gillet.
<p>
<h2><a name="1860" href=#1860>1860</a></h2>
<h3>January 5, 1860</h3>
Bishop John Neumann dies. He was the bishop when the IHMs 
came into Pennsylvania. He invited them to establish the convent in Reading.
<p>
<h3>May 1, 1861</h3>
Charter is approved for St. Joseph Academy in Susquehanna 
County. First school staffed by IHMs in Pennsylvania.  The parish was 
staffed by Redemptorists. <p>
<h3>October 15, 1861</h3>
Mother Theresa Maxis is named superior of the community at Susquehanna Depot.<p>
<h3>May 25, 1864</h3>
<a href="../Photos/abbey.gif"><img src="../Photos/abbey-th.gif" 
alt="[Picture of the Abbey]"></a> Pere Marie Celestin (Father Gillet) 
arrives at the Hautecombe Abbey. This is where he would 
live out the rest of his life. <p>
<h3>February 2, 1867</h3>
<a href="../Photos/grey_nun.gif"><img src="../Photos/grey_nun-th.gif" 
alt="[Picture of Mother Theresa as grey nun]"></a> Mother Theresa Maxis 
leaves Susquehanna County for Ottawa Canada. She begins her exile with 
the Grey Nuns. 
Though she wore their habit she always considered herself to be a member 
of the IHMs. <p>
<h3>March 3, 1868</h3>
The Diocese of Scranton is established.  This eventually 
caused the foundation on the Scranton branch of the IHM Congregation.
<p>
<h2><a name="1870" href="#1870">1870</a></h2>
<h3>July 7, 1871</h3>
St. Alphonsus Liguori is declared a Doctor of the Church. He was the 
founder of the Redemptorists and is a patron of the IHMs.<p>
<h3>September 8, 1872</h3>
Academy at West Chester [Philadelphia] Motherhouse is opened. <p>
<h3>October 16, 1872</h3>
First Reception Ceremony is held at West Chester 
Motherhouse. In this ceremony young women in training to become members 
of the community received the habit with a white veil and begin a more 
intensive period of training.<p>
<h2><a name="1880" href=#1880>1880</a></h2>
<h3>February 27, 1881</h3>
Fire at St. Patrick's Orphanage in Scranton which results in the death 
of seventeen children.<p> <h3>January 21, 1885</h3>
Mother Theresa Maxis returns to IHM Congregation in West 
Chester, Pennsylvania. Her exile ends and she is reunited with the IHM 
community.<p>
<h3>July 22, 1889</h3>
Scranton IHMs elect Mother Mary Magdalen Jackson their first elected  
superior general. <p> 
<h2><a name="1890" href=#1890>1890</a></h2>
<h3>August 30, 1890</h3>
Scranton IHMs take on administration of St. Joseph's 
Foundling Home (now St. Joseph Center) for neurologically impaired 
children. It also houses a home for unwed mothers and arranges adoptions.
<p>
<h3>February 8, 1891</h3>
Father Gillet (Pere Marie Celestin) is reunited with the 
IHM Congregation. Connection reestablished through the efforts of Sr. 
Clotilde (Immaculata).  He is able to provide facts about the 
Congregation's founding. <p>
<h3>January 14, 1892</h3>
<a href="../Photos/cemetery.gif"><img 
src="../Photos/cemetery-th.gif"></a> Mother Theresa Maxis dies at West 
Chester, Pennsylvania. <p>
<h3>November 14, 1892</h3>
Father Gillet (Pere Marie Celestin) dies at the Royal Abbey of Notre Dame 
d'Hautecombe, France. <p>
<h3>September 24, 1897</h3>
Opening of mission in Tillamook, Oregon. This was 
the first Scranton IHM mission outside the diocese of Scranton.
<p>
<img src="../Lines/sb10.gif" 
alt= 
" ____________________________________________________________________
          ____________________________________________________________________">
<P>
<h2><a name="1900" href="#1900">1900</a></h2>
<p>
<img src="../Lines/sb10-1.gif" 
alt="____________________________________________________________________">
<h2>|<a href="1900">1900</a>|<a href="1910">1910</a>|<a 
href="#1920">1920</a>|<a href="#1930">1930</a>|<a 
href="#1940">1940</a>|<a href="#1950">1950</a>|<a 
href="#1960">1960</a>|<a href="#1970">1970</a>|<a 
href="#1980">1980</a>|<a href="#1990">1990</a><P>
<a href="#IHM Timeline"><img src="../Graphics/up.gif" 
alt="HOME"> Return to Top</a></h2> 
<img src="../Lines/sb10-1.gif" 
alt="____________________________________________________________________">
<p>
<h3>August 29, 1907</h3>
Congregation of Sisters of St. Casimir is founded with the assistance of 
the Scranton IHMs. <p>
<h3>November 6, 1908</h3>
Ground is broken for Villa Maria Academy. This was 
the future Immaculata College in West Chester.
<p>
<h3>September 11, 1909</h3>
Congregation of Sisters of Sts. Cyril and 
Methodius is founded with assistance of the Scranton IHMs.<p>
<h2><a name="1910" href=#1910>1910</a></h2>
<p>
<h3>December 28, 1910</h3>
Charter is approved to St. Mary College in 
Monroe.  In 1927 the college was moved to Detroit and named 
Marygrove. St. Mary College was the second IHM college to be established.
<p>
<h3>July 26, 1915</h3> 
Immaculata IHMs make perpetual vows for the first 
time. Previously sisters vows were taken annually -- they needed to be 
renewed every year.<p>
<h3>May 23, 1917</h3> 
Marywood College in Scranton has its charter 
approved by the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania.  Marywood is the third IHM 
College to be established.<p>
<h3>October 8, 1918</h3>
Archbishop Dougherty meets with major superiors of 
Sisters in Philadelphia to organize volunteer service during flu 
epidemic. The IHMs respond to the needs of the community.<p>
<h2><a name="1920" href=#1920>1920</a></h2>
<h3>July 26, 1920</h3>
Monroe IHMs receive Papal Decree of Final Approbation for their 
Constitutions. This established them as a papal community -- 
they are no longer under the direction of the bishop.<p>
<h3>November 12, 1920</h3>
<a href="../Photos/immaculata.gif"><img 
src="../Photos/immaculata-th.gif" alt="[Picture of Immaculata 
College]"> Immaculata  College</a> obtains its charter.<p> 
<h3>December 
12, 1922</h3>
First Immaculata IHMs arrive in Peru. The beginning of service outside 
of United States.<p> 
<h3>June 4, 1925</h3>
The first graduation is held at Immaculata College.
<p>
<h3>September 8, 1925</h3>
Scranton IHMs open first Southern mission at St. Mary 
in Upper Marlboro, Maryland. This was the first southern mission.<p>
<h3>July 6, 1926</h3>
St Joseph Hospital (now Marian Community Hospital after 
merger with Carbondale General Hospital) in Carbondale, Pennsylvania 
opens its doors. This is the only general hospital owned and operated by 
IHMs.<p>
<h3>March 10, 1929</h3>
<a href="../Photos/sr_rosalita.gif"><img 
src="../Photos/sr_rosalita-th.gif" alt="[Picture of Sr. Rosalita]"></a> The 
remains of Father Gillet are received by the IHM Congregation at Monroe. 
This was made possible through the efforts of Sr. Rosalita (Monroe) who is 
pictured here. <p> 
<h3>June 3, 1929</h3>
<a href="../Photos/monroe_fire.gif"><img 
src="../Photos/monroe_fire-th.gif" alt="[Picture of fire]"></a> St. 
Mary's Academy in Monroe is destroyed by fire.<p> 
<h3>August 2, 1929</h3>
<a href="../Photos/gillet_chapel.gif"><img 
src="../Photos/gillet_chapel-th.gif" alt="[Picture of Gillet Chapel]"> 
Father Gillet's tomb</a> in Monroe is dedicated. This is Father Gillet's final 
resting place.<p> 
<h3>March 25, 1931</h3>
<a href="../Photos/monroe_motherhouse.gif"><img 
src="../Photos/monroe_motherhouse-th.gif" alt="[Picture of 
Motherhouse]"></a> Ground is broken for the present motherhouse and 
academy at Monroe. <p> 
<h2><a name="1940" href=#1940>1940</a></h3>
<h3>June 19, 1942</h3>
<a href="../Photos/cemetery.gif"><img src="../Photos/cemetery-th.gif" 
alt="[Picture of cemetery]"> The cemetery at Immaculata</a> is dedicated. 
The obelisk in the background of the picture marks Mother Theresa's final 
resting place.<p>
<h3>November 21, 1946</h3>
Daily exposition of the Blessed Sacrament is begun at Immaculata 
Motherhouse. <p> 
<h3>October 5, 1948 </h3>
IHM Sisters begin to serve in the influenza 
epidemic in Scranton. The Sisters respond to the needs of the community 
as volunteers.  Service is given without regard to race, creed, etc.
<p>
<h3>August 23, 1948</h3>
Monroe IHMs open their first overseas mission in Puerto Rico.<p>
<h2><a name="1950" href=#1950>1950</a></h2>
<h3>April 26, 1950</h3>
St. Alphonsus Liguori is declared patron of moral 
theologians and of confessors and spiritual directors. He is an IHM 
patron and founder of Redemptorists.<p>
<h3>December 17, 1955</h3>
Constitutions of the Immaculata IHMs receives the 
Decree of Praise. This made them a papal order. <p>
<h3>April 9, 1956</h3>
<a href="../Photos/marian_covent.gif"> <img 
src="../Photos/marian_convent-th.gif" alt="[covent]"> The Marian 
Convent</a> at Marywood is 
dedicated. The is the retirement home for the Scranton IHMs.<p>
<h3>March 19, 1958</h3>
Ground is broken for the building of Camilla Hall 
Infirmary at Immaculata. This is provision for the care of elderly and 
infirm sisters.<p>
<h2><a name="1960"  href=#1960>1960</a></h2>
<h3>November 21, 1960</h3>
Scranton Congregation receives Pontifical 
Approbation. This increases autonomy of the community.  It is no longer 
controlled by the bishop. <p>
<h3>October 28, 1961</h3>
First meeting of Tri-Community Board of 
Education is held at Our Lady of Grace Convent in Manhassett, New 
York. This board's purpose is to further the apostolic works of the 
three Congregations. <p>
<h3>May 30, 1962</h3>
<a href="../Photos/ihm_center.gif"> <img 
src="../Photos/ihm_center-th.gif" alt="[IHM Center]"> The 
Novitiate Building (now the IHM 
Center)</a> at Marywood is dedicated. <p> 
<h3>July 19, 1965</h3>
Scranton IHMs open their first Latin American 
mission in Lima, Peru. This was the beginning of foreign service for the 
Scranton IHMs.<p>
<h3>August 2, 1965</h3>
Mother Theresa's remains are transferred from St. 
Agnes Cemetery to Immaculata Cemetery.<p>
<h3>August 26, 1965</h3>
First Tri-Comminuty Conference is held in Scranton. This 
was the first joint venture since separation of the three branches.<p>
<h3>April 23, 1967</h3>
<a href="../Photos/villa_maria.gif"><img 
src="../Photos/villa_maria-th.gif" alt="[Villa Maria House]"> Villa 
Maria House of Studies at Immaculata</a> is 
dedicated. This house of studies would provide intercommunity 
training for young women belonging to various orders.<p>
<h2> <a name="1970" href=#1970>1970</a></h2>
<h3>February 22, 1971</h3>
<a href="../Photos/scranton_fire.gif"> <img 
src="../Photos/scranton_fire-th.gif" alt="[Scranton fire]"></a> 
Motherhouse of Scranton IHMs is destroyed by fire.<p>
<h3>August 1, 1976</h3>
IHM Sisters meet at Bishop Neumann Shrine in 
Philadelphia on the occasion of the Eucharistic Congress. <p>
<h3>September 12, 1976</h3>
First postulants of School Sisters of Christ the King 
arrive at Villa Maria House of Studies in Immaculata, Pennsylvania. This 
house of studies would provide intercommunity training for young women 
belonging to various orders. <p>
<h2><a name="1980" href=#1980>1980</a></h2>
<h3>January 22, 1983</h3>
Present Constitutions of Scranton IHMs are approved by 
the Sacred Congregation. This is modern  post-Vatican II approval of the 
revised constitutions.<p>
<h3>April 26, 1983</h3>
Present Constitutions of the Immaculata IHMs are approved by the Sacred 
Congregation in Rome. This is modern  post-Vatican II approval of the 
revised constitutions.<p>
<h2><a name="1990" href=#1990>1990</a></h2>
<h3>November 10, 1995</h3>
<a href="../Photos/ses-q-logo.gif"><img 
src="../Photos/ses-q-logo-th.gif" alt="[sesqui]"> 
IHM Sesquicentennial</a>, celebrating 150 years since the foundation. <p>
<img src="../Lines/sb10.gif" 
alt= 
" ____________________________________________________________________
          ____________________________________________________________________">
