<html>
<head>
<title>IHM Web:  About Us:  IHM Present:  Who We Are</title>
</head>
<body>
<h2>
<img src="../Graphics/ihmlogo3.gif" alt="IHM Web:  About Us:  "><img 
src="../Graphics/who_are.gif" alt="Who We Are"></h2><br>
-- adapted from <cite>We Speak the Word of Life</cite>
<P>

	<BLOCKQUOTE>We Sister, Servants of the Immaculate Heart of Mary<BR>
	rejoice in the redeeming love of Jesus Christ,<BR>
	who joins us to himself and to all others in his Church<BR>
	by the power of the Holy Spirit.<BR>
	By membership in this congregation,<BR>
	we seek to grow in friendship and union with the Lord<BR>
	and to share in his redeeming mission.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
From <cite>Our Call</cite>, the first paragraph of the 
<cite>Constitutions of the Congregation of the Sisters, Servants of the 
Immaculate Heart of Mary, Scranton, PA (1992)</cite>.
<P>
<h2>Who We Are</h2>
<P>
This fellowship of ours is with the Father and with his son, Jesus Christ.
<P>
Our mission as Sisters, Servants of the Immaculate Heart of Mary of 
Scranton, Pennsylvania is to follow Christ as a community of disciples, 
aware that we are sent to be a clear and understandable witness to the 
presence of God in the world.  Throughout our congregation's history, we 
have responded to the changing needs of the time.  This, of course, 
means knowing the world: how it has changed, why it is changing and how 
we IHMs can respond. 
<P>
IHMs -- Church women:  Who are they, really?
<P>
A Belgian Redemptorist priest, Father Louis Florent Gillet, was led to 
frontier Michigan in the 1840s.  Here in 1845, with the cooperation of 
Mother Theresa Maxis Duchemin, he founded the Congregation with the 
purpose of furthering the human aspirations of the people of the area; 
specifically the preservation, deepening and spreading of the community 
of faith in Jesus Christ.  They chose the work of education as the one 
most appropriate in that time and place for the fullfilment of their purpose.
<P>
Dedication for the poor and spiritually neglected persons led Mother 
Theresa to establish a mission in northeast Pennsylvania in 1858.  She 
thereby set forth the roots of the Scranton IHMs. 
<P>
The early years of the Scranton Congregation were largely occupied with 
supplying education for the immigrant working persons who crowded into 
northeast Pennsylvania's coal mining and railroad camps.  The sisters 
supported the workers struggles to overcome poverty and oppression and 
to achieve more fully human lives. 
<P>
Today, as in our early years, all our ministries are works of justice 
and peace.  They receive and give life in relation to the depth of our 
spiritual union with Jesus and our participation in his mission. 
<P>
Members of the laity have been invited to <a 
name="cby" href="CBY/cby-menu.html">share in our mission</a> in the Church 
as <a name="prayer" href="CBY/prayerasso.html">prayer associates</a>, <a 
name="vols" href="CBY/volunteer.html">associate volunteers</a> or to 
consider seeking full membership through the <a 
name="pre" href="CBY/formation.html">formation program</a>.  We serve in 
<a href="where_are.html">many different places</a> where the reality of 
God's redeeming mercy in Jesus Christ has not yet been effectively 
communicated. 
<P>
Because we are ministers with God, for and with his people, God's 
inspiration has led IHMs to cities, to rural areas, to the barrios of 
Lima, Peru, and the mountains of British Columbia.  Our times and our 
faith call us not only to pray as Jesus did, not only to know how Jesus 
would act, but, in fact, to act as he would act.  We seek to promote 
social justice, the dignity of the human person and the cause of peace 
through every means at our disposal; specifically by raising the 
consciousness of others through our teaching, healing and pastoral ministries.
<P>
We are women who acknowledge the diversity of gifts among us and who 
respect the uniqueness of each of our sisters who live together in 
community with the Eucharistic Christ as the center of our lives.  God 
has led and does lead us to ministries which make the most productive 
use of our God-given talents. 
<P>
Artists ... teachers ... campus ministers ... religious education 
directors ... social workers ... secretaries ... pharmacists ... 
guidance counselors ... administrators ... Christian clowns ... 
advocates for immigrants ... musicians ... nurses ... dieticians ... 
pastoral ministers ... librarians ... canon lawyers ... grief counselors 
... sisters who work with handicapped children. 
<P>
Our lives and labors have a faith dimension that gives special meaning 
to what we do and why we do it. 
<P>
The religious call of each IHM sister is a call to grow in friendship 
and union with the Lord and to share in his redeeming mission.  "I shall 
be with you," he promised in Exodus; and in the book of Jeremiah we hear 
the Lord again, "To whomever I send you, you shall go."  The greatest 
gift we give to the Congregation and to those whom we serve is a life of 
personal wholeness rooted in prayer. 
<P>
Mary is a guiding force who stands before each of us as the ultimate 
embodiment of a life rooted in the Lord. 
<P>
Our <a name="vision" href="CBY/formation.html#vision">religious formation</a> is a 
process which is personal and life-long beginning with a young woman's 
call to the Congregation.  At first (<a 
href="CBY/formation.html#pre">pre-admission</a>) it may involve a live-in 
which offers the young woman an opportunity to spend a weekend of prayer 
and discussion of the basic elements of religious life and at, the same 
time, to experience the community life of the sisters. 
<P>
The first official step of religious formation, the <a 
name="affiliate" href="CBY/formation.html#pre">affiliate program</a>, 
follows.  It is a time of written application and interviews, weekends 
of prayer and serious discussion with a sister advisor and the Director 
of Affiliates.  But it is still a time of search until, one day, a 
decision is made to apply for admission to the IHM community as a 
candidate. 
<P>
The <a name="candidates" href="CBY/formation.html#initial">candidacy phase</a> can 
be as brief as six months or can be longer.  Its goal is initiation into 
community life. 
<P>
The next period, <a name="novitiate" href="CBY/formation.html#initial">the 
novitiate</a>, usually lasts two years, the first of 
which is called canonical.  This first year's primary focus is on 
growing in relationship with Christ through prayer, community life and 
studies, which include the vows and scripture.  The canonical year 
usually includes a formative activity experience of a month's duration 
outside the novitiate. 
<P>
The second year novitiate concentrates on helping the novice to move 
toward ministerial life by emphasizing the integration of prayer and 
ministry.  It may include a short or extended ministerial experience. 
<P>
The <a name="vowed" href="CBY/formation.html#initial">juniorate experience</a> follows 
first vows of povery, chastity 
and obedience, made for three years, during which the young sister continues 
to live in a local community, sharing full responsibility for prayer, 
ministry and community life. 
<P>
After a minimum of three years to a maximum of 6 years, the sister may 
make profession of final vows
as a Sister, Servant of the Immaculate Heart of Mary.  The IHM sister 
continues to participate in ongoing religious formation aimed at 
furthering her spiritual, psychological and intellectual development. 
<P>
In 1979, Our Lady of the Lake Spiritual Renewal Center was opened in 
Verona, New Jersey, to nourish the IHM apostolic spirituality of 
contemplation in action.  The Spiritual Renewal Center was later moved to 
Cresco, Pennsylvania in the heart of the Pocono Mountains where 
it continues to offer <a href="../Calendar.cresco.html">retreats and other 
programs</a> primarily for IHM sisters. 
<P>
Today there are more than 700 IHMs who have come from many parts of the 
country, all with a common desire to serve God well and extend his love 
to others whenever and wherever possible. 
<P>
One of the most precious charisms is a joyful, loving spirit which has 
touched the hearts and faces of untold thousands down through the years 
since we began in 1845. 
<P>
These spirited, prayerful, giving women face the challenge of bringing 
the gospel message to our world today; and with great freedom to 
give their lives away in the service of others as signs of God's 
presence among us, they are sources of hope and vision that the spirit of a 
world in pain and confusion cannot diminish. 
<P>
We share in Christ's redeeming mission and we invite you to come, learn 
more about us that together we may grow in friendship and union with the 
Lord and bring his message to those we serve. 
<P>
<img src="../Lines/sb10-1.gif" 
alt="____________________________________________________________________">
<P>
<a href="../about-us.html">Go to the About Us Menu</a><br>
<a href="../index.html">Go to the IHM Web Home Page</a>
