<html>
<head>
<title>IHM Calendar:  Community Workshop</title>
</head>
<body>
<a name="top"></a>
<h1>
<img src="../Graphics/ihmlogo3.gif" alt="IHM Web"><img 
src="../Graphics/calendar.gif" alt="IHM Calendar of Events"></h1><br>
<center>
<h2>Community:  Life Giving or Stagnant?</h2>
<H3>A workshop on creative and evolving community living</H3></center>
This workshop will focus on the basic foundations which create the atmosphere for communal living:  faith and the human psychological dimension.   What qualities are necessary to facilitate human growth and companionship?  How do we face the shadow side of our own selves and that of community?
<P>
Participants will:
<UL>
<LI>indentify life-giving qualities of contemporary religious community and characteristics of stagnant community patterns
<P>
<LI>explore several dimensions of life-giving community
<P>
<LI>learn to encourage movement away from stagnation toward growth
<P>
<LI>begin reflection on their own "shadow side" and how that is operative in their interrelationships, etc.
</UL>
<CENTER><H3>Presenter:  John Malich, FMS</H3>
9:30 a.m. - 4:00 p.m.
<P>

Saturday, November 16, 1996<BR>
Notre Dame High School<BR>
East Stroudsburg, PA<BR>
<P>

April 19, 1997 <BR>
Silver Spring, MD<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
Cost: $5.00, includes lunch.<BR>
For further information, contact the IHM Communications Office at <A HREF="mailto:sanders@ac.marywood.edu">sanders@ac.marywood.edu</A><BR>

<img src="../Lines/sb10-1.gif" 
alt="____________________________________________________________________">
<P>
