<HEAD>
<TITLE>Marywood College Legal Assistant Paralegal Pre-Law Academic Programs
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY Background="bgrnd003.jpg" BGColor=#FFFFFF Text=#000000 Link=#0000FF VLink=#800080 ALink=#FF00FF>

<P>

<BGSOUND SRC="xgfrwks2.mid" LOOP=INFINITE><Br>

<embed src="xgfrwks2.mid" hidden="true" loop=infinite>



<Center><IMG src="gr_ban01.gif" alt=""><IMG src="redlogo2.gif" alt=""><IMG src="gr_ban01.gif" alt=""></Center><P>

<Center><IMG src="img8a.gif" alt=""></Center>

<Center><B><Font Size=-1>Liberal Arts Center - Marywood College</Font></B></Center>

<Center><IMG src="g_links.gif" alt=""><BR></Center>

<H1><CENTER><I>The Legal Studies Programs<BR></I></CENTER></H1><P>

<Center><IMG src="g_links.gif" alt=""></Center><BR>

<H2><U><I>The Preprofessional Major<BR>
</I></U></H2>

<P>
This curriculum is designed for students preparing for a career
in law as an attorney. The program provides a liberal arts and
social science foundation to enable a student to develop a broad
cultural background; habits of thoroughness, intellectual curiosity
and scholarship; the ability to organize materials and communicate
the results; and verbal skills. In addition to the 64 credits
in the liberal arts area required of all Marywood students, 66
credits in history, political science, social sciences, and legal
studies are required to fulfill the Preprofessional program.<BR>

<P>
Special features of this program include:
<UL>
<LI>A four week (160 hour) internship uniting the theory of the
classroom with the practical experience of a law office.
<LI>Continuing career advice from the College; from Marywood's
Law Advisory Board, a panel of area attorneys, judges, legal assistants
and others in the field of law, and from the College's director
and assistant director of legal studies.
<LI>The annual Law Day Red Mass and appreciation banquet.
<LI>Continuing legal education seminars.
<LI>Lackawanna Lawyer's Auxiliary Scholarship to a Preprofessional
major for excellence at graduation.
<LI>Schneider &amp; Harris, Esq. annual essay competition award
to students planning to attend law school. 
</UL>

<P>
For a copy of the complete curriculum, send request via e-mail to the  <A href="mailto:boland@marywood1.marywood.edu" Alt="">Office Manager</A>, Karen Boland, at the Department of Social Sciences.<BR>

<P>
<Center><IMG src="hline037.gif" alt=""></Center>
<H2><U><I>The Legal Assistant Major<BR>
</I></U></H2>

<P>
This program, fully approved by the American Bar Association,
provides preparation for a legal assistant (paralegal) career. Graduates are qualified
to assume a position as an assistant to attorneys in various substantive
areas of the law. Students are trained to prepare, summarize,
and interpret a variety of legal documents; do legal research;
conduct client interviews and maintain file control and handle
other administrative duties on behalf of an attorney. Students
in the four-year B.A. program and the two-year Associates program
graduate with a degree in Legal Studies and a Legal Assistant
diploma. The four-year program requires 127 credits; the two-year
program, 63 credits. Further, college graduates may apply to the
Post-Graduate Legal Assistant Diploma Program.
<P>
Special features of Marywood's Legal Assistant program include:
<UL>
<LI>The Legal Assistant Program holds membership in The American Association for Paralegal Education (AAfPLE).
<LI>The John R. Lenahan Sr., Esq. Scholarship Award for excellence
in the Legal Assistant Program is awarded to a Legal Assistant
major at the completion of the junior year.
<LI>Legal Assistant majors are invited to become members of Sigma
Pi Mu, Marywood's legal studies student association.
<LI>The annual Law Day Red Mass and Law Appreciation Dinner.
<LI>Legal Assistant majors conduct continuing education seminars
and attend professional seminars of legal assistant and bar associations.
</UL>

<P>
For a copy of the complete curriculum, send request via e-mail to the <A href="mailto:boland@marywood1.marywood.edu" Alt="">Office Manager</A>, Karen Boland, at the Department of Social Sciences.
<P>
<Center><IMG src="g_links.gif" alt=""></Center><BR>

<H1><CENTER><I>The Legal Studies Courses</I> </CENTER></H1>

<P>
<Center><IMG src="g_links.gif" alt=""></Center><BR>
<B>LE 200 - Introduction to the Legal System</B> (<I>Thomas M.
Jackson, J.D., Ph.D. </I>) As an orientation course, seeks to
create a better understanding of the law, the legal process and
the operation of the judicial system. Analyzes the role of the
lawyer and the legal assistant within the system.
<P>
<B>LE 210 - Writing for Legal Studies</B> (<I>Dr. Philip J. Tama</I>)
Accuracy and precision are fundamental to written legal expression.
This course stresses revision and logic as means to that end.
Students are introduced to the microcomputer and word processing
software. All papers are written, revised and printed using the
micro.
<P>
<B>LE 211 - Legal Writing and Research</B> (<I>Armand E. Olivetti
Jr., Esq.</I>) A core course which introduces the Legal Studies
student to the various modes and procedures of legal research
and writing. Focus is on practice and research. Several classes
are conducted in the Lackawanna County Law Library.
<P>
<B>LE 212, 213 - General Litigation</B> (<I>Bruce L. Morgan, Esq.</I>)
Studies jurisdiction of state and federal courts and the methods
of legal actions. Analyzes the litigation process.
<P>
<B>LE 252 - Business Law I</B> (<I>James J. Gillotti, Esq.; Joseph J. Galante, Esq.</I>)
After introductory material on sources of law, court systems,
civil procedure and tort liability, a substantial part of this
course is then devoted to the law of contracts. Also discussed
at length are business organizations, namely partnerships, limited
partnerships and corporations.
<P>
<B>LE 253 - Business Law II</B> (<I>James J. Gillotti, Esq.; Joseph J. Galante, Esq.</I>)
Agency and employment, bankruptcy, secured transactions, commercial
paper, the sale of goods under the uniform commercial code.
<P>
<B>LE 300 - Estates and Trusts</B> (<I>Michael Kosh, Esq.</I>)
Presents fundamental principles of law applicable to wills, trusts
and estate planning.
<P>
<B>LE 301 - Real Estate Law</B> (<I>Armand E. Olivetti, Esq.</I>) Deals with ownership,
sale, leasing and regulation of land.
<P>
<B>LE 314 - Interviewing and Counseling for Legal Studies</B>
(<I>Ms. Rosemary Munley, M.S.</I>) Examines techniques of effective
communications with clients of varying backgrounds. Current counseling
methods are presented with videotaped role plays of simulated
cases utilized to develop student interviewing skills.
<P>
<B>LE 315 - Constitutional Law I</B> (<I>Thomas M. Jackson, J.D.,
Ph.D.</I>) As the first of a two semester sequence on United States
Constitutional Law, this course deals with Supreme Court decisions
on separation of powers, federalism and powers of Congress and
the President. Gives particular emphasis to the Court's interpretation
of the contract clause, state and federal exercise of the commerce
power and other provisions of the main body of the Constitution.
<P>
<B>LE 316 - Constitutional Law II</B> (<I>Thomas M. Jackson, J.D.,
Ph.D.</I>) As the second part of a two semester sequence on United
States Constitutional Law, deals with the Supreme Court's interpretation
of the substantive rights of the First Amendment to the Constitution:
speech, press, petition, assembly and religion. Also emphasizes
the rights of persons accused of crimes, as outlined in the Fourth,
Fifth, Sixth, and Fourteenth Amendments. Deals with minority rights,
as protected under the Fifth and Fourteenth Amendments.
<P>
<B>LE 317 - Consumer Law</B> (<I>J. P. McGowan, Esq.</I>) Studies
the legal principles and remedies available to consumers.
<P>
<B>LE 318 - Family Law</B> (<I>Armand E. Olivetti, Esq.</I>) Covers
laws governing marriage, divorce, annulment, support, custody
and adoption.
<P>
<B>LE 319 - Criminal Law</B> (<I>Andrew J. Jarbola III, Esq.,
Steven Guccini, Esq.</I>) Introduces the criminal justice system
and the study of law dealing with criminal offenses.
<P>
<B>LE 320 - Landlord and Tenant Law</B> (<I>TBA</I>) Examines
current landlord and tenant problems along with statutory and
case law developments. Emphasizes enforcement of landlord-tenant
obligations.
<P>
<B>LE 321 - Legal Ethics</B> (<I>Theresa Pezak, Esq.</I>) Students
will examine ethical issues raised in the course of the practice
of law. In addition to examining rules and standards of the legal
profession, issues such as lawyer-client confidentiality, advertising
and solicitation, attorney fees, legal malpractice, conflicts
of interest and judicial conduct will be discussed.
<P>
<B>LE 322 - Torts</B> (<I>Paul K. Paterson, Esq.</I>) A study of the body of law whichconcerns private or civil wrongs or injuries, including negligence, product liability and malpractice.
<P>
<B>LE 323 - Workers' Compensation Law</B> (<I>James E. Pocius,
Esq., Joseph M. Caputo, Esq.</I>) A study of the law which focuses
on employment related accidents and diseases and the remedies
available to clients.
<P>
<B>LE 334 - Federal Taxation</B> (<I>Joseph A. O'Brien, Esq.</I>)
Presents a detailed study of federal income tax laws and regulations,
including a major emphasis on the federal income tax provisions
having common applications to all types of taxpayers.
<P>
<B>LE 340 - Environmental Law</B> (<I>Christopher P. Cullen, Esq.</I>)
Overview of the growing field of environmental law and the major
related statutes. Explores particular categories, issues and concerns
that affect American society and government in this field.
<P>
<B>LE 350 - Bankruptcy Law</B> (<I>TBA</I>) Study of the proceedings
whereby assets of a debtor are distributed to creditors with the
debtor then discharged from the obligation to pay the debts.
<P>
<B>LE 400 - Administrative Law</B> (<I>Paul K. Paterson, Esq.</I>)
Offers a case study approach to the impact of law and its administrative
application and interpretation.
<P>
<B>LE 401 - Seminar in Constitutional Interpretation </B>(<I>Thomas
M. Jackson, J.D., Ph.D.</I>) This course examines the writings
of Constitutional scholars such as Tribe, Levy, Ely and Bork to
explore the debate about the proper approach to Constitutional
interpretation and the interrelationship of law and politics.
<P>
<B>LE 402 - Computer Applications in Legal Studies</B> (<I>Kenneth
Boecker, M.B.A.</I>) Focuses on computer technology as a tool for
data gathering and problem solving in legal research.
<P>
<B>LE 437 - Taxation of Business Entities</B> (<I>James J. Gillotti,
Esq.</I>) Income taxation of corporations, tax implications of
the formation of a corporation, corporate distributions in and
not in complete liquidation, Subchapter S corporations and partnership
taxation.
<P>
<B>LE 440 - Advanced Legal Research</B> (<I>Marita E. Paparelli,
M.S.L.S., C.L.L.</I>) Designed to reinforce and expand the fundamentals
of legal research from a historic and theoretical perspective
and examine the basics of research, including those supported
by computer assisted legal research(CALR) such as Westlaw and
Premise and some non-legal research devices.
<P>
<B>LE 451A - Legal Internship</B> A seven-week (280 hour) placement
as a legal assistant in a law office under the supervision of
a lawyer. Evaluation of essential paralegal skills. Required for
all four-year Legal Assistant majors.
<P>
<B>LE 451B - Legal Internship</B> A four-week (160 hour) placement
as a legal assistant in a law office under the supervision of
a lawyer. Required for all two-year Associate Degree and Diploma
Program Legal Studies majors.
<P>
<B>LE 452 - Legal Assistant Management Principles</B> (<I>TBA</I>)
Focuses on applying knowledge and skills to the efficient operation
of an attorney's office.
<P>
<B>LE 453 - Senior Seminar</B> (<I>Lisa Tagliaterra, B.A.</I>)
Required of all four-year Legal Assistant majors. Reviews basic
legal assistant skills, helps student prepare resumes and develop
interviewing skills; analyzes job market; introduces students
to professional associations; discusses issues of current concern
to the profession.
<P>
<B>LE 499 - Independent Study</B> Involves faculty directed, student
initiated study and research on a topic relevant to student interest.
<P>
<IMG src="g_links.gif" alt="">
