<Head>
<Title>Marywood College-Supreme Court Circuit Appeal Cases Decisions Federal State</Title>
</Head>

<Body Background="bgrnd003.jpg" BGColor=#FFFFFF Text=#000000 Link=#0000FF VLink=#800080 ALink=#FF00FF>


<BGSOUND SRC="solfeggi.mid" LOOP=INFINITE><Br>

<embed src="solfeggi.mid" hidden="true" loop=infinite>




<Center><IMG src="gr_ban01.gif" alt=""></Center>
<Center><IMG src="redlogo3.gif" alt=""></Center>
<Center><IMG src="gr_ban01.gif" alt=""></Center><P>

<Center><IMG src="hline037.gif" alt=""></Center>
<Center><H3><I>"Prophecies of what the courts will do in fact, and nothing more pretentious,<Br>are what I mean by law."</I>    Mr. Justice Holmes, <I>The Path of the Law</I></H3></Center>
<Center><IMG src="hline037.gif" alt=""></Center>

<I><B><Center><H1>The Federal Courts</Font></H1></Center></B></I>

<I><B><U><H2> United States Supreme Court</H2></U></B></I><P>

<A href="http://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/" Alt="">Supreme Court Decisions</A>...Brought to you by the Legal Information Institute of Cornell University School of Law, this is an excellent searchable collection of all Supreme Court decisions from 1990 to the present.<P>

<A href="http://www.usscplus.com/" Alt="">USSC+</A>...Provides a searchable database of <U>leading</U> cases since 1793. Among the other points of interest included at this site:<U1>
<Li>A "Classic Case of the Week"
<Li>The rules of the U.S. Supreme Court
<Li>The U.S. Constitution
<Li>The Declaration of Independence
<Li>The Federalist Papers</Ul><P>

<IMG align=bottom src="redstar.gif" alt=""> <A href="http://oyez.at.nwu.edu/oyez.html" Alt="">Oyez Oyez Oyez</A> <IMG align=bottom src="redstar.gif" alt=""> A recent and growing database from Northwestern University, this site provides the actual oral arguments from landmark Supreme Court decisions since they first began recording them in 1955. Listen in to both sides arguing such all time greats such as <I>Gideon v. Wainwright</I> and <I>Terry v. Ohio</I>.<P>

<A href="http://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/justices/fullcourt.html" Alt="">The Justices</A>... Cornell's Legal Information Institute brings us this profile of current Supreme Court Justices. Included are photographs, biographical data, and a list of accessable decisions authored by each.<P> 

<I><B><U><H3>United States Circuit Courts of Appeal</H3></U></B></I>

<A href="http://www.law.emory.edu/FEDCTS/" Alt="">U.S. Federal Courts Finder</A>...The Emory University School of Law has compiled a directory to each of the First through Eleventh, the D.C. and the Federal Circuit Courts.  While most of these searchable sites have only recent decisions, i.e. since 1995, they are nonetheless a fine resource for finding that case decided only last week.<P>

<A href="http://www3.law.cornell.edu/Harvest/brokers/circuit-x/fancy.query.html" Alt="">All Circuit Court Opinions</A>...Another site maintained by Cornell, this page allows one to search all Circuit Court opinions on the internet simultaneously by keyword, phrase, party name or cite.<P>

<A href ="http://www.uscourts.gov/" alt="">The Federal Courts Home Page</A>...Provided by the Administrative Office of the U.S. Courts, this site functions as "a clearinghouse of information from and about the judicial branch of the U.S. Government".  Mostly administative type information.<P>

<I><B><U><H3>Federal Rules</H3></U></B></I><P>

<A href="http://www.law.cornell.edu/rules/fre/overview.html" Alt="">Federal Rules of Evidence</A>...From Cornell Law School's LII and Lawyers Cooperative Publishing, a searchable version of the complete Rules.<P>

<A href="http://www.law.cornell.edu/rules/frcp/overview.htm" Alt="">Federal Rules of Civil Procedure</A>...The complete Rules with chapter outlines, again from the Legal Information Institute at Cornell.<P>

<I><B><Center><H1>The State Courts</H1></Center></B></I>

<A href="http://www.law.vill.edu/State-Ct/index.html" Alt="">The State Court Locator</A>...Villanova School of Law provides this directory to the home pages and opinions of the 50 state judiciaries. Many states publish at least some of their appellate court decisions, but sadly Villanova's own home state of Pennsylvania has yet to do so.<P>

<IMG align=bottom src="redstar.gif"alt=""> <A href="http://www.findlaw.com/11stategov/index.html" Alt="">State Resource Locator</A> <IMG align=bottom src="redstar.gif" alt="">FindLaw maintains this site which allows Boolean searches of any or all of the 50  state government sites indexed, including but not limited to state judiciary sources. Very comprehensive.<P>

<IMG align=center src="eye_bar.gif" alt=""><BR>

