<html>
<head>
<title>IHM Web:  About Us:  IHM Present:  What We Do:  Sr Helene Hicks, 
IHM</title>
</head>
<body>
<h1>
<img src="../../Graphics/ihmlogo3.gif" alt=""><img 
src="../../Graphics/what_do.gif alt="What We Do" alt=""></h1>
<P>
<h2>
<img src="../../Photos/helene.gif" alt=""> Sr. Helene Hicks, 
IHM</h2>
serves as a registered nurse at the Spanish Catholic Center Medical 
Clinic and resides at St. John the Evangelist Convent, both in Silver 
Spring, MD.
<P>
<img src="../../Lines/sb10-1.gif" 
alt="____________________________________________________________________">
<P>
Our local community gathers for morning prayer and Mass in our convent 
chapel every weekday and uses this opportunity to praise and worship the 
Lord with several lay persons who join us.  It is a time of sharing 
concerns, praying for our Church and our world and for building 
community beyond the convent walls.
<P>
The work day begins at 8:30, usually preceded by a leisurely drive 
through Sligo Park -- this is the scenic route and it affords one the 
opportunity to see the seasonal beauty and handiwork of God before the 
hectic, frequently frustrating, workday begins.  Once the door to the 
clinic is opened, there is the almost unceasing ringing of the telephone 
with requests seeking medical advice, asking for vaccine records, 
appointments for laboratory work, pregnancy tests, well-baby check ups, 
OB/GYN exams, requesting food, receiving scheduled appointments from the 
Archdiocesan Health Care Network, as well as other agencies seeking help 
for their clients.
<P>
This particular morning I see several patients who have obstetrical 
problems.  The first is a 22 year old mother who was having thyroid 
problems and had missed her menses.  Is she pregnant again or are her 
symptoms a result of her malfunctioning thyroid?  How can she take care 
of another baby when she already has a 2-1/2 month old infant and the 
whole experience of motherhood is so new?
<P>
I see a second woman who has been married for six years and has been 
unable to conceive.  She had previously been seen at another clinic and 
told "everything" was "normal" and yet given no further help or advice.  
After some discussion and further questioning, she agreed to obtain her 
records and bring them to the clinic at which time we would give her an 
appointment with our OB/GYN doctor.  She departed with a smile and words 
of gratitude.
<P>
The next patient was an unscheduled walk-in, 28 years of age, mother of 
five with complaints about back pain radiating down her legs, having 
difficulty walking and 8 months pregnant without prenatal care.  She 
was crying and nervous.  Since our clinic does not have prenatal 
facilities, we have to refer these cases to other local agencies.  Time 
was given to this woman to calm her and urge her to go to the county 
hospital for immediate care.  I make a note to call her on Monday and 
verify that she had, indeed, gone to the hospital with the note 
describing her symptoms and requesting assessment and treatment as needed.
<P>
The morning passed all too quickly after seeing other patients and, 
since one of the six volunteer pediatricians was coming that afternoon, 
the clinic closed for lunch.  The staff eats in a kitchen at the clinic 
and there was a lively exchange about the latest happenings in the area, 
news topics, and family events -- an over-all relaxing period in a busy 
work day.
<P>
That afternoon, one of our special clients, Pablo, stopped by to say 
hello and to spend some time with us.  Pablo is a 30 year old Guatemalan 
who came to the U.S. so that he could earn money to buy a truck and 
return to his country to help his father transport produce to the 
market.  He had not foreseen that he would be diagnosed with lymphoma, 
be unable to work and have to undergo chemotherapy, but, of course, 
neither did we, when he first appeared at the clinic door with swollen, 
painful arms and nowhere to go for help.  He has a wonderful outlook, 
always has a smile, never complains even though he has lost all his hair 
and frequently feels nauseated.  When he cannot find work or is unable 
to work he comes to the clinic and does "little" jobs that need 
to be done.  Pablo is an inspiration to all of us.
<P>
That afternoon while I was preparing the infants/children for their 
examinations, the social worker from downstairs came up and asked if I 
would be able to "squeeze" another "special" child into the doctor's 
already crowded afternoon.  After I heard the background, my only 
response could be "Yes."  The toddler's story began last July when a man 
requested that Maria take care of his son until he attended to an 
emergency at the hospital.  Needless to say the man never returned and 
Maria has added another member to her family of five children.  She did 
not and does not know the boy's age, name or origin -- but after five 
months she has grown to love this little boy who she has fed and 
nourished and nurtured with motherly care and concern.
<P>
When he came up to be measured prior to seeing the doctor, he appeared 
to be a well-mannered, friendly, well-nourished toddler of about 18-19 
months.  This little "John Doe" immediately won a place in our hearts 
and obviously had a large part of his new mother's for she had named him 
after her own father since none of her birth children had received it.  
Once again I looked at another person sent to us, who was a valiant 
woman, personifying Christian values and not hesitating to act upon them.
<P>
The other infants/toddlers seen that day for checkup and vaccines had 
the routine problems for that age period.  The clinic usually closes at 
5:00 but because of a few "extras," the doctor didn't finish until 5:00, 
so by the time we closed the door for the weekend, night had arrived and 
rush hour was well on its way.
<P>
Dinner at the convent is at 6:00.  There is a real attempt to ask 
everyone how her day went and to share the funny as well as the poignant 
points of the day's work and I shared the story of little "John Doe."  
After dinner the evening news attracts a large number of viewers with 
comments and statements frequently being made about the topic of the moment.
<P>
The chapel offers the quiet and solitude where I can go after the 
evening activities to reflect on the day and how I was able to "see" 
God's presence and workings in the events and persons that made up these 
last 12-14 hours.  He had indeed manifested Himself in various people 
and I was grateful that I was able to see once again.  Thus passed the 
normal  day in the life of a clinic RN.  Yet, I can remember in nursing 
school one of the instructors saying that the word NORMAL is never used 
because what is normal for one person may not be normal for another.  As 
I ponder this thought, an acronym came to mind that might, indeed, allow 
me to use the word "NORMAL" for my work in the Medical Clinic for the 
Spanish Catholic Center:  Numerous Opportunities for Reflection, 
Mission, Advocacy, Love.
<P>
<img src="../../Lines/sb10-1.gif" 
alt="____________________________________________________________________">
<P>
