<html>
<head>
<title>IHM Web:  About Us:  IHM Present:  What We Do:  Sr. Mary 
Newett</title>
</head>
<body>
<h1>
<img src="../../Graphics/ihmlogo3.gif" alt=""><img 
src="../../Graphics/what_do.gif" alt="What We Do"></h1>
<P>
<h2>
<img src="../../Photos/mary_n.gif" alt=""> Sr. Mary 
Newett, IHM</h2>
serves as a pastoral associate at St. Bernard Parish in Riverdale, MD, 
and lives at St. John the Evangelist Parish in Silver Spring, MD.
<P>
<img src="../../Lines/sb10-1.gif" 
alt="____________________________________________________________________">
<P>
Someone asked me, "What is a typical day for you?"  The answer came forth 
immediately, "There's no typical day!"  Because pastoral work involves 
meeting people's needs, it is of necessity flexible, unplanned many 
times and often subject to change.  That has been my experience for 
these past 20 years.
<P>
However, the daily horarium that is somewhat typical is rising about 
5:30 a.m., dressing, eating breakfast, and then spending 30 minutes in 
private prayer, until communal prayers begin at 6:45 a.m. in the 
chapel.  Each sister takes a turn at preparing the morning prayers and 
it is interesting to find out what she has planned.  Mass is at 7:00 
a.m. and by 7:30 it is usually finished.
<P>
Since my commute to St. Bernard's in Riverdale, MD doesn't begin until 
8:30 a.m., I have an hour to continue prayer for awhile, read, etc.  By 
the Washington Beltway it takes about 20 minutes to get to the rectory 
where I have an office and begin my duties as Pastoral Associate.
<P>
Tentative plans for the day are to visit a parishioner in a nearby 
hospital, plan for a Eucharistic ministers meeting that evening, and 
take Holy Communion to two shut-ins, who recently had surgery and are 
unable to attend Mass.  Afterwards, I will assign Eucharistic ministers 
to see them on a regular basis.
<P>
After arriving I may receive word that a parishioner has died.  I then 
call the family to schedule a time to meet with them to plan the funeral 
Mass.  A form is filled out indicating their preferred scripture 
readings, lectors, people for offertory procession, people to place the 
pall on the casket, etc.  This form is given to the priest, cantor and 
organist.  A visit to the funeral home, attendance at the funeral Mass 
and services at the cemetery complete my involvement in the process.
<P>
Three days a week I leave the rectory at 4:00 p.m.; Wednesday is "duty 
day" and I arrive at 11:00 a.m. and leave at 8:00 p.m.  Friday is a day 
off, Saturday I arrive at 3:00 p.m. staying until 6:30 p.m. and Sunday 
goes from 7:00 a.m. to 1:00 p.m.
<P>
Most meetings are scheduled in the evening, i.e., parish council, 
liturgy training sessions, interviews, etc.  The weekend schedule is 
centered around the Eucharistic liturgies.  Greeting the people is the 
ministry of hospitality.  I welcome them to this sacrificial banquet 
where they will be nourished by the Word and Sacrament so that they can 
be witnesses of Christ in all they do during the following week.
<P>
This is the time when people stop to let me know if someone in the 
family is sick, or to ask for prayers for some intention.  In this way I 
have come to know personally many people in the parish.
<P>
The convent community gathers at 6:00 p.m. for supper and afterwards I 
may watch TV in the community room, read, do domestic chores and usually 
watch a program or two until retiring around 9:30 p.m.
<P>
<img src="../../Lines/sb10-1.gif" 
alt="____________________________________________________________________">
