<html>
<head>
<title>IHM Web:  About Us:  IHM Present:  What We Do:  Sr. Mary Elizabeth 
Muir</title>
</head>
<body>
<h1>
<img src="../../Graphics/ihmlogo3.gif" alt=""><img 
src="../../Graphics/what_do.gif" alt="What We Do"></h1>
<P>
<h2>
<img src="../../Photos/elizabeth.gif" alt=""> Sr. Mary Elizabeth Muir, 
IHM</h2>
is a first grade teacher at Holy Rosary School, Scranton, PA.
<P>
<img src="../../Lines/sb10-1.gif" 
alt="____________________________________________________________________">
<P>
<dl>
<dt>4:30 a.m. 
<dd>I spend my prayer time waking and centering myself on the 
readings I prepared for prayer last night.  The two pieces that struck 
me and connect are from Isaiah: "strengthen the weak hands, and make 
firm the feeble knees" and from Luke's Gospel the image of the crippled 
man's friends bringing him to Jesus despite many difficulties.  I find 
myself in touch with my own weaknesses and limitations yet grateful for 
the people who have brought me in faith closer to Jesus to find 
strength.  I pray that I may be that faithfilled person for another day.
<P>
<dt>6:30 a.m. 
<dd>As we gather for communal prayer, I find myself continually 
amazed by the reality of our diversity.  Our commitment to prayer 
reminds me that it is our faith alone that binds us in community.
<P>
<dt>7:00 a.m. 
<dd>Mass is in the school chapel with a consistent group of 
people whom I do not know well and yet with whom I feel a connection as 
we share this celebration together regularly.  As I am reading the first 
reading, thinking about the lines that struck me, I looked up.  Usually 
no one makes eye contact, but I found myself connecting with a parent of 
one of my first graders.  Because she is not someone usually present at 
Mass, I figured that it must be a mass for one of her family members and 
I remember that at a recent conference she shared the pain of loss that 
their family has experienced.  I am grateful to have the opportunity to 
pray with her.
<P>
<dt>7:30 a.m. 
<dd>Quick trip home for breakfast and last minute scheduling of 
after-school plans with one of the sisters.
<P>
<dt>8:00 a.m. 
<dd>The children have arrived and begin to fill the classroom 
with noise and conversations of the past weekend happenings.  They 
notice even the smallest changes in our classroom that I made over the 
weekend.  I appreciate their awareness.
<P>
<dt>8:30 a.m. 
<dd>We gather in our class and remember in a sign language 
prayer that we are all connected and we desire to work together during 
the day.  The children are particularly attentive to our prayer this 
morning.  Excitement builds when we spend our first half hour practicing 
for the Christmas show.  The children are very confident and doing well.
<P>
<dt>9:00 a.m. 
<dd>We join the other primary classes for an advent prayer in 
the hallway.
<P>
<dt>9:15 a.m. 
<dd>It's time for hard work!  Reading time.  Today we are 
practicing rhyming words that will be part of our next story.  I notice 
that the rain outside and the coming Christmas activities are making it 
difficult for the children to concentrate ... so we take those rhyming 
words and make a song.  A song always captures their attention.
<P>
<dt>10:00 a.m. 
<dd>A little break before sending them to Miss Scalese for 
music practice.  We play a number game that is directed toward a couple 
of children having difficulty with auditory perception but which all the 
children enjoy playing.
<P>
<dt>10:15 a.m. 
<dd>While the children are out for music practice I take time 
to make final preparations for lessons for the week and write a thank 
you note to the Post Office for the field trip we took last Friday to 
see Mr. and Mrs. Santa Claus.
<P>
<dt>11:05 a.m. 
<dd>We have just enough time to squeeze in some handwriting 
practice before lunch.
<P>
<dt>11:20 a.m. -- Lunch time --
<dd>after getting the children settled with their chicken nuggets, I 
join some of the other teachers for lunch and we talk over some of the 
logistics for the Christmas Show.
<P>
<dt>11:55 a.m. 
<dd>Lunch is over, the children did not get out for recess 
because of the rain and are now feeling the effects of being indoors all 
morning.  I make some adjustments to our afternoon schedule to include 
some light activity to accommodate their little bodies:  acting out the 
twelve days of Christmas in math as we reviewed counting backwards was 
their favorite.  We viewed a video titled, "Nicholas, the Boy Who Became 
Santa," which was my favorite part of the afternoon.  It gave a little 
shift in attitude towards some tasks I needed to do that I wasn't 
looking forward to.
<P>
<dt>2:15 p.m. -- Dismissal time --  
<dd>We remember to pray for a little boy who is absent.  During the day 
we received news that his grandfather had died.
<P>
<dt>3:00 p.m. 
<dd>I met a Sister to run errands.  We had a great conversation 
and she encouraged me in areas that recently have been of great 
discouragement to me.  We experienced what seemed like a comedy of 
errors that brought lots of laughs.  It felt good to laugh.
<P>
<dt>5:15 p.m. 
<dd>We met as a community for evening prayer.  I was conscious 
of one sister's absence, aware that she was working very hard and long 
hours wondering if there is anything I could do to assist her.
<P>
<dt>5:30 p.m. 
<dd>We enjoy dinner together telling stories of family and 
community Christmas celebrations gone by -- most of them very humorous.
<P>
<dt>6:30 p.m. 
<dd>Decorating time for the Christmas show and I am aware that 
I am tired at this point in the day.  Doing what I can, I decide it 
would really be best to go home and take care of some odds and ends to 
be ready for another day tomorrow.
<P>
<dt>8:00 p.m. 
<dd>I jot down notes to be ready to write this journal entry 
tomorrow night and then take time to prepare the readings for tomorrow 
morning's prayer.  It seems sometimes the days pass and they are full of 
"busyness," little details and quick encounters with others.  But it is 
in reflecting on the little things that I find God most present.
<P>
</dl>
<img src="../../Lines/sb10-1.gif" 
alt="____________________________________________________________________">
<P>
