</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>IHM Web:  About Us:  IHM Present:  What We Do:  Sr. Nancy 
DeCesare</title>
</head>
<body>
<h1>
<img src="../../Graphics/ihmlogo3.gif" alt=""><img 
src="../../Graphics/what_do.gif" alt="What We Do"></h1>
<P>
<h2>
<img src="../../Photos/nancy.gif" alt=""> Sr. Nancy DeCesare, IHM</h2>
is the Director of Social Services for the New York Foundling Hospital, 
an agency that cares for over 10,000 children and their families.  She 
resides at Blessed Sacrament Convent, Staten Island, NY.
<P>
<img src="../../Lines/sb10-1.gif" 
alt="____________________________________________________________________">
<P>
I usually rise in the morning between 5:45 and 6:00.  The sisters often 
tease me as I can dress in record time.  It must be a carry-over from my 
novitiate days.
<P>
Today is the Feast of St. Albert the Great who was a theologian in the 
early church and a great writer of policies for the Vatican.  Hearing 
our resident prison chaplain preach about his life this morning reminds 
me of my work as I daily address the policies of our society that both 
protect and exploit our children.
<P>
The gospel reading is from Luke 19:1-10.  Zaccheus is the main character 
who, because he was a tax collector, was considered a man involved with 
"dirty deals."  I have lots of little Zaccheuses where I minister.  They 
are young boys and girls, ages 10 to 15, who are children involved in 
dirty deals through their live on the streets.  These are children used 
and abused by parents and adults who should be their protectors.
<P>
This morning I arrived at the hospital at 7:20 to find Michael running 
down the fire escape with the garbage from the third floor boys' living 
area.  Michael has been with us a little over two months.  This is the 
longest he has stayed anywhere.  He has been in 14 different placements 
since his mother abandoned him at age 10.  She is a drug addict and no 
one has heard from her in over four years.  Most likely she has died 
from her addiction.
<P>
Angel stands guard from the fire escape making sure Michael reaches the 
dumpster.  One could write a book about Angel.  As I soon found out ... 
Angel is no angel.  At age nine he became the youngest drug runner to a 
gang called the Latino Kings in the Bronx.  He rarely attended school 
and he cannot read or write at age 15.  He is a child who was sexually 
abused by his uncle continually as a young boy as was his brother who is 
also in care.  No mother, no father, no extended family, this child is a 
survivor of the streets and proudly wears a blue and white bandana to 
witness to the world his true gang colors.  It is the only family he as 
ever known.
<P>
Angel, as is the case with many of our children, will eventually be 
placed in a residential treatment center, a facility for troubled youth 
in upstate New York.  Perhaps it will offer him the kind of love and 
attention he has never known as a child.
<P>
This morning I attend two diagnostic treatment conferences to discuss 
Doug, age 14, and Anna, age 12.  I chair the diagnostic team consisting 
of the psychologists, social workers, psychiatrists, educational staff 
and medical team.  All have completed their testing and have come to 
make recommendations regarding the needs of these children.  We are very 
lucky today since for the first time in many months we have actually 
found not one but two of Doug's parents.  Although divorced they have 
enough interest to attend.  Perhaps in a year or so with family therapy 
it may be possible for Doug to return home to one of them.
<P>
We're not so lucky however with Anna who went AWOL before her conference 
day.  Although she originally went AWOL to her drug addicted mother in 
the Bronx, she ran back to the streets before anyone could intervene.  
We made our recommendations in this conference, but who knows if Anna 
will ever escape the life of the streets to try and implement them?  We 
can only pray for her at this point.
<P>
Time flies quickly in the hospital and my afternoon finds me driving to 
New York City with two other social workers for a case review on eight 
children in care.  We pray there is no traffic as we know this will 
surely make us late.  Our internal review team asks questions as to why 
these children are still in placement after nine months.  There are no 
simple answers and they know it.  These are throw-away children, many 
are already orphans or will be soon as parents die of AIDS.  Even though 
we know most of our children will be placed in residential treatment 
facilities, there is still a need to explore any possible family member 
or foster home placement.  Most of the children are so damaged by the 
time they arrive they cannot return to the community just yet.  For most 
we are their only advocates and family and so daily we struggle to 
provide the best for them.
<P>
The latter part of the afternoon finds me driving home by myself as the 
other two workers finished early and returned by train.  As I cross the 
lower westside I pass Covenant House's Right of Passage Program.  There 
is a young girl standing on 19th Street hustling.  I wonder if anyone 
sees her or will reach out to her.  I take special note of her face, her 
size and her clothing as she may well be our next placement tonight.  So 
many Zaccheuses, so many "dirty deals."  Only God knows how to save all 
of them.
<P>
At 5:00 I return home in time for evening prayer and dinner with the 
sisters.  Tonight's prayer is on community.  It is a good source of 
strength for me as I see so much brokenness each day.  It reminds me 
that we are all in this together.
<P>
Tonight is a good night, no evening meetings to attend.  It is however 
my night to cover emergency intakes for the hospital and the group 
homes.  I wonder as I sit back and relax just how many Zaccheuses will 
God send us this night.  I pray that God will help us to do so much more 
to reach this quickly dying population of street children.
<P>
Although they are living on the streets, stealing and prostituting to 
survive, involved in gangs, they are still God's children who, like 
Zaccheus, if given the opportunity, can find a better quality of live 
and love.  I easily fall asleep but, as I do so tonight, I pray for 
deeper acceptance by our world of children and for the transformation of 
those who do "dirty deals" to them.
<P>
<img src="../../Lines/sb10-1.gif" 
alt="____________________________________________________________________">
<P>
<a href="domenu.html">Return to What We Do Menu</a><br>
