<html>
<head>
<title>IHM Web:  About Us:  IHM Present:  What We Do:  Sr. Mary Elaine 
Anderson</title>
</head>
<body>
<h1>
<img src="../../Graphics/ihmlogo3.gif" alt=""><img 
src="../../Graphics/what_do.gif" alt="What We Do"></h1>
<P>
<h2>
<img src="../../Photos/mary_e.gif" 
alt=""> Sr. Mary Elaine Anderson, IHM</h2> 
is a pastoral minister in San Felipe, Sicuani, Peru. 
<img src="../../Lines/sb10-1.gif" 
alt="____________________________________________________________________">
<P>
<dl>
<dt>4:30 a.m. 
<dd>I am awakened by the voices of our neighbors who are early 
risers.  I can hear them loading up their trucks and also the voices of 
men, women and children as they prepare for the journey that will take 
them up into the mountains and to market in Santa Barbara.  As I lay in 
bed I too begin to plan my day ... recalling the activities marked on my 
calendar and askng God for the energy to complete each one.
<P>
<dt>5:30 a.m. 
<dd>This time I am awakened by my alarm.  I rise, and as I open 
the door to my bedroom, I am greeted to a blast of cold air and watch 
our dog sleep on the balcony outside my room.  Crossing the patio to the 
kitchen I realize that it rained during the night, and think of our many 
neighbors who have been worried that the dryness will ruin their crops 
and who no doubt are grateful for last night's rain.  In the kitchen as 
I boil water for the thermoses I also wash the dishes left from the 
night before (water is turned off throughout Sicuani from 8:00 p.m. to 
5:00 a.m.) and sweep the floor.  Then I take my cup of coffee to the 
chapel where I spend 15 minutes preparing the day's readings.
<P>
<dt>6:00 a.m. 
<dd>I am back in the kitchen where I get a head start on 
preparing dinner ... washing rice and cutting the meat.
<P>
<dt>7:00 a.m. 
<dd>Peggy (a Sister of St. Joseph who lives with us) and I meet 
for prayer.  We are the only two because Eileen Egan is attending a 
meeting in Puno and Tomasa Fernandez left early for the campo.  The 
readings are filled with rich images of God's kingdom.  I reflect on the 
wolf that lies down with the lamb, the calf that eats with the lion and 
the child who cares for them.  I pray for Peru, for understanding among 
its different cultures and for peace and respect between the rich and 
the poor.  I wonder if I am not a little like Jesus' disciples who fail 
to see the kingdom in their midst, and so I pray for eyes to see God 
hidden in my day.
<P>
<dt>8:30 a.m. 
<dd>I wash my clothes (by hand) and hang them on the line.
<P>
<dt>9:00 a.m. 
<dd>Rufina's father (Rufina is a little girl who used to live 
on the street and is now in an orphanage in Cusco) comes to our door.  I 
scold him for drinking too much, ask him whether he is working and send 
him on his way with an orange.
<P>
<dt>9:15 a.m. 
<dd>I shower, dress and organize the art materials which I will 
need for the children in Sillota.
<P>
<dt>11:00 a.m. 
<dd>As Peggy and I are leaving for Sillota two men stop us 
outside our house to ask about having a funeral in San Felipe's chapel.  
They tell us about a young woman who was struck by lightening the day 
before.  We walk with them to the elementary school where we ask 
Guillermina, the daughter of the sacristan, to open the church for the 
priest and the family at 2:00 p.m.  By now it is too late to take the 
longer route and more gradual climb to Sillota, so we take the short cut 
which means crossing the mountain.  We are huffing and puffing when we 
reach the top, but the view is glorious.  Seeing our house on the edge 
of town and the green fields below, I am energized.  At that moment, God 
is so real to me.
<P>
<dt>12:00 p.m. 
<dd>The children of Sillota are waiting for us.  The school 
includes grades one to four and there are about 30 students.  They are 
the poorest in the area.  Even though they live close to Sicuani they 
cannot afford to go to school there.  The children are anxious to finish 
the nativity sets that we had begun making from stones.
<P>
<dt>2:30 p.m. 
<dd>We arrive home.  I heat up our dinner, and we eat.
<P>
<dt>3:30 p.m. 
<dd>I set out alone taking the back route across streams and 
fields and through the woods to Acobamba.  The catechist and about 30 
children are waiting for me.  We sing carols and practice a play based 
on Luke's account of the birth of Jesus which we are preparing for the 
Christmas celebration.  The children are very happy, and they insist 
that I play a game with them before I leave.  I also enjoy playing, so I 
don't refuse.
<P>
<dt>6:00 p.m. 
<dd>I arrive home, I am tired and decide to relax for awhile.  
I fall asleep.
<P>
<dt>7:30 p.m. 
<dd>I fix a cup of hot chocolate and take it to the community 
room.  Peggy and Thomasa are already there.  As we talk I prepare the 
materials I need for the workshop that I am giving in Yanaoca tomorrow.
<P>
<dt>9:00 p.m. 
<dd>I go to my room.  As I am preparing for bed I think about 
the day's activities and thank God for all the opportunities I had to 
meet Him/Her during the day.  I pray especially for the husband and 
children of the woman who was buried this afternoon.  I read a few pages 
of my current novel, and I am soon sleepy.
<P>
<dt>9:45 p.m. 
<dd>I turn out the light and quickly fall asleep.
</dl>
<img src="../../Lines/sb10-1.gif" 
alt="____________________________________________________________________">
