<head>
<title>IHM Web:  About Us:  IHM Past:  Theresa Maxis Duchemin:  Letter 
23</title> </head>
<body>
<h2>
<img src="../../Graphics/ihmlogo3.gif" alt="IHM Web:  About Us:  "><img 
src="../../Graphics/theresa_maxis.gif" alt="Theresa Maxis Duchemin"></h2><br>
<h2>Mother Theresa to Sister Genevieve</h2>
<pre>
                           J.M.J.A.T.
                          West Chester
                           June 1887
</pre>
Sister M. Genevieve<br>
Ever dear Child
<P>
As a note I had written to you some day last January did not reach you, 
and being anxious for you to be informed of at least a part of its 
contents.  I again make the attempt to write without any scruple, since 
I have received no prohibition in that regard as you have, and for which 
I cannot see the reason why.  Even M. Gonzaga sent letters I had written 
to Scranton.  Still for prudence sake, the Superiors and myself think it 
is better for me not to write only on some particular occasions.  So I 
intend sending this note, if I can find the opportunity, wrapped up in 
such a way that the bearer will not think it is a letter, but only a 
small parcel.  I pray daily for a change in circumstances. 
<P>
Now, for the matter in question, the fine picture of the Holy Face, 
which you left with me, when you were here last November to be sent to 
Rev. F. Gaudet in your name.  This I did when writing him for Christmas, 
and it happened well, having at the time no card to send as I had the 
year previous, and which was one of those fine one I had received from 
M. Francis and yourself the last Christmas I spent in Ottawa, which I 
had kept for that purpose. 
<P>
Well in the Father's letter to me he first thanked for the picture, as 
he always does on receiving the Annual every year, for he feels very 
grateful and is much pleased with the attention.  In his first letter 
after my arrival here, he sent his most hearty thanks to M. Francis and 
to you for all you both done [sic] for my return for which he had been 
as much interested as if it was for himself.  I did tell you about it at 
the time. 
<P>
***
<P>
Being here now, I understand better the state of perplexity existing in 
our Order, and I think that the present situation of things the best for 
us, is remain quiet and pray, pray daily to obtain a more favorable 
prospect in regard to our beloved Institution and the completion of what 
is yet wanting. 
<P>
God alone knows what a great and painful disappointment it is for me of 
not having been after nearly 3 years able to visit Scranton, and see 
there all my dear Sisters.  I who thought that when once here, I would 
be at liberty of choosing my own home, and my heart prompted me for 
Scranton, since it was from there all sympathy and encouragement came to 
me.  To all I say <u>Fiat</u> and still hope in the Almighty power of 
God for a change. 
<P>
***
<P>
As I liked [sic] very much to know if you have received this paper, 
since you cannot write I will suggest one way to let me know, which 
would be, if you should send me by mail a nice card directed to me 
before of after your retreat, that I may have it to send to Fr. Gaudet 
for his feastday the 28 of August, St. Augustin, then I will be sure 
that you received my note.  Besides dear M. Francis told me when here to 
ask if I should want anything.  I would have more to say had I more 
assurance. 
<P>
With sentiments of deep affection for dear Mother Francis and yourself, 
I will conclude, embracing you both with my whole heart. 
<P>
Believe me dear child, in union of prayers,<br>
Truly and gratefully yours,<br>
In the Sacred Hearts of Jesus and Mary Immac.<br>
Sr. M. Theresa, C.I.M.
<P>
<img src="../../Lines/sb10-1.gif" 
alt="____________________________________________________________________">
