<html>
<head>
<title>IHM Web:  About Us:  IHM Past:  Louis Florent Gillet:  
Reunion</title>
</head>
<body>
<h2>
<img src="../../Graphics/ihmlogo3.gif" alt=""><img 
src="../../Graphics/louis_gillet.gif" alt="Louis Florent Gillet"></h2><br>
<h2>Reunion . . .</h2>
The following description of Father Gillet's reunion with the IHM 
Congregations is adapted from Sister Maria Alma's (Immaculata) <cite>The 
Reverend Louis Florent Gillet:  His Life, Letters and Conferences</cite>, 
1940, Philadelphia:  The Dolphin Press.
<P>
<img src="../../Lines/sb10-1.gif" 
alt="____________________________________________________________________">
<P>
A special blessing was reserved for Pere Marie Celestin in his declining 
years.  His whereabouts were sought for many years.  It was known that 
he had entered a Cistercian community, but there all traces ended.
<P>
To the motherhouse in Reading came in 1868 (20 September) one who had 
long been familiar with religious life.  At her reception in December of 
the same year she took the name, Sister M. Clotilde.  Few besides Mother 
Gonzaga, who received the postulant of thirty-eight years of age, 
dreamed of the interest attaching to her earlier life.  She had been for 
almost twenty years a Visitandine, in Moselle, France, and for one term, 
at least, Mother Superior ...
<P>
In this same Visitation Convent lived her friend in Christ, Sister Marie 
Stephanie, who later sought the monastic life of Citeaux, and who with 
many of her Sisters [after the dissolution of their community] joined 
the community of Cisterciennes of Notre Dame de Pres d'Hautecome, at 
Reillanne in Southern France.  The Cistercian Fathers of Hautecombe 
served as chaplains to the community at Reillanne, and thus Father 
Gillet, who spent the last twenty-eight years of his life at Hautecombe, 
met and knew well Sister Marie Stephanie, who was for several terms the 
Prioress of Notre Dame de Pres.
<P>
To these same Cisterciennes had come, in 1867... Sister Marie Celestine, 
Father Gillet's sister Catherine, who for twenty-eight years (1839 - 
1867) had been a Sister of Charity of Ghent in Belgium, but who, 
following the example of her brother, sought the contemplative life.  It 
was Mother Marie Celestine who welcomed the Visitandines to Reillanne.
<P>
Sister Clotilde has left some very interesting correspondence between 
herself and Sister Marie Stephanie, covering a period of forty-two 
years, (1866 - 1908) from which may be gleaned precious scraps of 
information regarding the long-sought Founder, who was a chaplain at 
Notre Dame de Pres and life-long friend to the Cisterciennes.  To the 
Sisters, Servants of the Immaculate Heart of Mary, however, these held 
no connotation:  to Sister Marie Stephanie he was Pere Marie Celestine, 
the Cistercian; to his American children, he was known as Father Louis 
Florent Gillet; neither dreamed that the two were the same person.
<P>
Then in 1888 a chance word in the correspondence lead to the suspicion 
that this much-loved Cistercian was in some way connected with the 
long-sought Founder;  Sister Marie Stephanie chanced to write:
<P>
<blockquote>
     I ought to write very soon to the good Reverend Father 
     Superior at Hautecombe, and I shall not forget your 
     commission for Father Gillet.  It is almost ten years 
     since he was elected Prior.
</blockquote>
<P>
Sister M. Clotilde at once began inquiries through her nephew, Father 
Cesaire, a Cistercian, stationed at the motherhouse in Lerins.
<P>
The Sisters in Michigan, in commemoration of the forty-fifth anniversary 
of their foundation, published in the Michigan Catholic  of 25 December 
1890, a short account of the community, with sketches of the first log 
convent and of Father Gillet.  Mother de Chantal secured one of these 
for Sister Clotilde, who immediately forwarded it to Father Cesaire, at 
Lerins.  The letter was transmitted to Hautecombe, and to Father Marie 
Celestin.  Very soon -- one can surmise with what emotion -- the Father 
and his "daughters" were <a name="letter1" 
href="letter1.html">reunited</a>!  The tiny seed planted in 1845 in 
the unpromising soil of pioneer Michigan had become a great tree whose 
branches spread over three separate sections of our country, sheltering 
within their shadows thousands whose lives were touched by the Sisters, 
Servants of the Immaculate Heart of Mary.
<P>
Sister Marie Stephanie's letters make very frequent references to Father 
Gillet, telling of the joy he experienced in finding again his "spiritual 
daughters of the new world," a joy shared not only by his good Father 
Abbot, but also by all the Cistercians at Hautecombe...
<P>
The Sisters, in their joy at the long expected but nevertheless 
surprising answer to their years of persevering prayer, invited the 
founder to visit them.  To this the increasing infirmities of advancing 
years proved an insurmountable obstacle, for he was now seventy-eight 
years of age.  He sent, however, in a letter dated 4 May 1891, a detailed 
and authentic account of the <a name="letter2" href="letter2.html">origin 
of the community</a> ... 
<P>
But the years were taking their toll on the life of the founder; his 
infirmities increased until each day became an oblation of prayer and 
suffering.  Writing of these last days, his Prior, Father Marie 
Symphorien, says:
<P>
<blockquote>
     He seldom left his cell; he occupied his days with prayer, 
     saying the divine office regularly, and directing from this holy 
     solitude his beloved retreatants.  On All Saint's Day (1892) he 
     received the Last Sacraments in the presence of the 
     assembled community.  Responding with feeble voice to the 
     exhortations of the Prior, he spoke touchingly, as only his 
     noble heart could, of his love for the Christ of the Holy 
     Eucharist, his remembrance of the needs of those who 
     surrounded them, with the promise to pray for each in heaven,
     his regret for the faults of his entire life ...
<P>
     For a short space it seemed that the grace of Extreme Unction 
     had given the dear Father a new lease on life; he even, with 
     great effort went to his work table to pen some <a name="letter3" 
     href="letter3.html">last words of adieu</a> to his daughters in 
     America.  But scarcely was he able to write six short lines, almost 
     illegible, when he laid down the pen forever.
</blockquote>
<P>
On the night of 13-14 November, 1892, his agony began.  After touching 
prayers and the recommendation of his soul to God he pressed the Prior's 
hand to signify that he still understood; then the Reverend Father 
bestowed upon Father Gillet the last absolution and the Apostolic 
Benediciton.  "Very soon the soul of God's Priest passed sweetly to 
Heaven on the wings of prayer, the Holy and adorable Name of Jesus."  It 
was one o'clock in the morning of Monday, 14 November 1892.
<P>
<img src="../../Lines/sb10-1.gif" 
alt="____________________________________________________________________">
