<html>
<head>
<title>IHM Web:  About Us:  IHM Past:  Louis Florent Gillet: Letter Feb 
9, 1891</title>
</head>
<body>
<h2>
<img src="../../Graphics/ihmlogo3.gif" alt=""><img 
src="../../Graphics/louis_gillet.gif" alt="Louis Florent Gillet"></h2><br>
<h2>Reunion</h2>
<h3>February 9, 1891</h3>
<P>
<pre>
Le 9 Fevrier, 1891
J.M.J.B.				Abbaye Royale de N.D. d'Hautecombe
						Ordre de Citeaux (Savoie)
</pre>
<P>
Very Reverend Mother,
<P>
A most mysterious letter reached me a few days ago; it was accompanied 
by a paper (The Michigan Catholic) and a prospectus of Villa Maria 
Boarding School.  The packet was directed by a person who signed herself 
Sr. M. C. from the Convent of Villa Maria, religious of the Immaculate 
Heart of Mary, to her nephew, with the request that he forward it to 
me.  This gentleman who is unknown to me (unless it is our Father 
Cesaire) has sent all to me through the kindness of our Father Abbot of 
Lerins, and it was thus that I received the letter that you directed to 
your nephew, the Michigan paper, etc.  The whole packet was a mystery to 
me, as I received it without explanation, without direction, without a 
word from Father Cesaire.
<P>
After a serious reading of the letter, I began to understand!  And it is 
that charitable kindness of yours that brings me to break the silence of 
fifty years!  In truth that is a very long time!  But the thousand 
vicissitudes of my career, my profound distaste for things of the world, 
my entrance into the Order of Citeaux in 1858, where I have since led 
the contemplative life; all these motives have contributed to break up 
for me all intercourse with the world.  Our manner of life being one of 
continual silence, with the exception of one half-hour recreation on 
Sundays, you will understand that, knowing nothing, one finds nothing to 
say.  Having lived all these years in the beautiful solitude of 
Hautecombe, I little thought that, far away across the ocean, there was 
still some remembrance of me, and that from a legion of Mary's Children, 
sprung from Monroe, the cradle of your Congregation which is today so 
flourishing, should come at the end of my days, the consoling message 
that the little grain which I planted long ago, has produced a great 
tree under whose shadow numberless souls have been sheltered, have been 
saved!
<P>
May God be praised for the deep consolation this news has brought me!  
It is to your charity, [Very Reverend Mother], that I owe it all; 
receive here the expression of my gratitude.  For all that you tell me 
recalls to my mind memories which the long years past could never 
efface!  I have read with care the paper with its good picture of 
myself.  What is said there of the beginnings of your Congregation is 
correct.  Miss Renauld is, I think, Sister St. Celestine.  After her 
came Mother Theresa with Sister Anne.  Then the [cousin] of the Mayor of 
Monroe, the first after them to take the habit publicly in the church of 
Monroe, was a young widow.  I have forgotten her name [Josette 
Godfroy-Smyth, later Mother M. Alphonsine].  The paper does not speak of her 
... has she not persevered?
<P>
Mother Theresa could tell you the story of the veil and our going to 
Toledo for the purpose of obtaining a pattern of the habit.  How great 
was their Poverty!  Even before taking the vow, they were forced to 
practice it, and to add to their miseries, not one of them knew how to 
cook!  They were afraid at night, and many a time I told them that they 
were more trouble to me than my congregation and all my missions (and I 
had ten of these).  Then they would weep!
<P>
You tell me that Mother Theresa is still living?  She was so frail, so 
delicate!  I thought she had long ago gone to Heaven.  I cannot believe 
that she is so old!  Eighty-one years!  I thought she was much younger 
than myself, and I am now in my seventy-eighth year.  Except for trouble 
in walking, I am well, with a little care.  I still go around the house 
with the aid of a cane, and I am able to assist at Divine Office in the 
choir during the day ...
<P>
Twenty-five years ago, having gone to see my mother at Louvain, I met a 
Father of the American College, who had succeeded me at Monroe [Reverend 
Edward Joos].  I asked him what had become of the newly established 
community.  To my great astonishment, he told me that it had prospered 
and spread far away.  Thinking that the new religious were all 
Americans, and did not know me, I remained in silence ...
<P>
The work of God has prospered in a marvelous manner ... I needed your 
affirmation and that of the paper to make me believe it ... Be [my] 
interpreter with the dear Sisters, members of the community of the 
Immaculate Heart of Mary.  I would be glad to express to each one my 
sentiments of paternal affection, but their number is too large for my 
poor voice to reach each one:  it is to the Immaculate Heart of Mary 
that I confide them, it is to that sweet Heart that I shall tell my 
wishes for their spiritual and temporal happiness.  In the past, God has 
blessed you most generously; your existence in the Church is His work; 
your remarkable expansion, a striking miracle and your life a lasting 
Apostleship!
<P>
How many souls you have already saved!  Everything is extraordinary!  
Everything proclaims God's work!  His Power!  Who would, considering all 
that, dare to glorify himself with the title Founder of a work in which 
his own nothingness is so visible, and for which God seems to have taken 
pleasure in choosing such poor instruments on both sides! ... a young 
man without experience, without means, and some poor creatures, 
strangers in the district.
<P>
However, I love to claim that title by which I am remembered among souls 
dearly beloved by Mary!  May they think of me in their prayers!  They 
will never see me in this life; but united by the ties of charity, in 
the Sacred Hearts of Jesus and Mary, I have the hope that we shall know 
one another in Heaven!
<P>
It is in these sentiments and with this hope that I beg you, Very 
Reverend Mother, to accept the assurance of my profound respect
<P>
<pre>
						    Fr. Marie Celestin, O.C.
							     (Louis Gillet)
</pre>
<P>
<img src="../../Lines/sb10-1.gif" 
