<head>
<title>IHM Web:  About Us:  IHM Past:  Louis Florent Gillet:  Letter May 
4, 1891</title>
</head>
<body>
<h2>
<img src="../../Graphics/ihmlogo3.gif" alt=""><img 
src="../../Graphics/louis_gillet.gif" alt="Louis Florent Gillet"></h2><br>
<h2>Historical Account</h2>
<h3>Written by Father Gillet and enclosed in his letter of 4 May, 1891.</h3>
<P>
Account of the origin of the Congregation of the Sisters, Servants of the 
Immaculate Heart of Mary, founded in Monroe, State of Michigan in 1845, 
Bishop Lefevre being Bishop of the Diocese, under the original name of 
Sisters of Providence.
<P>
Very Reverend Mother Superior and dear Sisters in our Lord,
<P>
It is in answer to your legitimate request that I take the pleasure of 
sending you this account of the origin of your Congregation.  Difficult 
as it is to write at my advanced age, I do it nevertheless, all the more 
willingly because in invoking memories already very old, I am carried 
back to those happy years of my early priesthood, years of zeal and fervor.
<P>
These pages will tell you better than anyone could, the Divine action of 
your Congregation, so small in its beginnings; and in return all that 
God expects of a work which is His and destined to exercise a glorious 
apostolate among youth, as past experience has shown ...
<P>
I am not ignorant of the fact, Reverend Mother and dear Sisters, that 
the ordinary conduct of Providence is to choose the weakest to effect 
great things, in order so much the better to display His power, and in 
order that man may not attribute success either to his skill or to his 
resources.  I know also that the great works of God, such as the 
foundation of those religious orders which for centuries have been the 
ornament of the Church, have all had weak beginnings and have taken 
birth in obscurity, but on the other hand, their founders were men 
filled with the spirit of God, already Saints, although still on earth.  
I may say as much for the Congregations of persons of your sex, founded 
often by simple souls, deprived of all human advantages, but again,
 they were chosen souls, distinguished only for their humility, drawing 
after them by the power and inspiration of their virtues a multitude of 
souls desirous of putting themselves under their direction.
<P>
In all this, Reverend Mother and Sisters, let me tell you, and let these 
words remain inscribed in the annals of your Congregation; yes, in all 
this, you are an exception.  You must indeed recognize it.  Your origins 
are not illustrious, your titles to nobility are poverty and obscurity; 
it is of these elements that God has formed the great Congregation of 
the Children of the Immaculate Heart of Mary.
<P>
In fact, you founder, if it pleases you to give him this name, who was 
he?  A young priest, full of zeal, it is true, but perhaps indiscreet 
zeal, without experience in the ways of God, without resources.  And 
your first Sisters?  Four poor creatures, unknown to the world and 
hiding under the religious habit their humble origin.  However, in spite 
of elements so weak, that which is your glory is to have risen by a 
continual correspondence to grace and your perseverance in the midst of 
difficulties, I shall say, daily sacrifices, to this height where you 
are today, and which has made of your Congregation one of the most 
beautiful ornaments of the Church in the United States.  Glory to God!  
Glory to Mary!  Honor to you all, privileged children of the Queen of 
Heaven! ...
<P>
I had been in Monroe but a few years following a very successful Mission 
which had revived the faith of the Canadians, and my plan was to make 
this our first French house, all the others being German.  The 
approbation of the Superiors being obtained, as well as that of the 
Right Reverend Bishop, two other Fathers were sent to me.  In addition I 
received two lay brothers in quality of novices.  We were five (fathers 
and brothers) living in two small houses.  It was not long before I 
realized that these dwellings were quite insufficient and that at any 
price, I had to think of building.  A serious obstacle presented 
itself.  The Church at Monroe and its appurtenances were the property of 
the congregation administered by trustees.  Before undertaking anything, 
I called a meeting of the congregation as well as of the trustees.  
After having explained to them my plan to establish ourselves 
permanently in their midst and to build, I asked the congregation for 
the renunciation of all properties in my favor, and the abandonment of 
all their rights.  This was granted to me unanimously, and the deed was 
drawn up and registered with the government.
<P>
A first step was taken, but in order to build, money was necessary -- a 
great deal, and I had nothing.  It was impossible to get anything from 
Baltimore, from the Bishop or from the Propagation of the Faith, which 
allowed the Bishop 50,000 francs a year with which he was building his 
Cathedral.
<P>
At that time I was officiating in ten stations, three between Monroe and 
Detroit, four beyond Detroit and three in the direction of Adrienne.  
Being the only one familiar with the three languages, I was more often 
on horseback than at home, always on the road.  The two other Fathers 
officiated in the parish, one for the Canadians, the other for the Irish 
and the Germans.  The income from my missions and the resources accruing 
from the Church at Monroe enabled me, by living frugally, to begin 
little by little to enlarge the house adjoining the Church which was 
also enlarged.  We were going very slowly, stopping work whenever money 
was lacking, and never contracting any debts.  I must add that the 
Canadians helped me greatly by their labor.  The house was going up 
slowly and I was anticipating in the near future, the day when we could 
live in it.
<P>
Relieved of this anxiety, a need of another kind remained to be filled, 
a need which concerned my conscience and the souls of the numerous 
children forced to attend the Protestant school and more often growing 
up in ignorance.  This need was greater for the girls than for the boys; 
the girls, seeking to resemble in everything the American Protestants, 
associated only with them and disdained the Canadians, spoke only 
English, went to English schools, kept by Protestants; and all this 
ended with a mixed marriage, and from that day they were Catholics only 
in name.  The music in the Protestant Churches charmed them, the singing 
pleased them and our services bored them.
<P>
Such was my plight!  But how to remedy this evil and prevent these 
dangers?  By a Catholic school kept and directed by religious women.  
But where was I to get them?  There was not a single religious in the 
vast State of Michigan.  Those who had been at Detroit had left as a 
result of differences with the Bishop (Rese).  How could I procure any 
from another State, having only privations to offer?  In a visit to my 
neighbor, Father Rappe, Pastor of Toledo and later Bishop of Cleveland, 
former Chaplain of the Ursulines in Boulogne, France, I learned that he 
was expecting three [Notre Dame de Namur Sisters] for his parish in 
Toledo.  His project pleased me, but meant nothing to me, even while 
exciting my jealousy.  One day when he was congratulating himself 
on the good fortune which he had had, I ended by saying that if I did 
not find the means of obtaining any religious, I would make some.
<P>
A short time after, having gone to Baltimore to solicit help from our 
Fathers, though I did not obtain any, I gave a retreat to the "Sisters 
of St. Charles," then entirely abandoned, living still in community, but 
whose vows had not been renewed for a long time.  Two of them expressed 
the desire to be admitted into a regular congregation.  One was 
sufficiently educated to accomplish the object which I was considering.  
I told them to wait and that probably in a short time I would try to 
associate with them some pious souls determined to second my efforts to 
take charge of the education of the children of Monroe, and that we 
could begin with a school for girls.  My intention in bringing these 
persons together was to lay the foundations of a little religious 
congregation which would perhaps, with the help of God, develop later.
<P>
Thus a year passed in waiting.  In the meantime I was seeking these 
souls of good will!  I found two.  This was sufficient considering the 
smallness of the house and the lack of resources.  I prepared a very 
short Rule, modeled on that of the Redemptorists, which would suffice 
for the moment.  Bishop Lefevre approved it, and the new Congregation 
was placed under his immediate jurisdiction with vows for one year.  All 
that was only temporary in my thoughts.  The Institute was to bear the 
name of "Sisters o f Providence," which it actually took.
<P>
When I saw the new house ready for use, (after a fashion) I sent to 
Baltimore for my two "Charlatines," and kept them for some weeks at some 
distance from Monroe at the home of Mr. Robert O'Connor, an excellent 
Catholic, where they remained in secular dress without being noticed.
<P>
There remained to be decided the habit which my future religious would 
adopt, a rather difficult matter for me.  After having uselessly 
searched my memory without being able to decide on anything definite, I 
went to Toledo to examine from head to foot the habit of the [Poor 
Clares], for I kept my plan a secret.  I succeeded in remembering the 
style of the veil and with the help of that information, I sent my 
postulants to work.  Everything being in readiness for my future 
religious, we took possession of our new house before there were doors 
or windows or a stairway, a ladder served the latter purpose.  
Immediately my four poor candidates entered the two little houses which 
we had just left.  They were Mary Maxis, Charlotte Schaaf, Therese 
Renauld and Mrs. [Godfroy-Smyth], a widow, a relative of the Mayor of 
Monroe, of a mature age, without children and who promised to make a 
good superior later, of a firm and determined character, enjoying the 
esteem of the entire population of Monroe.
<P>
Three days later, Sunday, Sister Anne and Sister Theresa, having 
received the new habit privately and renewed their three vows, appeared 
in the dress of the Professed Sisters in the Church where I was about to 
give the habit solemnly to the other.  Never had a religious been seen 
in Monroe, still less the taking of the veil.  It was quite a 
revelation.  The Church could not contain the crowd eager to gaze upon 
those creatures who seemed to come from another world.
<P>
After the usual questions and the blessing of the habit, the postulant, 
dressed in white and lead by the two professed Sisters, withdrew into 
one of the chapels, prepared for the occasion, and reappeared a short 
time later, transformed, in the habit of a novice.  The whole assembly 
gave a start, they stood on the benches in order to see better.  The 
sermon completed the instruction of my Americans and excited their 
admiration for such great devotion.
<P>
The work was founded!  On the solid rock of poverty!  Naturally it was 
necessary to provide everything and for a rather long time.  This was 
what concerned me least ...
<P>
Invited a short time after to preach a course of Lenten Sermons in New 
Orleans, I undertook this long journey in the winter with the prospect 
that I should find there perhaps some resources to help my poor 
religious.  Instead of giving a retreat, it was rather a large mission 
which produced extraordinary fruits of conversion, so that after the 
exercises I was obliged to remain nearly two months longer to hear the 
confessions.  My labors were amply rewarded.  I received $525.00, an 
offering from the ladies, $300.00 from the trustees, and having left 
with a little carpet bag, I returned to Monroe with thirteen large boxes 
containing provisions of all kinds.  I was rich then and from that time 
on the condition of the Sisters improved.
<P>
Our house finished, there remained to me only to enjoy in peace the 
realization of my plans.  That consolation was not to be mine.  I must 
have other trials.  After having been Superior for four years at Monroe 
and having founded the French house, I was recalled to Baltimore ... The 
hour of trial was about to begin for me.  Those trials were personal, I 
shall not speak of them ...
<P>
If until now I did not seek to recover any trace of the little work at 
Monroe, it is because I had already learned many years ago at the 
American Seminary at Louvain, that there were indeed religious in 
Monroe, but Sisters of the Heart of Mary.  From that time I was 
convinced that my work had died out ... From that time I did not receive 
any more news from Monroe until the day on which there arrived this 
mysterious letter from Mother Clotilde who told me that I still lived in 
the thoughts and memory of some friends beyond the sea.  Great was my 
joy as well as my surprise at seeing renewed the ties which I thought 
broken forever and which I hope in the future become closer ...
<P>
It is in these sentiments of fatherly affection that I remain, Reverend 
Sisters,
<P>
<pre>
			   Your very humble and affectionate
					   Brother in Jesus Christ,

						   Father Marie Celestin
</pre>
<P>
<img src="../../Lines/sb10-1.gif" 
alt="____________________________________________________________________">
