<HTML>

<Head>
<Title>Marywood Pre-law Paralegal Legal Assistant Law Schools Student Resources</Title>
</Head>

<Body Background="bgrnd003.jpg" BGColor=#FFFFFF Text=#000000 Link=#0000FF VLink=#800080 ALink=#FF00FF>


<BGSOUND SRC="wm111mov.mid" alt="" LOOP=INFINITE><Br>

<embed src="wm111mov.mid" hidden="true" loop=infinite>



<Center><IMG src="gr_ban01.gif" alt=""></Center>
<Center><IMG src="redlogo6.gif" alt=""></Center>
<Center><IMG src="gr_ban01.gif" alt=""></Center><P>

<Center><IMG src="g_links.gif" alt=""></Center>
<Center><I><B>"There is no better way of exercising the imagination than the study of law. <Br>No poet ever interpreted nature as freely as a lawyer interprets the truth."</B></I><Br> Jean Giraudoux, <I>Tiger at the Gates</I></Center> 
<Center><IMG src="books02.gif" alt=""></Center>
<Center><IMG src="g_links.gif" alt=""></Center><P>

<Center><H1><I>Pre-Law & Paralegal</I></H1></Center><P>

<H2><I><U>Law Schools</U></I></H2><P>

<A href="http://www.hg.org/students.html" Alt="">Hieros Gamos</A>..."Basic information on every law school on earth." 1300+ law schools, with links to their home pages.<P>

<A href="http://www.yahoo.com/Government/Law/Law_Schools/" Alt="">The "Yahoo!" List</A>...From the renowned folks at Yahoo, a searchable directory of law school links.<P>

<A href="http://www.jmls.edu/law/schools/" Alt="">Law School Internet Sites</A>...From John Marshall Law School, searchable by map, alphabetical list, or by state.<P>

<A href="http://www.usnews.com/usnews/FAIR/law1.htm" Alt="">U.S. News Law School Rankings</A>...Information on accredited U.S. law schools; academic reputation by academics, judges and lawyers; median LSAT scores; Specialties and employment after graduation percentages.<P>

<H2><I><U>Pre-Law Resources</U></I></H2><P>

<A href="http://www.urich.edu/~polisci/prelaw.htm" Alt="">Pre-Law Handbook</A>...Everything you've always wanted to ask about law school, but didn't know who to ask. A fine guide by Bill Swinford at the University of Richmond.<P>

<A href="http://www.lsac.org/" Alt="">Law School Admission Council</A>...These are the folks that bring us the dreaded <B>LSAT</B>. Complete information on the test, registration, publications, et al.<P>

<A href="http://www.kaplan.com/lsat/" Alt="">Kaplan</A>...LSAT preparation materials, as well as information about the law school application process.<P>

<A href="http://www.review.com/law/law_homepage.html" Alt="">Princeton Review</A>...LSAT review courses, along with search engine to visit law schools.<P>

<A href="http://www.ot.com/multi-app/" Alt="">MULTI-App</A>...This commercial software allows preparation of more than one law school application at a time by placing common information on each of the law school's replicated application forms which can then be printed out.  Accepted by 60 law schools.<P>

<H2><I><U>Paralegal Resources</U></I></H2><P>

<A href="http://www.nala.org/index2.htm" Alt="">NALA</A>...The homepage for the 15,000 member National Association of Legal Assistants.  Information on professional certification, professional standards, publications, and membership.<P>

<A href="http://www.paralegals.org/" Alt="">NFPA</A>...The website for the National Federation of Paralegal Associations.  Information on certification, membership, publications.  Career related topics, legal research links, list services, and more.<P>

<A href="http://www.wuacc.edu/sas/paralegal/paralegal.html" Alt="">ParaLaw</A>...Provided by the Washburn Legal Assitants Society of the Washburn University Legal Assistant Department.  Information of interest to paralegals/paralegal students.
<P>

<H2><I><U>Jobs</U></I></H2>
<P>

<A href="http://rescomp.stanford.edu/jobs/" Alt="">JobHunt</A>...A huge list of on-line job search resources and services put together by the folks at Stanford.
<P>

<A href="http://loki.fedworld.gov/jobs/jobsearch.html" Alt="">Federal Jobs</A>...A searchable database of Federal jobs by the government organization FedWorld. Search by type of job and the state where you would like to work.
<P>

<A href="http://www.ajb.dni.us" Alt="">America's Job Bank</A>...From the U.S. Department of Labor and state employment services, provides listings of jobs posted through the various state agencies.
<P>
<H2><I><U>Miscellany</U></I></H2><P>

<A href="http://www.law.onu.edu/exams.html" Alt="">Law Exams</A>...Actual old (a couple of years) law school examinations from Ohio Northern University School of Law in such areas as Torts, Contracts, Criminal Law, Remedies, Consumer Protection, etc.<P>

<A href="http://192.41.4.29/study.html" Alt="">Course Outlines</A>...From our friends at the 'Lectric Law Library, law school course outlines gleaned from throughout legal cyberspace.<P>

<A href="http://www.law.cornell.edu/citation/citation.table.html" Alt="">Basic Legal Citation</A>...Don't have a Blue Book handy? By Peter Martin, through Cornell's LII, an excellent reference for both beginner and experienced alike.<P>

<A href="http://www.emanuel.com/" Alt="">Emanuel Law Outlines</A>...Can't fathom that twenty pound text? You can view free samples or order these well known outlines.  You need PkUnzip or comparable, but if you don't have it you can download here.<P>

<Center><IMG src="colbartn.gif" alt=""></Center>
<Center><I><B>"A judge is a law student who marks his own examination papers"</B></I><Br>H.L. Mencken</Center>
<Center><IMG src="colbartn.gif" alt=""></Center><P>

<IMG src="eye_bar.gif" alt=""><Br>
<Table border=0 width=100% align=Center Colspec="L20 L20 L20 ">
<Tr><Td><Font Size=-2>Created With</Font></Td><Td></Td><Td><Font Size=-2>Best Experienced With</Font></Td></Tr>
<Tr><Td><IMG src="webthing.gif" alt=""> <A href="http://www.arachnoid.com/index.html" Alt="That's a spider"> WebThing</A> CareWare</Td><Td></Td><Td><A href="http://www.microsoft.com/ie/" Alt=""><IMG src="iestatic.gif" alt=""></A></Td></Tr>
</Table>

<P>

<IMG align=left src="mus06.gif" alt=""> <FONT SIZE=2>With thanks
to <A href="mailto:gbreed@connectnet.com" Alt="">Greg Breed</A> for his midi sequence arrangement of Suite No. 1 in F from Handel's Water Music.
More may be found at the <A href ="http://www.prs.net/midi.html" alt="">Classical Midi Archives.</A></FONT><P>

<Center><Font Size=-1>Special thanks to <A href="mailto:pap95@worldnet.att.net" Alt="">Marita E. Paparelli</A>, Director, Lackawanna County Law Library, for her gracious assistance.</Font></Center>
<Hr Width=80% Align=Center><P>

