<A NAME="editorial"></A> 


<STRONG>January notes - Microscopy-UK 1997</STRONG><BR>

<P>A new year has arrived and here at Microscopy-UK our intrepid
bunch of

Amateurs are full of ideas and ambitions to spread the growth and

interest of Microscopy throughout the world.</P>



<P>And we're not ones to hang around.... The first Amateur
Microscopy

Web-Radio is now open to bring you interviews, tips, news,
exhibition

coverage, Nature Walks, and other related broadcasts while you
browse the

web. Check out:

<a
href="http://www.micropix.demon.co.uk/radio/amfront.htm">AM.NET-UK</a>

 to hear our first historical broadcasts.</P>



<P>And that's not all: we've released our first Amateur
Microscopy CDROM,

hopefully the first of many to come. <a

href="http://www.micropix.demon.co.uk/radio/cdrom1.htm">Take a
look</A>

and see what fantastic goodies can come your way!</P>



<P>Looking  forward - come and take part in the Microscopy UK
workshops which are being held at the<B> 1997 Edinburgh
International Science Festival at Gorgie City Farm from 31 March to 4 April</B>. More
details of these events will be found on these pages shortly, in
the meantime contact Anne Bruce <A HREF="mailto:abruce@netcomuk.co.uk">  for more information.</A></P>



<P>Lots more surprises are on their way to implementation so if
you love the

microscopic world, stay with us. We just love having you as our
friends.</P>

<P><I>Maurice Smith - Microscopy-UK coordinator</I></P>

<BR><BR> <P> <CENTER> <STRONG>  Scroll
up/down or   <A HREF="#newstop">   Go back to top of news  </A>
</STRONG> </CENTER> </P> 

<BR><BR>

<A NAME="fieldstudies"></A> 

<br>
<b>Natural History Courses in Britain for 1997</b><br>

<P>The Field Studies Council (FSC) offer a wide range of weekend and week-

long residential courses throughout Britain in a relaxed and very

friendly atmosphere. These are based in Field Centres sited in some of

Britain's finest countryside.</P>



<P>The FSC's latest catalogue of courses for 1997 is now available from the

address below. Almost every branch of natural history is covered

including plants, birds, mammals, pond and stream dipping as well as

courses on art, local history, archaeology, crafts etc. Many of the

courses cater for the novice and family as well as for the more

experienced and are led by experienced tutors.</P>



<P>Even if you are not UK based but were planning a stay in the UK, a

weekend course could be an ideal way of learning about Britain's nature

as well as seeing some of its best countryside.</P>



<P>Warning: if the author's experiences are anything to go by these courses

are highly addictive!! </P>



<P>Address: Field Studies Council, Preston Montford, Montford Bridge,

Shrewsbury SY4 1HW, UK. Tel 01743 850674. Fax 01743 850178. <a

href="mailto:fsc.headoffice@ukonline.co.uk"><b>Email FSC</b></a>.</P>



<P>Information on overseas courses organised by the FSC can be found at <a

href="http://www.soton.ac.uk/~dace/fsco/index.htm"><b> FSC

Overseas.</b></a></P>
<BR><BR> <P> <CENTER> <STRONG>  Scroll
up/down or   <A HREF="#newstop">   Go back to top of news  </A>
</STRONG> </CENTER> </P> 

<BR><BR>


<A NAME="reallywild"></A> 

<Strong><BOLD><FONT SIZE=4>"Wild"</FONT>goings on at Microscopy UK</BOLD></Strong><BR>
<P>Two of the Microscopy UK team (Polly and Andrew Syred) were invited to  the BBC's Natural History Unit at Bristol to visit the set of<B> "The Really Wild Show"</B>. This popular programme is to feature the dustmite in its<B> BAKER'S BASEMENT</B> section. Readers of Microscopy UK should be familiar with this creature's features as captured by Andrew in his SEM pictures. Why don't you <BLINK><A href="http://www.micropix.demon.co.uk/spotdec2.htm"></BLINK>read the whole story</A> for yourself. </P>

 <P><B>Watch out</B> for the Baker's Basement slot in the Really
Wild Show  on BBC1 at 4.35pm -  <B>every Thursday from the 2nd
Jan to 27th March inclusive</B>.</P>


<BR><BR> <P> <CENTER> <STRONG>  Scroll
up/down or   <A HREF="#newstop">   Go back to top of news  </A>
</STRONG> </CENTER> </P> 

<BR><BR>



<A NAME="newsection"></A> <P> <strong>New Section opens on
Microscopy-UK</strong> </P> 



<P> Yup, we know you teachers out there (and you students) are
under stress and duress. Some of our best friends are teachers
and they are telling us how it is! </P> 

<P> So we thought we would try and help a little bit. We asked
our friends at  Brunel Microscopes if they could put together a
video and a set of lectures covering all aspects of human
biology and boy did they come up with a real treat. </P> 



<P> We thought it was so good, that we decided to open a
complete new section to offer real lectures on chosen themes
from our pages both here and in the states. The first of these
is available now from our main index as: THE BRUNEL LECTURES.
The lecture topic will change-out periodically and if you have a
specific theme you would like us to cover then please  <A
HREF="mailto:mol@molcol.demon.co.uk"> let us know! </A> </P> 



<P> <em>Maurice Smith</em> (Microscopy-UK coordinator). </P> 

