<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>www.microscopy-uk.org.uk : Microscopy Movie Player and Movies   </TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#000000" text="#dd0000" vlink="#ff8000" link="#a000a0" alink="#aa0000"><center>
<h3>** Version 1.1 of player now available **</h3>

<h4>"You are not alone!"<br>
4487 movie-goers have been here since  April 7th 1996</h4></center>
<br><IMG SRC="http://www.micropix.demon.co.uk/movies/movi.gif" width=400 height=200 align=left>
<HR>
<P><h1>*FREE* Microscopy Movies from the Amateurs</h1>
<br><A name="movietop"><CENTER>
<h2>Point, Click, and Select!<br>(Use HELP if this is new to you)</h2>
</CENTER><center><table cellpadding=6>
<tr>	<td colspan=3><A HREF="#about"><img src="http://www.micropix.demon.co.uk/movies/buthlp.gif"></A></td>	</tr>	<td><A HREF="#downplay"><img src="http://www.micropix.demon.co.uk/movies/butply.gif"></A></td>	<td><A HREF="#downgrp"><img src="http://www.micropix.demon.co.uk/movies/butwin.gif"></A></td>	<td><A HREF="mailto:mol@molcol.demon.co.uk"><img src="http://www.micropix.demon.co.uk/movies/butreg.gif"></A></td>	</tr>	<tr>	<td colspan=3><A HREF="http://www.micropix.demon.co.uk/movies/downmovi.htm"><img src="http://www.micropix.demon.co.uk/movies/butmov.gif"></A></td>		</tr></table></center><center><h1><strong><a href="../mag/indexmag.html">Return to Micscape Main Index</A></strong></h1></center><center><h1><strong><a href="../index.html">Go to Microscopy-uk Front Page</A></strong></h1></center><p><br><br><br><br><a name="about"><center><H2>About Micscape Movies</h2></center><br><h2><center>Select from this Sub-Index or Scroll down the lot!</center></h2><table cellpadding=6>		<tr><td><a href="#moviefiles">Movie Files</A></td> <td><a href="#compat">Compatibility</A></td> <td><a href="#player">The Player</A></td> <td><a href="#free">Conditions of use</A></td>	</tr>	<tr><td><a href="#swap">Enhanced Version</A></td> <td><a href="#dos">DOS version</A></td> <td><a href="#windows">WINDOWS version</A></td> <td><a href="#downplay">Download Player</A></td>	</tr>	<tr><td><a href="#downgrp">Download Win3.n bits</A></td> <td><a href="#movietop">Return to Button Selector</A></td>	</tr></table><a name="moviefiles"><H3>The Movies</H3>Micscape Movies are small video sequences. Subjects are filmed either through a microscope or with a special camera directly, and then digitised for 'play-back' on IBM compatible PCs.Each movie is very short but, through the way the images are organised, will 'run' continuously on your monitor. This keeps the files small enough for trouble-free and speedy downloading from the Micscape Magazine Web Site.<p>Each one or more microscopy movies will be made available from these pages. Movie files are stored on Micscapeas compressed (self-extracting) executable files - that is: you need to <b>Run</b> them first after downloadingthem to extract the real movie file or files.<p>The Movie Player expects a movie file to be a <b>M{number}.QPL</b> file. All movie filenames start with the letter 'M' and havea suffix of '.QPL'. The rest of the filename consists of a sequence of numbers. The filename must not be altered in any way!! An example of an extracted movie filename is: M1295513.QPL<br><br><center><h4><em><a href="#about">Sub-Index</A> / <a href="#movietop"> Button Selector</A></em></h4></center><br><br> <a name="player"><p><H3>The Movie Player</H3>Micscape Movies can only be played back by using Micscape's special movie player software. This is <b>very special software</b> because it allows you to see real-time animation on a wide range of hardware and software platforms. We could make it into a 'helper' application for Netscape but it seems quicker and cheaper for you to simply bring movies down to your PC and run them off-line. If you think a helper application would be better then <a href="mailto:mol@molcol.demon.co.uk">drop us a line.</A><br><br><center><h4><em><a href="#about">Sub-Index</A> / <a href="#movietop"> Button Selector</A></em></h4></center><br><br> <a name="compat"><p><h3>Compatibility</h3>The player will run micscape movies on all of these: <i>286, 386, 486, &  Pentium Processors; on any speed processor <b>even SX16's</b>, any VGA card - as long as it is a colour VGA - from VGA to SVGA; it will work under most forms of DOS from MSDOS 3.1 to 7.0, Norton DOS, PCDOS, etc.</I> It will also run underWindows from 3.0 to Win95 in a DOS session. You don't need any other software like mpeg players, special drivers,nor do you need a mouse, soundblaster card, or a fast access hard disk. The Micscape Movie Player was designed by Molcol Software to show the incredible life-forms and the savage beauty of our Microscopic world. The softwarehas been created to be as hardware and software independent as possible, except for the limitation that it can onlybe used on IBM compatible PCs <em> or possibly MAC computers</em> (see below).<H3>MAC computers</h3>The Movie Player has been reported to work fine on a MAC computer using Soft 'Windows', although we (the amateurs) havenot tested it ourselves!<br><br><center><h4><em><a href="#about">Sub-Index</A> / <a href="#movietop"> Button Selector</A></em></h4></center><br><br> <p><a name="free"><h3>Conditions of use</h3>And the good news is: <b>you can use it for as long as you like without paying for it!</b>
The Micscape Movie Player, and the movies it is designed to work with, are SHAREWARE but with a vital difference. You can use it for as long as you want to <i>payment-free</i> simply by emailing us and registering your payment-free use.Simply <b><A HREF="mailto:mol@molcol.demon.co.uk">contact us</A></b> stating your real name and address, your e-mail address, and a one-liner saying "I'm registering for payment-free use". <br><br>
<center><h4><em><a href="#about">Sub-Index</A> / <a href="#movietop"> Button Selector</A></em></h4></center><br><br> <a name="swap"><center><h4><em><a href="#about">Sub-Index</A> / <a href="#movietop"> Button Selector</A></em></h4></center><br><a name="dos"><h3>How to set up and use the Movie Player (Dos Users)</h3><ol><li> Save this html page to your PC for future reference.<li> Download the Movie Player.<br><li> Download a movie.<br><li> Exit your Browser.<br><li> Create a new directory on your PC Hard Disk and call it <b>\micscape</b><br><li> Move or copy the downloaded files into your new directory.<br><li> Log onto the new directory.<li> Issue a directory command 'Dir' to list the compressed movie file names.<br><li> Run the compressed files by entering their names at the command line.<br>     (This will extract a .QPL file from each M{number}.exe compressed file.<br><li> From the DOS command line, Enter: MICMOVIE<br><li> Next time you visit us, register your free-use .<br>

<LI> Each month, download a new movie into your Micscape directory.<br><p>     (Note: you can delete the compressed M{number}.exe movie file from your      hard disk once you have extracted the M{number}.QPL movie file).<p></ol><p><br><center><h4><em><a href="#about">Sub-Index</A> / <a href="#movietop"> Button Selector</A></em></h4></center><br><p><a name="windows"><h3>How to set up and use the Movie Player (Windows 3.n Users)</h3>Follow the instructions 1 to 9 for DOS users above then either run by shelling out to DOS, or click on the Program Manager's 'RUN' option and enter {PATH}\MICMOVIE.EXE in the appropriate boxes in the RUN window. Note that{PATH} will be your drive+the directory where you put the movie player and movies -e.g. c:\micscape\micmovie.exe<p>If you wish to set up a Windows Program Group to run the Movie Player, download the Micscape Resources Group file and Movie Player Icon file from here (see top of page) into your newly created\micscape directory <i>(where you copied the player software to)</i> and do the following:-<p><ol><li>From Program Manager click on the <b>FILES</b> menu.<li>Select <B>RUN</B><LI>Enter into the 'Run' box: WINMOVIE.EXE<br>    (This extracts MICSCAPE.GRP and MOVIE.ICO files from the compressed file).<br><li>From Program Manager, click on the <b>FILES</b> menu.<li>Select <b>NEW.</b><LI>When asked if you wish to create a Program Group or Program Item,<br>    choose: <b>Create Program Group.</b><li>In the Description Box, enter: <b>Micscape Magazine Resources.</b><li>In the Group File Box, enter: <b>C:\micscape\micscape.grp</b><br><b><i>Note: Replace the 'C:' above with your correct hard disk drive designation letter if it is notcalled drive 'C:'</i></b><li>Click on the <b>OK</b> button.... and you should get to the new Group Box complete with the Micscape Movie Player Icon inside.<br></ol><p><h3>How to set up and use the Movie Player (Windows95 Users)</h3>Er... (blush), we don't know!<p>Only seen it once. Just started to see how it all worked and it fell over. My colleague (who is a professional PC support person) is still trying to get Win95 working again. I guess, since Win95 is meant to be a really friendly user-interface, it's easy! If you know how to set up Micmovie in Win95, be a friend for life and <A href="mailto:mol@molcol.demon.co.uk">let me know</A> please.<p><center><h3>Ah-ha! A friend is made:-</h3></center><strong>Gord Burton wrote in to say...</strong>
<pre>
To: mol@molcol.demon.co.uk
From: g_burton@magi.com (Gord Burton)
Subject: Using Micscape From Windows95

I don't know how but I discovered your site tonite and downloaded the
software and all of the demo movies. I downloaded for two reasons,

(1) they sounded interesting and...
(2) the challenge existed for using Windows 95

Just in case you have not been able to get it working from this platform
as yet, I followed the following procedure.
(a) I created a directory and copied all of the program files to it
(b) I extracted all the required executables and then deleted
    the originals
(c) I double clicked on micmovie.exe and voila, no problems!
(d) I did not bother with the group file or icon.

The only problem I faced after watching all 7 movies and quitting the
program was the intense brightness of the Windows 95 screen as compared
to the Micscape screen.Well done, very interesting.  

Gord Burton (Orleans, Ontario, Canada)</pre>
<em>Thanks Gord. (The editor).</em>
<p>
And of course, if that doesn't work, you can always use the DOS option in Win95 to run Micmovie.exe so you should be okay in this respect.<p><br><br><p><br><center><h4><em><a href="#about">Sub-Index</A> / <a href="#movietop"> Button Selector</A></em></h4></center><br><p><br><br><a name="downplay"><h3>Download Micscape Movie Player</h3>I hope you took the time first to read <b><A HREF="#about">About Micscape Movies</A></b><p><ul><li><A Href="http://www.micropix.demon.co.uk/movies/micmovie.exe">HTTP Download Movie Player</A> and save it as MICMOVIE.EXE<br>File Size: 96k (This is NOT a compressed file)</ul><p><br><br><center><h4><em><a href="#about">Sub-Index</A> / <a href="#movietop"> Button Selector</A></em></h4></center><br><p><br><br><a name="downgrp"><h3>Download Micscape Group and Icon File (Windows Users).</h3>I hope you took the time first to read <b><A HREF="#about">About Micscape Movies</A></b><p><ul><li><A Href="http://www.micropix.demon.co.uk/movies/winmovie.exe">HTTP Download Micscape Windows File</A> and save it as WINMOVIE.EXE<br>File Size: a COMPRESSED file of a few hundred bytes (very small).</ul><p><br><center><h4><em><a href="#about">Sub-Index</A> / <a href="#movietop"> Button Selector</A></em></h4></center><br><br><br><P><CENTER><B>Please report any errors OR offer comment to <A HREF="mailto:mol@molcol.demon.co.uk"> <I> The Editor </I></A></B></CENTER><BR><HR>
