<CENTER>
<FONT COLOR="#FF0000">
<H2>WHAT'S NEW THIS MONTH</H2>
</FONT>
</CENTER>
</P>
<P>
The <EM>MEDIA</EM> comes to the World Wide Web! Science Magazines and Television Programs have come to the Web and brought with them their amazing abilities to teach science in a fascinating way. Here are a few of the <EM>MEDIA</EM> Science Web Sites I discovered.
</P>
<P>
<CENTER>
<TABLE CELLSPACING=10 CELLPADDING=0>
 <TR>
  <TD ALIGN=RIGHT>
   <A HREF="http://nyelabs.kcts.org/">
    <IMG SRC="http://nyelabs.kcts.org/heads2.gif"></IMG>
   </A>
  </TD>
  <TD>
  <STRONG>
First, there is "<A HREF="http://nyelabs.kcts.org/">Bill Nye, the Science Guy</A>." Bill Nye is a little <I>layed-back</I> in his approach to science, but is <EM>very</EM> informative. This Web Site is in no way <I>layed back</I>, however. There are experiments you can do (called "Daily Demos"), Quicktime movies you can download and just loads of other activities. The Web Site closely parallels the television science program and is definitely worth checking out, especially if you can't watch the TV show in your area. <I>("Bill Nye, the Science Guy" &copy 1996 KCTS Television)</I>
  </STRONG>
  </TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD>
  <STRONG>
The 
<A HREF="http://www.dc.enews.com/magazines/discover/">Discover Magazine</A> Web Site is an online version of the paper magazine. In the current issue (December, 1996), you can learn what a "Twiddle-Fish" is and why it is significant, as well as read about how a star completely disappeared. <I>("Discover Magazine" &copy 1996 The Walt Disney Company)</I>
  </STRONG>
  </TD>
  <TD ALIGN=LEFT>
   <A HREF="http://www.dc.enews.com/magazines/discover/">
    <IMG SRC="http://www.dc.enews.com/magazines/discover/gifs/cover.gif"></IMG>
   </A>
  </TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD ALIGN=RIGHT>
   <A HREF="http://ericir.syr.edu/Projects/Newton/">
    <IMG SRC="http://ericir.syr.edu/Projects/Newton/13/Images/apple.gif"></IMG>
   </A>
  </TD>
  <TD>
  <STRONG>
Adding a <EM>touch of class</EM> to the field of youth oriented television science programs is 
<A HREF="http://ericir.syr.edu/Projects/Newton/">"Newton's Apple"</A>. This is a very interesting Web Site... you could get lost in it for days just reading and doing all of the wonderful things in there! It's chocked <EM>FULL</EM> of "Science Try Its <FONT SIZE=-5>TM</FONT>." Don't let the term <I>Lessons</I> fool you. These are well thought out, fully illustrated science experiments that you can easily do at home. This is a <FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><I>MUST SEE</I></FONT> Web Site! <I>("Newton's Apple" is produced by KTCA Twin Cities Public Television by a grant from 3M Coproration)</I>
  </STRONG>
  </TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD>
  <STRONG>
<FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">"Man... I <EM>LOVE</EM> Science!"</FONT> YES!! Those <EM>famous</EM> words, spoken by none other than.... you guessed it! 
<A HREF="http://www.nbn.com/youcan/beakworld/beakTV.html">BEAKMAN!!</A> "Beakman's World" is a <I>fast paced</I>, Emmy Award winning, science based television program and nationally syndicated comic strip, and this Web Site lives up to the name! You've just <EM>GOT</EM> to see it to believe it! "Varoooom... Zalooooom!" <I>("Beakman's World" &copy 1996 Universal Press Syndicate and Jok. R. Church)</I>
  </STRONG>
  </TD>
  <TD ALIGN=LEFT>
   <A HREF="http://www.nbn.com/youcan/beakworld/beakTV.html">
    <IMG SRC="http://www.nbn.com/youcan/colloid-quiz/right.gif" WIDTH=108 HEIGHT=158></IMG>
   </A>
  </TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD ALIGN=RIGHT>
   <A HREF="http://www.nationalgeographic.com/main.html">
    <IMG SRC="http://www.nationalgeographic.com/images/navmt.gif"></IMG>
   </A>
  </TD>
  <TD>
  <STRONG>
What list of <I>MEDIA on the Web</I> would be complete without a link to 
<A HREF="http://www.nationalgeographic.com/main.html">National Geographic</A>? This Web Site not only includes the work of the National Geographic Society, but includes a wonderful online magazine for kids. The National Geographic Society has earned its excellent reputation and this Web Site reflects their high standards of excellence! <I>("National Geographic" &copy 1996 National Geographic Society)</I>
  </STRONG>
  </TD>
 </TR>
 <TR>
  <TD>
  <STRONG>
This one isn't a <I>MEDIA</I> Web Site, but it is one of the cutest Web Sites I've seen, even if it does describe itself as <EM>yucky</EM>. It is New Jersey Online's  
<A HREF="http://www.nj.com/yucky/worm/">Worm World</A>! It is all about... Worms!... what else? The artwork is excellent and the Web Site is just darling! There are sound and video files, as well as very imaginative interviews with... Worms! (It is a <I>Worm World</I>, after all.) I fell in love with this Site and you will, too. <I>("Worm World" &copy 1996 New Jersey Online)</I>
  </STRONG>
  </TD>
  <TD ALIGN=LEFT>
   <A HREF="http://www.nj.com/yucky/worm/">
    <IMG SRC="http://www.nj.com/yucky/worm/front2.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=158></IMG>
   </A>
  </TD>
 </TR>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>
</P>
<P>
Our last entry is a 
<A HREF="http://www.yk.rim.or.jp/~aisoai/index.html">Molecular Biology</A> Sites Link page from Japan. If you are a student of amino acids, proteins, or DNA, this is the place for you. There are databases, tables, software, a free plugin for viewing 3D models of PDB files, and much, much more! As a student of DNA, myself, I found this Web Site to be a virtual paradise! <FONT COLOR="#FF0000">The Server for this Site tends to issue <I>connection errors</I> frequently. Just be persistent. :)</FONT> <I>("Molecular Biology Links" is the Home Page of Atsushi Isoai, Ph.D.)</I>
</P>

