<CENTER> <STRONG> <P>  <H2>THE NEWS</H2> </STRONG></CENTER></P> 

<A NAME="topical"></A> <P>  <Center><H3>   Topical Microscopy and
Biology News from Around the World  </H3> </Center></P> 

<P>  <CENTER><EM>Select a topic here or just scroll down to browse</EM>
</P> </CENTER> </STRONG> <P> 



<UL>

<LI>  <A HREF="#fsexchange">   Mind over matter for sex change fish</A>   January 12th '97 </LI> 

<LI>  <A HREF="#mousevirus"> Deadly virus on the loose </A>   January 12th '97 </LI> 

<LI>  <A HREF="#opticalmic">   New Breed of Optical Microscopes breakthrough!   </A>   January 5 '97 </LI> 

<LI>  <A HREF="#seadrugs">Prescriptions from the sea? </A>   December 21  '96 </LI>

<LI>  <A HREF="#mothflight">Moth flight <I>does </I>obey the laws of physics  </A>   December 21  '96 </LI>

<LI>  <A HREF="#jellyfish"> Jellyfish used to hunt down Cancer </A>   December 21  '96 </LI>

<LI>  <A HREF="#elephantman"> Elephant man - a new diagnosis </A>   December 14 '96 </LI>

<LI>  <A HREF="#hedges">Hedging one's bets on the future of England's 

countryside  </A>   December 14 '96 </LI> 
 
<LI>  <A HREF="#eyetooth">   A tooth for an eye  </A>   December 8  '96 </LI> 



</UL> </P>

<BR><HR>

<A NAME="fsexchange"></A> 

<B>Mind over matter for sex change fish</B><BR>

<P>Dr John Godwin of North Carolina State University has carried
out experiments that show that the expression of gender specific
behaviour in the blueheaded wrasse (a species of Coral reef
fish) seems to be directly related to the amount of a hormone
called<B> arginine vasotocin </B>(AVT), which is produced in the
animal's brain. His studies seem to suggest that aggressive
behaviour in males normally thought to be controlled by sex
hormones can occur in animals that lack testes.</P>



<P>Blueheaded wrasse are ideal subjects for studies of this type as
they are <B> diandric protogynous hermaphrodites</B>, in other words
they can rapidly change sex in response to changes in
environmental conditions. This means, for example,  that a  fish
which started life as an egg producing female can transform into
a sperm producing aggressive supermale.
</P>


<P>A series of experiments has been carried out by Dr John Goodwin
with colleagues from the University of Texas, University of
California and Arizona State University West. One of studies
involved the removal of all the supermales from a colony of
wrasse on a reef in the Virgin Islands, so leaving the largest
females as the dominant fish. Within hours the dominant females
began to exhibit supermale  behaviour - i.e. defending
territories, aggressiveness and courting of the other females.
Within a week their ovaries had changed into fully functional
sperm producing testes.</P>


<P>In addition to removing the supermales, the ovaries from some of
the females were removed before returning them to the colony. It
was found that even these females exhibited full dominant
behaviour, but did not produce testes or the supermales'
distinctive coloration.
</P>


<P>It has been found that the sexes produce different amounts of
AVT, and when the wrasse changes sex, its levels of AVT seem to
change accordingly. The females were found to produce about half
the AVT of ordinary males and roughly one third to a quarter of
that produced by supermales - suggesting that the gender
specific behaviour was linked to AVT levels in the brain.When scientists investigated the levels of AVT in the females
that had changed to males they found that they had risen to
supermale levels.</P>
<P> Scientists have yet to decide whether the rise in AVT causes the
behavioural sex change or whether it is a result of it.
</P>
<P><I> (Source:The Telegraph 27  December 1996)</I></P>


<BR><BR> <P> <CENTER> <STRONG>  Scroll
up/down or   <A HREF="#newstop">   Go back to top of news  </A>
</STRONG> </CENTER> </P> 

<BR><BR>

<A NAME="mousevirus"></A> 
<strong>Deadly Virus on the loose</strong><br>

<P>The United Press International reports that the Ohio Department
of Health

are keeping a close eye on the spreading a deadly virus which
can cause

chronic breathing problems and is fatal in nearly 50% of
cases. The carriers of the disease, hantavirus pulmonary
syndrome, are rodents. Transmission of the disease is via dust
from  infected rodents' urine, droppings and saliva. 

</P>

<P>Although, there is no evidence that this potentially fatal agent
has infiltrated Ohio, no chances are being taken, health
officials have checked hundreds of rats and rodents in 15
counties to ensure they are not carriers. As a further measure,
the disease has been placed on the state's list of  reportable
diseases that must be reported to the health department within
24 hours.
</P>


<P><I>(Source: United Press International December 30 1996)</I></P>

<BR><BR> <P> <CENTER> <STRONG>  Scroll
up/down or   <A HREF="#newstop">   Go back to top of news  </A>
</STRONG> </CENTER> </P> 

<BR><BR>


<A NAME="opticalmic"></A> 

<strong>New Breed of Optical Microscopes breakthrough!</strong><br>

<P>It is well known that the resolving power of optical microscopes is 

restricted by the wavelength of light. Obtaining images greater than

1500x magnification results in larger pictures but not better detail,

leaving exploration of the microscopic world at greater resolution, 

up to the pioneers using scanning electron microscopes. </P>



<P>But now, thanks to IBM, a new breed of optical microscopes have come

into being which out-perform <strong>all</strong> previous instruments:

<em>SIAM  (Scanning Interferometric Apertureless Microscope).</em></P>



<P>This new optical microscope is capable of seeing objects 500 times 

smaller than previously possible with conventional optical microscopes.

It provides an unprecedented 1 nanometer (nm) resolution, which is about

five times larger than an individual atom, with the potential to image

single atoms in visible light.</P>



<P>Scientists are now able to view images much smaller than the wavelength

of light and approaching the atomic level, an achievement considered 

impossible according to the basic principles of traditional optics.</P>



<P>Don't believe me..? 

<a href="http://www.research.ibm.com/research/press/optical.html">Then take a 

look for yourself!</a></P>

<BR><BR> <P> <CENTER> <STRONG>  Scroll
up/down or   <A HREF="#newstop">   Go back to top of news  </A>
</STRONG> </CENTER> </P> 

<BR><BR>

<A NAME="seadrugs"></A> 

<strong>Prescriptions from the sea?</strong><br>

<P>Marine scientists are looking to algae, sponges and other
organisms as producers of a wide variety of potentially valuable
and useful pharmaceutical chemicals.  It has been estimated that the 10,000
marine organisms that have been identified make up only a very
small proportion of the total, so the potential for such
chemicals is enormous.</P>



<P>The combination of predators, salinity and high pressure in
the environment  has resulted in the evolution of marine
organisms that can produce a cocktail of chemicals for self
defence. Many of these compounds are thought to be unique,
produced no where else on earth.</P>



<P>Chemicals already isolated include compounds called
<I>topsentins </I>which may be effective against arthritis and
<I>discodermolide </I>that works in the treatment of breast and ovarian
cancer. Another, <I>ecteinascidia, </I>from the invertebrate animal,
the sea squirt had been found in clinical trials to kill the
most lethal form of skin cancer - melanoma.</P>

 

<P>However, for all the promise of these life saving marine
derived drugs, there is a worrying side effect. To produce one
gram of ecteinascidia requires one tonne of sea squirts. The
harvesting of marine life for pharmaceutical drug production is
going to put huge demands on the extremely delicately balanced
marine ecology. In addition, the search for new marine derived
chemicals is an expensive and chancy operation. Once found, the
drugs may be ten years in development and during this time
equally effective drugs may be produced or unwanted side effects
identified.</P>



<P><I>(Source: The Scotsman 18.12.96 Summarised by A. Bruce from an article by Jim Loney)</I></P>
<BR><BR> <P> <CENTER> <STRONG>  Scroll
up/down or   <A HREF="#newstop">   Go back to top of news  </A>
</STRONG> </CENTER> </P> 

<BR><BR>



</P> <A NAME="mothflight"></A><Strong> Moth flight  <I>does </I>obey the laws of  physics 
</Strong></P>
<P>Bees and moths have confounded aerodynamic experts by their
ability to fly.  The laws of physics suggest that the wings of
moths are too frail to generate enough lift to get the animal
off the ground.</P>

<P> By using a robotic hawkmoth model, researchers
at Cambridge University have been able to elucidate that the
extra lift is generated during each downstroke by a spiral
vortex that travels across the leading edge of the wing from
base to tip. This effect had been missed previously as wind
tunnel studies of insect flight have viewed the insect from the
side.</P>
<P><I>(Source: The Scotsman 19.12.96.   & BBC news</I>)</P>
<BR><BR> <P> <CENTER> <STRONG>  Scroll
up/down or   <A HREF="#newstop">   Go back to top of news  </A>
</STRONG> </CENTER> </P> 

<BR><BR>
</P> <A NAME="jellyfish"><Strong>Jellyfish used to hunt down Cancer</Strong></A></P>
<br>

<P>Jellyfish employing a unique fluorescent chemical to deter predators are now

being considered as a secret new weapon in humankind's battle against

cancer. A cancer research team at Cambridge work in darkened laboratories  

using the dye to inject into human cells. It is helping them to understand 

how proteins move when the cell divides - an important mechanism because it 

is 'uncontrolled' cell divison that leads to cancer.</P>



<P>Professor Gorden McVie is reported as saying: "It is fascinating to think 

that jellyfish, which appeared in the sea 700 million years ago, are 

offering a modern-day solution to one of science's greatest mysteries. This 

is yet another example of nature lending a helping hand."
</P>


<P><em>Source: Evening Standard, London, Dec. 11th</em></P>

<BR><BR> <P> <CENTER> <STRONG>  Scroll
up/down or   <A HREF="#newstop">   Go back to top of news  </A>
</STRONG> </CENTER> </P> 

<BR><BR>




<A NAME="elephantman"></A> 

<strong>Elephant man - a new diagnosis</strong><br>

<P>New X ray studies of Joseph Merrick (the nineteenth century
"Elephant man") made by Anita Sharma and colleagues at the Royal
London hospital suggest that he did not suffer from
neurofibromatosis as once thought, but from a much rarer disease
- Proteus syndrome.</P>



<P>Neurofibromatosis is a genetic disease which causes the
uncontrolled growth of nerve cells. Such growth results in
tumours developing beneath the skin surface. In contrast,
Proteus disease results in abnormal growth of bone and soft
tissue. Sharma states that Merrick's skeleton, which is kept at
the Royal London hospital, is studded with many bony outgrowths,
apparently typical of the disease. In addition, Merrick's ribs
lack the notches and thickening common in neurofibromatosis.</P>


<P>The gene for neurofibromatosis was isolated in 1990 by American
scientists. Sharma suggests that one way of confirming her
diagnosis is to conduct DNA tests on some bone tissue to
determine whether or not the gene is present.</P>

<P>(Source: various )</P>

<BR><BR> <P> <CENTER> <STRONG>  Scroll
up/down or   <A HREF="#newstop">   Go back to top of news  </A>
</STRONG> </CENTER> </P> 

<BR><BR>


<A NAME="hedges"</A>
<Strong>Hedging one's bets on the future of England's 

countryside</Strong>



<P>Never before has the rural countryside of England and the Natural Life it 

supports been under such threat. Year on year, new roads cut through 

tranquil spots and deliver the kiss of death. Slowly, like a sinister, 

creeping, plague, advertising hoardings, roadside vending ventures, and 

the ever-growing throng of urban siteseers invade the oldest monuments 

in the remotest of places.</P>

<P>And now a new threat!</P>


<P>Over 40,000 miles of English country hedgerows, which for centuries have 

been strictly protected by Parliamentary Enclosure Acts, could see 

themselves whittled away over the next few decades. Ex-teacher, Colin 

Seymour, is fighting to save 56 yards of ancient hawthorne hedge in East 

Yorkshire, which to some, may seem a trivial battle. Unfortunately, it is a 

Crown court case, which - if lost - could bring about a change in the laws 

protecting the living network of adjoining hedgerows which divide and abound

the thousands of fields seen in the country; a network which provides 

natural home and shelter to a diverse range of wild life.
</P>

<P>This small section is threatened by the desire of some local villagers of 

Flamborough, less concerned with these issues, to build a bowling green. Mr. 

Seymour has taken on the council in an effort to preserve not just 56 years 

of hedge, but the future of at least one important aspect of the English 

countryside.</P>
<BR>

<em>Source: Daily Express, London, Dec. 12th 1996</em>

<BR><BR> <P> <CENTER> <STRONG>  Scroll
up/down or   <A HREF="#newstop">   Go back to top of news  </A>
</STRONG> </CENTER> </P> 

<BR><BR>



<A NAME="eyetooth"></A> 

<strong>A tooth for an eye</strong><br>


<P>Using techniques pioneered by  Professor Giancarlo
Falcinellu, surgeons in Britain are hoping to restore a blind
man's sight, using a tooth. If successful, this operation could
offer hope to those patients who are not suitable for corneal
transplants.</P>

<P>A single-rooted tooth,  removed together with a wedge of bone,
is sanded down to a rectangular shape and drilled. A plastic
lens is then placed in the 4mm diameter hole. This section is
then grafted into the patient's cheek. At the same time, tissue
from the skin inside the cheek is grafted onto the patient's
eye. After two months the section will have sufficient tissue
growing on it to allow surgeons to remove it and stitch  it into
the cheek skin graft on the eye. Finally, a coloured contact
lens will be placed over the tooth section to disguise it.</P>

<P>The success rate of the 180 such operations carried out in Italy
has been high,  with many patients being able to read again with
glasses.</P>

<P>(Sources: various)</P>
<BR><BR> <P> <CENTER> <STRONG>  Scroll
up/down or   <A HREF="#newstop">   Go back to top of news  </A>
</STRONG> </CENTER> </P> 

