<HEAD><TITLE>MICROSCOPY UK / MICSCAPE - MICROSCOPIST'S FACTFILE.</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="./images/magcova.gif" TEXT="#002873" LINK="#BF0000" VLINK="#007C3F" ALINK="#B30000">
<STRONG><CENTER><FONT SIZE=5 color=darkred>MICROSCOPIST'S FACTFILE</font><P> 

 <FONT SIZE=4>A miscellany of information of interest to Microscopists<P>


Compiled by Frank Rowntree  <A HREF="#footnote">(see footnote)</A><BR>(Micscape's Book Reviews and Information Editor)</font>
</CENTER></STRONG><P>
 <FONT SIZE=4>
<STRONG>3D MICROSCOPY</STRONG> a new form of Microscopy is appearing on the scene with
the new R400 transmitted light optical microscope which provides high
definition, real time 3D imaging giving improved resolution, increased
sharpness, enhanced depth of field and greater contrast . Details from
Parallax UK Ltd, 40 Shenley Pavilions, Chalkdell Drive, Shenley Wood,
Milton Keynes, Bucks MK5 6LB.<P>

<STRONG>LABMARKER PENS</STRONG> for writing on glass, wet surfaces, plastic etc from
Elkay Laboratory Products UK Ltd., PO Box 6004, Basingstoke, Hampshire,
RG24 8HL.<P>

<STRONG>COPYRIGHT</STRONG> On January 1st 1996  the new EU copyright directive came into
effect. Previously copyright was owned by the author's estate for fifty
years after death but this is now increased to 70 years. In addition
after that period anyone wanting to make use of the deceased authors or
artists work has to search out the estate and agree a "reasonable fee".
Infringement could be costly so beware when "borrowing" illustrations or
text.<P>

<STRONG>POISONOUS PLANTS</STRONG> is the title of a set of three beautifully illustrated
posters from RoSPA which depict poisonous plants in the garden, in the
home and in the country and offering advice on how to deal with
accidental poisonings. Useful for Botanists, Gardeners and Countryside
lovers. Price 6.00 from RoSPA, Publications Department, Cannon House,
The Priory Queensway, Birmingham B4 6BS.<P>

<STRONG>THE NATURAL HISTORY MUSEUM</STRONG> has the largest collection of natural history
materials in the world both ancient and modern. They acquire publications
from around the world and are a database as well as a gateway to other
databases. Their facilities are available free for genuine enquiry and
research. A ticket is required for personal visits (the admission fee
to the museum is waived for library users). It is best to formulate
enquiries first and write or telephone the Librarian 0171-938-9238 or
Fax 0171-938-9290. (You can also e-mail j.thakray@nhm.ac.uk). An
information brochure is available on the services. The NHM also operates
one of the best natural history bookshops in the world.<P>

<STRONG>ENDANGERED SPECIES</STRONG> is the theme of the current set of commemorative
stamps from the United Nations Postal Administration. Details from
Administration Postale des Nations Unies a Geneve, CH-1211. Geneve 10
Switzerland. The stamps are really beautiful. They do many Natural
History related series.<P>

<STRONG>VARROASIS</STRONG> the highly dangerous bee disease is spreading and there has
been an extension of the Statutory Affected Area. Many cases have been
identified outside the statutory area already. Microscopists in the UK
can assist their beekeeping friends by helping with identification of
bee pests and by giving advice on the use of microscopes for this
purpose. Contact your local beekeepers association or the local Bee
Advisor. They will be glad to hear from you.<P>

<STRONG>COLD CURING RESINS FOR MICROSCOPY </STRONG> are available from TAAB Laboratories.
Minerva House. Calleva Park. Aldermaston Berks RG7 8NA. They also
produce or stock many specialist microscopical items for example :-
MICROSCOPE WARM STAGE MT1 Price 299.00 and :-
TAAB TWEEZERS in varying sizes and tips from 6.77 to
9.01.<P>

<STRONG>PHILLIPS AUCTIONS</STRONG>  are held regularly at 101, New Bond Street London for
the sale of scientific instruments both old and new including
microscopes. A future date is 3rd December 1996 . Viewing takes place
during the preceeding 4-5 days.<P>

<STRONG>SECONDHAND PHOTOGRAPHIC AND AUDIO VISUAL EQUIPMENT</STRONG> is available in vast
quantities from KJP and Hargreaves. They also rent out equipment if a
trial is required. They have branches all over the UK  as well as
throughout Europe. Check your local telephone directory for a branch
near you.<P>

<STRONG>FLUORESCENCE FILTER SELECTION GUIDE</STRONG>  (Omega Optical) available from Glen
Spectra, 2-4, Wigton Gardens, Stanmore, Middlesex HA7 1BG. Tel 0181-204-951.<P>

<STRONG>MSAC Ltd (MICROSCOPY SUPPLIES AND CONSULTANTS)</STRONG> is a new name on the
microscopical supply list. They advertise microscopes from mono' models
for schools at under 70 to postgraduate teaching microscopes and
accessories in the 6,000 plus range (with VAT on top) MSAC Ltd., Park
House, 6A Carneil Road, Carnock, Fife KY12 9J.<P>

<STRONG>EDMUND SCIENTIFIC CATALOGUE </STRONG> is available from Ealing Scientific. Ealing
Electro Optics plc, Greycaine Road, Watford, Herts, WD2 3PW. Full of
American scientific and microscopical "goodies" available through
Ealing. The latest edition has just been circulated (September 1996).<P>

<STRONG>SECONDHAND AND ANTIQUARIAN GEOLOGICAL BOOKS </STRONG>are available from Stuart A
Baldwin. Baldwins
Books. Fossil Hall, Boars Tye Road, Silver End, Witham, Essex CM8 3QA.<P>

<STRONG>INSTANT PHOTOGRAPHY THROUGH THE MICROSCOPE</STRONG>  is the title of a guide for
Polaroid users which is full of tips about photomicrography. From
Polariod UK Ltd. Wheathamstead House, Wheathamstead, Herts AL4  8SF.
Normal cost about $12 but free whilst stocks last.<P>

<STRONG>MICROSCOPISTS AS WELL AS MAD DOGS AND ENGLISHMEN  GO OUT IN THE MIDDAY
SUN</STRONG> and are often unaware that one of the most dangerous consequences is skin
cancer now affecting 40,000 new sufferers every year in the UK with a
high risk of death especially amongst the 4,000 who develop malignant
melanoma. The Imperial Cancer Research Fund has launched a campaign to
make everyone aware "When it's hot use your Block". They are marketing a
SunSafe suncare range available through Boots (It is the only one that
does not help tan the skin). They also recommend wraparound sunglasses
to BS 2724:1987 label.<P>

<STRONG>THE MANTIS FX</STRONG> is  an unusual and useful bench/laboratory magnifying
device that  fills the gap between a microscope and bench magnifier.
Slightly expensive for the amateur but well worth watching out for
secondhand. It is almost like watching TV with a superb "Screen Image"
( I have one of the models that won the Queen's award for Industry and find it enormously useful). Details from Vision Engineering, Send Road, Send, Woking, Surrey GU33 7ER.<P>

<STRONG>MEASUREMENT OF TOTAL DISSOLVED SOLIDS</STRONG> is often essential in
microscopical and ecological research. The Oakton TDS Test Series of
meters is a low cost means to these determinations. Catalogue from Sigma
- Aldrich Techware, The Old Brickyard, New Road, Gillingham, Dorset SP8
4JL. Tel. 0800-717181<P>

<STRONG>MICROSCOPE REPAIRS</STRONG> are undertaken by Microscopes Plus Ltd. who also
supply a wide range of microscopes and accessories from their HQ at
Microscopes Plus Ltd, 44 Enterprise Centre, Cranbourne Road, Potters
Bar, Herts EN6 3DQ. Tel. 01707-663776 (There have been many favourable
reports about their speed, quality and costs).<P>

<STRONG>MAGNIFICATION...??????</STRONG> wow !!  IBM have taken the biscuit with their new
scanning interferometric apertureless microscope (SIAM) which can see
objects which are actually 500 times smaller than those previously
possible to see with a microscope. It is claimed they may be able to
see individual atoms in visible light !  With a resolution of 1nm it has
a tremendous potential in fields such as genetics, particularly the
Genome project.<P>

<STRONG>PITY THE POOR CRAYFISH</STRONG> Britain's native Crayfish (the white-clawed
crayfish) is under threat from the predatory American Signal Crayfish
which was imported for farming in the mid 70's and is now spreading
nationwide. Many areas have now been declared "NO go" for these beasts
and licences are required to keep them. Details of the Regulations from
the Fisheries Departments as well as advice on keeping the animals secure
lest they wander in the night ! Biologists can help by accurate
observation and record keeping.<P>

<STRONG>CASH FOR SSSI's </STRONG> (Sites of Special Scientific Interest) has been put up
by 100,000  to increase the number of sites and to help encourage the
number of volunteers who manage them. Perhaps you can help. Details from
Maurice Massey of English Nature, Northminster House, Peterborough, PE1
1UA.<P>

<STRONG>CARBARYL </STRONG>has been shown to be potentially carcinogenic and is being
phased out. If you have gardening chemicals containing this substance
contact  your Waste Regulation Authority for assistance with disposal.
( If no assistance is forthcoming and they advise you to just dump it
please advise Frank Rowntree for the information of the National
Committee who are concerned about the lack of facilities for the
disposal of potentially lethal substances found in homes and amateur
laboratories and workshops).<P>

<STRONG>THE LIVING TREE CAMPAIGN</STRONG>  is being sponsored by Esso. Details from the
Esso Living Tree Campaign
 c/o Trevor Benton 0171-215805.<P>

<STRONG>MICSCAPE MICROSCOPY MAGAZINE</STRONG>  is a spinoff from Micscape the Internet
Microscopical Magazine. Available in hard copy from  Micscape Microscopy
Magazine, 69, Commonside, Mitcham, Surrey CR4 4HB. Price 6-10 pounds for two
issues preferably by Postal Order or Cheque. Details Tel. Maurice Smith.
0181-685-0528<P>

<STRONG>VERSALITE</STRONG> is claimed to be the "worlds brightest swivel head
flashlight". It has  6,000 CANDLE POWER XENON LMX  lamp module. Very
useful for night hunting of specimens. Lamp 29.86  Bulbs 8.25, from
Analytical Supplies Ltd., Duffield Road, Little Eaton Derby, DE1 5DR. Tel.
01332-831671.<P>

<STRONG>THE FRESHWATER BIOLOGICAL ASSOCIATION</STRONG> HAS A DEVELOPMENT PLAN 1996 .
Details from the Director, FBA, The Ferry House, Far Sawrey, Ambleside,
Cumbria LA22 OLP. (Ask for the publications catalogue too. Their books
are a  boon to freshwater biologists and pond dippers alike).<P>

<STRONG>THE WINSTON CHURCHILL TRAVELLING FELLOWSHIPS</STRONG> have enabled many people to
fulfill ambitions to make specialist visits and study programmes (note
not formal academic study) the subject areas change every year and can
often relate to natural history. Forms available from Winston Churchill
Memorial Trust, 15 Queens Gate Terrace, London SW7 5PR. Tel 01-584-9315.
Find out.........who knows......it could be you!<P>

<STRONG>CARBON MONOXIDE</STRONG> is lethal and often a by-product around workshops and
enclosed snuggeries. New detectors are  available from Codect.
Straightpoint Building, Clovelly Road, SOUTHBORNE, Emsworth, Hants, PO10
8PE and from Innotec International, Glendale Business Centre, Deeside
Industrial Estate, Deeside, Clwyd CH5 2LR.<P>

Frank Rowntree<BR>
<P>

<A NAME="footnote"></A>
<STRONG>Editor's Note:</STRONG> we are sad to report that Frank Rowntree who regularly contributed book reviews and factfiles to Micscape, died in October 1996. He will be sadly missed. <P>

