<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>MICROSCOPY UK / MICSCAPE -   1996 Quekett Microscopical Club Annual Exhibition Report</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#002EC2" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#CA00E2" ALINK="#FF0000"><CENTER><IMG SRC="./images/qmclogo.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5 color =darkblue><B>Quekett Microscopical Club  Annual Exhibition<BR>
Natural History, Museum, London October 5th 1996</strong><P></B></FONT>
 
<FONT SIZE=4>a report by Maurice Smith, Microscopy UK Editor</CENTER><P>

October 5th this year of 1996 (today, at the time of writing), The Quekett 
Microscopical Club (QMC) held its Annual Exhibition at The Natural History Museum in 
S. Kensington, London, England. I went along to enjoy the day, as a club 
member, and to represent Microscopy-UK in our friendly relationship with the 
Club itself. And of course ... to see some old friends who help contribute 
towards our pages.
<p>
All the old favourites were there showing a diverse range of microscopical 
equipment, specimens, techniques, and knowhow. Eric Marson of Northern 
Biological Supplies had a good position in one corner of the exhibition room, 
and it was good to see one of his booklets (Practical Microscopy) available 
on his table. I personally think this bright yellow covered work, spanning 
years of experience and personal learning is a 'must' for any one new 
entering into Amateur Microscopy. In a hall filled with many experts, new 
technology and old historical instruments, it pleased me greatly to see a work 
of this nature which so adequately caters for the newcomer and novice, 
available at a low price. (Editor's note: available at address below).
<p>
Several commercial tables were set up offering a range of second-hand Olympus 
and Biolam Microscopes. These instruments were in good condition and I really 
fancied one of the stereo microscopes on offer for around 450.00 pounds. It 
is unfortunate though that the prices for these instruments seemed to be a 
bit dearer than their normal cost and I believe instruments of similar 
quality and make can be purchased (normally by way of another amateur selling 
 one) at much cheaper prices. A good example of over-pricing was the McArthur 
ex-Open University microscope which was, if  I remember correctly, on sale 
for around 25 pounds but can be purchased via contacts within the Club for 
about half this price. I guess the small busineses need to charge certain 
amounts to stay in business, and amateur microscopists need a source of 
supply, but when you are in a club - most items seem available from somewhere 
within the membership much cheaper just by asking around.
<p>
The cosy tea-room adjacent to the main hall was buzzing with gossip and 
activity and, as I fancied a cup of tea and a sandwich, I settled down in 
there for half-an-hour to have a break. I spent some time watching the 
excellent slideshow, and video films by Ken Jones which formed a central 
feature of interest for anyone in the tea-room not engaged in rapid 
conversation. Ken has contributed some of his fine work to our movies section 
here on Microscopy-UK and it was an ideal opportunity to discuss the 
possibility of future contributions.
<p>
Several friends of Microscopy-UK were spotted and our very own Frank Rowntree 
were all prominent and engaged in conversation.
<p>
Back in the main exhibition hall, I realised  a slight difference in the 
overall 'feel' and atmosphere of the proceedings compared to previous years'
events. It took me a moment, standing back and musing, to realise what it 
was: of course, it was the increased presence in the room of modern 
technology. Video cameras, PCs, monitors, and image-grabbers were included as 
part of the process of presentation on several tables... and yes... there, 
alone, a single PC stood with a notice before it which said: 'Live Internet 
Connection!'
<p>
Impressed and pleased, I went over to take a look. Sure enough, I was 
witnessing a first. Here, on display, in this oldest of Amateur Microscopy 
clubs in the UK was the 'new world' of information-sharing with live links 
right into our very own site here at Microscopy-UK where the QMC pages are 
maintained by our small team as part of our contribution to the Amateur World 
of Microscopy. Well done QMC for this history-making moment. And a slap on 
the back to all the crew here at Microscopy-UK for helping to make this 
happen. It's fantastic what can be achieved with friendly co-operation, 
unselfish help, and sharing of different skills.
<p>
Maurice Smith Oct. 5th 1996<P>


Learn more about the <A HREF="../amateurs/qmc/mainqmc.html"> Quekett Microscopical Club</A>, who have a suite of pages here on Microscopy UK. Members are welcomed from around the world. Membership benefits includes two Bulletins and two issues of their journal 'Microscopy' each year.<P>

The booklet on 'Practical Microscopy' mentioned by Maurice is available from <A HREF="../prodir/indexpro.html#otherads"> Northern Biological Supplies</A>, who also advertise on Microscopy UK.<P>

