<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>www.microscopy-uk.org.uk : Microscopy Training at Belstead House  </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<center>
<img src="eric1.jpg" border=1 width=192 height=163>
<br>
<H2>A Summer Break for Amateur Microscopy Training at Belstead House</H2>
</center>
<hr>
<CENTER><H3>BELSTEAD HOUSE<br>
Education and Conference Centre<br>
Belstead<br>
Ipswich IP8 3NA<br>
England</H3>
Telephone:   Ipswich (01473) 686321<br>
FAX: (01473) 686664<br>
Course WE 4026<br>
Course Date: 29th August - 1 September (or) September 5th - 8th 1996<br>
<H4>PRACTICAL MICROSCOPY<BR>
Tutor: J. Eric Marson<br>
Subject: Insect Life Histories<br>
</H4>
</center>
An ideal summer break for the amateur scoper: come and stay in 4 star comfort and learn
all about studying, preparing, and mounting insects under the gentle guidance of a 
expert - Mr. J. Eric Marson - a renowned English Microscopist.
<P>

<p>
<b>Under Study</b><br>
The Heterometabola are those insects whose young stages, known as nymphs, closely
resemble the adult in body form and type of mouth parts.
<P>
The Holometabola have young stages known as larvae, which differ markedly
from the adult in body form and mouth parts. So great is the difference between the 
larva and the adult, that an instar known as the pupa bridges the gap between them.
<p>
In most cases both the young stages and adult males and females will be mounted, but in some cases
where the adults are too large, only the young stages will be mounted.
<p>
During the course the following aquatic and non-aquatic insects will be studied, in the following order
of difficulty.
<p>
<OL>

<LI>Water Cricket (Velia)
<LI>Pond Skater (Gerris)
<LI>Water Scorpion (Nepa)
<LI>Waterboatman (Notonecta)
<LI>Waterboatman (Corixa)
<LI>Waterboatman (Sigara)
<LI>Stone Fly (Peria)
<LI>Dragon Fly (Aeshna)
<LI>Damsel Fly (Agrion)
<LI>Alder Fly (Sialis)
<LI>Caddis Fly (Phryganea)
<LI>Caddis Fly (Hydropsyche)
<LI>Caddis Fly (Rhyacophilia)
<LI>Honey bee Worker (Apis)
<LI>Blowfly (Callisphora)
<LI>Water beetle (Agabus)
<LI>Phantom midge (Chaoborus)
<LI>Bloodworm (Chironomus)
<LI>Fruit Fly (Drosophila)
</OL>
<p>
<B>Course members should bring the following equipment</B><br>
2 pairs very fine forceps. I pair very fine scissors. Spirit lamp. Tripod.
Evaporating basin. Ringing table for fluid mounts of Chaoborus larva.
Microscope. Protective coat. Extension leads and adaptors are always of use.
<p>
All slide covers and other equipment will be provided for a charge of 20.00 pounds
payabler during the course.
<p>
The course <b>starts with dinner at 19.00</b> on Thursday and ends with tea at 15.30
on Sunday.
<p>
The course is open to all English-speaking adults. No translators available for oversees
visitors. Please write, fax, or phone Belstead House for booking form, further details, 
and prices.
<p>


