<P>
<HR>
<h2>SPECIMEN MEASUREMENT</h2>
The <b>measurement</b> of specimen dimensions with a microscope is normally under
taken by using an <b>eyepiece micrometer.</b> This is a glass disc with a scale
etched onto its surface, usually 10mm divided into 100 parts. The disc 
(micrometer) may be inserted into the eyepiece and sits upon the eyepiece
field stop which is a small ledge approximately half way down inside most
eyepieces. The top lens unscrews to make this possible. Alternatively a
micrometer eyepiece with a permanent fitting is used.
<p>
The image of the micrometer is superimposed upon the specimen image, both 
being in focus at the same time, and the specimen features or overall size
can be compared directly with the scale. The value of each eyepiece 
micrometer scale division depends upon the magnification of the objective 
being used. For each magnification, the eyepiece scale has to be calibrated
with a <b>stage micrometer.</b> This is a glass slide on which is etched a <b>real 
scale.</b> The value of each division of the eyepiece scale is then recorded
for each magnification option of the microscope.
<p>
<pre>
Compound x10 eyepiece with micrometer (complete) (BM787) - 12.00 UK Pounds
Stage micrometer                                 (BM945) - 16.00 UK Pounds
Compound eyepiece micrometer disc.               (BM183) - 12.00 UK Pounds
</pre>
<hr>
<h2>POLARISER / ANALYSER</h2>
Illuminating specimens with <b>polarised light</b> can be particularly useful
ith geological material and also biological specimens that are 
<i>birefringent</i> such as hair and crystals. To see polarising effects a 
combination of two filters made from polaroid material are used. The first
 - the <b>polariser</b> is placed in the filter carrier of the microscope, and 
the second - the <b>analyser</b>  is fitted in the form of a cap over the viewing
eyepiece. When the analyser is rotated through 180 degrees compared to the
polariser, no light passes through except that which has travelled through
substances that are said to be birefringent - i.e. having the ability to
rotate light into a different plane of vibration. Such substances will then
show as bright objects against a black background. In geology the exact 
angle of rotation of the analyser needed to obtain maximum brightness of
the object can be used for identification purposes.
<p>
<pre>Polariser/analyser set    (BM704) - Ask for price.</pre>
<p>
