<ul>
<center><h3>About our Fractal Image Gallery Images</h3></center>

<h4>As part of our continual aim to spread the word on 'microscopy for
everyone', these images may be downloaded and freely distributed provided
they are NOT used commercially: they are not to form part of any commercially 
distributed package or used in commercial publications. You are welcome to link your web site to our gallery 
provided your own visitor is advised that he/she is popping over to us for
a quick visit. If in doubt, <a href="mailto:mol@molcol.demon.co.uk">give us a shout!</A>

<p>
<a name="yeast2">
<center><strong>Fractal Image 1: <em>Yeast</em></strong></center>
We had a request from a beer brewer recently, asking if we could show
a good image of yeast. Well here you go. This one by our very own
Andrew Syred is magnified 5000x. Its proper name is: Saccharomyces cerevisiae.
<br>
<br>

<p>
<a name="bryo2">
<center><strong>Fractal Image 2: <em>Bryozoa</em></strong></center>

When scientists noticed what appeared to be brown golf balls floating in 
the Weddell Sea, Antarctica, they thought they were worth a closer look.
They were subsequently found to be colonies of bryozoans (moss animals),
which are normally found firmly attached to rocks.
<P>
They were found to be the first free-swimming bryozoan colonies ever recorded.<BR>
What were they doing there and were they a new species... <a href="../mag/articles/bryozoa.html">read the illustrated article</A> by Dave Walker to find out!
This image was provided by Lloyd Peck of the British Antarctic Survey and the Natural Environment Research Council,
who in the true spirit of sharing knowledge with others, have kindly made it available for viewing here 
on this amateur site. Our many thanks and appreciation to them for sharing this with other web users around the world.
<p>
* Editor's Note: please remember this image remains copyright of the contributors. Permission to use  or republish it
must be obtained from them.
<p>
<br>
<br>
<center><a href="#sel">Return to Image Selector</A></center>
<p>
<br>
<a name="lady">
<center><strong>Fractal Image 3: <em>Ladybird</em></strong></center>
Wow! It looks too good to be true. A real ladybird caught in flight with perfect
clarity. Is it real? Well yes... it is a real ladybird! Using astonishing skill
our very own Team Member - Andrew Syred,  has created this stunning image, much larger and even more
detailed than this <strong>much-reduced copy</strong> shown here. Afraid we can't
give away his trade secrets. Just be thankful (as the rest of the team are here) that although 
Andrew produces images like these for a living, his passion as an amateur and his 
desire to see others follow his interest in Nature, motivate him to share his work
with others. 
<p>
<center><a href="#sel">Return to Image Selector</A></center>
<p>
<p>
<a name="leaf">
<center><strong>Fractal Image 4: <em>Leaf Section</em></strong></center>
This leaf section is by Anne Bruce, a fine teacher who recently joined our
small crew here at Microscopy-uk to give her time 'payment-free' to help bring 
knowledge of Biology and Microscopy to a wider audience. Anne is now involved
looking at Educational content and will be building up our resources for students...
an area where we had felt we were not doing enough to help. You can read
Anne's first article on <strong><a href="../mag/articles/anne1.html">Plant Adaptions</A> in the August edition
of Micscape (our very own on-line magazine).</strong> 


<p>
<center><a href="#sel">Return to Image Selector</A></center>
<p>
<p>
<a name="netb">
<center><strong>Fractal Image 5: <em>Stinging Nettle Hair</em></strong></center>
Another first from Andrew Syred. This is a single hair from a stinging nettle
as seen through a SEM (Scanning Electron Microscopy) but with a lot of extra work
and toil by Andrew in post-processing the image. The bulb at the tip is a swelling of the
silicacious cell wall that, being a point of natural weakness, breaks to
produce a fresh, needle sharp surface capable of piercing skin. Liquid
is then forced up through the shaft into the skin akin to a hypodermic
needle. Here at Microscopy UK, we produce a non-profit making amateur magazine in paper
format and issue it to subscribers. This image was used on the front
cover of Issue Number 2. (ISSN 1365-0696)
<p>
<p>
<center><a href="#sel">Return to Image Selector</A></center>
