<a href="../index.html">Return to Microscopy UK Front Screen</A>
</center>
</h3>
<p>
<a name="share">


<center><h1>Sharemail of the moment</h1></center>
<em>Please note:</em>Email exchanges are only published after
consent has been obtained from the writers of the email messages. No post 
received at Micscape or Microscopy UK is published without seeking permission 
first! Email exchanges may be slightly edited to make them more readily 
readable and shorter. Gaps in exchanges can be filled in by inferences in the 
responses given by either party.
<p>
<center><em>The Editor</em></center>
<p>
<br>
<pre>
From:-					To:-   
     Mark Stewart		                 mol@molcol.demon.co.uk
     mst@earth.ftech.co.uk                 Micscape Magazine.

Subject: Capturing Dust Mites   Re: your article:- dustmite.html
</pre>
<em>
I work at the National Physical Laboratory and use a Hitachi Field 
Emission SEM. We are having our schools open day soon and I am trying to 
find some of these "common" dust mites to put in the SEM but as yet no 
success. Have you improved your hunting methods since you wrote the 
article?
</em>
<P>
Reply from Maurice Smith of Micscape Magazine at Microscopy UK:-
<p>
<em>
Hi Mark, <br>
I've passed your email to Andrew Syred, one of my colleagues who sent 
me a small colony of Dustmites. He might be able to help you out. As I 
pointed out in the article, these little creatures are not as easy to find
as most people would have us believe. I hope Andrew can help.
</em>
<p>
<strong>Email Exchange between Andrew and Mark:-</strong>

<p>
<em>Andrew:-</em><br>
Hi Mark,<br>
<p>
I might be able to help. When is your special day? I could send you
one of two if you like, although you may have problems preparing it for SEM
work if you're field is not biology? To be honest - I can't normally take the time to 
help so specifically but it just so happens I am working on a project involving
dustmites right now, so I can afford the time to help and if it helps you 
interest students and their parents then great!
<p>
<em>Mark:-</em><br>
Thanks for the offer of the dust mites, the open days are on the 2nd
and 3rd of July so I have plenty of time. As you have surmised biological
work is not my field and we do not have a critical point dryer. I was aware
of the problem as I have previously used some of those red spider mites, which
collapse under vacuum, but I thought that the shell of the dust mite looked
more stable. 
<p>
<em>Andrew:-</em><br>
Dust mites have much the same exterior as spider mites; it's tough and
leathery rather than hard and rigid so will likely collapse as the
hapless beast dries out. You can sometimes reduce the effect of air
drying by controlled evaporation from a volatile liquid such as ether
but I have not tried this procedure with mites.
<p>
<em>Mark:-</em><br>
What exactly does a critical point dryer do, perhaps we could 
simulate it with some of the vacuum equipment we have here?
<p>
<em>Andrew:-</em><br>
Probably not if you are not geared for it. Critical point drying is a
potentially dangerous technique that really should not be done without
purpose built equipment. At a given temperature and pressure a liquid
will pass from the liquid phase to the gaseous phase without a change in
density or latent heat of vaporisation, it exists as a dense fluid. This
point is known as the critical point and is different for different
liquids. Water should be the ideal liquid to use but god decided that
the critical temperature and pressure would be 374 deg C and 3184 psi
respectively. A fairly destructive combination!
<p>
Various liquids have
been advocated but the most commonly used is liquid carbon dioxide which
has a critical temp. and pressure of 31 deg. C and 1072 psi. Water in
the specimen is replaced with and intermediate fluid such as ethanol
(water and liquid CO2 are not miscible). In a small pressure vessel the
specimen is purged with liquid CO2 for half an hour or so to ensure
total substitution of the ethanol within the specimen. The pressure
vessel is then sealed and slowly heated. The liquid CO2 expands greatly
as the temperature rises and at the critical point all the liquid gas in
the chamber (including that infiltrated into the specimen) flips to the
dense fluid phase with no change in density and of greater importance
with no transitional menaces; the specimen is not subjected to surface
tension. Once the CP has been exceeded the gas is SLOWLY bled off until
the chamber is returned to atmospheric pressure. Voila, one dried
specimen ready for sputtering.
<p>
An automatic pressure relief valve and last resort blow-out safety disc
are built into commercially available kit.
<p>
Freeze drying is an alternative method but the skin, designed to prevent
the mite from drying out whilst alive, restricts sublimation of ice
making the end result unreliable.
<p>
<em>Mark:-</em><br>        
Incidentally where do you hunt for the dust mites, I have tried in the past to
no avail? We are led to believe that our houses are infested with these 
creatures, are they camera shy or is it a scare story by hoover salesmen :-).
<p>
<em>Andrew:-</em><br>
Got it in one - just a big con. trick. All those stories are put about
by people who want to sell flashy vacuum cleaners and expensive
allergenic bedding materials, like mattresses, pillows and blankets.
Even knowing where to look and what to look for they are incredibly
difficult to find, an opinion shared by all my colleagues and like-minded
contacts. Having found a few in a donated sample of under-carpet debris
(following a country-wide request for house dust, fluff etc.), I have
maintained a small culture for about 12 months or so but these are now
dwindling. I gave a large part away to Mol for filming some while ago
which was more or less the end of the culture but I'm sure to have one
or two knocking about.
<p>
<em>Mark:-</em><br>       
Lastly thanks for the suggestions, a ball point might be interesting. One of 
the problems with my SEM is the lowest mag is around 60 times, so the eye of
a moth looks good but I cant show them the whole moth. That's why a dust mite
is attractive because I can get the whole thing on the screen at once,
<p>
<em>Andrew:-</em><br>
Yes I have the same problem - people wanting pictures of things that
really don't warrant the use of an SEM.
Butterfly wings then zooming in on the intricate structure of an
individual scale always captures the attention. Cabbage White
butterflies have interesting grape-like structures (@ ca. 20k) hanging
from the bars of the scale. Don't know for sure what they are but
believe them to be pigment granules. Also if you brush off a few scales
first you can additionally show their attachment site and stalks to the
wing membrane.
<p>
For a whole mount, garden ants are good especially if you can arrange
them in a confrontational position, jaws open etc. Kill them with ether
and they remain relaxed for some while enabling arrangement of legs etc.
They dry easily from air without any need for special drying techniques.
<p>
Hope this has been of some help. I'll contact you shortly when I find
some mites.
<p>
Late news update. I've found 16 mites which I have now bumped off. as
you are not set up for CPD and I will need to do a run within the next
week or so I'll do them for you. Hope you're prepared for their small
size (ca 300um). Recommend you use an eyelash attached to a cocktail
stick to handle them whilst mounting on a stub. I'll also include a
Large White (Pieris brassicae) butterfly when I send the mites.
<p>
<br>
<em>Editor's footnote:</em> If this email exchange interested you, why 
not take a look at our first <a href="project1.html">Worldwide project</a> 
to involve all microscopists, both amateurs and professionals (who may be inclined to help).
<p>
<center><h3><a href="#top">Top of page</A></h3></center>
<p>


<p>
<a name="who">
<center><h1>Who's visiting Microscopy UK</h1></center>
Just about everyone from all walks of life! There are five of us running
this site in our spare time but with lots of support from other amateur microscopists,
professionals, and educationalists from around the world! Everything is run at a loss
or breaking-even and that's the way we intend it to be. Knowledge and love of 
exploration are humankind's greatest assets and we hope that - with your help and small 
contribution - together, we can  provide something worthy here without worrying about 
anyone getting 'money-rich' through the experience. Now 'knowledge-rich' is a different
thing... perhaps we will all benefit!
<p>
Our weekly/monthly logs detailing who's popping in are freely available so why not take 
a peek and see who is as interested as you and us. Please note, these logs show our hits 
below their real rate due to downloads of software, movies, and sound files not being
counted. At out last check on other Microscopy sites around the world, we discovered we were receiving an
average daily hit rate greater than other similar site - including the big 
professional sites. Well done for taking part and for popping in to share the 
Amateur Experience. 
<p>
<a href="../logs/microscopy-uk_log.html">Take a look at our Monthly / Weekly Summary</A> and use your browser's<em>'Back'</em>
option to return here afterwards.
<br>
<br>
<p>
<center><h3><a href="#top">Top of page</A></h3></center>
<p>
<center>
<h3>
<a href="#who">Who's visiting Microscopy UK</A><br>
