<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Microscopy UK / MICSCAPE - Snowflakes - Microscopy Article </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<body background="../images/snw2.gif" bgcolor="#000000" text="#ffffff">
<body background="../images/snw3.gif" bgcolor="#000000" text="#ffffff">


<Strong>
<center>
<img src="../images/snw1.gif" alt="">
<h2>Snowflake Ice Crystals</h2>
<h3>by<br>
Andrew Syred Dec.95</h3>
<p>
<br>
<br>
</center>
<h3>A seasonal thing</h3>
<i>Snow</i>: you either love the stuff or hate it. In the UK we mostly hate
it since, despite weather forecasts warning us of its imminent arrival, we 
are never prepared for it and the slightest dusting brings the entire 
country to a standstill. I personally think we see far too little snow and 
eagerly await the first falls of Winter with childish anticipation. It's an 
annual sport of mine to try and photograph snowflake ice crystals.
<p>
<h3>Working outside</h3>
The first requirement is an outside laboratory where the microscope can be 
used safely in a moderately protected environment whilst still subject to 
the low prevailing temperatures. A garden shed with the windows and door 
open is ideal but in the past I have utilised an old Volkswagen Van, a 
polytunnel or just a sheet of polythene to make a windbreak and roof 
attached to the outside of an out-building. So long as the environment 
remains cold and protected from direct wind or further falls of snow any 
temporary shelter is acceptable. 
<p>
The microscope and all utensils have to be chilled to the outside ambient 
temperature and to achieve this they should be placed in the outside 
`laboratory' several hours before attempting to look at any snowflake 
crystals. The other items required are a couple of needles mounted in wooden 
handles and a selection of clean microscope slides.
<p>
<h3>Tools</h3>
The microscope requirements are simple. Since many of the crystals 
encountered will be quite large it is only necessary to fit a single low 
power objective lens, (e.g. x4 mag.); the others being removed and left 
indoors. An Abbe condenser is more than adequate for the purpose especially 
if the top lens can be removed. This arrangement will provide an even spread 
of light with the attendant property of not warming the microscope slide so 
quickly.
<p>
<h3>In the dead of night</h3>
Depending upon weather conditions and temperature I find it best to work at 
night but if the daytime temperature remains a few degrees below freezing 
then there should be no problems though you should work in shadow as the sun 
has a powerful warming effect. Using a wooden spatula a sample of snow is 
taken to the microscope where it is examined by eye. By altering its 
attitude to a remote light source or shining a torch over it, a few 
well-defined crystals lying on the surface will be seen. With the aide of 
one of the mounted needles, transfer a selected ice crystal to a chilled 
microscope slide and place on the microscope stage. With luck you will have 
a perfect six sided crystal to draw, photograph or just admire.  Care must 
be taken not to breath on the microscope or slides as the merest warming 
will melt the sample. If a gentle cold draft can be maintained through the 
area so much the better.
<p>
Remember to wrap yourself up well. This not only prevents you from getting 
cold but also helps to protect your microscope and snow samples from your 
radiant heat. Its not as daunting as you might imagine; have a go and 
perhaps we shall be able to see some of your results on these pages. The 
pictures here are examples of snowflakes I prepared earlier.
<p>
Once you have finished outside bring the microscope (and camera equipment) 
indoors and allow it to return to room temperature slowly before using it. 
<p>
Good luck! <i>Andrew Syred</i>
<p>
<br>

<p>
<center>
<H3>
<A HREF="../../index.html">Microscopy UK Front Page</A><br>
<A HREF="../indexmag.html">Micscape Magazine</A><br>
<A HREF="../libindex.html">Article Library</A><br>
</H3>
</center>

<P>
<hr>
