<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Microscopy UK / MICSCAPE : Mammalian Hair</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<CENTER>
<H1>Microscopy of Mammalian Hair</H1><H3>by Andrew Syred Feb. 1996</H3><BR><P>
</CENTER>
<HR>


<br>

<br>


<P>
<h3>Hair: a good subject to begin 'scoping' on.</h3>

<IMG SRC="../images/hairhum.gif"  ALT="" hspace=8 vspace=4 ALIGN=right>
When a microscope is procured for the first time, one of the first objects 
usually looked at is  hair extricated from the nearest willing scalp but
once the novelty has worn off and the hair discarded, few budding 
microscopists consciously return to such a humble specimen. However, 
the study of hair, whether as a separate interest or as an aspect of a much
larger project, can provide hours of fun and serious study. 
<p>
Completely unambiguous identification of an unknown hair sample is not 
always possible but if one is able to compare hair of unknown origin against
that of a reference sample from an authenticated source much of the 
guess-work can be removed and a more confident identification provided.
Combined with additional local knowledge of where the hair was found a short
list or two or three possible candidates may be reduced to just one.
<p>
<h3>Building a Reference Library</h3>
A reference library of correctly identified hairs is therefore essential 
and creating a collection of permanently mounted hair for oneself provides
valuable knowledge gained through experience. With so many sources of hair
available, a collection will increase rapidly. Family pets and dead wild 
animals are the most obvious starting points for a reference collection 
but zoos or an obliging veterinary surgeon are excellent sources for exotic
or more difficult samples; even hair taken from an old fur coat will be 
useful if its identification can be guaranteed.
<p>

<h3>The Structure of Hair</h3>
<IMG SRC="../images/hairfig1.gif"  ALT="" hspace=8 vspace=4 ALIGN=left>

The structure of hair may be divided into three distinct parts, the medulla,
cortex and epidermis (fig.1). The medulla or inner-most region comprises of
shrunken cell aggregates and air spaces and may vary considerably from being
almost absent to constituting the greatest component. Its morphology is an 
important diagnostic feature. When filled with air the medulla appears dark 
often to the point of being almost opaque but when infiltrated with a 
suitable medium such as canada balsam becomes transparent allowing more 
detailed examination. The cortex is a layer of dead cells packed into a 
homogeneous mass so that little, if any, cellular detail can be seen.
It too varies considerably in width and the medulla-to-cortex ratio is used 
for identification purposes. Both layers may contain pigment granules, the 
form and distribution of which should be noted. The thinnest outer-most 
epidermal layer comprises of overlapping scales akin to tiles on a roof 
where the leading edge of one scale obscures the base of the one ahead. 
The organisation and nature of the scales form a distinctive pattern along
the shaft of hair and is a key identification feature. 
<P>
<h3>Preparing a Sample</h3>
Prior to making permanent whole mounts, the sample of hair should be 
thoroughly washed and cleaned in an organic solvent, such as 
ethanol/diethyl ether (1:1) mixture, and allowed to dry flat between two 
pieces of  absorbent filter paper. To avoid an untidy jumble of hair a thin 
coating of very dilute gum tragacanth or acacia is smeared along the 
length of a clean microscope slide. Before it is allowed to dry short 
lengths of hair are positioned on the gummed area and gently pressed into
placed to secure them. Once thoroughly dry the hairs should be mounted in
euparal or canada balsam then covered with a suitable cover slip. 
Providing it was completely dry the gum adhesive should not be detectable
by routine illumination techniques. 
<p>
The cut ends of hair will allow some
infiltration of mounting medium to occur enabling the characteristics of 
both infiltrated and non-infiltrated hair to be examined. Long hairs should
be cut into short, manageable lengths and mounted in sequence so that the 
full length may be scrutinised. This is important since the characteristics
of a single hair changes along its length as it grows and ages.
<p>
<h3>Making a Cast</h3>
It will frequently be found that the epidermal scales if not totally 
obscured by the opacity of the medulla matrix or strong pigmentation, 
will be very difficult to observe by direct examination. To circumvent this
problem a method of producing a surface replica is employed. Various 
replica media are used for the purpose and include solutions of `Gloy' 
paper gum, thick polyvinyl alcohol, formvar, cellulose nitrate (model 
makers clear dope) or thinned nail varnish. 
<p>
<IMG SRC="../images/haircast.gif"  ALT="" hspace=8 vspace=4 ALIGN=left>
To make a replica a thin, even
coating of the preferred replica casting medium is smeared along the full
length of a clean microscope slide. The thickness of the smear and 
concentration of the medium has to be judged by experience since hairs of 
differing coarseness and age behave differently. Lengths of hair are then 
laid onto the medium by lowering from one end, to prevent entrapment of air,
and gently pressed into place. Several hairs may be laid side by side on the
same slide without touching each other. It is also convenient if the hairs 
overhang the end of the slide by a few millimetres to facilitate easy 
removal later.
<p>
Place the slides in a warm dust-free environment for a 
sufficient period of time to allow complete drying of the casting medium 
after which the hair is carefully peeled away by lifting from one end with 
a pair of fine forceps.  The resultant replica is then examined dry using 
bright field illumination to reveal the full scale architecture without 
difficulty.
<p>
<h3>Cutting Cross-Sections</h3>
Determining the shape of the hair shaft and medulla in cross-section are
essential elements for a correct identification. If very thin sections are 
required, such as when dealing with very heavily pigmented hair, then an 
expensive, purpose designed fibre microtome is needed that will cut sections 10-15um thick but as such thin sections are rarely necessary in all but exceptional cases a considerably cheaper alternative is available. Widely known as the `plate method' of Ford and Simmens, it employs a thin stainless steel plate with its length and width dimensions approximately the same as those of a standard microscope slide but less than 0.5mm thick. In the UK pieces of steel or brass of suitable thickness, known as shim stock, are available from ironmongers or model maker suppliers.  A 0.8mm diameter hole is drilled centrally through the plate and contoured slightly on both sides using a fine abrasive to remove any burrs or sharp edges. The general principle is to fill the hole with a small bundle of hair and cut off the excess on either side to leave a wad of hair in the hole for microscopical examination. It will now be appreciated that the thickness of the plate determines the final length of hair section and the thinner the plate the shorter the section. A plate thickness of 0.2mm with a 0.8mm 
diameter hole appears to be optimum for most hair samples since a thinner 
plate is no longer sufficiently rigid. Additionally the diameter of hole 
has to be reduced as the retained hair wad has a tendency to breakup and 
fall out during cutting. From experience the minimum limits imposed by 
this method are a plate thickness of 0.1mm with a hole diameter of 0.6mm, 
though one should be prepared for a degree of frustration if working to 
these dimensions.
<p>
<br>
<IMG SRC="../images/hairfig2.gif"  ALT="" hspace=8 vspace=4 ALIGN=right>

In practice it is not necessary of even desirable to completely fill the
hole with sample hair and a packing yarn is normally used. This may be any 
thin, easily cut thread such as silk or perhaps cotton but beyond doubt the
most suitable is 330 decitex cellulose acetate. It is very soft, cuts
cleanly, grips the hair sample well and is soluble in acetone which will
be seen later to be an advantage. To introduce the packing yarn into the 
hole two ends of a strong cotton or nylon thread are passed through the
plate to leave a loop on one side (fig.2) into which a bundle of packing 
yarn will be placed.
<p>
A convenient way to produce a bundle of packing yarn 
is to wind a length a dozen times around a strip of cardboard 50mm wide 
then cut through one end giving 100mm lengths of yarn folded in the middle. 
Depending upon the diameter of hole drilled in the plate and the quantity of
hair being sectioned about 8 to 12 lengths of packing yarn will be 
sufficient for the purpose. 
<p>

The full length of packing yarn is passed 
through the loop of the pull-through thread as far as the fold and by
pulling the thread from the opposite face of the plate the bundle is 
pulled a few millimetres through the hole. The packing yarn is then 
fanned out as uniformly as possible in all directions. The sample of hair 
is then introduced into the centre of the fanned yarn which is then pulled 
through about half way so forming an inverted cone in which the sample hair
is trapped. 
<p>
The whole bundle should feel tightly secured in the hole with 
no tendency to move unless pulled very firmly. If the bundle is too loose 
pull it all the way through and repeat the process adding a few more 
lengths of packing yarn. Using a de-greased, single edged razor blade 
cut the bundle flush with both sides of the plate. Permanent mounts may 
be made by applying a suitable mountant, (e.g. canada balsam), and cover
slip directly to the plate and examined as a conventional microscope 
slide; a separate plate being supplied for each sample. However, if  
cellulose acetate is used as the packing yarn, a small amount of acetone 
applied to both surfaces of the wad will cause it to partially dissolve 
and adhere to itself as a solid mass. 
<p>
Once the acetone has evaporated and
the sample wad hardened it may be carefully punched out of the plate using 
a blunt-cut wooden cocktail stick. If cotton or silk has been used as the 
packing yarn a small quantity of model makers shrinking dope can be applied
to one side of the sample wad which will hold it together whilst being punch
ed from the plate. In both cases, the wad can be subsequently mounted in 
canada balsam as a standard specimen on a glass slide.
<P>
<br>
<h3>Identification</h3>
<IMG SRC="../images/hairrab.gif"  ALT="" vspace=4 hspace=8 ALIGN=right>
Possessing a knowledge of the locality from where the hair sample was found 
together with its colour, physical attributes and the information acquired
through detailed microscopical examination, the investigator should be 
able to narrow the list of possible suspect mammals to just two or three. 
Once a library of reference hair has been compiled enabling comparison
against accurately identified samples it will often be possible to 
positively identify the sample to a single species.
<p>
<br>
<b>
<center>'Hair today and gone tomorrow...'<br>
Andrew Syred</center>
<br>
</b>
<p>
<br>
<b>References and bibliography </b><br>

Ford, J.E., Simmens, S.C. Fibre Section Cutting by the Plate Method. Shirley Institute Memoirs, Vol31, 289-299, 1958
<p>

Appleyard. H.M. Guide to the Identification of Animal Fibres. Wool Industries Research Association. Leeds 1960 
<p>
Brunner H., Coman, B.J. The Identification of Mammalian Hair. Inkata Press (Australia) 1974
<p>
Stoves, J.L. Fibre Microscopy. London: National Trade Press 1951
<p>
Syred, A. Microscopy of Mammalian Hair. Microscopy and Analysis  vol.24, 23-25, 1991
<p>
Wildman, A.B. The Microscopy of Animal Textile Fibres. Wool Industries Research Association. Leeds. 1954    
<p>

<P>

