<HEAD>
<TITLE>Microscopy UK / MICSCAPE : SEM Specimen preparation </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<center>
<h3>Specimen Preparation for the Scanning Electron Microscope (SEM)</h3>
<h3>by Andrew Syred. Nov 27th 1995</h3>
</center>
<hr>

<b>Editor's Introduction:</b><br>
<em>Most amateur 'scopers' are limited to light microscopy and may well envy the ownership of a Scanning Electron Microscope, an expensive instrument with incredible resolution. As most light microscopists will
realise, preparing specimens for viewing under a light microscope
can be a detailed and pain-staking procedure. I thought it might be 
interesting to compare this process with that of preparing specimens for 
SEM study and asked Andrew Syred of Microscopix if he would write a short article for us. I am sure you will appreciate some of the problems and limitations involved.</em>
<p>
Andrew is a keen microscopist and provides images from both SEM and Light Microscopy sources to publishers, educationalists, and advertisers throughout the world. You may well have seen some samples of his work in newspapers and magazines, all of which, have helped gain further public awareness of the incredible beauty and sophistication of our microscopic world.
<p>
<b>Overview</b><br>
As with all aspects of microscopy good sample preparation is critical; poor preparation leads inextricably to poor results - the SEM being no <img src="../images/semart.gif" alt="" align=left hspace=12>
exception. Though a vast and complex subject, for the purposes of these notes it will be kept basic and confined to the SEM. In preparing specimens for <i>light microscopy</i>, the process would involve the following (although not necessarily in this order): fixation, preservation, dehydration, clearing, staining, dissecting, softening, and mounting. Similar stages are involved preparing specimens for SEM study, although much of the process in concerned with ensuring the specimen will remain intact when placed in the dynamic environment of the SEM. For example, you can see here an image showing the papilla cells on a Snapdragon petal (Antirrhinum majus) x1000 which, if not fixed and dried properly, totally collapses when studied by a Scanning Electron Microscope.
<p>
<b>The Scanning Electron Microscope (SEM)</b><br>
Whilst a complicated piece of electrical equipment the scanning electron microscope compares simply (if one substitutes monocular for binocular) to a low-power stereoscopic light microscope where the specimen is placed on the stage, illuminated from the side at and angle of about 45 and viewed directly from above. In the SEM the effective result is the same except that in practice the specimen is 'illuminated' by a beam of electrons perpendicular to the stage and 'viewed' from the side. An accurately focussed beam of electrons is projected onto the sample which it scans, line by line, in a similar manner to an operating television cathode ray tube. On striking the sample secondary electrons are dislodged and widely scattered many of which are subsequently captured by a sensitive collector and converted, by a little electronic wizardry, into an image on a small TV-like monitor.
<p>
Since electrons do not travel very far in air and the tungsten electron source has also to be heated to around 3,000 C without melting or oxidising, the entire system operates in a high vacuum of which the specimen becomes an integral part. The hapless specimen is subjected to a very hostile environment of low pressure (a barometer reading of about 0.0001mm or 0.0000039 inches of Hg) and bombardment by high energy electrons - points to be noted.
<p>
<b>Cleaning</b><br>
Any material destined for examination in the microscope has ideally to be fully dehydrated, scrupulously clean, mechanically rigid, stable in a vacuum and electrically conductive. A demanding set of criteria rarely complied with in any sample, least of all biological samples.
<p>
Since scanning electron microscopy is a surface technique it follows that any surface impurity  will obscure detail of the specimen itself. Oil and grease even from the fingers will be sufficient to ruin an otherwise well prepared sample as in the electron beam it will cause it to char and blacken whilst being examined rendering it useless. Careful surface preparation is vital but depends greatly upon what the sample will tolerate and may range from a judicious application of an organic solvent through to prolonged immersion in strong mineral acids. Once clean the specimen should only be handled with forceps.
<p>
<b>Mechanical rigidity</b><br>
Vacuum instability or lack of mechanical rigidity, if an inherent feature of the specimen, are not easily overcome and their effects may only be reduced by accepting short exposures and/or employing low electron beam accelerating voltages. In severe cases it is often possible to make a stable plastic replica of the specimen and treat it as if it were the actual sample. Beam damage can be a problem especially at high voltages and magnifications where a small area is being bombarded by high energy electrons. The area heats up causing movement, cracking and even melting creating obvious difficulties during photography. Faster scan speeds or lower accelerating voltages then have to be resorted to and the subsequent loss of image quality accepted.
<p>
<b>Dehydration</b><br>
Hydrated specimens present special problems as water is neither rigid or stable and when placed in the low pressure environment of the microscope rapidly evaporates. In biological samples it is generally the greatest constituent and often the main structural component that maintains the specimen's shape and form. If allowed to dry naturally most biological samples shrivel and distort leaving behind a dried relic bearing little resemblance to the live and fully turgid structure. Removing the 'structural water' whilst retaining the near-natural state of the specimen is difficult and never perfect since the main problem to overcome is the crushing force of surface tension that develops during evaporation. This may be reduced by substituting water for an extremely volatile organic solvent such as diethyl ether though the results are rarely satisfactory. 
<p>
<b>Freeze-drying and Critical Point Drying</b><br>
Two methods usually employed for removing water are freeze drying and critical point drying (CPD). In freeze-drying the sample, previously fixed in an aqueous fixative, is washed thoroughly in water prior to being quickly frozen by quenching in liquid nitrogen. Such rapid freezing prevents the formation of large ice crystals that would otherwise damage the specimens micro-structure. 
<p>
The sample is then transferred to a vacuum chamber housing a cold stage maintained at a temperature of between -70C and -90C. The air in the chamber is then pumped out and over a period of time the ice sublimes, i.e. it converts directly to the gaseous phase without passing through the liquid state, so avoiding the destructive forces of surface tension. Some distortion does occur but it is a tolerable artifact if maintained within acceptable limits. More commonly used is the process of critical point drying.
<p>
CPD makes use of the fact that all liquids and gases when taken above a certain pressure and temperature, the critical point, no longer exist as distinct phases but merge into a single fluid phase. At this point there is no density change or heat of vaporisation. The simplest method would be to utilise water itself but with a critical temperature of 374C and critical pressure of 3184 psi few samples would survive the treatment. Carbon dioxide however has a critical pressure of 1072 psi and critical temperature of only 31C. Liquid carbon dioxide is not miscible with water and a transition fluid, commonly ethanol, is used to replace the water. The appropriately fixed sample is dehydrated in an ascending series of ethanol baths terminating in absolute ethanol from where it is transferred to a pressure vessel containing fresh absolute ethanol in which it is sealed. The pressure vessel, previously connected to a supply of liquid carbon dioxide, is cooled to about -5C at which point the liquid gas is introduced. Once completely filled with a carbon dioxide/ethanol mixture the vessel is purged with liquid carbon dioxide for about 30 mins. so to completely displace the alcohol that is allowed to run to waste. 
<p>
The vessel temperature is maintained throughout at below 0C. Once full displacement of the alcohol from the sample and chamber has been achieved, the ports to and from the pressure vessel are closed off and the chamber itself slowly heated to a final temperature of about +40C. As the temperature rises from below 0C the liquid carbon dioxide contained within the sealed pressure vessel expands and the pressure within the vessel increases rapidly exceeding the critical pressure of 1072 psi. The temperature is allowed to rise to beyond the critical temperature after which point a fine bleed valve is opened and the carbon dioxide SLOWLY vented. Once the chamber is returned to atmospheric pressure the dried sample is then removed and almost ready for the SEM.
<p>
<b>Surface preparation</b><br>
As mentioned the sample has to become an integral part of the microscope, it must be earthed and electrically conductive to allow charge build-up produced in the electron beam to dissipate. To achieve this the sample is coated with a very thin layer of metal that must be thin enough not to obscure detail but thick enough to survive the electron beam. It must be a continuous, electrically conductive layer that will not oxidise in addition to having such a fine grain structure that it is not itself visualised at user magnifications. Various metals and alloys are used for this purpose with gold being perhaps the most common. 
<p>
Samples securely attached to metal stubs are placed on a plinth (electrically at ground potential) in a vacuum chamber. The lid of the chamber houses a gold disc to which a high voltage supply is attached that forms an anode during use. When sealed the air in the chamber is pumped out and thoroughly purged with argon after which time low pressure is maintained by slowly bleeding in a small volume of argon to balance that being removed by the vacuum pump. A high voltage DC current applied to the lid of the chamber causes the rarefied argon in the chamber to ionise and strike the gold target. Atoms of gold become dislodged by the continual bombardment of ionised argon molecules and become deposited on the sample. To ensure uniform deposition of gold, including on the underside of the sample, the stub is rotated at different angles during the sputtering process. A layer of between 15 to 30 nm (1nm = 1/1,000,000mm) is usually sufficiently thick for most purposes. The specimen is then ready to be placed into the SEM for examination. 
<p>
<b>Miscellaneous</b><br>
The end result of using a SEM is to obtain a recorded image of the 
<img src="../images/dustmite.gif" alt="" hspace=12 align=right>
specimen. Much work is often required to ensure the final image has an
attractive composition, for example when producing images for book publishing or for general public viewing. As much time arranging a 'scene' can be spend as for preparing the specimen itself; for example - when taking an image of a dustmite, a more attractive result is obtained by carefully positioning the dustmite into a background of fine fibres and debris from its natural environment. The example image reproduced here from the microscopix showcase on micscape demonstrates this point.

<p>
SEM images are always orginally captured in black and white (greyscale) and are turned into colour images only through the use of computer software tools. 
<p> 
<br>
<br>
<b>
<center> Andrew Syred (Microscopix Photolibrary). <br>
Email: <a href="mailto:andrew@micropix.demon.co.uk">Andrew</A><br>
</b>
</center>
<p>

<center>
