<HEAD>
<TITLE>Microscopy UK / MICSCAPE - 3D Stereo Microscopy : Strange Crystals</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#000000" text="#00ff00">

<a name="top">

<P>
<center><h1>3D Crystals</h1></center>
<center><em>Please wait for image to load... it's worth it!</em></center>
<p>

<center><IMG SRC="3dxtals.jpg" width=272 height=204></center>
<p>
<h4>
<em>An explanation from Andrew:-</em><br>
I was asked to produce a 'dramatic' image of a burned-out light bulb
filament but from experience, filaments rarely do anything other than
melt cleanly in a very localised area and retain a high polish. So I
tried a different approach. A 60W domestic light bulb was deliberately
cracked to allow air into the envelope whilst maintaining the integrity
of the filament. The bulb was inserted into a light holder, power
supplied and within seconds the filament burned-out. Upon disassembling
the bulb the filament had turned the characteristic tungsten blue, had
welded itself to the wire supports and burned-out in one place. In the
SEM the filament was observed to have become covered with needle-like
crystals but at the point of weld on the supports a forest of pyramidal
crystals had developed. That's the history, know any chemists? 
Magnification of the xtals was x5000.
</h4>

<H3>
<center>
<A HREF="3dfront.html#select">3D Image Selector</A>
